<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AirTran Accuses Delta on Pricing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- AirTran is accusing Delta Air Lines of matching  
its fares and adding flights to drive out low-cost competition and 
ultimately raise fares. 
</P>
<P>
	``Delta's competitive response to AirTran over the years, and  
increasingly in recent days, has only one objective -- drive a 
small-but-growing, successful low-fare carrier out of its 
markets,'' AirTran wrote in a brief sent to the federal Justice and 
Transportation departments. 
</P>
<P>
	The allegations come on the heels of a government lawsuit  
against American Airlines for predator pricing against smaller 
rivals. The Justice Department charged in the suit that American 
cut fares and added flights temporarily to drive low-cost 
competitors out of its giant hub airport outside Dallas and Fort 
Worth. 
</P>
<P>
	Delta spokesman Bill Berry called the charges ``insulting and  
untrue.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Executives at the Orlando, Fla.-based AirTran, who insisted they  
were working on the brief before the May 13 American suit, said 
they aren't seeking a lawsuit or specific remedy. 
</P>
<P>
	``What we've done is reviewed the competitive practices,''  
AirTran President Robert Fornaro said. ``We want the DOJ and DOT to 
pass judgment on them however they see fit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Berry said AirTran, formerly ValuJet, has made such claims for  
years to divert attention from its own problems. 
</P>
<P>
	``No government agency has ever found Delta to be in the wrong.  
It's time for AirTran, which is one of the largest discount 
carriers in the country, to accept responsibility for its past 
marketing failures and stop blaming the competition,'' Berry said. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the AirTran brief:  
</P>
<P>
	-- Delta has raised walk-up fares 52 percent on the  
Atlanta-Richmond, Va., route since AirTran withdrew last winter in 
the face of intensive fare-matching. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Delta last fall began flights to Chicago-Midway Airport, which  
it had never before served, and undercut AirTran's average fares by 
8 percent. AirTran said it may be forced to withdraw from that 
route, too. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Delta responded to a recent AirTran sale by not only matching  
fares but also dropping round-trip and weekend stay requirements. 
The response, which AirTran claims was unprecedented, came after it 
announced a first-quarter profit -- only its second in the past two 
years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
