<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Berry Pickers' Union Votes Counted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALINAS, Calif. (AP) -- Workers at the nation's largest  
strawberry grower won't know which union will represent them in 
contract negotiations until state labor officials sort out 
challenges to the eligibility of some voters. 
</P>
<P>
	The vote by workers at Coastal Berry Co. on Wednesday was  
considered a key test of the United Farm Workers' effort to regain 
the influence it had in agriculture under the leadership of the 
late Cesar Chavez. 
</P>
<P>
	But the best the UFW can appear to hope for is a runoff election  
against its rival union, the Coastal Berry of California Farm 
Worker Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	The UFW received votes from 577 of the opened ballots, Coastal  
Berry had 646, and 79 opted for no union representation, labor 
officials said. The eligibility of 60 additional voters was 
challenged, mostly by labor officials but some by the unions. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the voting rules, a runoff is required unless one of the  
three options wins a simple majority. Because of the eligibility 
challenges, it was still uncertain today whether Coastal Berry 
would have enough to win a majority, or if it would have to face 
UFW in a runoff. 
</P>
<P>
	Agricultural Labor Relations Board officials planned to meet  
today to discuss the unresolved ballots, said the board's regional 
director Fred Capuyan, but a final tally could be days away. 
</P>
<P>
	The sweat was visible on the forehead of strawberry picker Jose  
Rojas as he waited to learn the results of the balloting. 
</P>
<P>
	For nine years, Rojas has worked in Watsonville at Coastal  
Berry. He cast his ballot in favor of the UFW, and said a vote to 
unionize would make his backbreaking efforts for his three sons 
worthwhile. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want my sacrifice to be worth a better life for them,''  
Rojas said in Spanish. 
</P>
<P>
	The results of the vote are considered pivotal in the UFW's  
effort to overcome the doldrums it fell into even before the 1993 
death of Chavez, who inspired 80,000 farm workers to join up by 
1970. Union membership had declined to 20,000 by the time he died. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1995, the UFW launched its rebuilding campaign in the  
strawberry fields, where picking the crops is entry-level farm 
work, the most backbreaking, low-skilled labor available. 
</P>
<P>
	Since then, the UFW has won 18 union elections and signed 22  
first-time contracts with growers of other crops, increasing 
overall membership to 27,000. 
</P>
<P>
	But the state's $600 million strawberry industry, which employs  
about 20,000 workers, has been resistant. Until this week, the only 
strawberry grower to sign a UFW contract was a small organic farm 
with 50 workers. 
</P>
<P>
	The UFW committed itself to winning at Coastal Berry five years  
ago, hoping a victory would create momentum for similar successes 
throughout California's farm fields. 
</P>
<P>
	The campaign has been plagued by setbacks.  
</P>
<P>
	``This has been a long struggle at Coastal Berry,'' said UFW  
spokesman Marc Grossman. ``The strawberry industry wants to stop 
UFW progress at all costs, and Coastal Berry could be a crucial 
turning point for the workers statewide.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coastal Berry Co. President Ernie Farley said the company was  
neutral on who represents the workers. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're just looking forward to an end to the whole process,''  
he said. ``We spend an awful lot of time managing that process 
rather than managing the business.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coastal Worker's pickers are treated better than some in the  
berry fields, Farley said. They earn an average wage of $7.50 to 
$8.50 an hour and have full medical and dental benefits for 
themselves and dependents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
