<DOCNO> APW19990527.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 04:32:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Silverbulletday Adds Belmont Spice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The sizzle of Charismatic's Triple Crown bid in  
the Belmont Stakes has gotten some added spice with the commitment 
of the filly Silverbulletday to the 1 1/2-mile classic June 5. 
</P>
<P>
	While Charismatic will be trying to become the 12th Triple Crown  
winner and first since Affirmed in 1978, Silverbulletday will be 
attempting to become the third filly to win the Belmont. The only 
winners were Tanya in 1905 and Ruthless in 1867, in the first 
Belmont. 
</P>
<P>
	``She's in the Belmont,'' trainer Bob Baffert said by telephone  
Wednesday from Churchill Downs. 
</P>
<P>
	Baffert's spoiler role follows his failed bids to win the Triple  
Crown with Silver Charm in 1997 and Real Quiet last year. Both 
colts finished second. 
</P>
<P>
	`She's a pure athlete, and athletes sometimes do things they are  
not supposed to do,'' owner Mike Pegram said of the decision to 
have Silverbulletday make her debut against colts in the Belmont. 
``We have absolutely nothing to lose.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Silverbulletday, winner of 11 of 12 starts and unbeaten in five  
races this year, will be only the 21st filly to start in the 
Belmont. 
</P>
<P>
	Baffert said the decision to run Silverbulletday in the Belmont  
was made after she worked six furlongs in 1:10 4-5 Tuesday at 
Churchill Downs. 
</P>
<P>
	``She cooled out great after a good, hard work,'' Baffert said.  
``She was playing and bucking.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Baffert said Silverbulletday will be flown to New York next  
Wednesday, the day entries are taken for the Belmont. Jerry Bailey 
will ride her for the second time in her career. Charismatic will 
be flow from the Downs to New York on the same day. 
</P>
<P>
	Silverbulletday also was entered in the Kentucky Derby and  
Preakness, but also was entered into filly stakes held the day 
before either of those races. She won the Kentucky Oaks at 
Churchill Downs and the Black-Eyed Susan at Pimlico. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked if he second-guessed himself about not running  
Silverbulletday in the Derby or Preakness, Pegram said, ``Not one 
bit. But if I didn't run her in the Belmont, I would be 
second-guessing myself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Silverbulletday being in the race means that owners of the last  
unsuccessful Triple Crown challengers will be represented in the 
Belmont. 
</P>
<P>
	Pegram, owns Real Quiet; Charismatic is owned by Bob and Beverly  
Lewis, owners of Silver Charm, and Menifee is co-owned by Arthur 
Hancock III, co-owner of Sunday Silence, runnerup in 1989. 
</P>
<P>
	A field of 12 to 14 3-year-olds was shaping up for the Belmont.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
