<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) -- Joao Carlos de Oliveira, who held the  
world record in the triple jump for a decade, slipped into a coma 
and was listed in ``extremely serious condition,'' doctors said 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Oliveira, who was hospitalized in April with lung and liver  
ailments, was bleeding from the lungs and responded only to painful 
stimuli, according to a statement signed by Dr. Jose Carlete and 
Dr. Antonio Pinheiro at the Beneficiencia Portuguesa Hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	Oliveira, 44, became a national hero when he set the world  
record with a jump of 58 feet, 8 1/4 inches at the 1975 Pan American 
Games in Mexico, a mark that stood for 10 years. 
</P>
<P>
	He also won bronze medals in the 1976 and 1980 Olympics.  
Brazilians dubbed him ``Joao do Pulo,'' Portuguese for ``Jumping 
John.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1981, however, Oliveira's car was hit head-on by a drunk  
driver going the wrong way at night on an interstate highway. 
Oliveira was seriously injured, and doctors amputated his right 
leg. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) -- A soundman for Chile's state television  
was shot in the head Thursday near the border between Albania and 
Yugoslavia's Kosovo province, the station reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Abner Machuca, 30, was apparently shot by a sniper and was in  
serious but stable condition, the station said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were heard a fire exchange between Kosovo guerrillas and  
Serb soldiers. Suddenly, Abner dropped to the ground, wounded,'' 
reporter Claudio Mendoz said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said Machuca was rushed to a hospital in Tirana, the Albanian  
capital, and that arrangements were being made to transfer him to 
Italy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
