<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Former Chase Vice President Arrested </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A former vice president and chief financial  
officer of the Credit Card Division of Chase USA was arrested 
Thursday at his Connecticut home on charges that he submitted false 
documents to obtain $4.3 million in loans. 
</P>
<P>
	John F. Wilson was fired by Chase USA, a subsidiary of Chase  
Manhattan Corp., after Chase officials discovered that he had 
allegedly provided false information on his loan documents, 
prosecutors said in a release. 
</P>
<P>
	Wilson was charged with three counts of filing a false loan  
application and one count of bank fraud in the scheme, which 
allegedly occurred in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors accused Wilson of obtaining two loans worth $2.36  
million from Chase Manhattan Bank and Chase Manhattan Mortgage Co. 
by falsely claiming ownership of about $1.1 million in stock 
options from his previous employer, General Electric Capital Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Wilson left GE Capital in June 1996 to move to Chase and did not  
possess any stock options at the time he submitted the loan 
applications in 1998, prosecutors said. He was fired by Chase last 
month after the bank discovered what it said was false and 
fraudulent information in his loan application. 
</P>
<P>
	A criminal complaint alleged that Wilson obtained a $1.56  
million loan from Chase Manhattan Mortgage to buy a $2.4 million 
property in Ridgefield, Conn. 
</P>
<P>
	The complaint, filed in U.S. District Court in Manhattan, also  
alleged that he obtained a third loan worth $2 million from Webster 
Bank in Cheshire, Conn., by falsely concealing that he had an 
outstanding loan from Chase Manhattan Bank. 
</P>
<P>
	If convicted, Wilson faces a maximum sentence on each of the  
four counts of 30 years in prison and a $250,000 fine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990527.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 16:22:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Texas OKs Electric Deregulation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- Texas' $20 billion utility market faces a  
sweeping overhaul under an industry deregulation bill that 
supporters say will reduce electric bills. 
</P>
<P>
	The legislation was approved by the state Senate Thursday and  
sent to Gov. George W. Bush, who plans to sign the bill into law 
joining Texas with 20 other states that also have moved to 
deregulate the industry. 
</P>
<P>
	Bill supporters say the measure will mean lower rates and better  
reliability for consumers who could shop for their utility 
providers. The Senate approved the bill on a voice vote. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the legislation, electric rates would be frozen at their  
current level until Jan. 1, 2002. They would then be lowered by 6 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Bill supporters expect utility companies to be enticed into  
moving to Texas to offer lower prices and new technology, including 
devices that tell consumers when they are wasting electricity. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill was criticized by some consumer groups who have  
questioned whether consumers want to move toward deregulation and 
whether the bill provides enough consumer protections. 
</P>
<P>
	Opponents had pointed to other examples of deregulation where  
states saw power companies ignore residential consumers in favor of 
commercial customers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990527.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 04:32:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Drivers Encouraged By Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Drivers, owners and officials with the IRL  
and CART are encouraged by peace talks between the rival leagues, 
saying a reconciliation will ensure success for both sides. 
</P>
<P>
	``They've got to do it,'' said Robby Gordon, an owner-driver in  
the Indy Racing League and Championship Auto Racing Teams. 
</P>
<P>
	After four years of a bitter feud that threatens the future of  
open-wheel racing in the United States, CART and the IRL have begun 
face-to-face talks. 
</P>
<P>
	Word of the negotiations came as teams prepared for the  
Indianapolis 500, which lost its luster during the fight when the 
best-known drivers decided to stay away. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can confirm that there have been some very informal talks  
with Tony George,'' Andrew Craig, president and CEO of CART, told 
The Associated Press. ``However, I am not prepared to comment on 
any of the details.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There is no comment -- but also no denial of the talks -- from  
George, the Indianapolis Motor Speedway president who started the 
war when he formed the Indy Racing League late in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	CART fired back by boycotting Indy, leaving George to stage the  
world's most famous auto race with virtually no stars. 
</P>
<P>
	The differences between the two circuits once seemed  
insurmountable, with different chassis and engine rules. But the 
last few weeks have brought hope that a settlement could be reached 
as early as 2001. 
</P>
<P>
	``What they need to do is keep the IRL specs,'' Gordon said,  
referring to the rules in the newer series. 
</P>
<P>
	Gordon, scheduled to drive in the CART race on Saturday in  
Madison, Ill., and the Indy 500 on Sunday, says one problem that 
has been construed as the biggest hurdle -- engines -- should really 
be easy to overcome. 
</P>
<P>
	CART teams lease their engines, starting at about $1.3 million a  
season, while the IRL teams buy theirs for $80,000 each. But IRL 
teams also have to do all their own engine work. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of people, including me, would rather not have to have  
an engine shop,'' Gordon said. ``That costs a lot of money, and 
every rebuild is $50,000. My engine budget for Indy this year is 
$400,000.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Virtually everyone on both sides agrees a unified series is  
imperative for the sport. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's CART's position that open-wheel racing would benefit  
greatly from having one series instead of two,'' Craig said. 
</P>
<P>
	Greg Ray, one of the bright new IRL stars, said: ``We're  
continuing to prove ourselves as drivers, as teams and as a sport. 
But when everybody's fighting, it's hard. 
</P>
<P>
	``If two people are trying to climb Mt. Everest, it's harder to  
get to the top if they're fighting each other. Hopefully, we'll 
come together or learn to coexist.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ray also pointed out a unification would add to the  
already-strong competition. 
</P>
<P>
	``Instead of 30 competitors at each race, you might see 60,'' he  
said. ``Twenty or 30 might have to go home each week, sort of like 
NASCAR. ... It would be exciting. It would be fun.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A unification also would make it a lot easier to market  
open-wheel racing. 
</P>
<P>
	Bruce Barnes, president of a California marketing firm that  
works with a number of former Indy 500 champions, said it's tough 
to sell the sport to corporate America because of the split. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you're trying to sell the CART series, you're missing the  
major element, the Indy 500,'' he said. ``If you're trying to sell 
the IRL, to be candid, it's really a Triple-A league.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Eddie Cheever, the defending Indy 500 champion and a former CART  
driver, said he's for unification as long as CART is willing to 
keep costs down and promote NASCAR-type competition. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would be very reluctant to be involved in any series that  
doesn't adhere to those principles,'' Cheever said. 
</P>
<P>
	NASCAR president Bill France Jr., the most powerful man in  
American auto racing, is widely reported to be brokering the peace. 
He did not return phone calls for comment. 
</P>
<P>
	His interest, however, would not be surprising. France also  
heads International Speedway Corp., which after its recent purchase 
of Penske Motorsports has 10 racetracks with at least three more 
planned in the near future. 
</P>
<P>
	ISC will need more than just its stock car and truck divisions  
to keep those tracks busy and prosperous. 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990527.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 04:32:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Drivers Encouraged By Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
