<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stewart To Start 27th in Coca-Cola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONCORD, N.C. (AP) -- Tony Stewart was assured a spot in the  
Coca-Cola 600 field even though he didn't even attend the second 
round of time trials Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart, trying to become just the second driver to compete in  
the Indianapolis 500 and the Coca-Cola 600 on the same day, failed 
to qualify in Wednesday night's first round of qualifying at Lowe's 
Motor Speedway at Charlotte. 
</P>
<P>
	But he stood on his speed, a lap of 182.865 mph, for Thursday's  
second round, electing instead to fly to Indianapolis and take part 
in the final practice session for the 500. 
</P>
<P>
	Standing on his speed meant Stewart got the 27th starting spot  
in Charlotte's 43-car field, but he likely will start at the back 
of the grid. That's NASCAR's mandatory penalty for any driver who 
fails to show up for the start of the drivers' meeting. Sunday's 
meeting is scheduled to start two hours before the race, and it's 
unlikely Stewart will have arrived by then. 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart will start 24th at Indianapolis, where he plans to run  
500 miles before flying immediately to Charlotte for the early 
evening start of the 600. 
</P>
<P>
	Darrell Waltrip, one of eight drivers to take part in  
second-round qualifying, was the only one to go fast enough to earn 
a spot in the field. Waltrip will start 33rd. 
</P>
<P>
                              *------	 
</P>
<P>
	HORNADAY'S ASCENT: Ron Hornaday, winner of two championships in  
three years on NASCAR's Craftsman Truck Series, is moving to the 
Busch Grand National circuit in 2000 with his same team and same 
sponsor. 
</P>
<P>
	Hornaday, driving a Dale Earnhardt Inc.-owned truck, will drive  
Chevrolet Monte Carlos on the Grand National circuit. DEI's current 
Grand National driver, Dale Earnhardt Jr., is moving up to the 
Winston Cup circuit next year. 
</P>
<P>
	NAPA auto parts, Hornaday's primary Truck Series sponsor, said  
Thursday it has signed a three-year deal to back the Grand National 
car. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ever since I was little I've watched the No. 3 car of Dale  
Earnhardt,'' Hornaday said. ``To drive for him now is pretty 
awesome.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hornaday's move into Grand National racing raises the question  
of what will become of DEI's truck team. Earnhardt said it's too 
soon to tell. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're looking right now at our options for drivers and our  
options for sponsors for 2000,'' he said. ``The team's intact. The 
equipment's there. We plan to win the championship this year with 
Ron and look at our options for next year. The door's wide open 
right now.'' 
</P>
<P>
                              *------	 
</P>
<P>
	TOURIST ATTRACTIONS: With relatively few activities scheduled at  
the track Friday, many of the visiting race fans were expected to 
take part in what has become an annual ritual -- touring the 
region's race shops. 
</P>
<P>
	In nearby Mooresville, authorities planned to dispatch extra  
police to help direct traffic at Lakeside Park, a complex that 
houses about 50 race teams and related businesses. Lakeside got so 
many visitors last year on the Friday before the 600 that police 
had to briefly close off the park because of traffic jams on the 
surrounding roads. 
</P>
<P>
	Two new facilities are expected to be among the most popular on  
the unofficial shop tour. 
</P>
<P>
	Dale Earnhardt Inc.'s 112,000-square-foot complex in south  
Mooresville features a 15,000-square-foot museum and gift shop that 
just opened this week. The museum houses memorabilia from The 
Intimidator's career, and visitors also can look through large 
glass panes at work going on in portions of DEI's shop. 
</P>
<P>
	Even bigger is the 125,000-square-foot new home of Joe Gibbs  
Racing, which opened at the turn of the year in the north Charlotte 
suburb of Huntersville. Gibbs' complex includes a movie theater 
with stadium-style seating and a 100-yard-long window that enables 
visitors to see into the main shop. 


</P>
</TEXT>
