<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> McCain Discusses Education, Taxes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- Sen. John McCain, a Republican presidential  
candidate who jump-started his campaign with a hawkish stance on 
Kosovo, broadened his political agenda Thursday with campaign 
initiatives on Social Security, education and tax reform. 
</P>
<P>
	In a commencement address to Johns Hopkins University graduates,  
McCain challenged Republicans and Democrats alike to dramatically 
change their approach to domestic policy debates and end ``this 
sickness in American political life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It is we who have squandered the public trust. We, who have --  
time and again, in full public view -- placed our personal or 
partisan interests before the national interest, earning the 
public's contempt with our poll-driven policies, our phony 
posturing, the lies we call spin, and the damage control we 
substitute for progress,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain, a three-term senator from Arizona, trails Texas Gov.  
George W. Bush and former American Red Cross president Elizabeth 
Dole in GOP polling but has emerged as a solid alternative should 
the early front-runners falter. 
</P>
<P>
	His poll ratings inched upward nationally, doubling in New  
Hampshire, as he conducted hundreds of television and newspaper 
interviews to criticize President Clinton's handling of Kosovo. The 
former Vietnam prisoner of war was the first presidential hopeful 
to say the United States must win at all cost, even if that means 
using grounds troops. 
</P>
<P>
	A self-styled political maverick, McCain has bucked his party  
leadership by proposing tax increases on tobacco and sweeping 
campaign finance reforms. Both initiatives failed. 
</P>
<P>
	With the campaign finance reform debate stirring anew in  
Congress, McCain said Thursday that the impasse won't end until 
politicians in both parties act ``with courage to break with the 
corrupting practices of the past.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats must wean themselves from large, unregulated donations  
by labor unions, he said. As for his own party: ``Republicans will 
have to risk their financial superiority.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That is not a new formulation for the Arizona senator, but  
McCain expanded his attack-all-sides technique to outline new 
initiatives that he hopes will move his campaign beyond Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	``Rank-and-file Republican voters don't really know him. A lot  
do, but those who don't are just getting to know him with Kosovo,'' 
said Republican consultant Charlie Black, a Bush ally. ``He 
certainly needs to fill out his agenda for them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Republican pollster Tony Fabrizio said his surveys show that 51  
percent of GOP voters approve of McCain's position on Kosovo. 
``While a majority, it isn't overwhelming and isn't enough to get 
you elected,'' the pollster said. 
</P>
<P>
	Foreign policy still ranks last on a list of issues important to  
GOP voters, with only 11 percent choosing the topic over three 
topics that tied for the lead: the economy, morality and social 
issues, Fabrizio said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't care,'' McCain said in an interview before his  
address. ``If the polls showed 1 percent approved of my position, 
it wouldn't change my mind about what's right for America.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The senator is taking care not to become a single-issue  
candidate. His speech Thursday was designed to produce a slim 
outline of his non-Kosovo agenda. 
</P>
<P>
	He plans a series of speeches detailing his plans for Social  
Security, campaign finances, education and taxes, beginning next 
week. 
</P>
<P>
	With his first step Thursday, he urged Republicans to resist  
using Social Security revenues to balance the budget and demanded 
that Democrats ``stop using the issue to scare the elderly into 
voting against Republicans.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He criticized both parties in Congress for passing an emergency  
Kosovo bill that he said pays for nine ``pork barrel projects for 
every legitimate emergency.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He proposed forbidding the use of Social Security revenues on  
anything other than Social Security benefits. Under his plan, 
Americans would be allowed to invest part of their payroll taxes in 
private accounts. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain said 60 percent of the federal budget surplus should be  
used to bolster Social Security, with the rest going to tax cuts. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain said he also would close special interest loopholes and  
subsidies to help pay for his tax-cut plan, which would lower the 
tax rate from 28 percent to 15 percent for people earning less than 
$35,000 or couples earning less than $70,000. 
</P>
<P>
	He also would end the tax penalty for married people, eliminate  
the policy that reduces Social Security benefits for elderly people 
who are still working; and reduce the inheritance tax. 
</P>
<P>
	On education, McCain said Republicans should recognize the  
``urgent necessity'' to raise teacher pay. Democrats, he said, must 
learn to accept ``teacher testing and merit pay.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Good teachers should be rewarded and bad teachers should be  
encourage to ``do something else for a living,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
