<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 07:51:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Targets Unruly Passengers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Unruly airline passengers could be banned from  
flying for a year under a proposal pressed by two senators. 
</P>
<P>
	Sens. Harry Reid, D-Nev., and Bill Frist, R-Tenn., also proposed  
increasing the civil penalty for interfering with a flight crew 
from $1,100 to $25,000, and deputizing local law enforcement 
officials so they can arrest an unruly passenger when a plane is 
diverted, instead of further inconveniencing passengers by waiting 
for a federal official. 
</P>
<P>
	The people who most often encounter unruly passengers -- flight  
attendants -- cheered the proposals as they were unveiled Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's apparent that the current penalty is not a sufficient  
deterrent because the number of incidents has increased in spite of 
some fairly high-profile cases where the maximum penalty has been 
applied,'' said Patricia Friend, president of the Association of 
Flight Attendants. The group represents 43,000 flight attendants at 
27 airlines. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1994, the government received reports of 296 unruly  
passengers; the number increased to 921 by 1997. In 1996, the 
Federal Aviation Administration imposed civil penalties against 121 
unruly passengers; in 1997, the number increased to 195. 
</P>
<P>
	Under current criminal law, passengers face up to 20 years in  
jail and a fine of $10,000 for interfering with a flight crew. They 
can be imprisoned for life if they use a weapon. Civil penalties 
are far less, however. 
</P>
<P>
	Noting the increased number of reports, Reid said more serious  
action is needed. 
</P>
<P>
	``This isn't a question of someone being rude to a stewardess or  
a steward,'' he said. ``This is a question of physical abuse.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reid described a recent flight he took from Baltimore to Las  
Vegas that had to land in Omaha, Neb., after a passenger got in a 
fight with a flight attendant. 
</P>
<P>
	Frist also spoke from a firsthand perspective: In addition to  
being a senator, he's a doctor, a pilot with a commercial license 
and the husband of a former flight attendant. 
</P>
<P>
	``For night after night coming home from flying around the  
country, I would hear these stories,'' Frist said. 
</P>
<P>
	The House is weighing a different bill that would also crack  
down on unruly passengers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
