<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Analyst Urges Enforcing Truck Safety </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Better law enforcement, improved data  
collection and attention from top transportation officials can 
improve truck and bus safety, according to an official who studied 
the commercial vehicle industry. 
</P>
<P>
	Former Rep. Norman Mineta, a California Democrat who once headed  
the House Transportation Committee, offered the suggestions 
Wednesday as he concluded a 90-day review of the Transportation 
Department and the federal Office of Motor Carriers, which oversees 
the safety of large commercial vehicles. 
</P>
<P>
	The review came in response to complaints that the motor carrier  
office is too soft on the trucking industry and at a time when a 
string of fatal bus accidents has raised concerns about safety. A 
crash in New Orleans on May 9 killed 22. 
</P>
<P>
	``Continuation of such fatality and injury trends is  
unacceptable, and therefore there has rightfully been a growing 
concern and resurgent call for increased attention to this issue,'' 
Mineta told the House Transportation's ground transportation 
subcommittee. 
</P>
<P>
	His eight recommendations:  
</P>
<P>
	--Increased surveillance, compliance and enforcement activities,  
including increased inspections by state and federal law 
enforcement officials. 
</P>
<P>
	--Increased truck inspections at the border with Mexico before  
Jan. 1, when the North American Free Trade Agreement will allow 
Mexican trucks to travel freely into the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	--New motor carrier regulations, as well as a streamlining of the  
rule-making process. 
</P>
<P>
	--Improved safety data and information systems, especially  
pertaining to crashes. 
</P>
<P>
	--New motor carrier safety entry requirements because studies  
show that carriers with less than three years' experience have 
higher crash and lower safety compliance rates. 
</P>
<P>
	--New license training and testing programs, including a  
commercial learner's permit and apprentice driving program. 
</P>
<P>
	--Increased truck and bus crash-avoidance initiatives, including  
using devices to avoid collisions with passenger vehicles. 
</P>
<P>
	--Greater attention by management to motor carrier issues,  
including adding ``motor carrier'' to the name of the Federal 
Highway Administration and hiring two top executives to oversee 
motor carrier safety. 
</P>
<P>
	Highway Administrator Ken Wykle, who also attended Wednesday's  
hearing, said he supported the recommendations and Mineta's 
analysis. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, Wykle and Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater  
announced a series of steps aimed at cutting the number of 
truck-related highway deaths in half over the next decade. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997, the year for which the most current statistics are  
available, 5,355 people were killed in accidents involving trucks. 
In many cases, the accidents were caused not by truck drivers, but 
by motorists who cut in front of them, slammed into them or stopped 
in front of them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
