<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Board of Trade Sets Eurex Vote </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- The Chicago Board of Trade leadership has given  
itself four weeks to convince reluctant members of the benefits of 
embracing a fast-growing all-electronic exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	As the world's largest futures exchange struggled to find  
direction against a sea of challengers, its board of directors set 
June 24 as the date that could prove key to its future. On that 
day, members will vote on a broad alliance with Frankfurt-based 
Eurex. 
</P>
<P>
	The exchange on Thursday also announced other measures aimed at  
fending off competition, including slashing fees for large 
customers who want to trade electronically and lobbying federal 
regulators to relax restrictions the CBOT contends hamper growth of 
U.S. exchanges. 
</P>
<P>
	The moves highlight a startling about-face for the Board of  
Trade, which is in danger of losing its No. 1 ranking this year to 
Eurex. In January it chose a go-slow approach by sticking with the 
auction-style trading, known as open outcry, that many call an 
anachronism. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, exchange Chairman David P. Brennan called Eurex  
``the best business alternative'' and urged members to accept the 
alliance, which insiders say is virtually identical to the one they 
rejected nearly six months ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chicago exchange has not revealed details of the pairing,  
but news reports have indicated it involves giving up its 
electronic trading platform, known as Project A, in favor of 
Eurex's electronic platform and cross-trading each other's 
contracts over the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	The Project A platform was a key sticking point in the previous  
failed alliance bid. Smaller traders, called locals, also have been 
reluctant to cede authority to outsiders and abandon a 150-year 
tradition. That intransigence has killed merger hopes with rival 
Chicago Mercantile Exchange several times. 
</P>
<P>
	But large trading firms appear to be gaining the upper hand in a  
power struggle at the Board of Trade. 
</P>
<P>
	Board members recently backed exchange President Thomas Donovan,  
an advocate of speedier change, after Brennan sought to have him 
removed. And the Board of Trade Clearing Corp. voted Wednesday to 
change the way its directors are elected, giving larger firms more 
power in decision-making. 
</P>
<P>
	Such large trading firms have migrated to computer-based  
trading, saying it is easier and cheaper because it saves keeping 
expensive staff at individual exchanges. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our members and customers told us what they want, and the  
board acted quickly and decisively to keep their business,'' 
Donovan said Thursday of the board's actions. 
</P>
<P>
	Many in the industry say U.S. exchanges must adopt electronic  
trading amid stiff competition from overseas exchanges and 
over-the-counter trading. 
</P>
<P>
	Exchanges in London and Paris clung to open outcry, only to find  
much of their business stolen away by Eurex. They now have been 
forced to cut jobs and seek alliances with Eurex to survive. 
</P>
<P>
	Former exchange Chairman Patrick Arbor, who narrowly lost a  
re-election bid in December, had argued the Board of Trade must be 
prepared to end the open outcry system if it wanted to save many of 
the Chicago area's 150,000 futures industry jobs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990527.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 06:05:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jazz May Face Hard-Nosed Battle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- In a series notable for its defense and  
the offending elbows of Karl Malone, the Portland Trail Blazers and 
Utah Jazz may be in for their most hard-nosed battle yet. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think that if we go out there and play a good, solid game  
defensively and rebound, and step up to any physical challenge that 
may occur, we'll win the game,'' Portland's Brian Grant said of 
tonight's Game 6. 
</P>
<P>
	The Blazers lead the best-of-7 Western Conference semifinals  
3-2, but Utah stole the momentum with an impressive 88-71 victory 
Tuesday night in Salt Lake City. The Blazers also lost their cool 
and some blood on the Delta Center court. 
</P>
<P>
	Malone opened up a gash over Grant's right eye in the first  
quarter while Malone was going for a rebound. Grant lay on the 
floor in pain, and came back after getting six stitches. He was 
ineffective, however, scoring eight points on 1-of-7 shooting for 
the game. 
</P>
<P>
	Grant, who didn't talk to the media after the game, said  
Wednesday that the hit was just part of a rough-and-tumble series. 
In fact, the cut represents what Grant wants to learn from Malone 
and the Utah Jazz: how to play with the intensity needed to win the 
biggest of games. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sure he wasn't planning on elbowing me in the eye,'' Grant  
said. ``Even if it was intentional, that's part of the game. Those 
things are going to happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the fourth quarter, with the outcome decided, Grant was  
frustrated after Malone made a swipe at the ball. Grant faked a 
throw at the back of Malone's head, drawing a technical foul. That 
sent Blazers coach Mike Dunleavy into an uncharacteristic rage. 
</P>
<P>
	He stomped onto the court toward an official and, after being  
ejected, had to be restrained by assistant coaches and players. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Grant was in Malone's face, exchanging heated words  
with the future Hall of Famer. Malone said later that Grant had 
told him he disliked him. Malone said the feeling was mutual. 
</P>
<P>
	``We know where each other's coming from, and that's the way it  
is,'' Malone said. ``In the playoffs, you don't have to like me. I 
don't play this game for you to like me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Grant said the substance of the obscenity-laced confrontation  
will stay a secret. 
</P>
<P>
	``This isn't about Brian Grant playing Karl Malone. It's about  
the Trail Blazers trying to win a championship this year,'' Grant 
said. ``I know we're not going to be able to do it with me 
bickering with one player. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't have any ill feelings toward any of the Jazz. If  
anything, I can take a page from their book someday as far as how 
to win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After Game 5, Blazers teammate Isaiah Rider hinted that the team  
might bring a role player off the bench to take out Malone, a 
suggestion quickly shot down by Dunleavy and Grant. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's not my approach,'' Grant said. ``I'm a ballplayer, not  
a wrestler. I'm not a fighter.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Blazers guard Damon Stoudamire said Grant was in a tough spot,  
having to show he won't back down without doing something that 
would get him thrown out of the game, or suspended. 
</P>
<P>
	``He has to focus and do the things he was doing up until this  
point,'' Stoudamire said. ``I don't think the Jazz are going to 
change up their game plan. They're going to come right after him, 
but Brian has to understand that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Malone was fined $10,000 by the NBA for elbowing Grant in the  
mouth in Game 1. As in Tuesday night's game, Malone was not 
whistled for a foul. 
</P>
<P>
	``He does have a problem with his elbows,'' Dunleavy said. ``I  
don't want to make excuses. But if a guy continually hits people 
with elbows and they get cut, what does that tell you?'' 
</P>
<P>
	The rough play in Game 5 overshadowed an otherwise impressive  
performance by the Jazz, who say the pressure is now on the Blazers 
to win on their homecourt to avoid going back to Salt Lake City for 
Game 7. 
</P>
<P>
	``If they say they're not feeling a little pressure, I would say  
they're lying a little bit,'' Malone said. ``Because they're 
supposed to close us out because we're getting old, we can't do 
this, and we're predictable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Jazz are trying to become the seventh team in NBA history to  
come back from a 3-1 deficit. The last to do it was the Miami Heat 
in 1997, against the New York Knicks in the Eastern Conference 
semifinals. 
</P>
<P>
	The Jazz have trailed 3-1 five times in the Malone-John Stockton  
era, and have yet to win a series. 
</P>
<P>
	But Utah is 6-1 the last two seasons when it had to win or go  
home. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're not going to lay down,'' Grant said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
