<DOCNO> APW19990527.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 19:19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Netanyahu Quits Politics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TEL AVIV, Israel (AP) -- Outgoing Prime Minister Benjamin  
Netanyahu, trounced in elections earlier this month, quit politics 
Thursday but left the door open for a comeback. 
</P>
<P>
	Netanyahu had resigned as leader of his Likud party 28 minutes  
after the polls closed on May 17. On Thursday, in an expected 
announcement, he said he would leave parliament as well. 
</P>
<P>
	``I will resign from the Knesset but in no way will I resign  
from the struggle for the future of Israel,'' he told central 
committee members of his Likud party at a gathering in Tel Aviv. 
</P>
<P>
	Likud members waved banners reading ``Bibi, don't quit,'' and  
chanted ``Bibi, we love you,'' referring to Netanyahu by his 
nickname. 
</P>
<P>
	The premier was visibly moved by the outpouring of warmth from  
some 500 Likud members who sang his name for eight minutes after he 
entered the conference hall. ``I thank each and every one of you 
from the bottom of my heart,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``God willing, we will make a comeback,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Netanyahu's aides have said he plans to write a book and hit the  
U.S. lecture circuit. 
</P>
<P>
	Ariel Sharon, the hawkish outgoing foreign minister, was voted  
temporary chairman of Likud until primaries are held later this 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	Sharon's first move in the post was to appoint a committee to  
explore ways to rehabilitate a party electorally crushed and 
alienated from many of its traditional voters. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he would let party members decide whether to join a  
coalition government led by Prime Minister-elect Ehud Barak of the 
dovish Labor party. Labor has said it was giving Likud preferential 
status in coalition-building talks. 
</P>
<P>
	In his first political speech since a stunning election defeat,  
Netanyahu said his greatest achievements were demanding reciprocity 
in peace talks with the Palestinians and weakening Arab negotiating 
demands. Other accomplishments he mentioned included maintaining 
sovereignty over disputed areas of Jerusalem, protecting Jewish 
settlements on disputed territory and lowering inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	``Netanyahu for now has left the stage, but Netanyahu the  
politician will probably be back,'' said Hanan Christal, a 
political commentator for Israel TV. Christal is co-author of a new 
book that claims Netanyahu was suffering deep depression before the 
election and was desperately looking to save his career. 
</P>
<P>
	The book, ``Elections '99'' published in Israel on Thursday,  
alleges Netanyahu had planned to ignore opposition from military 
and security officials and send troops into the PLO headquarters in 
Jerusalem three days before the elections in an effort to win back 
right-wing voters. 
</P>
<P>
	Such a move, involving the sensitive area of disputed Jerusalem,  
would have likely ignited an explosion of violence between Israelis 
and Palestinians. 
</P>
<P>
	A Supreme Court injunction prevented the closure.  
</P>
<P>
	The book, written by Christal and Ilan Kfir, a writer with the  
Maariv newspaper, claimed Netanyahu had planned several actions 
against Palestinian officials and members of the militant Hamas 
movement, including the assassination of Hamas spiritual leader 
Sheik Ahmed Yassin. The book said Shin Bet security chief Ami 
Ayalon torpedoed plans for the kidnapping of his Palestinian 
counterpart, who Netanyahu believed was behind terror attacks 
against Israelis. 
</P>
<P>
	Netanyahu's senior aide David Bar-Illan dismissed the claims and  
said the book, which quotes unnamed sources, was simply the latest 
in an unending string of media attacks against the premier. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
