<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senators Seek Tougher Inspections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republican and Democratic senators want the  
Food and Drug Administration to increase inspections of imported 
foods, which have been blamed for thousands of cases of illness. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, Democratic Sens. Edward Kennedy of Massachusetts,  
Barbara Mikulski of Maryland and Richard Durbin of Illinois 
proposed a requirement that food imported to the United States be 
produced, prepared and packed under conditions that keep it as safe 
as food that is domestically produced. 
</P>
<P>
	The FDA, which has responsibility for the safety of most food  
imports, and the Health and Human Services Department would be 
responsible for determining that countries have such ``equivalent'' 
food safety systems. 
</P>
<P>
	The cost of establishing such systems would be borne by overseas  
producers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Citizens deserve to know that the food they eat is safe and  
wholesome, regardless of its source,'' said Kennedy. 
</P>
<P>
	The Grocery Manufacturers of America immediately criticized the  
proposal as erecting unnecessary barriers to free trade. It said it 
could unfairly halt all imports from a country instead of targeting 
offending companies. 
</P>
<P>
	``Well-intentioned but misdirected proposals like these will do  
little to increase the safety of the food supply,'' said Stacey 
Zawel of the grocery manufacturers. 
</P>
<P>
	Another bill, by Sen. Susan Collins, R-Maine, would also give  
the FDA greater authority to detain or destroy suspect shipments 
and would increase the number of inspectors who check food at U.S. 
borders. 
</P>
<P>
	FDA inspects less than 2 percent of imports. The Agriculture  
Department inspects meat, eggs and poultry and has equivalency 
agreements with those who export those foods to the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Collins hasn't proposed any equivalency requirements for fruits,  
vegetables or other foods under FDA's jurisdiction, saying such 
mandates would be unworkable. The grocery manufacturers said 
Collins' bill is ``headed in the right direction.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Incidents of food-borne illness have gained attention as imports  
have increased. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1996, the United States imported $7.2 billion worth of fruit  
and vegetables from at least 90 different countries, up from the 
1990 level of $4.8 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Total food imports increased from 1.1 million shipments in 1992  
to 2.7 million in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Outbreaks of illness linked to imports include more than 1,000  
people sickened in 1997 by the parasite cyclospora on Guatemalan 
raspberries. That same year, children in five states became ill 
with hepatitis A after eating strawberries from a Mexican farm 
where workers had little access to sanitation. 
</P>
<P>
	The Consumer Federation of America, which supports the  
Democratic bill, said 9,000 people die each year from food 
poisoning, but it didn't say how many of those deaths were 
attributable to imports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
