<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Acting Company Performs 'Tartuffe' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *An AP Entertainment Review    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Acting Company has a strong concept for a  
new take on Moliere's ``Tartuffe,'' but most of the young actors 
don't excel in their roles. 
</P>
<P>
	The play's title character is a religious fraud, who uses his  
charisma to dazzle the character Orgon and hoodwink Orgon into 
giving him the deed to his house and disinheriting his son. 
</P>
<P>
	But director Mark Ax takes the emphasis off clerical greed and  
conniving and places it on the harm to Orgon's family, in the 
production running at the off-Broadway Playhouse at St. Clement's. 
Not only is Orgon's son sent away but Tartuffe gets Orgon to tell 
his daughter she must marry Tartuffe instead of the young man she 
loves. And Tartuffe attempts to rape Orgon's wife. 
</P>
<P>
	The wife puts Orgon under a table to witness his advances, which  
Tartuffe has hinted at. Orgon sits frozen under the table so long 
the attempted rape gets quite far along. 
</P>
<P>
	Ax was assistant director when Garland Wright, who taught  
directing at the Juilliard School, directed ``Tartuffe'' there in 
1998, his final work before he died. A program note states that Ax 
is following Wright's ideas about the play. 
</P>
<P>
	The most effective acting in the cast was by Rayme Cornell as  
Orgon's wife. This graduate of the University of Missouri has an 
inner electricity which makes the stage brighten when she is 
present. Andrew McGinn's Orgon was properly awed by Tartuffe. 
</P>
<P>
	Christopher Jean plays Tartuffe. He needs to show a face of  
religious devotion to Orgon and somehow convey to the audience that 
he's a hypocrite and quite aware of it. At this point in his 
career, Jean is capable only of presenting the former, and this 
lessens the play's humor. 
</P>
<P>
	The Acting Company was formed in 1972 from the first graduating  
class of the Juilliard School's Drama Division. It tours a great 
deal, mainly to smaller cities. The company now is made up of young 
actors from a number of schools. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
