<DOCNO> APW19990527.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 10:44:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Auschwitz Crosses Hassle Continues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OSWIECIM, Poland (AP) -- A conservative Catholic who rallied  
others to erect crosses near the Auschwitz Nazi death camp said 
Thursday he put explosive devices in a hut near the crosses to 
prevent it from being demolished. 
</P>
<P>
	Kazimierz Switon said he mined the wooden hut and the nearby  
tent he has been living in a day after the local municipality 
ordered the hut torn down because it was built illegally. 
</P>
<P>
	The order was issued under a law that took effect Tuesday that  
allows the state to take control of a 100-yard band surrounding 
former Nazi camps throughout Poland. That band includes the 
property where the wooden hut and the 300 crosses are standing. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have to safeguard myself. I don't have any other way,''  
Switon said by cellular telephone from the site. 
</P>
<P>
	The 68-year-old Switon has threatened to set himself on fire if  
a 26-foot wooden cross from a 1979 papal mass at the Birkenau 
extermination camp is removed from the lot next to Auschwitz, as 
demanded by Jewish groups. 
</P>
<P>
	The cross was erected on the lot in 1988 to honor 152 Polish  
Catholics slain there by the Nazis in 1941. 
</P>
<P>
	The Roman Catholic church and the government have called this  
week for the removal of the smaller crosses, but say the papal 
cross should remain. 
</P>
<P>
	Jews say the crosses violate the memory of more than 1 million  
Jews who died in Auschwitz-Birkenau. 
</P>
<P>
	Switon last year urged conservative Catholics to plant the  
smaller crosses next to the papal cross. 
</P>
<P>
	Switon also oversaw construction of the wooden hut, which was  
consecrated as a chapel by a retired priest May 16, without Church 
approval. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
