<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Star Wars' Bootlegs Sold in Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Pirated copies of the ``Star Wars'' prequel --  
with washed out desert scenes and noise from a theater's audience -- 
have hit stores in Asia, after the film opened in the United States 
and before its Asia debut. 
</P>
<P>
	Pirated video CDs of ``Star Wars Episode I: The Phantom Menace''  
are widely available in shopping malls in Hong Kong for between $3 
and $4, a fraction of the cost of movie tickets. In Beijing, street 
vendors were sold out. 
</P>
<P>
	Roadside vendors in Malaysia and at least one store in Jakarta,  
Indonesia, were also selling the discs. 
</P>
<P>
	All copies sold in Hong Kong appeared to be from the same  
source: a home video recorded in a U.S. movie theater. 
</P>
<P>
	Forget about computer-generated special effects, a main selling  
point of the latest ``Star Wars'' installment. The video is dark 
and fuzzy, and the sound quality is poor. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the scenes -- especially those in space -- are almost  
black, while the desert scenes are so bright they appear washed 
out. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is a very bad copy. You can see the back of people's heads  
moving and hear them talking and shouting,'' said Sam Ho, the 
director of the Motion Pictures Association's Hong Kong and Macau 
anti-piracy operation unit. 
</P>
<P>
	As soon as the ``Star Wars'' logo appears on screen and the  
familiar soundtrack begins, the audience in the theater can be 
heard cheering wildly. 
</P>
<P>
	Ben Leung, acting deputy head of Hong Kong Customs Department's  
intellectual property investigation section, said customs officials 
were working with the film's Hong Kong distributor, 20th Century 
Fox, on further action. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokeswoman at 20th Century Fox refused comment.  
</P>
<P>
	The film opens in Asia Friday at a charity event in Singapore.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
