<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> SLOC Picks Torch Relay Coordinator </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- The company that spearheaded the Atlanta  
and Nagano Olympic torch relays and will organize the event in 
Sydney has been selected to orchestrate the torch relay for the 
2002 Winter Olympics in Salt Lake City. 
</P>
<P>
	Negotiations are under way to finalize the deal with ALEM  
International Inc., but the company, based in Boulder, Colo., on 
Thursday agreed in principle to the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	The size and scope of the torch relay for the Salt Lake City  
games will depend on what kind of corporate backing the event can 
rally, said Shelley Thomas, vice president of communication and 
public affairs for the Salt Lake Organizing Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	The torch could travel through as few as five states or,  
theoretically, through all 50, depending on how much financial 
support sponsors are willing to give. A route should be settled on 
by the end of the summer, along with a means of selecting 
torchbearers. In Atlanta, United Way selected ``heroes'' along the 
route to carry the torch. 
</P>
<P>
	``The torch relay is an event that brings the Olympic spirit to  
people across the country and around the world,'' Thomas said. 
``The flame is one of the most recognizable symbols of the Olympic 
Games.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For the 1996 games, ALEM organized an 84-day journey for the  
torch, reaching from Los Angeles to Atlanta, covering 15,000 miles 
and 43 states. Some 12,500 people carried the torch and were 
supported by more than 40 vehicles. 
</P>
<P>
	``The relay becomes this rolling picture postcard of everything  
that's great about the Olympics,'' said Steven McCarthy, president 
and chairman of ALEM. 
</P>
<P>
	The first torch relay took place at the Berlin Olympics in 1936.  
It was inspired by ancient Greek drawings and writings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
