<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sallie Mae Buys New England Firm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Sallie Mae, the nation's largest financer of  
student loans, announced today is buying Nellie Mae Corp., a New 
England student loan maker, for $320 million in cash. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the first major acquisition by Sallie Mae since the  
former government-sponsored company became private two years ago 
amid a bitter battle between management and dissident shareholders, 
who eventually took control. 
</P>
<P>
	Nellie Mae, with offices in Braintree, Mass., and Rumford, R.I.,  
is the seventh-largest holder of federal student loans with a 
portfolio valued at $2.6 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the merger agreement, Nellie Mae will become a subsidiary  
of Reston, Va.-based Sallie Mae and will retain its New England 
operations and regional sales offices across the country. 
</P>
<P>
	As a result of the deal, Sallie Mae will be making more than $1  
billion a year in loans for study at nearly 250 colleges and 
universities by next year, Albert Lord, Sallie Mae's chief 
executive officer and vice chairman, told reporters in a telephone 
conference call. 
</P>
<P>
	``It fits right into our strategy ... of expanding our presence  
on campus,'' said Paul Carey, executive vice president of Sallie 
Mae. 
</P>
<P>
	The merger must be approved by the Justice Department and  
Massachusetts' attorney general. Sallie Mae officials said they 
expect it to be completed by June 30. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are pleased to combine resources with Sallie Mae to  
continue to build the premier full-service education finance 
company,'' Lawrence O'Toole, president and CEO of Nellie Mae, said 
in a statement. He said the combination would enhance Nellie Mae's 
ability ``to serve our campus-based clients, students and family 
borrowers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Officially named the Student Loan Marketing Association, Sallie  
Mae formerly benefitted from its status as a federally sponsored 
enterprise by borrowing at below-market interest rates with 
government guarantees to buy loans from banks. As a fully private 
company it now competes with banks -- its former clients -- by making 
loans directly to students and schools. 
</P>
<P>
	Sallie Mae currently holds and manages $47 billion in student  
loans for more than 5 million borrowers. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of its parent company, SLM Holding Corp., were down 6 1/4  
cents to $41.06 1/4 in early afternoon trading on the New York Stock 
Exchange. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
