<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Strawberry Farmer Union Vote Fails </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALINAS, Calif. (AP) -- The United Farm Workers, struggling to  
regain the clout it had under Cesar Chavez, was dealt a tremendous 
setback when California strawberry pickers voted to join an upstart 
committee that has never negotiated a contract. 
</P>
<P>
	Even though the results are not official and the UFW can still  
force a runoff, the election this week was widely seen as another 
sign of the union's failure to recover from years of decline. 
</P>
<P>
	``The UFW made a lot of mistakes here,'' said John Borrego,  
associate professor of community studies at University of 
California, Santa Cruz, who follows the agricultural labor 
movement. ``This should send them the message that they have to 
change their strategy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	About 1,300 pickers working for Coastal Berry, the nation's  
largest strawberry grower, voted Tuesday and Wednesday, in favor of 
being represented by the Coastal Berry of California Farm Worker 
Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	State labor officials have yet to finalize the 646-577 vote.  
About 60 ballots are in dispute, and another 79 workers voted for a 
third option of no union, meaning that neither the UFW nor the 
novice committee has obtained the majority support necessary for 
victory. 
</P>
<P>
	The UFW cannot win, said the state Agricultural Labor Relations  
Board, though it still could force a runoff if the Farm Worker 
Committee does not receive enough of the remaining votes. 
</P>
<P>
	UFW president Arturo Rodriguez said he was saddened by their  
loss to the upstart union. He blamed interference by antiunion 
growers who feared a victory at Coastal Berry might spread to other 
berry fields. 
</P>
<P>
	``Their organization has nothing to offer, while we have  
demonstrated and proven results,'' he said. ``Clearly there was 
intimidation and coercion here, and we're going to continue our 
fight.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The results were considered pivotal in the UFW's effort to  
recover from the years of decline that came even before the 1993 
death of its legendary founder, Cesar Chavez. 
</P>
<P>
	Under Chavez, 80,000 farmworkers were working under UFW  
contracts by 1970. Union membership had dwindled to 20,000 at the 
time of his death. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1995, the UFW tried to kindle a resurgence in the state's  
$600 million, 20,000 worker strawberry industry. 
</P>
<P>
	But outside observers said the UFW made mistakes, including  
replacing about 10 local organizers with out-of-town professionals, 
and underestimating the tight relationship pickers had with 
growers. 
</P>
<P>
	``There were tremendous accusations when the UFW started  
organizing here that they were acting like bullies and they were 
telling these fiercely independent people that they should turn to 
them for support and give them part of their paycheck,'' said 
Borrego. ``This generation of workers hasn't even heard of Cesar 
Chavez. They don't bring with them a history that unions are 
wonderful things.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The result came as no surprise to Jess Brown, executive director  
of the Santa Cruz County Farm Bureau. He said the worker's choice 
is a sign of the UFW's weakness in the community. 
</P>
<P>
	``The union wasn't able to clearly show that it could do more  
than what the workers presently have or could have,'' he said. 
``The UFW didn't do their research. They thought this was something 
they could easily attain.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Harley Shaiken, an industrial relations professor at  
UC-Berkeley, said the close vote suggests the UFW remains a force 
to be reckoned with in agriculture. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would be easy to say they had the election, the UFW lost,  
end of story. But it's more interesting that under circumstances 
that have been very difficult, the union has come very close to 
victory at a pivotal company,'' Shaiken said. 
</P>
<P>
	Coastal Berry Co. President Ernie Farley, who has repeatedly  
asserted his neutrality, said his company will ``abide by whatever 
representing body the state labor board certifies.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Attorney Jim Gumberg, who represents the Coastal Berry of  
California Farm Worker Committee, said his group has no president 
and is led by a vice president -- Sergio Leal -- who was fired by 
Coastal Berry for alleged misconduct. He said he isn't sure whether 
they have obtained Labor Department recognition as a union, and he 
said none of them has negotiated a contract. 
</P>
<P>
	``Workers weren't voting for our agenda here,'' he said. ``They  
were voting against the UFW with its slick organizers who threaten, 
cajole, intimidate, and have never picked a berry in their lives.'' 
</P>
<P>
	ALRB officials planned to meet Thursday to discuss the  
unresolved ballots, said the board's regional director, Fred 
Capuyan. He would not speculate on how long it would take to 
determine a winner. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
