<HEADLINE> Prodigy To Buy Cable &AMP; Wireless Unit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) -- Prodigy Communications Corp. signed an  
agreement to acquire Cable &AMP; Wireless PLC's U.S. dial-up Internet 
service for $50 million to $75 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Prodigy estimates that it will acquire between 125,000 to  
200,000 consumer, business and campus subscribers, according to 
today's Wall Street Journal. The final price of the deal will 
depend on how many of those subscribers stay with Prodigy. 
</P>
<P>
	Prodigy's current membership is 736,000.  
</P>
<P>
	The acquisition from Cable &AMP; Wireless only covers subscribers  
using standard modems and phone lines to connect to the Internet, 
not high-speed lines, the Journal reported. 
</P>
<P>
	White Plains-based Prodigy, previously a joint venture between  
IBM Corp. and Sears, Roebuck &AMP; Co., is trying to reinvent itself as 
an Internet-access service aimed at consumers and small businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	Cable &AMP; Wireless, based in London, provides Internet, data,  
voice and messaging services. 


</P>
</TEXT>
