<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 1 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Serbs Dismiss War Crimes Indictment  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- A senior Yugoslav official today  
dismissed the indictment of President Slobodan Milosevic on war 
crimes as a political maneuver and said his government does not 
recognize the jurisdiction of the U.N. tribunal in the Netherlands. 
Indictments against Milosevic and four others on war crimes charges 
were announced today in The Hague by the tribunal's chief 
prosecutor, Louise Arbour. The indictments overshadowed continued 
heavy bombing in the 65th day of NATO's air campaign. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Hails Milosevic Indictment  
</P>
<P>
	YULEE, Fla. (AP) -- President Clinton applauded an international  
tribunal's war-crimes indictment today of Yugoslav President 
Slobodan Milosevic but said NATO's objectives are unchanged. ``It 
will reassure the victims of Belgrade's atrocities in Kosovo and it 
will deter future war crimes by establishing that those who give 
the orders will be held accountable,'' the president said in a 
statement issued by the vacation White House. ``The objectives of 
NATO's military effort remain unchanged.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Highway Fatalities Fell in 1998  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Highway fatalities fell again in 1998, with  
alcohol-related traffic deaths hitting an a record low last year, 
according to preliminary figures released by the government today. 
Overall, 41,480 people were killed on the nation's highways in 
1998, down from 42,103 in 1997. Alcohol was involved in 15,936 
traffic fatalities, or 38.4 percent of total highway deaths, as 
opposed to 16,189 fatalities, or 38.6 percent, the year before. It 
is the lowest level since the government began keeping records in 
1975. 

</P>
<P>
	Palestinians Protest in Jerusalem  
</P>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- In the first violent confrontation since the  
Israeli election, club-wielding Israeli police charged into a crowd 
of Palestinian protesters today to keep them away from a Jewish 
neighborhood under construction in disputed east Jerusalem. The 
protesters, among them also Israeli peace activists and Arab 
Israeli lawmakers, rattled the fence ringing the plot owned by 
Irving Moskowitz, a Florida millionaire and benefactor of settler 
groups. A Jerusalem police spokesman said four people were detained 
on suspicion they attacked police officers and were later released. 

</P>
<P>
	Drunken Driver Gets 15-30 Years  
</P>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- A carpenter who predicted he would get a light  
sentence because the two people he killed while driving drunk were 
from another country was sentenced today to 15 to 30 years in 
prison. Nicholas Kurch was convicted this month of vehicular 
homicide and drunken driving in the deaths of Sujan Tuladhar and 
Dr. Alok Chalise, both of Nepal. It was Kurch's fifth conviction 
for driving drunk. He reportedly told a jailhouse informant that 
nobody would care because the victims were foreign. 

</P>
<P>
	Exxon, Mobil Shareholders OK Merger  
</P>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- Shareholders of Exxon and Mobil voted today to  
approve the $82.2 billion merger between the two largest U.S. oil 
companies. More than 99 percent of the shares in Exxon were voted 
in favor of the marriage, as were more than 98 percent of Mobil 
shares. Shareholders of both companies met separately in Dallas. 
Regulators in the United States and Europe must still approve the 
deal before the companies could effect the merger. The 
shareholders' approval had been expected by company officials and 
independent analysts. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Falls 187; Nasdaq Down 10  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 1 p.m. EDT, the Dow industrials were  
down 187.00 points at 10,515.16. Declining issues on the New York 
Stock Exchange led advancers 1,759-970. The Nasdaq was down 10.79 
at 2,416.38. 

</P>
<P>
	Sampras Loses at French Open  
</P>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- Failing yet again to win the one Grand Slam title  
that eludes him, Pete Sampras lost in the second round in the 
French Open today to 100th-ranked Andrei Medvedev, 7-5, 1-6, 6-4, 
6-3. The result was eerily similar to Sampras' loss last year at 
Roland Garros, when he fell to the 97th-ranked player, Ramon 
Delgado of Paraguay. In other action today, Jennifer Capriati 
advanced to the third round over fellow American Lilia Osterloh. 

</P>
<P>
	IRL Reducing Speeds for Texas Race  
</P>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Taking another step to improve safety  
following a crash that killed three fans, the Indy Racing League 
announced today it will reduce speeds for the June 12 race at Texas 
Motor Speedway. Leo Mehl, the IRL's executive director, said 
engines will be required to operate at no more than 10,000 rpms 
after Sunday's Indy 500. The new specifications, which reduce the 
cars' horsepower, will be used for the remaining seven IRL events, 
beginning with the Longhorn 500. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAVID GOODMAN  
</P>
