<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Penguins: Arena Lease Is a Loan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- The Pittsburgh Penguins plan to argue Friday  
in bankruptcy court that an onerous lease blamed for the team's 
financial troubles is in large part a loan that is nearly paid off. 
</P>
<P>
	Separately, former Penguins star center and NHL Hall of Famer  
Mario Lemieux's plan to save the team from dissolution calls for 
paying leaseholder SMG $15 million to buy out the agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	But, if the Penguins' prevail in their argument that most of the  
lease is really an almost-satisfied loan, the value of the lease 
would drop considerably, perhaps relieving Lemieux of having to 
make that payment. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is huge,'' said Lemieux's attorney, Doug Campbell.  
</P>
<P>
	When Howard Baldwin bought the team in 1991, SMG provided $24  
million toward the purchase price. As a result, the team pays an 
estimated $6 million to $7 million per year to SMG, payments 
Penguins officials say helped drive the team into bankruptcy and 
are preventing a financial recovery. 
</P>
<P>
	While the deal was drawn up as a lease through 2012, it was  
actually a loan, Penguins' attorney Robert G. Sable said. He 
calculated that the unpaid balance is under $3 million, assuming a 
9 percent interest rate on the loan. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday Sable filed a motion asking U.S. Bankruptcy Judge  
Bernard Markovitz to terminate the lease. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need to reject the lease because a plan won't work with  
this lease in place,'' Sable said. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge scheduled an emergency hearing on the motion for  
Friday, the same time as the initial hearing on a rival takeover 
plan submitted by SMG and Fox Sports Net Pittsburgh and on the 
National Hockey League's proposal to dissolve or move the Penguins. 
</P>
<P>
	SMG President Wes Westley dismissed the Penguins' motion as  
``another legal maneuver.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Greg Cribbs, the team's vice president of legal affairs, said  
rejecting the lease would put all of the takeover plans on even 
footing because all will require a new arena lease. 
</P>
<P>
	``Both the judge and the NHL have identified the lease as the  
key to the case and the key to saving the Penguins for 
Pittsburgh,'' Cribbs said. 
</P>
<P>
	Westley has disputed that the lease is responsible for the  
team's financial woes, citing rising player salaries and cash 
withdrawals by the team's co-owners as more important factors. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux on Tuesday submitted a revised plan, reducing the amount  
of money he claimed he was owed by the team by $5 million, to $27.5 
million. He said he would convert $20 million of that into equity 
in the team and forgive the remaining $7.5 million. 
</P>
<P>
	He also proposed raising $65 million in new capital from other  
investors, up from $50 million in his initial plan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
