<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Euro Hits New Low Against Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The euro dropped to a new low against the dollar  
Thursday, but recovered slightly after European central bankers 
expressed support for the struggling new currency. 
</P>
<P>
	In late New York trading, the euro was quoted at $1.0420, down  
from $1.0455 Wednesday. Earlier in Europe, it fell to $1.0409, down 
more than 10 percent from where the euro started in January when it 
replaced the currencies of 11 nations in the European Union. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro has stumbled in recent weeks amid concerns about the  
soundness of the European Union and slowing economic growth in the 
region. 
</P>
<P>
	Those worries were exacerbated this week by an EU decision to  
allow Italy to increase its budget deficit. Many fear that other 
European nations will soon let their budget deficits increase. 
</P>
<P>
	But the jitters eased somewhat on Thursday after Bank of France  
governor Jean-Claude Trichet said that he expected ``a very big 
potential for appreciation'' in the euro in the near future. 
</P>
<P>
	Adding to his remarks were bullish comments from Otmar Issing,  
chief economist of the European Central Bank, and Hans Tietmeyer, 
president of the Deutsche Bundesbank and governing council member 
of the European Central Bank. 
</P>
<P>
	``The national central bank officials that form the EU are  
content that the decline in the euro is due to temporary factors 
and the euro will strengthen on a long-term basis,'' said David 
Gilmore, partner at Foreign Exchange Analytics in Essex, Conn. 
</P>
<P>
	In other trading Thursday, the dollar fell to 120.38 yen from  
122.17 yen after a top Japanese official was quoted as saying that 
Japan's financial crisis had come to an end. 
</P>
<P>
	In an article in the Asian Wall Street Journal, Japanese vice  
finance minister for international affairs Eisuke Sakakibara said 
Japan's financial ``crisis that started in November of 1997 ended 
in the first quarter of 1999.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He did, however, also say that there was uncertainty over when  
and how strongly the Japanese economy will recover. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Wednesday, the dollar also was quoted at 1.5238 Swiss  
francs, up from 1.5229; and 1.4751 Canadian dollars, up from 
1.4720. The British pound rose to $1.5990 from $1.5954. 
</P>
<P>
	The currencies of the 11 countries that have switched to the  
euro are no longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a 
fixed rate. 
</P>
<P>
	Based on the euro's latest exchange rate, the dollar was worth:  
1.8769 German marks, up from 1.8706; 6.2933 French francs, up from 
6.2735; and 1,858.74 Italian lire, up from 1,851.85. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
