<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton's Vacation During Wartime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	YULEE, Fla. (AP) -- It's vacation during wartime: Kosovo keeps  
intruding on President Clinton's fun in the sun. 
</P>
<P>
	When he's not on the links, bicycling with the first lady or  
touring the wildlife preserve on White Oak Plantation, he's on the 
phone with world leaders or donning jacket and tie to speak to 
reporters about events in Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	But there's been plenty of down time.  
</P>
<P>
	``Having a good time?'' Clinton asked reporters as he ventured  
outside the edge of the plantation for the first time Thursday to 
address the U.N. Yugoslav war crimes tribunal's decision to indict 
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic. 
</P>
<P>
	Someone turned the question back on him. ``Oh yeah. We need  
it,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	After a brief statement praising the tribunal's work, he climbed  
back into his bronze Chevrolet Suburban and rode back to the 
compound for a round of golf. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton's day included phone calls to French President Jacques  
Chirac, British Prime Minister Tony Blair and Czech President 
Vaclav Havel. He talked with Chirac and Blair about the NATO 
mission, but the call to Havel was more personal -- Clinton wanted 
to check on Havel's recovery after a hospital stay. 
</P>
<P>
	White House press secretary Joe Lockhart said Clinton has been  
playing with the golf pros who work at White Oak, mainly a group of 
25- to 30-year-olds the president described as ``excellent 
teachers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``He said the round yesterday was one long lesson,'' Lockhart  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Other than golf, Clinton roamed the 7,500-acre preserve and saw  
zebras, rhinos and a baby giraffe. Lockhart said the president came 
away saying he saw more animals than he had last year on a safari 
in Botswana. 
</P>
</TEXT>
