<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Stocks Sharply Lower / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stock prices fell sharply in morning  
trading Friday in line with a plunge on Wall Street. The dollar 
dropped against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average lost 207.21 points,  
or 1.28 percent, to finish the morning session at 15,969.98. On 
Thursday, the Nikkei index shed 53.33 points, or 0.33 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 120.64 yen, down 1.79 yen from late Thursday  
in Tokyo but above its late New York level of 120.38 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, investors worried about a possible slowdown  
in the U.S. economy following Thursday's plunge in New York stock 
prices. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average sank 235.23  
points to 10,466.93, its worst single-session decline of the year 
and its lowest level since April 20. 
</P>
<P>
	Another negative factor affecting the Tokyo market was a sharp  
decline in near-term June Nikkei futures prices on the Chicago 
Mercantile Exchange, also Thursday, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hideyuki Okoshi, deputy manager at Chuo Securities, said the  
Nikkei 225 was likely, however, to find support between 15,700 and 
15,900 points. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices were lower almost across the board, with the fishery,  
precision and marine transportation sectors leading the decline. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors were also discouraged by a stronger yen against the  
dollar. A higher yen makes Japanese exports more expensive abroad 
and thus less competitive, cutting into earnings at export-led 
Japanese companies. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was down 12.53 points, or 0.96 percent, to 1,289.64 
points. The TOPIX closed down 1.15 points, or 0.09 percent, 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar's relative strength in Tokyo  
from its New York levels came after institutional investors bought 
dollars on dips. 
</P>
<P>
	The greenback tumbled to a low of 119.70 yen in New York -- the  
first time it broke through the 120-yen mark since May 3 -- as 
market players took cues from the selloff in the Dow Jones 
industrial average. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 125.82 yen, down  
from 127.58 yen late Thursday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond rose  
to 1.5650 percent from 1.4950 percent late Thursday, driving its 
price down to 98.57 yen from 99.17 yen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
