<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Sets Aside Part of Gun Suit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A federal judge today approved a jury's decision  
to order gun makers to pay $500,000 to a shooting victim who won a 
landmark lawsuit against the industry. 
</P>
<P>
	But Judge Jack Weinstein dismissed the cases against gun makers  
brought by the other six plaintiffs because the jury -- despite 
finding liability -- failed to award any damages. 
</P>
<P>
	Like some lawsuits against Big Tobacco, this one accused the gun  
industry of negligently marketing a legal product. The case was 
closely watched by several cities trying to recover the costs of 
gun violence. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit was filed in 1995 by Steven Fox, 19, who was  
accidentally shot in the head by a friend who bought a gun on the 
street, and the relatives of six homicide victims. 
</P>
<P>
	After a monthlong trial, a jury in February found several gun  
manufacturers responsible, but the only damages they awarded were 
$500,000 from three gun makers to Fox and his mother. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
