<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Two Charged in Dragging Incident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KINGSTREE, S.C (AP) -- Two white men were jailed on charges they  
grabbed a black man by the arm and dragged him as they drove down 
the road in a pickup truck. 
</P>
<P>
	Charone Green, 23, suffered leg and arm injuries but was not  
seriously hurt, the Sheriff's Department said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sheriff Kelvin Washington asked the FBI and the state to  
investigate whether the crime was racially motivated. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have no indication at this point that it is,'' he said.  
``There is a possibility that it may be drug-related.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Eric W. Jones, 38, and Arthur Marshall, 34, were charged with  
assault and battery with intent to kill. Marshall was also charged 
with possession of a stolen vehicle -- the pickup. 
</P>
<P>
	Last June, a black man was chained to a pickup and dragged to  
death in Jasper, Texas. Three white men were charged with murder. 
One has been convicted and sentenced to death. The others are 
awaiting trial. 
</P>
<P>
	The South Carolina incident occurred in rural Bloomingvale,  
about 90 miles east of Columbia, an area of tobacco fields and farm 
buildings with rusted tin roofs. 
</P>
<P>
	Green told investigators he was standing at the end of a  
driveway early Wednesday when two men pulled up. He said the 
passenger grabbed his arm, and the truck drove off, dragging him a 
quarter-mile. Green told investigators he bit the man holding him 
and the man let go. 
</P>
<P>
	Green, who lives with his grandmother, could not be located for  
comment Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	A cousin, Shirley Brunson, said that she saw the incident and  
that Green was released as the truck struck a culvert at the end of 
the road. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought they had killed the boy,'' she said.  
</P>
<P>
	Green's grandmother, Mary Green, said: ``I can't say whether  
it's a racial thing or not.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1995, a black church in nearby Greeleyville was burned down.  
Four former Ku Klux Klansmen were sent to prison for that crime and 
the burning of another black church in a neighboring county. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
