<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 12:12:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Philly Tries To Help Troubled Youth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- The mayor is assembling a team of police,  
social workers, clergy and other mentors to work intensively with 
92 young people considered extremely likely to kill or be killed. 
</P>
<P>
	The Youth Violence Reduction Project is modeled on a successful  
program in Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	It is scheduled to begin in Philadelphia's crime-ridden  
Kensington and Port Richmond neighborhoods, and will expand if it 
works well. 
</P>
<P>
	The 92 people, including eight women and girls, were identified  
from criminal records and school violence reports. Ninety percent 
of the group had arrest records for attempted murder, armed robbery 
or drug dealing. 
</P>
<P>
	The intervention team will steer the 92 youths to job training,  
counselors and social services and also warn them they will be 
dealt with harshly if they return to violence. 
</P>
<P>
	A similar program in Boston is credited with driving the number  
of murders down 77 percent, from 152 in 1990 to 35 in 1998. In a 
nearly 2 1/2-year period ending in January 1998, not one Boston 
teen-ager was shot to death. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
