</P>
<P>
 *Former Lutheran bishop resigns    	
</P>
<P>
	ROCKFORD, Ill. (AP) -- Ronald Hasley, a retired bishop in the  
Evangelical Lutheran Church in America has resigned from the 
denomination's clergy roster. 
</P>
<P>
	The resignation came a week after Hasley was stripped of his  
duties amid allegations of sexual misconduct, church officials 
said. Four women claimed Hasley engaged in improper sexual conduct 
while he was a bishop, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hasley, a bishop from 1987 to 1998, signed an agreement in April  
indicating his behavior at the Rockford-based Northern Illinois 
Synod constituted sexual harassment, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hasley had been a mentor for new bishops and provided other  
part-time pastoral services during his retirement. In the written 
statement, he is quoted as saying he is sorry and hopes that the 
disclosure ``will begin a healing process.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
 *'Family' guru prepares succession    	
</P>
<P>
	COLORADO SPRINGS, Colo. (AP) -- James Dobson of the influential  
``Focus on the Family'' multimedia ministry announced a plan for 
succession in his monthly letter sent to 2.5 million supporters. 
</P>
<P>
	The conservative Protestant leader, who is 63, started his daily  
radio program in 1977. He said he hopes to continue working for at 
least another decade, declaring himself in good health following a 
minor heart attack in 1990 and a mild stroke last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the plan, his duties would be split between a chief  
executive, hired from the business world, and a public spokesman. 
The latter is to be chosen within three years and would work as 
Dobson's understudy on the radio. 
</P>
</TEXT>
