<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sydney Olympic Tickets On Sale Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Tickets go on sale in Australia Sunday  
for the 2000 Summer Games and organizers should know quickly if the 
Olympic bribery scandal has dampened public interest. 
</P>
<P>
	Fans will have 48 days to return order forms for 5 million of  
9.6 million tickets to be sold for the games. 
</P>
<P>
	Full payments must accompany all orders.  
</P>
<P>
	Sandy Hollway, chief executive of the Sydney Organizing  
Committee for the Olympic Games, hinted this month that less than 
50 percent of the local tickets would be sold by the time the 
initial offer ends July 16. 
</P>
<P>
	But popular events such as the opening and closing ceremonies,  
swimming finals and some track, gymnastics and basketball sessions 
are expected to attract more demand that supply, with a random 
ballot used to decide who gets tickets. 
</P>
<P>
	Sydney organizers hope the ticket sales will help fill an almost  
$100 million budget hole blamed in part on the fallout from the 
corruption scandal surrounding Salt Lake City's successful bid for 
the 2002 Winter Games. 
</P>
<P>
	A survey released this week by Roy Morgan Research found that 66  
percent of Australians surveyed in March said they were interested 
in the games, down from 68 per cent in December 1998, when the Salt 
Lake City scandal broke. It was the lowest level of interest 
recorded by the survey in a year. 
</P>
<P>
	General interest in attending any event dropped 3 per cent, to  
41 per cent, in the same three-month period, the survey said. 
</P>
<P>
	One International Olympic Committee remains under investigation,  
and it happens to be an Australian -- Phil Coles, a SOCOG board 
member and key player in the city's winning bid. 
</P>
<P>
	And IOC panel meets in Lausanne, Switzerland, on Monday to  
consider the latest details in the case against Coles, who is 
accused of abusing his position and helping Salt Lake bidders. 
</P>
<P>
	Applicants will be limited to four tickets for the ceremonies  
and six for other premium sessions. 
</P>
<P>
	SOCOG will write to all applicants by early September, informing  
them whether they have been successful in getting the tickets they 
want. If not they will be given the chance to purchase others. 
</P>
<P>
	Games organizers have been buoyed by a better-than-expected  
response to international sales, and say they will offer more of 
the premium tickets overseas if they are not taken up by 
Australians. 
</P>
<P>
	``For most sessions, people will simply order tickets through  
official Olympic Games ticket books and automatically get their 
seats because we have so many tickets,'' SOCOG ticketing 
communications manager John O'Neill said. 
</P>
<P>
	He called the ticket plan ``a very fair system'' but warned that  
leftovers ``won't necessarily just be on offer to the Australian 
market.'' 
</P>
<P>
	SOCOG has not detailed what methods will be used to sell the  
remaining tickets. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices range from $12.35 at sports such as rowing and baseball  
to $900 for the best seats at the opening and closing ceremonies. 
Seventy percent of all tickets will cost less than $39 and SOCOG 
aims to make $390 million from sales. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990527.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 06:02:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Deal Made by Norwegian Oil Companies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OSLO, Norway (AP) -- The Norwegian state oil company Statoil on  
Thursday agreed to step aside so Norsk Hydro ASA could continue a 
takeover bid for Norway's third oil company, Saga Petroleum. 
</P>
<P>
	In exchange, Statoil, which owns about 20 percent of Saga, will  
accept access to parts of Saga's petroleum reserves on the 
Norwegian continental shelf in exchange for its shares. Statoil 
also will buy an additional 5 percent of Saga's assets. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal would avert a bidding war between Statoil and Norsk  
Hydro, which is 51 percent state-owned, over the smaller, 
economically troubled Saga. 
</P>
<P>
	On May 10, Norsk Hydro announced a 17 billion kroner ($2.18  
billion) bid for Saga, offering one of its own shares for every 
three Saga shares on the condition that 90 percent of the smaller 
company's shareholders accepted the offer. 
</P>
<P>
	With its 20 percent interest, Statoil had been in a position to  
block the takeover. Norsk Hydro, with interests in petroleum, light 
metals and fertilizers, has set a deadline of the end of June for 
shareholders to accept its bid. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, Saga reported that its operating profit dropped to  
378 million kroner ($48.5 million) in the first four months of the 
year from 618 million kroner ($79.2 million) million during the 
same period a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Saga said it had a net loss of 179 million kroner ($22.3  
million) for the first four months of 1999, compared with a profit 
of 280 million kroner ($35.9 million) a year earlier, mainly 
because of higher production costs. 
</P>
<P>
	Norsk Hydro, the largest company listed on the Oslo Stock  
Exchange, employs about 40,000 people worldwide. Saga has a staff 
of about 4,000. The larger company said it expected to cut about 
800 jobs if the takeover goes through. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990527.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 19:19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Lawmakers Hear Diverse Gun Views </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Two parents whose children were slain by  
classmates gave lawmakers diverse views Thursday on whether the 
slayers, guns or lawmakers themselves are to blame for their 
tragedies. 
</P>
<P>
	Darrell Scott of Littleton, Colo., told the House Judiciary  
Committee's subcommittee that he blames the April 20 death of his 
daughter, Rachel Joy Scott, 17, on Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are people behind those instruments of death,'' Scott  
told the panel. ``I do believe Eric and Dylan bear primary 
responsibility for my daughter's death, not the guns themselves.'' 
.
</P>
<P>
	But Byrl Phillips-Taylor of Richmond, Va., placed the blamed an  
AK47 for her son's 1989 death at the hands of a ``classmate with a 
grudge.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The easy availability of guns got my baby killed,''  
Phillips-Taylor told the panel, urging lawmakers to pass the 
mandatory background checks for gun show transactions and other new 
firearms restrictions voted by the Senate last week. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Senate has demonstrated that it cares about keeping guns  
away from children,'' she said. ``And that may be the turning point 
that every mother like me has been waiting for.'' 
</P>
<P>
	House Republican leaders this week said they support the concept  
of the gun restrictions passed by the Senate, but they rejected 
demands from Democrats to quickly rubber-stamp the measures. 
</P>
<P>
	Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde, who has co-authored gun  
control bills in the past, said careful consideration of the 
legislation next month would ensure that new controls would not 
infringe on the Second Amendment right to bear arms. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans at Thursday's hearing criticized the Clinton  
administration as failing to prosecute violators of existing 
firearms laws while pushing for more gun restrictions. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Bob Barr, R-Ga., suggested that if the Ten Commandments had  
been posted at high schools where the shooting occurred, ``we would 
not have had the tragedies that bring us here today.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Replied Deputy Attorney General Eric Holder Jr.: ``If the young  
people and adult criminals who committed these crimes had a tougher 
time getting their hands on guns, these horrible crimes might have 
been prevented.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Vice President Al Gore, who broke a 50-50 Senate tie last week  
in favor of the new gun show restrictions, returned to the Capitol 
Thursday to accuse House Republicans of trying to please the 
National Rifle Association. 
</P>
<P>
	``At this very moment, there are some of the other side meeting  
behind closed doors plotting to have more delays in order to 
preserve loopholes'' in firearms law, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	NRA Executive Vice President Wayne LaPierre told the House  
subcommittee Thursday that the Senate bill was a ``red tape 
nightmare.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Basically it would extend the reaches of the federal  
government into the homes of this country,'' LaPierre said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the NRA supports mandatory gun show background checks  
and other concepts in the Senate bill, but not as written. For 
example, he said, the Senate would ``your uncle's skeet-shooting 
range'' as a gun show subject to government regulations. 
</P>
<P>
	Scott, testifying at the request of committee Republicans,  
supported LaPierre's complaint that some gun control advocates were 
seeking to put the blame for the shootings at the NRA's doorstep. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't believe that they are responsible for my daughter's  
death,'' said Scott, who said he was not a member of the group and 
does not own a gun. 
</P>
<P>
	Scott also scolded lawmakers about their eagerness to pass more  
laws despite the cultural causes behind school shootings. 
``Political posturing and restrictive legislation are not the 
answers,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990527.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 19:19:29 </DATE_TIME>
