<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Names Foreign Aid Plan Head </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	YULEE, Fla. (AP) -- President Clinton announced Thursday that he  
would nominate J. Brady Anderson to head the U.S. Agency for 
International Development, which manages foreign aid programs. 
</P>
<P>
	Anderson, a lawyer from Charleston, S.C., was U.S. ambassador to  
Tanzania from 1994 to 1997. He succeeds J. Brian Atwood, who held 
the post for the past six years. 
</P>
<P>
	Prior to joining the diplomatic corps, Anderson lived in Kenya,  
Ethiopia and Tanzania researching African languages. He speaks 
Swahili. 
</P>
<P>
	A Vietnam veteran, Anderson worked as an Arkansas assistant  
attorney general, an adviser to then Governor Clinton and a senior 
law clerk to a federal judge in Little Rock, Ark. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, Atwood withdrew his nomination to become ambassador  
to Brazil, saying opposition by Sen. Jesse Helms ruled out the 
possibility of Senate confirmation. 
</P>
<P>
	Atwood said Helms, R-N.C., who chairs the Senate Foreign  
Relations Committee, opposed the nomination because of his 
successful campaign to defeat the senator's proposal to merge USAID 
into the State Department. 
</P>
<P>
	When he leaves his USAID post, Atwood will remain in charge of  
coordinating the president's humanitarian relief program for 
Kosovo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990527.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 04:22:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Four Guards Charged in Inmate Death </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	UNIONDALE, N.Y. (AP) -- Four prison guards have been charged in  
the beating death of an inmate who allegedly angered them by 
repeatedly crying out for his methadone treatment. 
</P>
<P>
	The guards pleaded innocent Wednesday in the death of Thomas  
Pizzuto, who died six days after entering the Nassau County jail to 
serve three months for a traffic violation. 
</P>
<P>
	Pizzuto, 38, a recovering heroin addict, had a seizure three  
days after the alleged beating and died. 
</P>
<P>
	All four guards were released on $500,000 bond. Lawyers for the  
men said they would be cleared. 
</P>
<P>
	Ivano Bavaro, along with fellow jail guards Edward Velazquez and  
Patrick Regnier, were charged with two counts of federal civil 
rights violations. The charges carry a maximum sentence of life in 
prison. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the indictment, Bavaro served as lookout when  
Velazquez and Regnier went to the inmate's cell and beat him 
repeatedly on Pizzuto's second day in custody. 
</P>
<P>
	After the alleged Jan. 8 beating, Pizzuto was left in his jail  
cell over the weekend to let his injuries heal, his family claimed. 
</P>
<P>
	A fourth guard, Joseph Bergen, was charged as an accessory after  
the fact for allegedly doctoring a report of the death to claim 
Pizzuto suffered his injuries in a shower room fall. The maximum 
sentence is 15 years in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	All four officers remain on modified duty at the jail pending  
trial. Their weapons were taken away, and they are permitted no 
contact with inmates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990527.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 16:01:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> White Sands' Horses Leave for S.D. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WHITE SANDS MISSILE RANGE, N.M. (AP) -- With the thunder of  
hooves, among the last of the White Sands wild horses clamored into 
aluminum trailers today, bound for South Dakota. 
</P>
<P>
	The trip ends a saga of a herd once numbering 1,800 horses that  
had roamed free long before the ranchland became an Army weapons 
range in the 1940s. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm really happy to do this so the horses have a home,'' said  
rancher Alan Amiotte, who is taking the horses to his ranch of 
10,000 acres outside Rapid City. 
</P>
<P>
	Ever since 122 horses died during a drought five years ago in  
southern New Mexico, the military and an animal protection group 
have been trying to find the horses new homes. 
</P>
<P>
	Adoptions whittled the population down to about 80 horses this  
spring. Last month, 35 horses were taken to Amiotte's ranch and on 
Thursday, 26 studs, seven mares and two foals were carted off. Some 
were so skinny their ribs could be counted. 
</P>
<P>
	As many as 10 horses remain on the 3,000-square-mile desert  
range. If any mares are found -- there are believed to be three or 
less -- they too will be sent to South Dakota, which is 21 hours 
away by truck. Any studs will live out their lives at White Sands. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a happy ending for these horses,'' said Karen Sussman,  
whose Scottsdale, Ariz.-based International Society for the 
Protection of Mustangs and Burros helped with the move. 
</P>
<P>
	The animals are among an estimated 20,000 wild horses roaming  
free in Nevada, California, Oregon, Idaho, Montana, Wyoming, Utah, 
Arizona, Colorado and New Mexico, Sussman said. 
</P>
<P>
	On the South Dakota ranch, the horses will retain their freedom  
in ranchland with knee-high green grass, rolling hills, towering 
pine trees and an abundance of fresh water. 
</P>
<P>
	``These horses are going to heaven, and I mean heaven,'' Sussman  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Although fear for their survival was what prompted the rescue  
effort, there was another reason for hastening their departure. 
</P>
<P>
	Because water is scarce in the desert conditions, the horses  
would tear up the banks of the few watering holes, dumping sediment 
into the water and potentially harming the White Sands pupfish, a 
species on the state's endangered list, said Patrick Morrow, a 
White Sands wildlife biologist. 
</P>
<P>
	``The environment doesn't have the ability to support the  
animals,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	White Sands Missile Range officials were relieved, if a little  
heavy-hearted, over the horses' departure. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm glad that we came up with a solution and the horses have  
found a place to go that will keep them together,'' spokesman Larry 
Furrow said. ``But as most people on the range, I'm a little sad to 
see them go.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
