<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 11:10 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Infinity Buying Outdoor Systems  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Infinity Broadcasting, the radio arm of CBS, is  
buying the nation's largest outdoor advertising company Outdoor 
Systems for $6.5 billion in stock, the companies announced today. 
The deal, which had been rumored for more than a week, makes 
Infinity the largest outdoor advertising company in the United 
States and gives CBS a wider array of options to offer advertisers. 
CBS has been moving toward selling packages of advertising across 
its media outlets, which include network TV, radio and Internet 
sites. Outdoor Systems has some 110,000 outdoor advertising spaces 
such as billboards in major markets throughout the United States, 
Canada and Mexico. Infinity is also assuming $1.8 billion in debt 
in the deal. Infinity shares were down 1 3/16 at 24 13/16, and 
Outdoor Systems was down 9/16 at 28 1/4. 

</P>
<P>
	Exxon, Mobil To Vote on Merger  
</P>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- Shareholders of Exxon and Mobil are voting today  
on a proposal to merge the oil giants in a $82.2 billion deal that 
would create the world's biggest company. Analysts expect 
shareholders to approve the deal. The deal is expected to lead to 
the loss of about 9,000 jobs -- 7 percent of the companies' 
worldwide work force. The combined company would be called Exxon 
Mobil Corp. and have headquarters in Irving, Exxon's current home. 
Mobil is based in Fairfax, Va. The merger is still awaiting 
approval from U.S. and European antitrust regulators, which the 
companies expect could be completed by the fall. Exxon stock was 
down 1 11/16 this morning at 80 1/4, and Mobil was down 2 at 101 1/16. 

</P>
<P>
	GDP Grows at 4.1 Pct. Annual Rate  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The U.S. economy, powered by the biggest boom  
in consumer spending in more than a decade, grew at a robust annual 
rate of 4.1 percent in the first three months of the year, the 
government said today. The Commerce Department said the increase in 
the gross domestic product occurred despite the fact that America's 
trade deficit from January through March was even worse than 
originally believed. The government said that corporate profits 
showed a big rebound in the first three months of this year, 
increasing at an annual rate of $31.8 billion. An inflation gauge 
tied to the GDP rose just 1.1 percent, only slightly faster than 
the modest 0.9 percent gain in the fourth quarter. 

</P>
<P>
	Unemployment Claims Unchanged  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Labor Department said today the number of  
Americans filing new claims for unemployment benefits was unchanged 
last week at 300,000. New claims have been at or below the 
300,000-person market for 12 of the last 21 weeks, a sign of the 
best job market conditions in three decades. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks Open Lower; Dow Down 141.89  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks opened lower as continued concerns about  
interest rates and inflation put the brakes on yesterday's rally 
that lifted the Dow industrials 171.07 points. Continued fears that 
inflation will prompt the Federal Reserve to raise interest rates 
drew investors away from stocks today. Just before 11 a.m. EDT, the 
Dow was down 141.89 at 10,560.27. On the NYSE, decliners led 
advancers 1,549-817. The Nasdaq was down 8.21 at 2418.96. 

</P>
