<P>
	Gucci Wins Court Battle With LVMH  
</P>
<P>
	AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) -- A Dutch court ruled today in favor  
of Italian fashion house Gucci and against the French company LVMH 
Moet Hennessy Louis Vuitton which is waging a hostile takeover 
battle for Gucci. The Amsterdam District Court rejected a demand by 
LVMH that Gucci's strategic alliance with French retailer 
Pinault-Printemps-Redoute be annulled. It also rejected LVMH's call 
for an investigation into Gucci's management. LVMH made an offer 
for Gucci in March but asked the court in a lawsuit filed in April 
to overturn measures taken by Gucci to avoid the bid, including 
issuing new shares to PPR. 

</P>
<P>
	Coca-Cola Steps Up Diversity Efforts  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Facing a racial discrimination lawsuit, Coca-Cola  
Co. has appointed its senior black executive to help step up 
efforts to diversify the staff at all levels. Carl Ware, senior 
vice president of the company's Africa Group, was named to co-chair 
the newly created Diversity Advisory Council. In an e-mail memo to 
all domestic employees, chairman M. Douglas Ivester he said he 
plans also to hold periodic meetings in the months ahead with small 
groups of employees to ``open the lines of communication.'' One 
former and three current black salaried employees sued Coca-Cola 
last month, claiming that the company discriminated against black 
employees in pay, promotions, performance evaluations and 
terminations. They are seeking class-action status. 

</P>
<P>
	Mitsubishi Posts Modest Profit  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Mitsubishi Motors Corp. posted a modest profit last  
year in contrast to a loss a year earlier, as cost cutting and a 
gain on the sale of a manufacturing facility contributed to the 
turnaround. The company earned 5.67 billion yen, or $46 million, 
for the fiscal year ended March 31 versus a loss of 101.85 billion 
in fiscal 1997. Sales fell 6 percent to 3.51 trillion yen, or 
$28.67 billion, from 3.74 trillion yen a year ago. Mitsubishi 
expects profit to fall to 2 billion yen on sales of 3.52 trillion 
yen this fiscal year which ends in March 2000. Exports are expected 
to drop because of falling shipments to Latin America and the 
Middle East, the company said. 

</P>
<P>
	Prodigy To Buy Cable &AMP; Wireless Unit  
</P>
<P>
	WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) -- Prodigy Communications Corp. signed an  
agreement to acquire Cable &AMP; Wireless PLC's U.S. dial-up Internet 
service for $50 million to $75 million. Prodigy estimates that it 
will acquire between 125,000 to 200,000 consumer, business and 
campus subscribers, according to today's Wall Street Journal. The 
final price of the deal will depend on how many of those 
subscribers stay with Prodigy. Prodigy's current membership is 
736,000. The acquisition from Cable &AMP; Wireless only covers 
subscribers using standard modems and phone lines to connect to the 
Internet, not high-speed lines. Prodigy shares were up 1 1/2 at 24 1/2, 
and Cable and Wireless was down 1 5/16 at 36 13/16. 

</P>
