<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Arresting Milosevic Is the Hard Part  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- After indicting President Slobodan Milosevic  
today, the Yugoslav war crimes tribunal still needs someone to 
arrest him, no small task. The tribunal indicted Milosevic and four 
other top officials on charges of crimes against humanity in the 
brutal expulsion of 750,000 ethnic Albanians from Kosovo. The 
tribunal has no police powers, meaning it is entirely dependent on 
the international community to arrest indicted war criminals. Both 
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and British Foreign Secretary 
Robin Cook were asked about the possibility of Milosevic's 
apprehension, but neither offered hope. 

</P>
<P>
	Reno Faults Aides on China Inaction  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Attorney General Janet Reno faulted  
subordinates today for not coming to her two years ago with their 
disagreement over whether to wiretap a nuclear weapons scientist 
suspected of spying for China. ``I was not briefed on the 
details,'' Reno said. National Security Adviser Samuel Berger also 
defended himself against accusations he wasn't aggressive enough 
when Energy Department officials briefed him in 1996 about security 
lapses at a weapons laboratory. ``I did take it seriously. I did 
act,'' Berger said on PBS' ``NewsHour With Jim Lehrer.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Poll: Clinton Help May Hurt Gore  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A CNN/USA Today/Gallup poll released today  
indicates the public, by a 52-to-29 percent margin, says President 
Clinton's active help in Vice President Al Gore's campaign for 
president would make them less likely to vote for Gore for 
president. Gore has a 2-to-1 lead in the poll among Democrats and 
those leaning Democratic against former New Jersey Sen. Bill 
Bradley. But four out of 10 of all respondents say there is no 
chance they would vote for Gore. 

</P>
<P>
	McCain Discusses Education, Taxes  
</P>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- Sen. John McCain, a Republican presidential  
candidate who jump-started his presidential campaign with a hawkish 
stance on Kosovo, broadened his political agenda today with 
campaign initiatives on Social Security, education and tax reform. 
McCain urged Republicans to resist using Social Security revenues 
to balance the budget. On education, McCain said Republicans should 
recognize the ``urgent necessity'' to raise teacher pay. He also 
said he would end the tax penalty for married people and reduce the 
inheritance tax. 

</P>
<P>
	Hectic Hurricane Season Predicted  
</P>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Federal officials predicted a busier-than-usual  
Atlantic hurricane season today and urged people in hurricane-prone 
areas to think about how they will handle the storms. This is the 
first time the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration has 
issued a preseason forecast. It calls for three or more intense 
hurricanes -- two is normal. Forecasters expect more hurricanes this 
year in part because of La Nina, which brings cooler-than-normal 
temperatures to the Pacific Ocean off South America. 

</P>
<P>
	Louisiana Mulls Internet Voting  
</P>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- Louisiana Republicans, planning to leap ahead  
of Iowa and New Hampshire with next year's first presidential 
preference vote, are also considering a leap technologically -- 
Internet balloting. State party executive director Becky Miller 
said Thursday that the party's executive committee is likely to 
vote June 12 on whether to use an Internet voting system in a party 
primary election that could be held Jan. 29. Details have not been 
worked out but a company called VoteHere.net is working on a 
proposal. 

</P>
<P>
	Original U.S. Flag To Be Restored  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Starting tomorrow, the public will be able to  
watch restoration efforts on the original ``Star-Spangled Banner.'' 
Removed from public display six months ago, the flag is now 
partially rolled out in a specially built laboratory for a 
three-year, $18.2 million restoration. Visitors to the Smithsonian 
Institution's National Museum of American History will file past a 
50-foot floor-to-ceiling glass wall. Behind it, technicians with 
microscopes and needles are busy picking out an estimated 1.7 
million stitches that attached the flag to a linen backing in 1914. 

</P>
<P>
	Japanese Stocks Open Sharply Lower  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stock prices fell sharply in early trading  
Friday in line with a plunge on Wall Street. The Nikkei shed 269.25 
to 15,907.94 in the first 30 minutes of trading. On Wall Street 
Thursday, the Dow Jones industrial average sank 235.23 points to 
10,466.93, its worst single-session decline of the year and its 
lowest level since April 20. 

</P>
<P>
	Clemens Leads Yanks Past Ex-Mates  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Roger Clemens, wearing the hated Yankees  
pinstripes for the first time against his former team, allowed two 
hits in seven innings to beat Boston 4-1 tonight and win his 19th 
consecutive decision. Clemens (4-00 has not lost in 29 starts, 
dating to last May 29. The winning streak is the longest ever in 
the AL. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by GABRIEL MADWAY  
</P>
