<DOCNO> APW19990527.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 13:01:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Teen Abortion Bill Debated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Eileen Roberts said she didn't find out about  
her daughter's abortion until the 14-year-old became depressed and 
needed hospitalization and $27,000 in additional medical care, 
including corrective surgery. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, Mrs. Roberts urged a House Judiciary panel to help  
make it a crime for a nonparent to transport an underage girl out 
of state for an abortion if doing so would violate parental 
involvement laws in the child's home state. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am here today to ask this committee to reject the eccentric  
notion that any adult stranger has the right to abduct our 
minor-aged daughters and take them to another state for a secret 
abortion,'' said Mrs. Roberts of Fredericksburg, Va., whose 
daughter was driven 45 miles from her home for an abortion. 
Virginia requires that the parents of underaged girls seeking 
abortions be notified. 
</P>
<P>
	But Billie Lominick of Newbury, S.C., opposed the bill. She said  
she would be in jail if such a law had been in effect for helping 
her grandson's girlfriend -- who had been abused by her parents -- 
get to Georgia for an abortion this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``Please don't pass this law,'' said Mrs. Lominick, whose home  
state also requires parental consent before an abortion can be 
performed on a minor. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Charles Canady, R-Fla., chairman of the House Judiciary's  
constitution subcommittee, said the measure would uphold parental 
consent or notification laws in the more than 30 states that have 
enacted them. 
</P>
<P>
	Supporters say the bill -- which died in the Senate last year  
after passing the House -- also would protect vulnerable girls from 
being spirited away for abortions by the self-serving, older men 
who get them pregnant 
</P>
<P>
	Canady said it was appropriate for Congress, with its powers to  
regulate interstate commerce, to enact such legislation. ``The 
safety of young girls and the rights of parents demand no less,'' 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Maxine Waters, D-Calif., criticized the proposal as a  
``thinly veiled attempt to chip away at a constitutionally 
protected rights.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``This bill is unnecessary,'' she said.  
</P>
<P>
	Abortion rights groups also oppose the bill, arguing that it  
would endanger the health of young girls, similar to those in Mrs. 
Lominick's case, who fear involving their parents in the decision 
to terminate an unplanned pregnancy. 
</P>
<P>
	Penalties in the bill would not apply if the abortion was  
necessary to save the girl's life, and parents may sue the 
individuals who take their daughters away. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, the White House and many Democrats opposed the bill --  
which is identical to the version considered Thursday -- and sought 
changes that, among other things, would exempt close family members 
from criminal and civil liability. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990527.0101 </DOCNO>
