<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 07:32:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mitsubishi Posts Modest Profit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Mitsubishi Motors Corp. posted a modest profit last  
year in contrast to a loss a year earlier, as cost cutting and a 
gain on the sale of a manufacturing facility contributed to the 
turnaround. 
</P>
<P>
	The improvement also reflected a return to profitability at  
subsidiaries in the United States, Europe and Thailand. 
</P>
<P>
	But in a sign that business conditions overall are still bleak,  
the company skipped its year-end dividend payment for the second 
straight year and said it expects a smaller profit this year on a 
slight sales increase. 
</P>
<P>
	The company earned 5.67 billion yen, or $46 million, for the  
fiscal year ended March 31 versus a loss of 101.85 billion in 
fiscal 1997 when auto demand slumped in Japan and other 
recession-stricken Asian nations. 
</P>
<P>
	Mitsubishi said earnings were boosted by the sale of a Tokyo  
truck-transmission plant but did not say how much. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales fell 6 percent to 3.51 trillion yen, or $28.67 billion,  
from 3.74 trillion yen a year ago amid a continued slump in auto 
demand at home and in Asia. 
</P>
<P>
	Mitsubishi expects profit to fall to 2 billion yen on sales of  
3.52 trillion yen this fiscal year which ends in March 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Exports are expected to drop because of falling shipments to  
Latin America and the Middle East, the company said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990527.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 19:19:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Democrats Want Investigation of GOP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Democrats want the Justice Department and  
Congress to investigate whether House Republican leaders are 
violating campaign finance laws with a planned $25 million fund for 
key House races next year. 
</P>
<P>
	Advisers to the House's third-ranking Republican, Majority Whip  
Tom DeLay of Texas, created the Republican Majority Issues Campaign 
to raise and spend that much in two dozen races in 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	House Speaker Dennis Hastert of Illinois, Majority Leader Dick  
Armey of Texas and the No. 4 Republican, Oklahoma's J.C. Watts, 
chairman of the Republican Conference, also are raising money for 
the effort. 
</P>
<P>
	Campaign finance watchdog groups criticized the fund-raising  
strategy on a variety of fronts -- not the least of which is 
organizers' decision to keep their donor list secret. 
</P>
<P>
	``For members of Congress to set up an invisible slush fund to  
collect $25 million to influence the 2000 elections raises all 
sorts of questions,'' Larry Makinson, executive director of the 
Center for Responsive Politics, said today. ``Who's giving the 
money? What promises are being made, either explicit or 
understood?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Also Thursday, the chairman and top Democrat on the House ethics  
committee took the unusual step of releasing a letter saying the 
panel had not approved the GOP leaders' campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Approval from the ethics committee ``was never sought and, thus,  
never granted,'' wrote the chairman, Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas, and 
Rep. Howard Berman, D-Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	The campaign's organizer, Karl Gallant, said his fund meets all  
federal election laws and simply mirrors get-out-the-vote and issue 
advocacy campaigns by organized labor. 
</P>
<P>
	He contended the fund's activities do not have to be disclosed  
because it will operate independently and will not explicitly 
advocate for or against individual candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	``It absolutely amazes me that Big Labor can go out and mobilize  
liberal votes ... but suddenly conservatives don't have First 
Amendment rights,'' he said Thursday, adding that his ``grudging 
admiration'' for the AFL-CIO's advocacy campaign prompted him to 
emulate that effort. 
</P>
<P>
	Gallant said he will not disclose contributors' names because it  
would put the campaign at a ``strategic disadvantage'' to unions. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1996, the AFL-CIO contributed $35 million in an unsuccessful  
effort to help Democrats retake control of the House. Union leaders 
are pledging more than $40 million for television ads and 
mobilizing voters next year. 
</P>
<P>
	One request for an investigation came in a letter this week to  
Attorney General Janet Reno from Robert Bauer, an attorney for the 
Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	The Justice Department declined comment Thursday.  
</P>
<P>
	DeLay's congressional aides referred questions to Gallant, who  
previously headed DeLay's leadership political action committee. 
Armey's office declined comment, as did Watts'. Hastert's spokesman 
could not be reached immediately. 
</P>
<P>
	Meantime, the top Democrat on the House Government Reform  
Committee asked the panel's chairman, Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind., to 
include the GOP fund raising in the committee's current 
investigation of Democratic fund-raising abuses from the 1996 
election. 
</P>
<P>
	A committee spokesman, Mark Corallo, said the letter from Rep.  
Henry Waxman, D-Calif., has not been received. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990527.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 12:32:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rik Smits Won't Get Needed Rest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Rik Smits could use some rest for his aching  
size 21 feet. The Indiana center knows he won't be getting much 
going against Patrick Ewing as the Pacers and New York Knicks clash 
in the Eastern Conference finals. 
</P>
<P>
	The big toe on his left foot, which was fractured during  
Indiana's first-round sweep of Milwaukee, has complicated matters 
for Smits. 
</P>
<P>
	``My broken toe is giving me a lot of trouble,'' Smits said  
Thursday after the team practiced at Market Square Arena. 
</P>
<P>
	Indiana hasn't played since it completed its sweep of  
Philadelphia in the second round Sunday, providing a one-week break 
before Game 1 in the conference finals at Market Square Arena. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was hoping the days off would help it, but I don't really  
feel that it has,'' said Smits, who is averaging 11.1 points in the 
playoffs after averaging a career-low 14.9 points in the season. 
</P>
<P>
	Smits averaged 14.7 points as Indiana won the season series with  
the Knicks 2-1, including a 94-71 rout in their last game here on 
May 2. Ewing was the top scorer for New York with a 22.7 average, 
and Smits thinks the rest the Knicks have had since completing 
their sweep of Atlanta on Monday will benefit the New York veteran. 
</P>
<P>
	The two centers have had several big battles in their careers,  
which include four previous playoff series since 1993. The Knicks 
won the first two playoff series and Indiana has won the last two. 
</P>
<P>
	The 7-foot-4 Smits has been doing much of his scoring in the  
playoffs from the perimeter. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel my weakness now is back to the basket, pivoting.  
Recovery time is not as good as it used to be. Jumping ability is 
pretty much gone, not that I had much to begin with,'' he said. 
``It will probably be the summer before (the feet) start feeling 
better.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Smits was a major reason the Pacers took Chicago to seven games  
in last year's conference finals, averaging 16.3 points on 55 
percent shooting from the field. He set a franchise playoff record 
by hitting 11-of-12 shots from the field in Game 6. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pacers' center has had his share of success against New  
York. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is usually because they had single coverage on me and I got  
a chance to do some stuff in the low post,'' he said. ``This season 
they would keep a forward on me and keep Ewing down low. Sometimes 
they had Larry Johnson on me and that gave me a big height 
advantage.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ewing, who has been hobbled by Achilles' tendinitis and sore  
knees, isn't the only Knick that concerns Smits. His backup, Chris 
Dudley, led the Knicks in rebounding against Atlanta and had 14 
points, 12 rebounds and two blocked shots in Game 3 of the series. 
</P>
<P>
	Dudley's preformance in that game, a 90-77 victory, allowed  
Ewing to sit out the entire fourth quarter. Ewing then scored 17 
points and grabbed a team-high nine rebounds as New York ended the 
series with a 79-66 win to complete its sweep. 
</P>
<P>
	``Dudley, the last two games has been real active offensively,''  
Smits said. ``It used to be he was just a banger, a rebounder who 
works hard all the time. You really didn't have to worry too much 
about him on offense. Patrick is much more offensive minded.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
