<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinians Protest in Jerusalem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- In the first violent confrontation since the  
Israeli election, club-wielding Israeli police charged into a crowd 
of Palestinian protesters today to keep them away from a Jewish 
neighborhood under construction in disputed east Jerusalem. 
</P>
<P>
	The protesters, among them also Israeli peace activists and Arab  
Israeli lawmakers, rattled the fence ringing the four-acre plot 
owned by Irving Moskowitz, a Florida millionaire and benefactor of 
Jewish settler groups. 
</P>
<P>
	Police, some on horseback, pushed and shoved protesters and beat  
a bodyguard for Faisal Husseini, the top PLO official in Jerusalem. 
Husseini also was slightly injured in the scuffle. 
</P>
<P>
	Jerusalem police spokesman Shmuel Ben-Ruby said four people,  
including two journalists, were detained on suspicion they attacked 
police officers. They were later released. 
</P>
<P>
	The disputed site is in Ras al-Amud, a neighborhood of 11,000  
Palestinians in east Jerusalem, the sector captured by Israel from 
Jordan in the 1967 Mideast war and claimed by the Palestinians as a 
future capital. 
</P>
<P>
	Moskowitz hopes to build 132 homes for Jews on his plot.  
Construction began last week, a day after Prime Minister Benjamin 
Netanyahu was trounced in general elections by opposition leader 
Ehud Barak. Netanyahu, apparently concerned about widespread 
Palestinian riots, had held up construction on security grounds. 
</P>
<P>
	Husseini said the building by Jerusalem settlers violates  
U.S.-brokered peace agreements. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a unilateral act,'' a hoarse Husseini said after being  
shoved by policemen. ``Those people are trying to make a new 
reality, to make it impossible to reach any kind of peace 
agreement.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Ras al-Amud dispute will become one of the first tests of  
Barak's new government, said Israeli Arab lawmaker Hashem Mahmeed, 
who joined the demonstration. 
</P>
<P>
	``Barak should make his stance felt about what happened here and  
about the settlement attempts on this piece of Palestinian land,'' 
Mahmeed said. 
</P>
<P>
	A senior aide to Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat demanded that  
Barak halt the Ras al-Amud project and construction in the larger 
Har Homa neighborhood in east Jerusalem when he takes power. In Har 
Homa, known in Arabic as Jabal Abu Ghneim, 6,500 apartments for 
Jews are to be built. 
</P>
<P>
	The Palestinian Authority demands the ``immediate cessation of  
all settlement activity launched by the previous government and the 
return of all lands grabbed for settlement,'' said the aide, Tayeb 
Abdel Rahim, the secretary general of the Palestinian Authority. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
