<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Russian PM Says He's in Charge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Prime Minister Sergei Stepashin began his first  
Cabinet meeting today by trying to squelch speculation he is not in 
charge. 
</P>
<P>
	Stepashin, who was confirmed just last week, already is  
embroiled in a growing political row over who is running the 
government. His deputy, First Deputy Prime Minister Nikolai 
Aksyonenko, created an uproar earlier by suggesting he would 
oversee all government policy. 
</P>
<P>
	Looking grim, Stepashin attempted to assert his authority  
Thursday, saying that ministers should stick to their specific 
areas of responsibility. 
</P>
<P>
	``In order to avoid various sorts of talk of who is the boss in  
the government, I state that its chairman (the prime minister) 
leads the government, and he is responsible for all that happens 
with the government,'' Stepashin said in his opening remarks, some 
of which were broadcast on national television. 
</P>
<P>
	It was not a promising start for a government facing the huge  
task of reviving an economy battered by years of depression. 
Stepashin was made premier after the abrupt dismissal earlier this 
month of Yevgeny Primakov. 
</P>
<P>
	The new government has yet to voice any clear policies, and  
Stepashin appears to be under the firm control of President Boris 
Yeltsin, who can remove him at any time. 
</P>
<P>
	Stepashin also told the ministers that Cabinet meetings would be  
strictly controlled, with set amounts of time for reports and 
questions. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have no time to sit for four, five hours,'' Stepashin said.  
</P>
<P>
	Stepashin's control of the government was questioned after  
numerous Russian press reports said Aksyonenko was attempting to 
assert direct control over all policy. 
</P>
<P>
	Aksyonenko fueled the speculation, telling the Echo of Moscow  
radio station Wednesday that he would oversee the Cabinet's work in 
``all fields.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Aksyonenko, whose candidacy was reportedly backed by  
controversial business tycoon Boris Berezovsky and Yeltsin's 
family, has insisted he will have control over all economic policy. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest intrigue looked like the handiwork of the president,  
who often pits his ministers against each other to keep them in 
check. On Wednesday, he snubbed Stepashin's choice for the other 
first deputy prime minister spot, naming former Finance Minister 
Mikhail Zadornov to the post. 
</P>
<P>
	Yeltsin's spokesman Dmitry Yakushkin denied Thursday that there  
was any conflict over formation of the government, saying it was 
difficult to put together the right combination of people. 
</P>
<P>
	Confusion continued over the appointment of the finance  
minister. The Kremlin initially reported that Zadornov would retain 
the post, but Yeltsin then appointed Mikhail Kasyanov as finance 
minister. There were unconfirmed reports Wednesday that Yeltsin had 
decided to reinstate Zadornov. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Zadornov and Yakushkin refused to clarify the situation  
Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
