<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Balances Golf, Milosevic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	YULEE, Fla. (AP) -- President Clinton ventured to the edge of his  
vacation retreat Thursday, coming out on a dirt road to speak about 
the indictment of Slobodan Milosevic. Then he went right back to 
his house in the midst of a vast nature preserve. 
</P>
<P>
	Midway through his second day on vacation, Clinton put on a  
yellow-patterned tie, a blue blazer and khakis, hopped in a bronze 
Chevy Suburban and made the short trip down an unpaved road to a 
guard shack posted at the entrance of White Oak Plantation. 
</P>
<P>
	He'd come to say for television cameras what he had already said  
on paper: that he was pleased with a war crime tribunal's 
indictment of the Yugoslav president. 
</P>
<P>
	``Having a good time?'' Clinton asked reporters as he approached  
a hastily erected lectern beside the guard shack. Someone turned 
the question on him, asking if he and the first lady were enjoying 
their time together. 
</P>
<P>
	``Oh yeah. We need it,'' Clinton said.  
</P>
<P>
	It was the only answer Clinton offered Thursday. He didn't  
respond to questions on Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, he rode back up the road to his vacation cottage -- if a  
two-story, five-bedroom house with cedar paneling can qualify as a 
cottage. 
</P>
<P>
	White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said the Clintons had kept  
busy and were not ``anxious to get out and travel around.'' They've 
been cooking their own dinners rather than eat in White Oak's 
dining rooms. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's quite a nice complex, and I think they're enjoying  
themselves and relaxing,'' Lockhart said. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton's day Thursday included making phone calls to French  
President Jacques Chirac, British Prime Minister Tony Blair and 
Czech President Vaclav Havel. He talked with Chirac and Blair about 
the NATO mission, but the call to Havel was more personal; Clinton 
wanted to check up on Havel's recovery after a hospital stay. 
</P>
<P>
	After his brief appearance, Clinton was going golfing. Lockhart  
said Clinton has been playing with the golf pros who work at White 
Oak, mainly a bunch of 25- to 30-year-olds who Clinton described as 
``excellent teachers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``He said the round yesterday was one long lesson,'' Lockhart  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Other than golf, Clinton roamed the 7,500-acre preserve and saw  
zebras, rhinos and a baby giraffe. Lockhart said Clinton came away 
saying he saw more animals than he had last year on safari in 
Botswana. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
