<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Attitude Led Atwater to Jets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. (AP) -- Safety Steve Atwater feels that the New  
York Jets' decision to sign him after he was released by Denver in 
March had as much to do with his performance off the field as on 
it. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the situation in Denver, when Denver released me, I  
didn't show any bitterness toward them,'' Atwater said during the 
Jets' veterans minicamp Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``That may have showed (Bill Parcells) that I'm a mature guy,  
not a guy that lets that stuff bother me. I know a lot of people 
maybe would have handled it differently. I handled it the way I 
honestly felt.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Of course, Atwater's talent didn't hurt, either. Parcells, in  
desperate need of a free safety, quickly snatched up the 10-year 
veteran for three years and $7.2 million, including a $2.8 million 
signing bonus, to anchor a defensive backfield that also includes 
Pro Bowl cornerback Aaron Glenn and hard-hitting strong safety 
Victor Green. 
</P>
<P>
	That Atwater, 32, was jettisoned by the Broncos as being a step  
too slow and a bit too expensive didn't bother Parcells much. In 
the Jets' 23-10 loss at Denver in January's AFC title game, the 
6-3, 217-pound safety forced a key fourth-quarter fumble with an 
open-field tackle of receiver Alex Van Dyke, effectively ending a 
comeback attempt by Parcells' club. 
</P>
<P>
	``Believe me, if I didn't have full confidence that he was able  
to do what we're asking him to do, he wouldn't be here,'' Parcells 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Atwater finished last season fourth among Broncos in  
regular-season tackles (85), earning his eighth Pro Bowl selection. 
Among Denver players, only now-retired quarterback John Elway, with 
nine, had more. 
</P>
<P>
	``My driving force right now is to play at a level that I feel  
comfortable playing at,'' said Atwater, who has almost 1,300 career 
tackles. ``I don't think I've reached that level the past two or 
three years. Sure, I've been to the Pro Bowl two of the last three 
years, but that's not what I base my performance on. I know that I 
can get to that point.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Denver's decision to cut him, which came on the heels of a  
frustrating season that saw him sometimes replaced on passing 
downs, is a motivating factor. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't want to prove the Broncos wrong,'' he said. ``I want  
to show everybody that I can still do it like I did it two or three 
years ago.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The veteran, who has undergone seven surgeries, including five  
on his shoulders, in recent years, still has his supporters around 
the league. 
</P>
<P>
	``My first thought, when the Jets signed him, was that obviously  
the Jets are truly trying to make their Super Bowl run this year,'' 
said Les Steckel, the Broncos tight ends coach in 1993 and '94 and 
now offensive coordinator for the Tennessee Titans. ``He's the 
biggest, fastest, hardest-hitting safety I can think of.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Added Jets linebacker Bryan Cox: ``Nobody's going to be catching  
the ball over the middle against us anymore. Those plays are 
gone.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
