<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 13 Named National Heritage Fellows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Folk artists ranging from a Haitian drummer in  
Brooklyn to a Ukrainian weaver in New Jersey are among 13 National 
Heritage fellows for 1999 selected by the National Endowment for 
the Arts. 
</P>
<P>
	They are ``outstanding artists ... who have dedicated their  
lives to preserving, reviving and celebrating this country's living 
cultural heritage,'' said NEA Chairman Bill Ivey. The awards were 
to be presented on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Drummer Frisner Augustin promotes Haitian music throughout the  
hemisphere with a group called ``La Troupe Makandal.'' He has 
taught at Columbia University and New York University, toured 
extensively and made four commercial recordings. 
</P>
<P>
	Another kind of drummer is Zakir Hussain. His specialty is the  
tabla drum of northern India, an expertise learned from his father. 
At 7, he began a career that has spanned four decades and several 
continents to his home in San Anselmo, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	Elliott Mannette of Morgantown, W.Va., works in the steel drum  
tradition and has been called ``the father of the modern steel 
band.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Weaving Ukrainian textiles is the specialty of Eudokia  
Sorochaniuk, whose family fled the Soviet Union during World War 
II. She now lives in Pennsauken, N. J., where she makes costumes 
for her husband's music and dance group. She has also visited 
Ukraine to help teach the skills she conserved. 
</P>
<P>
	Alfredo Campos of Federal Way, Wash., brought his craft from the  
family ranch in Arizona, creating horse gear from rawhide and 
braiding lariats and making quirts, reins and other equipment. He 
also makes special tools for Boeing jet planes. 
</P>
<P>
	Lila Greengrass Blackdeer makes baskets, moccasins and other  
traditional native American items in Black River Falls, Wis., while 
Mary Louise Defender Wilson of Shields, N.D., maintains the 
tradition of the Standing Rock Sioux with stories that embody their 
system of beliefs and behavior. Ulysses Goode of the Western Monos 
in North Fork, Calif., weaves baskets and teaches the art. 
</P>
<P>
	Music is also represented by Mick Moloney of Philadelphia, a  
singer and string player -- mandolin, mandola, bouzouki and guitar -- 
who has made his career in Irish music, by African-American gospel 
singer Shirley Caesar of Durham, N.C., and by Ozark Mountain 
fiddler Bob Holt of Ava, Mo., who has been performing for half a 
century. 
</P>
<P>
	Jimmy Godbolt of Hanson, Mass., tap-danced for Duke Ellington  
and Count Basie. He won a Tony nomination for his work in the 1989 
musical ``Black and Blue.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ralph W. Stanley comes from a long line of Maine boat builders,  
creating and restoring wooden boats, from lobstering vessels to 
racing sloops. He lives in Southwest Harbor. 
</P>
<P>
	Each fellow gets a $10,000 award and will be honored in a White  
House ceremony. Since 1982 the NEA has made 224 such awards. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990527.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 06:50:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Keeps Up Pressure With Strikes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO warplanes pounded more targets  
in Belgrade and throughout Yugoslavia early today while reports 
surfaced that the Yugoslav president has been indicted on war 
crimes charges. 
</P>
<P>
	Planes roared over Belgrade, and the rattle of heavy  
anti-aircraft fire resounded in the capital soon after air raid 
sirens sounded. Powerful explosions were heard in the city's New 
Belgrade area and the southern district of Rakovica, where thick, 
black smoke was seen rising from an engine factory. 
</P>
<P>
	The private Studio B television said 53 missiles hit Belgrade  
and the surrounding area overnight in one of the fiercest NATO 
attacks on the capital since the bombing started March 24. 
</P>
<P>
	In all, NATO said it flew a record 741 sorties on Day 64 of its  
air campaign, including 308 strike sorties and 74 others designed 
to suppress Serbian air defenses. 
</P>
<P>
	The 19-country alliance said the strikes hit a wide range of  
targets, including artillery and armor in Kosovo and strategic 
targets across Serbia. 
</P>
<P>
	The state-run Tanjug news agency said NATO struck a ministry  
building in New Belgrade that coordinates imports and exports of 
weapons, but the missiles did not explode. 
</P>
<P>
	Local media reported that two children and a woman were killed  
and several people were injured in Ralja, 18 miles south of 
Belgrade, when a missile struck residential buildings. Tanjug said 
three people were killed and two injured when NATO bombed two 
villages in the Kosovska Vitina area southeast of Pristina, 
Kosovo's provincial capital. 
</P>
<P>
	The reports could not be independently confirmed.  
</P>
<P>
	Serbian media also said a series of ``exceptionally strong  
explosions'' echoed early today from the direction of the Batajnica 
military airport, northwest of Belgrade. 
</P>
<P>
	Also reportedly targeted early today were an industrial zone in  
Nis, Yugoslavia's third-largest city, a communication tower near 
Novi Sad in the north of the country and a hill near Belgrade where 
an underground military complex is believed to be located. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Netherlands, the international war crimes tribunal based  
scheduled a press conference today to make an ``important 
announcement.'' U.S. officials in Washington, speaking on condition 
of anonymity, said an indictment against Yugoslav President 
Slobodan Milosevic had been issued by the U.N. court, accusing him 
of atrocities in the Balkans. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's another way of squeezing him and actively trying to stop  
him,'' a diplomatic source, speaking on condition of anonymity, 
told The Associated Press at NATO headquarters in Brussels, 
Belgium. 
</P>
<P>
	China and Russia both have expressed concern that a possible  
indictment would harm the search for a political solution for 
Kosovo, a province in Serbia, the main republic in Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	Russian special envoy Viktor Chernomyrdin delayed his return to  
Yugoslavia after marathon talks Wednesday and today with U.S. and 
European representatives. 
</P>
<P>
	Chernomyrdin was to hold a final meeting in Moscow with Deputy  
Secretary of State Strobe Talbott and Finnish President Martti 
Ahtisaari before departing later today. It was not clear whether he 
would be carrying any major new proposals to Milosevic. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia wants a political solution to the Kosovo crisis, but has  
made little progress. Russia also is pushing for an immediate pause 
in NATO airstrikes to give breathing room to diplomatic efforts. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Yugoslav capital, Foreign Minister Zivadin Jovanovic told  
a key U.N. envoy that his country continued to reject the 
deployment of foreign troops in Kosovo, state-run television 
reported. 
</P>
<P>
	He told Undersecretary-General Sergio Vieira de Mello, who has  
been heading a U.N. fact-finding tour, that the United Nations 
should take firm measures to halt NATO ``aggression'' and create 
``conditions for a political solution in Kosovo.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Milosevic repeatedly has rejected the key element of a  
U.S.-backed peace plan for Kosovo -- the deployment of as many as 
50,000 NATO-led troops to secure the safe return of hundreds of 
thousands Kosovo Albanian refugees who have fled his crackdown. 
</P>
<P>
	U.N. aid officials said today the latest surge of refugees  
fleeing to Macedonia from Kosovo had suddenly slowed to a trickle. 
Only about 60 ethnic Albanians crossed the border Wednesday after 
6,000 to 8,000 arrived daily during the previous four days. 
</P>
<P>
	The border crossing was quiet this morning.  
</P>
<P>
	Residents reached by phone in Pristina said buses that had been  
carrying people to the border stopped running Wednesday. It was not 
known why. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 840,000 people, mostly ethnic Albanians, have fled  
Kosovo since March. Before the allied campaign began, Kosovo had a 
population of about 2 million, of which 90 percent were ethnic 
Albanians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
