<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Two Charged in Dragging Incident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KINGSTREE, S.C (AP) -- Two white men are charged with dragging a  
black man beside their pickup truck for a quarter-mile, and federal 
authorities have been asked to examine whether it was a bias crime. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, investigators and even the victim's family are not sure  
the incident early Wednesday -- which did not result in serious 
injuries -- was racially motivated. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have no indication at this point that it is,'' said  
Williamsburg County Sheriff Kelvin Washington, who asked the FBI 
and State Law Enforcement Division to look into whether the 
victim's civil rights were violated. ``There is a possibility that 
it may be drug related.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Eric W. Jones, 38, of Gastonia, N.C., and Arthur Marshall, 34,  
of Georgetown were to be formally charged today with assault and 
battery with intent to kill. Marshall also was charged with 
possession of a stolen vehicle. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities said Charone Green was grabbed and dragged when he  
approached a pickup truck that had slowed in front of his cousin's 
house on a rural road in the Bloomingvale community, about 90 miles 
east of Columbia. 
</P>
<P>
	Green, 23, told investigators he was standing at the end of a  
driveway when two men pulled up in a red pickup truck and told him 
to come over. He said the passenger grabbed his arm and the truck 
drove off, Chief Deputy Dwight Williams said. 
</P>
<P>
	A cousin who witnessed it said Green broke free when the truck  
hit a culvert. 
</P>
<P>
	Green's grandmother, Mary Green, said last June's dragging death  
of a black man in Texas was the first thing that popped in her mind 
she heard what happened. One man has been convicted of murder and 
sentenced to death in that case, while trials are pending for two 
more. 
</P>
<P>
	But she said she wasn't sure the attack on her grandson was  
similarly motivated. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't say whether it's a racial thing or not,'' she said.  
</P>
<P>
	Investigators were unsure who was driving the truck that was  
reported stolen from Lexington County, near Columbia. It was found 
with flattened tires and a shattered windshield, its radio missing, 
Washington said. 
</P>
<P>
	The suspects were arrested at a home near Andrews, where  
Marshall has relatives. Washington wouldn't say what led 
investigators to them. 
</P>
<P>
	Green, who lives with his grandmother, could not be located for  
comment and did not return calls Thursday. A sheriff's report said 
his right leg, ankle and arm were injured. He was treated at a 
hospital and released. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
