<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Fear Backlash on Spy Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- With headlines in bold black, red and blue  
characters, Chinese newspapers stacked at Chinatown newsstands on 
Wednesday filled their front pages with the allegations China stole 
U.S. weapons secrets. Their editorials asked skeptically: Where's 
the evidence? 
</P>
<P>
	Many Chinese-Americans feared the coverage of the congressional  
report on Chinese espionage would fuel a backlash against them. But 
some recent immigrants admitted they haven't followed the story, 
too busy in the daily scramble to earn a living in their new 
country. 
</P>
<P>
	``This spy issue, it's only something we might think about after  
we're done working, eating our dinner and drinking our tea,'' 
electrician Wang Pian said, amid the clacking of retirees stirring 
mahjong tiles on nearby picnic tables in Chinatown's Columbus Park. 
</P>
<P>
	The espionage report released Tuesday is just the latest in a  
series of U.S.-China irritations that has included this month's 
accidental bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Yugoslavia as well as 
allegations that China illegally provided money to the Democratic 
Party fundraisers. 
</P>
<P>
	At least two U.S.-printed Chinese newspapers paired their  
front-page espionage stories with reports about China's dismissal 
of the allegations as ``baseless accusations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A writer in the Ming Pao Daily News sided with Beijing in an  
editorial, ``The Cox report lacks solid evidence.'' The piece 
criticized the report -- compiled by a special congressional 
committee chaired by Rep. Christopher Cox, R-Calif. -- for not 
naming names and lacking sufficient proof. The document was based 
on a longer classified report. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Beijing-funded China Press, an editorial -- ``Who exactly  
stole who's secrets?'' -- also expressed dismay that more details 
about how China stole secrets were not disclosed in the Cox report, 
which claims the theft occurred over 20 years at U.S. weapons labs. 
</P>
<P>
	The editorial said the allegations would cause needless harm to  
Chinese in America, making them targets of suspicion and distrust. 
</P>
<P>
	``We Chinese living in America hope that the defense of this  
nation is impregnable,'' the editorial said. ``We also hope that 
missiles fired by the People's Liberation Army won't land on our 
heads.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some Chinese worried that the congressional report wasn't making  
the distinction between Chinese-Americans and those who work for 
the Communist government in China. 
</P>
<P>
	``Suddenly, we're in the McCarthy era, where being Chinese  
American was synonymous with treason and espionage,'' L. Ling-chi 
Wang, an ethnic studies professor at the University of California, 
Berkeley, told the San Francisco Examiner. ``That's what the effect 
is. It really is an outrage.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The espionage allegations might mean some Chinese scientists  
will be denied promotions or work in this country, said a New York 
research scientist who would only give his surname, Yang. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe most Chinese here love this country. There's a lot  
of freedom,'' said Yang, who moved to New York two years ago from 
China and hopes to become a U.S. citizen. ``Most of us just want to 
live here, make a contribution and be comfortable.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
