<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Study Suggests 'Heart' Hospitals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- A new study says elderly patients who suffer heart  
attacks are more likely to survive if they are taken directly to a 
hospital with more experience in dealing with heart attacks. 
</P>
<P>
	The researchers concluded that up to 5,000 lives per year could  
be saved if such high-volume hospitals were designated as ``heart 
centers'' and ambulances with cardiac patients were directed to 
them, as long as travel time was not increased too much. 
</P>
<P>
	The study by Dr. David Thiemann of Johns Hopkins University  
looked at 98,898 Medicare patients around the country. It was 
published in Thursday's New England Journal of Medicine. 
</P>
<P>
	People taken to hospitals that treated fewer than 1.4 heart  
attack patients per week were 17 percent more likely to die within 
30 days than those taken to hospitals that treated at least 4.4 
cardiac patients per week, the study said. 
</P>
<P>
	The study confirmed previous research that found aggressive  
treatment with aspirin, beta blockers and other drugs accounted for 
about one-third of the improvement in survival rates. Treatment by 
cardiologists instead of other specialists also may improve 
survival slightly. 
</P>
<P>
	The study also confirmed previous research showing the  
availability of invasive procedures such as angiography, 
angioplasty and bypass surgery made no difference. 
</P>
<P>
	The researchers could not find other specific factors that would  
account for most of the improvement in survival at high-volume 
hospitals. That suggests it is the overall experience of the 
medical staff -- in small ways that aren't easily be measured -- that 
prevents deaths, the study's authors concluded. 
</P>
<P>
	However, in an accompanying editorial, Edward Hannan of the  
University of Albany School of Public Health cautioned that before 
changing ambulance policies, public health officials should look at 
survival rates at individual hospitals, not just the number of 
patients taken there. 
</P>
<P>
	He also cautioned that it is still unclear why some hospitals  
are more successful than others. He also noted the study may simply 
reflect the fact that good hospitals already get more heart attack 
patients because their reputations lead ambulance companies to 
bring people there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
