<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> WWII Relic Returned To Italy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) -- A small bell recovered by an American  
soldier in a bombed-out church in Italy in 1944 journeyed home 
today to mark the 55th anniversary of a village's liberation during 
World War II. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am just so elated that it's going back,'' said 84-year-old  
Herbert Roth. 
</P>
<P>
	He grabbed the 9-inch-tall bronze bell as a war memento during  
an Allied offensive in Anzio, a Mediterranean village where nearly 
50,000 soldiers were killed in one of the most ferocious encounters 
of the war. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I took that bell, it was in a heap of rubble and I  
thought to myself, `How can I leave it because what a reminder of 
World War II that was to me?' Far did I ever know what that bell 
was or what it meant to Italy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The bell was used for calling people into Mass at Saints Pio and  
Antonio Catholic Church. On its side is the protruding figure of a 
lion's head, a papal symbol marking the church's founding in 1856. 
</P>
<P>
	After keeping it on a shelf at home for a half-century, Roth  
donated it in 1997 to the Italian American Community Center in 
Gates, a Rochester suburb. The Anzio Beach Museum asked for its 
return and the community center agreed in January. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
