<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 10:35:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Yankees Could Open Houston Stadium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- The Houston Astros are negotiating with the New  
York Yankees to stage an exhibition game next spring that would 
inaugurate the Astros' new downtown park. 
</P>
<P>
	Such a contest at the new Enron Field would duplicate the  
ceremonial first game at the Astrodome when the world's first domed 
stadium opened April 9, 1965, Houston officials told television 
station KRIV Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Astros are vacating the Astrodome after this season for a  
new retractable-roof $265 million palace downtown. 
</P>
<P>
	``We just thought that would be a nice touch since that's how  
the Astrodome was originally opened,'' Bob McClaren, the Astros' 
senior vice president, said. ``That's when Mickey Mantle hit the 
first home run in the Dome. 
</P>
<P>
	``We thought the New York Yankees would be an appropriate team  
to play as an exhibition game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McClaren said the discussions are with Brian Cashman, the  
Yankees' general manager and with the approval of New York owner 
George Steinbrenner. 
</P>
<P>
	``Brian has explained the relationship between George  
Steinbrenner and (Astros owner) Drayton McLane is very strong,'' 
McClaren said. ``I know George would like to do this. So we are 
trying to make it all happen.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990527.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 19:31:13 </DATE_TIME>
