<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Names Foreign Aid Plan Head </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	YULEE, Fla.(AP) -- J. Brady Anderson, a former U.S. Ambassador to  
Tanzania, has been tapped by President Clinton to head the U.S. 
Agency for International Development, which manages foreign aid 
programs. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said Thursday that he would nominate Anderson, a lawyer  
from Charleston, S.C., to the post. He succeeds J. Brian Atwood, 
who held the post for the past six years. 
</P>
<P>
	Brady was ambassador to Tanzania from 1994 to 1997. Prior to  
joining the diplomatic corps, Anderson lived in Kenya, Ethiopia and 
Tanzania researching African languages. He speaks Swahili. 
</P>
<P>
	A Vietnam veteran, Anderson worked as an Arkansas assistant  
attorney general, an adviser to then Governor Clinton and a senior 
law clerk to a federal judge in Little Rock, Ark. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, Atwood withdrew his nomination to become ambassador  
to Brazil, saying opposition by Sen. Jesse Helms ruled out the 
possibility of Senate confirmation. 
</P>
<P>
	Atwood said Helms, R-N.C., who chairs the Senate Foreign  
Relations Committee, opposed the nomination because of his 
successful campaign to defeat the senator's proposal to merge USAID 
into the State Department. 
</P>
<P>
	When he leaves his USAID post, Atwood will remain in charge of  
coordinating the president's humanitarian relief program for 
Kosovo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
