<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Strawberry Farmer Union Vote Fails </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALINAS, Calif. (AP) -- The United Farm Workers, struggling to  
regain the clout it had under Cesar Chavez, was dealt a tremendous 
setback when California strawberry pickers voted to join an upstart 
committee that has never negotiated a contract. 
</P>
<P>
	Even though the results are not official and the UFW can still  
force a runoff, the election this week was widely seen as another 
sign of the union's failure to recover from years of decline. 
</P>
<P>
	``The UFW made a lot of mistakes here,'' said John Borrego,  
associate professor of community studies at University of 
California, Santa Cruz, who follows the agricultural labor 
movement. ``This should send them the message that they have to 
change their strategy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	About 1,300 pickers working for Coastal Berry, the nation's  
largest strawberry grower, voted Tuesday and Wednesday, in favor of 
being represented by the Coastal Berry of California Farm Worker 
Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	State labor officials have yet to finalize the 646-577 vote.  
About 60 ballots are in dispute, and another 79 workers voted for a 
third option of no union, meaning that neither the UFW nor the 
novice committee has obtained the majority support necessary for 
victory. 
</P>
<P>
	The UFW cannot win, said the state Agricultural Labor Relations  
Board, though it still could force a runoff if the Farm Worker 
Committee does not receive enough of the remaining votes. 
</P>
<P>
	UFW president Arturo Rodriguez said he was saddened by their  
loss to the upstart union. He blamed interference by antiunion 
growers who feared a victory at Coastal Berry might spread to other 
berry fields. 
</P>
<P>
	``Their organization has nothing to offer, while we have  
demonstrated and proven results,'' he said. ``Clearly there was 
intimidation and coercion here, and we're going to continue our 
fight.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The results were considered pivotal in the UFW's effort to  
recover from the years of decline that came even before the 1993 
death of its legendary founder, Cesar Chavez. 
</P>
<P>
	Under Chavez, 80,000 farmworkers were working under UFW  
contracts by 1970. Union membership had dwindled to 20,000 at the 
time of his death. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1995, the UFW tried to kindle a resurgence in the state's  
$600 million, 20,000 worker strawberry industry. 
</P>
<P>
	But outside observers said the UFW made mistakes, including  
replacing about 10 local organizers with out-of-town professionals, 
and underestimating the tight relationship pickers had with 
growers. 
</P>
<P>
	``There were tremendous accusations when the UFW started  
organizing here that they were acting like bullies and they were 
telling these fiercely independent people that they should turn to 
them for support and give them part of their paycheck,'' said 
Borrego. ``This generation of workers hasn't even heard of Cesar 
Chavez. They don't bring with them a history that unions are 
wonderful things.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The result came as no surprise to Jess Brown, executive director  
of the Santa Cruz County Farm Bureau. He said the worker's choice 
is a sign of the UFW's weakness in the community. 
</P>
<P>
	``The union wasn't able to clearly show that it could do more  
than what the workers presently have or could have,'' he said. 
``The UFW didn't do their research. They thought this was something 
they could easily attain.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Harley Shaiken, an industrial relations professor at  
UC-Berkeley, said the close vote suggests the UFW remains a force 
to be reckoned with in agriculture. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would be easy to say they had the election, the UFW lost,  
end of story. But it's more interesting that under circumstances 
that have been very difficult, the union has come very close to 
victory at a pivotal company,'' Shaiken said. 
</P>
<P>
	Coastal Berry Co. President Ernie Farley, who has repeatedly  
asserted his neutrality, said his company will ``abide by whatever 
representing body the state labor board certifies.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Attorney Jim Gumberg, who represents the Coastal Berry of  
California Farm Worker Committee, said his group has no president 
and is led by a vice president -- Sergio Leal -- who was fired by 
Coastal Berry for alleged misconduct. He said he isn't sure whether 
they have obtained Labor Department recognition as a union, and he 
said none of them has negotiated a contract. 
</P>
<P>
	``Workers weren't voting for our agenda here,'' he said. ``They  
were voting against the UFW with its slick organizers who threaten, 
cajole, intimidate, and have never picked a berry in their lives.'' 
</P>
<P>
	ALRB officials planned to meet Thursday to discuss the  
unresolved ballots, said the board's regional director, Fred 
Capuyan. He would not speculate on how long it would take to 
determine a winner. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990527.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 18:36:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AL Suspends Ramirez, Nitkowski </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Cleveland outfielder Manny Ramirez and Detroit  
pitcher C.J. Nitkowski, the two players ejected during last week's 
beanball battle at Jacobs Field, were suspended and fined Thursday 
by AL president Gene Budig. 
</P>
<P>
	Ramirez, leading the majors with 59 RBIs, is to start a  
three-game suspension Friday against Boston. Nitkowski is to begin 
a two-game suspension Friday against Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	There was no immediate word on whether either player would  
appeal the penalties. 
</P>
<P>
	Pitcher Jaret Wright of Cleveland and manager Larry Parrish and  
pitcher Jeff Weaver of Detroit also were fined undisclosed amounts. 
</P>
<P>
	And in an unusual step, Budig announced his intention to talk to  
Wright and Indians manager Mike Hargrove about Wright's 
``deportment on the mound'' when Cleveland visits New York next 
week. 
</P>
<P>
	``None of us wants to see Jaret told how to pitch,'' Indians  
general manager John Hart said. ``He pitches inside and will 
continue to so do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The trouble at Jacobs Field last Saturday began when Wright --  
suspended for five games in April and fined $1,000 after hitting a 
Boston batter with a pitch following a home run -- nailed Detroit's 
Tony Clark in the batting helmet with a fastball in the top of the 
sixth inning. 
</P>
<P>
	In the bottom of the sixth, Ramirez charged Weaver after being  
hit in the helmet with a pitch, setting off a bench-clearing brawl. 
During the fracas, Parrish wrestled down Wright from behind. 
</P>
<P>
	Both teams were warned against further trouble. In the eighth,  
Nitkowski was ejected when his first -- and only -- pitch knocked 
Kenny Lofton to the ground. 
</P>
<P>
	``The American League this year has suspended only players who  
were ejected by umpires,'' Budig said. 
</P>
<P>
	Parrish said he had not expected a fine, but ``I don't know that  
it's anything I'd fight, though.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As for Nitkowski, he said, ``He's the one suspended who wasn't  
throwing at anybody, for sure. But it happened after he'd been 
warned.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ramirez is batting .348 with 13 home runs.  
</P>
<P>
	``I think in Manny's case, obviously Manny was hit  
deliberately,'' Hart said. ``It was retaliation of some sort and 
Manny reacted.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nitkowski is 1-1 with a 5.50 ERA in 27 relief appearances.  
</P>
<P>
	``Every one of those pitches was an accident, whether anybody  
wants to believe it or not. Especially mine,'' Nitkowski said. 
``Anybody who knows my history will tell you that location isn't my 
long suit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``If I get two, how come Ramirez only gets three? I think that's  
pretty weak,'' he said. ``The fines better be in proportion -- what 
my salary is and what his salary is.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hart said he spoke with Budig couple of times this week.  
</P>
<P>
	``I was hoping for some leniency and obviously none was given.  
In our situation, all you can do is grind your teeth. I don't think 
it was overly fair,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hart also spoke to Budig about Parrish's involvement in the  
brawl ``and I told him I didn't think that was appropriate.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990527.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 15:41:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Finishes N. Korea Inspections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- U.S. technical experts have completed an  
inspection of a suspected nuclear weapons development site in North 
Korea, and their findings will be subjected to careful analysis, 
the State Department said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Spokesman James P. Rubin said the U.S. team found ``an  
unfinished site, the underground portion of which was an extensive, 
empty tunnel.'' No judgments about the inspection will be made 
before the analysis is completed, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The team began its inspection on May 20 and finished on May 24,  
earlier than expected. It credited North Korean officials with 
allowing unhampered access to the site and rapid completion of the 
work plan. 
</P>
<P>
	Satellite photos taken last year led some U.S. experts to  
believe the North Koreans were using the site to develop nuclear 
weapons in violation of a 1994 agreement between the two countries. 
North Korea denied any such intention. 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin said the U.S. team will make a return visit in May 2000,  
in accordance with an agreement reached in March. 
</P>
<P>
	The team completed its work shortly before the arrival in  
Pyongyang of former Defense Secretary William Perry, who is 
reviewing U.S. policy toward North Korea for President Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	There were reports that Perry planned to meet with North Korean  
leader Kim Jong-il. Rubin said he was unaware whether any such 
meeting had taken place. Perry carried a letter from Clinton for 
Kim. 
</P>
<P>
	Perry planned to leave North Korea on Friday and to brief  
Japanese and South Korean officials in Seoul on Saturday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990527.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 04:32:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NFL Commits Stadium Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- The NFL is using its financial clout to put an  
end to franchise free agency. 
</P>
<P>
	Using a new financial policy approved at the March meetings, the  
league committed more than $200 million Wednesday to help three of 
its bedrock franchises -- New England, Philadelphia and Denver -- 
build new stadiums. 
</P>
<P>
	The new policy was put into place as one way of solving the  
franchise movement that reached its peak four years ago when the 
Rams and Raiders deserted Los Angeles, the Browns left Cleveland 
and the Oilers left Houston. 
</P>
<P>
	The league has expanded to Cleveland and is working on putting a  
new team in Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a crucial policy for the league to have strong footing in  
the largest media markets,'' said Philadelphia Eagles owner Jeffrey 
Lurie, one of the beneficiaries. 
</P>
<P>
	The new policy allows backing of up to 50 percent of private  
financing used for stadiums in the top six markets and 34 percent 
in those below that level. 
</P>
<P>
	New England and Philadelphia are in the first group and Denver  
in the second. 
</P>
<P>
	Broncos owner Patrick Bowlen said he expects a commitment of $43  
million to $44 million, and the Eagles expect close to $50 million 
to $55 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The Patriots, recommitted to Massachusetts after a withdrawing a  
plan to move to Hartford, Conn., could get more than $100 million. 
</P>
<P>
	All three already have various commitments for public financing.  
</P>
<P>
	In other action on the final day of the league's spring meeting:  
</P>
<P>
	--The owners rejected a proposal to move kickoffs from the 30- to  
the 25-yard line to encourage returns. That first came up in March 
and was tabled, but proponents were still unable to get a 
consensus. 
</P>
<P>
	--The owners awarded the 2003 Super Bowl to San Diego, replacing  
San Francisco, which will not have a new stadium ready. South 
Florida was the only other contender. 
</P>
<P>
	--The league unveiled the technology for its new replay system,  
to be reinstated this fall after seven years. 
</P>
<P>
	--The owners extended NFL Europe for at least another season.  
</P>
<P>
	But the biggest impact long term is the commitment to financing  
both new stadiums and stadium improvements. 
</P>
<P>
	For while the money is more collateral than loan, it will allow  
the teams involved to get a commitment for funds to build stadiums 
and to get them at lower interest rates than they might have. 
</P>
<P>
	It's also not likely to cost the teams involved. Money will be  
paid back from club seat revenues that go to visiting teams, which 
get 40 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In part, it's a continuation of a league policy. But never  
before has the NFL backed as much as half the building cost. 
Thirty-four percent was the most committed in the past, and most of 
that was for renovations. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's an evolutionary thing not a new thing,'' commissioner  
Paul Tagliabue said. 
</P>
<P>
	That didn't sit well with everyone.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's a tax on all the teams that won't benefit,'' said Al  
Davis of the Raiders. ``Never before in the history of the league 
have the poor given to the rich.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Patriots owner Robert Kraft, who recently withdrew from a  
$380 million stadium deal in Connecticut and now has $70 million in 
state money from Massachusetts to help build roads around his new 
stadium, suggested it was simply a case of partners helping each 
other. 
</P>
<P>
	``Helping each other is one way to get things done,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	On replay, the owners were shown the technology in which coaches  
will get two challenges a game, plus an unlimited number in the 
last two minutes of each half. The calls will be made by a replay 
official from a stadium booth. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a system designed to correct a mistake that the whole  
world knows is a mistake,'' said Dennis Lewin, the league's top 
television official. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990527.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 19:13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IBM Exec Claims Microsoft Pressure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) -- During one of the lowest points of the  
soured relationship between two of the computer industry's giants, 
Microsoft offered an alliance with IBM if it agreed to sacrifice 
its rival operating-system software, an IBM manager told lawyers 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	He said that in a meeting during a trade show in Las Vegas with  
top Microsoft executives -- including Bill Gates -- IBM rejected the 
overture and said it planned to sell both Windows and its own OS/2 
operating system, which ultimately proved a commercial failure. 
</P>
<P>
	Garry Norris, the IBM manager who will be one of the  
government's final witnesses in its antitrust trial with Microsoft, 
contended in sworn testimony Thursday that Microsoft exerted 
pressure on IBM to cut its sales of OS/2, the software product that 
competed directly with Windows until the popularity of OS/2 waned 
in late 1994 and 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	He also testified that major computer makers, such as Compaq  
Computer Corp., agreed not to sell OS/2 on their machines because 
of threats from Microsoft. 
</P>
<P>
	Norris said a Compaq executive told him Microsoft had promised  
in 1993 ``to make it difficult for Compaq'' if it sold IBM's 
product, and he revealed that IBM complained about the alleged 
threats to the Justice Department as early as 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Norris, who works for IBM at nearby Research Triangle Park, will  
be the government's second witness during the rebuttal phase of the 
trial, which resumes Tuesday in Washington after a 13-week recess. 
A Microsoft lawyer, Rick Pepperman, questioned Norris in North 
Carolina about his expected testimony. 
</P>
<P>
	Norris said that after IBM rejected Microsoft's alleged offer in  
1994, Microsoft took an unusually tough stance negotiating the 
wholesale price that IBM paid to put Windows on computers it sold 
to consumers. 
</P>
<P>
	Norris said that weeks before the August 1995 rollout of an  
important new version of Windows, Microsoft threatened to end 
negotiations, which were at a standstill. The companies finally 
reached an agreed price, ``15 minutes before the launch of Windows 
95,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	IBM had paid only $9 for earlier versions of Windows, what it  
believed to be the lowest price paid by any company. But Microsoft 
wanted about $46 for Windows 95 -- much more than IBM believed some 
other computer makers were paying. 
</P>
<P>
	``Microsoft told us repeatedly, `Because you compete with us,  
you're going to get unfavorable terms and conditions,''' Norris 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Norris said IBM's costs rose from $40 million to $220 million.  
</P>
<P>
	Although the exact price that Microsoft charges for Windows is  
one of the industry's most closely guarded secrets, previous 
testimony indicated that favored companies, such as Compaq Computer 
Corp., generally pay less than IBM. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was told they (Compaq) received that deduction because they  
didn't compete with Microsoft,'' Norris said. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft contends that Compaq received lower prices because it  
qualified for some volume discounts and because Compaq helped 
develop some important technology that was incorporated into 
Windows 95. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of its antitrust case, the government alleges that  
Microsoft bullies the nation's computer manufacturers. Lawyers say 
it uses prices to punish its enemies and reward its friends, and to 
stem potential competition among operating system software, 
Microsoft's most lucrative franchise. 
</P>
<P>
	Court papers indicate Norris will testify at the trial about the  
threats Microsoft allegedly made over IBM's support of OS/2 and 
Internet browser software from Netscape Communications Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Norris' deposition was the second of three scheduled this week.  
The government will depose a Microsoft witness, software executive 
Gordon Eubanks, on Friday in California. 
</P>
<P>
	Reporters are allowed to attend the depositions under a 1913 law  
covering antitrust depositions, which are normally conducted in 
private. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990527.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 19:04:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Russians Angered by Serb Indictment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Russia responded angrily Thursday to the war  
crimes indictment of Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic, saying 
it would damage efforts to find a political solution to the Kosovo 
crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	The indictment came after Russia's special envoy on Kosovo,  
Viktor Chernomyrdin, concluded two days of talks with U.S. Deputy 
Secretary of State Strobe Talbott and Finnish President Martti 
Ahtisaari. 
</P>
<P>
	After the talks ended inconclusively, Chernomyrdin was scheduled  
to fly to Yugoslavia Friday for meetings with Milosevic, according 
to his spokesman, Valentin Sergeyev. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today, we reached the finish line in the negotiating process.  
But somebody needed to put obstacles on the road to a peaceful 
dialogue,'' Chernomyrdin said in response to the indictment, 
according to the Interfax news agency. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia, which opposes NATO airstrikes and has been participating  
in negotiations to end the war in Yugoslavia, said indicting the 
Yugoslav leader would make solving the crisis difficult. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you're dealing with Yugoslavia, you have to deal with one  
person -- the president of Yugoslavia,'' said Dmitry Yakushkin, a 
spokesman for President Boris Yeltsin. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.N. War Crimes Tribunal in The Hague, Netherlands, Thursday  
indicted Milosevic and four top aides on charges of planning and 
carrying out war crimes against ethnic Albanians in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russian Foreign Ministry said the indictment had been  
``purely politically motivated'' and questioned why the tribunal 
had not investigated NATO's bombing of Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	``We hardly consider it incidental that this step was undertaken  
at the moment when the talks to solve the Kosovo problem entered 
the most important stage,'' the Foreign Ministry said in a 
statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Dmitri Ryurikov, an international affairs adviser to the upper  
house of parliament, told the ITAR-Tass news agency the indictment 
was ``absolutely groundless.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no evidence whatsoever that he is to blame for what  
he is charged with,'' Ryurikov said. 
</P>
<P>
	Tribunal chief prosecutor Louise Arbour in The Hague insisted  
she had done the right thing, saying the indictment ``will make a 
major contribution to a lasting peace, not only in Kosovo, but in 
the whole region in which we have jurisdiction.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After meeting with Chernomyrdin, Talbott and Ahtisaari left  
Thursday for Bonn, Germany, for talks with German Chancellor 
Gerhard Schroeder. 
</P>
<P>
	Sergeyev said the three would meet again within the next few  
days, but a date or place had not been determined, the ITAR-Tass 
news agency reported. 
</P>
<P>
	German leaders signaled Thursday that peace talks could continue  
with Milosevic despite the indictment. 
</P>
<P>
	``To achieve peace, I'd even shake hands with the devil. That's  
the task of a foreign minister,'' Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer 
said on ZDF television. Diplomatic efforts should be strengthened 
``entirely independently from how a court decides.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder took a similar stand after meeting  
with Talbott and Ahtisaari. ``Sometimes there are goals -- such as 
peace in Europe -- that take precedence over other considerations,'' 
he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990527.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 19:01:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Lawmakers Hear Diverse Gun Views </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Two parents whose children were slain by  
classmates gave lawmakers diverse views Thursday on whether the 
slayers, guns or lawmakers themselves are to blame for their 
tragedies. 
</P>
<P>
	Darrell Scott of Littleton, Colo., told the House Judiciary  
Committee's subcommittee that he blames the April 20 death of his 
daughter, Rachel Joy Scott, 17, on Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are people behind those instruments of death,'' Scott  
told the panel. ``I do believe Eric and Dylan bear primary 
responsibility for my daughter's death, not the guns themselves.'' 
.
</P>
<P>
	But Byrl Phillips-Taylor of Richmond, Va., placed the blamed an  
AK47 for her son's 1989 death at the hands of a ``classmate with a 
grudge.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The easy availability of guns got my baby killed,''  
Phillips-Taylor told the panel, urging lawmakers to pass the 
mandatory background checks for gun show transactions and other new 
firearms restrictions voted by the Senate last week. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Senate has demonstrated that it cares about keeping guns  
away from children,'' she said. ``And that may be the turning point 
that every mother like me has been waiting for.'' 
</P>
<P>
	House Republican leaders this week said they support the concept  
of the gun restrictions passed by the Senate, but they rejected 
demands from Democrats to quickly rubber-stamp the measures. 
</P>
<P>
	Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde, who has co-authored gun  
control bills in the past, said careful consideration of the 
legislation next month would ensure that new controls would not 
infringe on the Second Amendment right to bear arms. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans at Thursday's hearing criticized the Clinton  
administration as failing to prosecute violators of existing 
firearms laws while pushing for more gun restrictions. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Bob Barr, R-Ga., suggested that if the Ten Commandments had  
been posted at high schools where the shooting occurred, ``we would 
not have had the tragedies that bring us here today.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Replied Deputy Attorney General Eric Holder Jr.: ``If the young  
people and adult criminals who committed these crimes had a tougher 
time getting their hands on guns, these horrible crimes might have 
been prevented.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Vice President Al Gore, who broke a 50-50 Senate tie last week  
in favor of the new gun show restrictions, returned to the Capitol 
Thursday to accuse House Republicans of trying to please the 
National Rifle Association. 
</P>
<P>
	``At this very moment, there are some of the other side meeting  
behind closed doors plotting to have more delays in order to 
preserve loopholes'' in firearms law, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	NRA Executive Vice President Wayne LaPierre told the House  
subcommittee Thursday that the Senate bill was a ``red tape 
nightmare.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Basically it would extend the reaches of the federal  
government into the homes of this country,'' LaPierre said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the NRA supports mandatory gun show background checks  
and other concepts in the Senate bill, but not as written. For 
example, he said, the Senate would ``your uncle's skeet-shooting 
range'' as a gun show subject to government regulations. 
</P>
<P>
	Scott, testifying at the request of committee Republicans,  
supported LaPierre's complaint that some gun control advocates were 
seeking to put the blame for the shootings at the NRA's doorstep. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't believe that they are responsible for my daughter's  
death,'' said Scott, who said he was not a member of the group and 
does not own a gun. 
</P>
<P>
	Scott also scolded lawmakers about their eagerness to pass more  
laws despite the cultural causes behind school shootings. 
``Political posturing and restrictive legislation are not the 
answers,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990527.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 12:21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bauer Opposes China Trade Boost </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republican presidential hopeful Gary Bauer  
challenged other GOP candidates Thursday to oppose normalized trade 
with China in light of allegations of Chinese spying at U.S. 
nuclear laboratories. 
</P>
<P>
	``One of the most pressing priorities facing the next president  
is the need for a new foreign policy with China, a policy rooted in 
America's vital national interest and basic human rights instead of 
a policy primarily rooted in trade,'' Bauer said. 
</P>
<P>
	Congress is expected to vote next month on whether to extend  
normalized trade relations, formerly called most favored nation 
status, with China. Beijing also is pushing for admission to the 
World Trade Organization. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. John McCain said this week's spying allegations will not  
change his support for normalized trade relations with China. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we cut off normal trade relations with every nation that  
spies on us, we might be trading with Canada -- and I am not even 
sure about that,'' the Arizona Republican said. ``It's hard for me 
to believe that anyone would be surprised that China is spying on 
us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Texas Gov. George W. Bush, in a news conference Tuesday, said,  
``I still believe it is important for China to open its markets to 
U.S. producers and U.S. products.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said U.S. producers should not be punished because of China's  
spying. 
</P>
<P>
	Elizabeth Dole believes China should be admitted to the WTO  
because ``trade is one of the most important tools for forcing 
humanitarian and pro-democratic change,'' said her spokesman Ari 
Fleischer. He said he expected her to support a continuation of 
normalized trade status. 
</P>
<P>
	Former Vice President Dan Quayle said in a speech last month  
that China is ``not ready for WTO'' entry and that the United 
States should be wary of renewing China's trade status. His 
spokesman Jonathan Baron said this week's developments have not 
changed Quayle's views. 
</P>
<P>
	Steve Forbes adamantly opposes China's entry into the WTO at  
this time, and thinks China's actions threaten its trade status as 
well, according to his spokeswoman Juleanna Glover. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990527.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 18:36:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Manchester United's Win for Ages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Manchester United has lifted English soccer back  
to the summit of Europe after a long, hard climb. And with their 
historic triple crown season, the Reds are being hailed as possibly 
the greatest English team ever. 
</P>
<P>
	United etched its place in English soccer folklore by beating  
Bayern Munich 2-1 in Barcelona on Wednesday night to win the 
European Champions Cup -- the world's most prestigious club title. 
</P>
<P>
	In one of the most dramatic finishes in cup history, United came  
from behind to win with two goals in the final 90 seconds of injury 
time by substitutes Teddy Sheringham and Ole Gunnar Solskjaer. 
</P>
<P>
	The victory completed an unprecedented sweep by an English club  
of the domestic league, F.A. Cup and European Cup titles in the 
same season -- something that even the great Liverpool teams of the 
late 1970s and early '80s never accomplished. 
</P>
<P>
	British newspapers hailed the win as one of the greatest moments  
in English soccer history, with the Daily Mirror headline even 
calling it ``The Greatest 2 Minutes in the History of Sport.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Thousands of fans poured into the streets of Manchester to  
celebrate Wednesday night, and the city was turned into a sea of 
red -- the team's color -- Thursday night as men, women and children 
turned out to greet their heroes. 
</P>
<P>
	Fans climbed lamp-posts and any available vantage points along  
the route to get a better view as manager Alex Ferguson and his 
players rode through the city in an open-top double-decker bus. 
</P>
<P>
	It took nearly four hours for the bus to wind its way through  
the masses on its seven-mile route from the outskirts of the city 
to the downtown Manchester indoor arena. 
</P>
<P>
	Car horns, whistles and the ``Glory Glory Man United'' anthem  
filled the air. 
</P>
<P>
	The size of the crowd was estimated at anywhere from 400,000 to  
750,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Ferguson and the players stood atop the bus, waving to the  
crowds and holding up the three trophies. The European Cup was 
propped up front like a huge hood ornament. 
</P>
<P>
	By the time the bus neared the city center, the route of the  
parade along the shopping street of Deansgate was packed. So many 
red-shirted supporters were waiting to welcome the team that police 
appealed for fans to stay away from the center. 
</P>
<P>
	Ferguson's team became the first United club to lift the  
European trophy since since 1968, when Matt Busby was manager and 
George Best and Bobby Charlton were the stars. 
</P>
<P>
	That triumph came 10 years after the Munich air crash which  
killed eight players of the United team known as the ``Busby 
Babes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In a powerful piece of symbolism, United's triumph Wednesday  
came on what would have been Busby's 90th birthday. 
</P>
<P>
	Charlton, who survived the Munich crash and is now a senior  
director of the club, wiped away tears as he watched the team's 
celebrations Wednesday night from the stands of the Camp Nou 
stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	The victory also helped erase some of the memories of another  
dark chapter in English soccer history. In 1985, 39 people died 
when English hooligans rioted before the Liverpool-Juventus 
European Cup final at Brussels' Heysel stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	The tragedy resulted in English clubs being banned from European  
competition for five years. Since the ban was lifted, Manchester 
United (1991), Arsenal (1994) and Chelsea (1998) won the Cup 
Winners Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	But, until this season, no English club had managed to progress  
to the Champions Cup final. The win over Bayern means English clubs 
are now tied with Italian sides with the most European Cup 
victories (9). 
</P>
<P>
	``English football has been in the wilderness for a long time  
and now we're back on the world stage,'' Charlton said. ``It's been 
all right saying English football is the healthiest and the best to 
watch, but you really need to have something to show for it and to 
win the Champions League, there's nothing bigger in world club 
football.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Debate is already raging on whether this Manchester United team,  
which has won the Premier League title in five of the past seven 
seasons, is the greatest English club of all time. 
</P>
<P>
	Comparisons are being made to the 1958 and 1968 United teams and  
to the Liverpool teams which won the European Cup four times (1977, 
1978, 1981 and 1984). Bob Paisley was the Liverpool manager during 
that era and his star players included Kenny Dalglish and Graeme 
Souness. 
</P>
<P>
	``I always said we would never be judged as a great team until  
we had won the Champions League,'' winger Ryan Giggs said. ``We've 
done that now and I think we deserve to be ranked along with the 
Liverpool teams of the 80s.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Much of the credit goes to Ferguson, the 57-year-old Scot whose  
achievements rank alongside those of Paisley, Busby, Bill Shankly 
and Jock Stein. 
</P>
<P>
	Ferguson has claimed 12 major trophies since taking over at  
United in 1986 -- five league championships, four F.A. Cups, one 
league Cup, one Champions Cup and one Cup Winners Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	That total puts Ferguson only one behind Paisley, who won 13  
trophies at Liverpool. Ferugson also won 10 major trophies with 
Aberdeen, bringing his career total to 22. 
</P>
<P>
	Ferguson may soon become ``Sir Alex.'' It's now widely expected  
that he will receive a knighthood -- an honor that also went to 
Busby. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990527.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 18:36:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
