<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> India Frontier Town Faces Shelling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KARGIL, India (AP) -- They say if you hear the shriek of the  
incoming shell, you're safe. 
</P>
<P>
	Small comfort for Mohammad Saddiq, who squatted against the  
concrete wall of his hotel for protection Thursday in this Indian 
town at the front line of the dispute between India and Pakistan 
over the Kashmir region. 
</P>
<P>
	A Pakistani artillery shell crashed into the ground nearby with  
an earth-shuddering boom, and several pieces of shrapnel landed in 
the courtyard of Saddiq's hotel. A few minutes later, another 
landed, hitting a house 300 feet away with another loud explosion. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe I will leave now. This shelling makes you mentally  
tense, mentally sick,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Most people in this town of 15,000 have already left. Officials  
say 75 percent are gone. More boarded buses Thursday, convinced the 
bombardment will continue for weeks or months. 
</P>
<P>
	Indian and Pakistani soldiers exchange fire along the disputed  
frontier almost every day and have gone to war over Kashmir twice. 
Tensions escalated Wednesday when India sent warplanes and 
helicopter gunships into the rugged Himalayan region to blast out 
separatist guerrillas encamped in the mountains. 
</P>
<P>
	Kargil, India's northernmost town situated in a fertile valley  
dotted with willow trees, is used to fighting. Shells have landed 
here every year for the last three years. In 1997, 20 people were 
killed. Last year, the town was abandoned under unusually heavy 
shelling. 
</P>
<P>
	Qamar Ali Akhoon, overseeing civilian operations in Kargil, said  
he expected the latest exodus to be almost complete in a few weeks. 
``If the firing continues as it did today, most people will leave 
to safer areas,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The town is boarded up tight, padlocked and sealed. Only a few  
shops were open. Men idled in small groups on the main market 
street. Few women were to be seen. When the shelling begins, 
everybody scurries for shelter. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Kargil's worst problem is not shells from Pakistan. It's  
food from India. 
</P>
<P>
	For eight months of the year, the road into town is snowed in.  
Residents survive through the winter on stores from the previous 
autumn, then quickly resupply when the roads open in May. This 
year, escalated fighting has kept the road closed to civilian 
traffic, blocking the long-awaited supplies. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have enough rice, flour and kerosene,'' said Akhoon. ``But  
no vegetables, no meat, no chicken, no eggs, no butter.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One truck got through Thursday, attaching itself to an army  
convoy. Citizens pounced on it when it unloaded at a store. Within 
three hours, all the potatoes, cabbage, and watermelon were sold. 
</P>
<P>
	``No convoys have been allowed in. My shop is empty,'' said  
Mohammad Hussain, 40, who owns another grocery store. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have nothing to sell, we only have last year's stock,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Shaleen Kabra, the senior administrator of the district, said he  
was rationing medicines, giving the local hospital just enough for 
two days at a time so they were not squandered. 
</P>
<P>
	Measles has broken out, and doctors were short of antibiotics.  
</P>
<P>
	``We are poor people,'' said Haji Abdul Rehman, a 58-year-old  
farmer. ``Both the countries are fighting, and we are sandwiched 
between them.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
