<HEADLINE> ADC To Buy Spectracom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MINNETONKA, Minn. (AP) -- ADC Telecommunications Inc. said it  
would pay $105 million to acquire Spectracom, which makes parts 
used in fiber-optic networks. 
</P>
<P>
	The acquisition is expected to be finalized by late June. It  
calls for ADC to pay $60 million in cash, with an additional $45 
million payable based on future technology developments. 
</P>
<P>
	Spectracom would be ADC's third acquisition in the  
optics-components market in the past four years. 
</P>
<P>
	ADC develops voice, video and data systems for telephone, cable  
television, Internet and wireless communications networks. In 1998, 
it had $1.5 billion in sales. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1995, ADC bought Australia-based AOFR, which makes coupling  
devices that feed the light from two or more fibers into a single 
fiber. In 1998, it bought Princeton Optics, a company that makes 
parts that align mirrors, prisms and lenses used in optical 
devices. 

</P>
</TEXT>
