<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Congress Haggles on HMO Legislation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Partisan maneuvering over patient rights  
legislation continued this week as House Democrats took the first 
step toward forcing a vote on the House floor. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Senate, meanwhile, bipartisan talks toward compromise  
legislation broke down as lawmakers looked to a long Memorial Day 
recess. 
</P>
<P>
	House Democrats said they had ``little choice'' other than to  
start collecting names on a discharge petition, which would pull 
the popular legislation out of committee and move it directly to 
the House floor. The petition would need 218 signatures -- a 
majority of the House -- to force a vote. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have repeatedly asked the majority for a commitment to  
schedule managed care reform for a vote,'' Rep. John Dingell, 
D-Mich., said Thursday. ``If the leadership is unwilling to 
schedule a vote, they'll have to explain for themselves exactly why 
they are running scared from the electorate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dingell cited a May 11 letter in which Commerce Committee  
Chairman Tom Bliley, R-Va., suggested he would hold hearings 
throughout the summer but did not promise a vote. 
</P>
<P>
	House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., accused Dingell of  
politicizing the issue with the petition. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is a disappointing maneuver that tells me the Democrat  
leadership has more interest in playing partisan political games 
than in enacting real reform,'' said Hastert, who has promised a 
vote this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Bliley ``has given public and private assurances'' that the  
committee will debate the issue, said his spokeswoman Christina 
Gungoll, though he has not set a vote. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, there was a similar effort to force a vote on the  
issue, but Republicans brought it to the floor on their own. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Senate, talks have broken down between Sen. William Roth,  
R-Del., chairman of the Finance Committee, and Sen. Daniel Patrick 
Moynihan of New York, the committee's top Democrat. 
</P>
<P>
	``Agreement is not possible at this time,'' Roth said in a  
statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Their staffs had been working since February to fashion a  
compromise, but this week, Moynihan walked away, saying little 
progress had been made and there were other priorities. 
</P>
<P>
	A committee spokeswoman, Ginny Flynn, said Republicans thought  
they were ``pretty close'' to an agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	``We felt that it was premature for them to walk away,'' she  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate Health, Education, Labor and Pensions Committee has  
already approved along party lines a GOP patient rights bill. But 
the Finance Committee is responsible for tax-related portions of 
the legislation, including Republican priorities that are 
tangential to patient protections, such as expanding medical 
savings accounts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
