<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans Up on Heat Worries / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
        CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures prices moved higher  
Thursday on the Chicago Board of Trade amid forecasts for very hot 
weather next week in Midwest growing regions. 
</P>
<P>
        Investors seeking to find support after several days of price  
weakness seized on forecasts for above-normal temperatures over the 
next 10 days in major growing areas. 
</P>
<P>
        The warm weather could signal a hot, dry summer that might  
threaten crop yields and reduce what is expected to be bumper production 
after large-scale plantings. 
</P>
<P>
        Wheat moved higher as a tour of the soft red winter wheat growing  
regions found heavy rainfall in the past few weeks have reduced yields 
and increased the potential for disease. 
</P>
<P>
        Wheat for July delivery rose 2 1/2 cents to $2.50 a bushel;  
July corn rose 1 3/4 cents to $2.16 1/2 a bushel; July oats rose 1/2 
cent to $1.21 a bushel; July soybeans rose 1 3/4 cents to $4.57 1/4 
a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
        Meat and livestock futures retreated on the Chicago Mercantile  
Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
        June live cattle fell .17 cent to 63.50 cents a pound; August  
feeder cattle fell .60 cent to 74.70 cents a pound; June lean hogs 
fell 1.83 cents to 52.17 cents a pound; July pork bellies fell 1.75 
cents to 52.72 cents a pound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
