<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> WWII Relic Returned To Italy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) -- A small church bell recovered by a U.S.  
soldier in the war ruins of Anzio, Italy, in 1944 is journeying 
home to mark the village's liberation during World War II. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am just so elated that it's going back,'' said Herbert Roth,  
84, who grabbed the 9-inch-tall bronze bell as a war memento during 
an Allied offensive in the Mediterranean village, 40 miles south of 
Rome. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I took that bell, it was in a heap of rubble and I  
thought to myself, `How can I leave it ... ?''' Roth said Thursday. 
``Far did I ever know what that bell was or what it meant to 
Italy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The bell was used for calling people into Mass at Saints Pio and  
Antonio Catholic Church. On its side is the protruding figure of a 
lion's head, a papal symbol marking the church's founding in 1856. 
</P>
<P>
	After keeping it on a shelf at home for a half-century, Roth  
donated it in 1997 to the Italian American Community Center in 
Gates, a Rochester suburb. 
</P>
<P>
	Last summer, the Anzio Beach Museum found out the bell had  
survived from members of the community center who went to Anzio 
hoping to find old photographs of the church. 
</P>
<P>
	When the museum asked for its return, the community center  
initially suggested sending a replica. In January, however, its 
board of directors agreed to send the bell back to help Anzio 
commemorate its liberation by U.S. troops 55 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	A delegation of nearly 30 people accompanied the bell on a  
flight from Toronto, Canada, to Rome on Thursday night. Roth cannot 
travel because of his frail health. 
</P>
<P>
	His daughter, Lynne Benzing, will read a letter on his behalf  
during a ceremony Sunday in the rebuilt church. 
</P>
<P>
	Nearly 50,000 soldiers were killed at Anzio in one of the most  
ferocious encounters of the war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
