<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Serbs Dismiss War Crimes Indictment  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- A senior Yugoslav official today  
dismissed the indictment of President Slobodan Milosevic on war 
crimes as a political maneuver and said his government did not 
recognize the jurisdiction of the U.N. tribunal in the Netherlands. 
Indictments against Milosevic and four others on war crimes charges 
were announced today in The Hague by the tribunal's chief 
prosecutor, Louise Arbour. Goran Matic, a minister in the Belgrade 
government, said the indictments make no sense because in 
Belgrade's view there is no war in Kosovo. The tribunal has said it 
has evidence of war crimes ``on a massive scale.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Discovery Departs For Space Station  
</P>
<P>
	CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- Space shuttle Discovery blasted off  
for the new international space station today, ending NASA's 
six-month launch drought, the longest since the Challenger 
disaster. The space station was soaring 235 miles over the 
Atlantic, due east of the Carolinas, when Discovery took off in 
pursuit. They're due to link up early Saturday. Discovery is due 
back June 6. 

</P>
<P>
	Farm Disaster Payments Due Next Week  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Farmers waiting for $2.3 billion in emergency  
disaster aid will begin to see checks next week, Agriculture 
Secretary Dan Glickman said today. Glickman and his agency have 
been widely criticized for the delay in distributing the money, 
which was included in a $6 billion farm bailout passed in October. 
Glickman told a Senate Agriculture hearing that payments to about 
260,000 farmers will begin on Tuesday. 

</P>
<P>
	Judge Rejects Pinochet Appeal  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- A High Court judge today rejected the latest  
attempt by former Chilean dictator Gen. Augusto Pinochet to block 
Spanish extradition proceedings, meaning that after seven months of 
wrangling the extradition hearing will go ahead. The first hearing 
is scheduled for June 4. Spain is seeking the general on charges 
that he ordered the torture of opponents during his 17-year rule. 
An official Chilean government report says that 3,197 people, 
including Spaniards, disappeared or were killed at the hands of 
Pinochet's secret police. 

</P>
<P>
	Barak Promises Lebanon Withdrawal  
</P>
<P>
	KIRYAT SHEMONA, Israel (AP) -- Prime Minister-elect Ehud Barak,  
reaffirming a campaign pledge to end Israel's long military 
presence in Lebanon, promised today to ``bring our boys back'' 
within a year. Barak spoke after surveying the smashed concrete of 
a white stucco house, parts of which were shattered on election 
night, May 17, by a rocket fired by Arab guerrillas in southern 
Lebanon. ``I will bring our boys back from Lebanon under an 
agreement and make it a more secure place,'' he said. 

</P>
<P>
	Louvre Strike Threatens Projects  
</P>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- With no end in sight to a weeklong strike by its  
staff, the Louvre museum said today it will have to cancel some 
upcoming cultural projects because of mounting losses. The Louvre 
said it has so far lost 3 million francs ($500,000) and that at 
least 100,000 people have been turned away due to the strike. The 
striking workers are expected to meet with Prime Minister Lionel 
Jospin Thursday. They want the government hire more people to cope 
with growing numbers of visitors. 

</P>
<P>
	GDP Grows at 4.1 Pct. Annual Rate  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The U.S. economy, powered by the biggest boom  
in consumer spending in more than a decade, grew at a robust annual 
rate of 4.1 percent in the first three months of the year, the 
government said today. The Commerce Department said the increase in 
the gross domestic product, the total output of goods and services, 
occurred despite the fact that America's trade deficit from January 
through March was even worse than originally believed. In a 
separate report, the Labor Department said the number of Americans 
filing new claims for unemployment benefits was unchanged last week 
at 300,000. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Falls 141; Nasdaq Drops 8  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 11 a.m. EDT, the Dow industrials  
were down 141.89 points at 10,560.27. Declining issues on the New 
York Stock Exchange led advancers 1,549-817. The Nasdaq was down 
8.21 at 2,418.96. 

</P>
<P>
	Davenport Advances at French Open  
</P>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- Lindsay Davenport survived a three-set scare from a  
promising 16-year-old at the French Open today, and Steffi Graf, 
Monica Seles and Anna Kournikova all advanced in much easier 
fashion. On the men's side, the popular Brazilian Gustavo Kuerten 
triumphed in four sets, continuing a confident run at the 
tournament he won two years ago. Davenport faced a surprise 
challenge from France's Justine Henin, but hung on for a 6-3, 2-6, 
7-5 win. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAVID GOODMAN  
</P>
</TEXT>
