<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lakers May Want Rambis As Coach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The Los Angeles Lakers are leaning strongly  
toward hiring Kurt Rambis as permanent coach, according to a 
published report. 
</P>
<P>
	The Los Angeles Times reported Thursday that several  
unidentified sources close to the situation said key Laker 
executives favor the selection of Rambis, who took over on an 
interim basis from Del Harris in February. 
</P>
<P>
	No contract negotiations have begun and team executive vice  
president Jerry West and general manager Mitch Kupchak have yet to 
formally present Rambis as their choice to owner Jerry Buss, the 
sources said. 
</P>
<P>
	Lakers spokesman John Black said the team had no comment on the  
Times report. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are not ready to discuss that publicly yet,'' Black said.  
</P>
<P>
	Rambis led the Lakers past Houston in the first round of the NBA  
playoffs before losing four straight to San Antonio. 
</P>
<P>
	``The feeling is this team has to grow together, and you don't  
do that by firing the coach after such a traumatic season,'' one 
Times source said. 
</P>
<P>
	West and Kupchak surveyed key Laker players about Rambis and  
several -- led by a rousing endorsement by Kobe Bryant -- said they 
would fully support his return, the Times sources said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990527.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 06:05:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NFL Commits Stadium Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- The NFL is using its financial clout to put an  
end to franchise free agency. 
</P>
<P>
	Using a new financial policy approved at the March meetings, the  
league committed more than $200 million Wednesday to help three of 
its bedrock franchises -- New England, Philadelphia and Denver -- 
build new stadiums. 
</P>
<P>
	The new policy was put into place as one way of solving the  
franchise movement that reached its peak four years ago when the 
Rams and Raiders deserted Los Angeles, the Browns left Cleveland 
and the Oilers left Houston. 
</P>
<P>
	The league has expanded to Cleveland and is working on putting a  
new team in Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a crucial policy for the league to have strong footing in  
the largest media markets,'' said Philadelphia Eagles owner Jeffrey 
Lurie, one of the beneficiaries. 
</P>
<P>
	The new policy allows backing of up to 50 percent of private  
financing used for stadiums in the top six markets and 34 percent 
in those below that level. 
</P>
<P>
	New England and Philadelphia are in the first group and Denver  
in the second. 
</P>
<P>
	Broncos owner Patrick Bowlen said he expects a commitment of $43  
million to $44 million, and the Eagles expect close to $50 million 
to $55 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The Patriots, recommitted to Massachusetts after a withdrawing a  
plan to move to Hartford, Conn., could get more than $100 million. 
</P>
<P>
	All three already have various commitments for public financing.  
</P>
<P>
	In other action on the final day of the league's spring meeting:  
</P>
<P>
	--The owners rejected a proposal to move kickoffs from the 30- to  
the 25-yard line to encourage returns. That first came up in March 
and was tabled, but proponents were still unable to get a 
consensus. 
</P>
<P>
	--The owners awarded the 2003 Super Bowl to San Diego, replacing  
San Francisco, which will not have a new stadium ready. South 
Florida was the only other contender. 
</P>
<P>
	--The league unveiled the technology for its new replay system,  
to be reinstated this fall after seven years. 
</P>
<P>
	--The owners extended NFL Europe for at least another season.  
</P>
<P>
	But the biggest impact long term is the commitment to financing  
both new stadiums and stadium improvements. 
</P>
<P>
	For while the money is more collateral than loan, it will allow  
the teams involved to get a commitment for funds to build stadiums 
and to get them at lower interest rates than they might have. 
</P>
<P>
	It's also not likely to cost the teams involved. Money will be  
paid back from club seat revenues that go to visiting teams, which 
get 40 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In part, it's a continuation of a league policy. But never  
before has the NFL backed as much as half the building cost. 
Thirty-four percent was the most committed in the past, and most of 
that was for renovations. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's an evolutionary thing not a new thing,'' commissioner  
Paul Tagliabue said. 
</P>
<P>
	That didn't sit well with everyone.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's a tax on all the teams that won't benefit,'' said Al  
Davis of the Raiders. ``Never before in the history of the league 
have the poor given to the rich.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Patriots owner Robert Kraft, who recently withdrew from a  
$380 million stadium deal in Connecticut and now has $70 million in 
state money from Massachusetts to help build roads around his new 
stadium, suggested it was simply a case of partners helping each 
other. 
</P>
<P>
	``Helping each other is one way to get things done,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	On replay, the owners were shown the technology in which coaches  
will get two challenges a game, plus an unlimited number in the 
last two minutes of each half. The calls will be made by a replay 
official from a stadium booth. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a system designed to correct a mistake that the whole  
world knows is a mistake,'' said Dennis Lewin, the league's top 
television official. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
