<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Helms Seeks Changess to ABM Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Sen. Jesse Helms reminded President Clinton  
Wednesday he wants the White House to submit proposed modifications 
by next week to a nuclear arms treaty he opposes. 
</P>
<P>
	Helms, chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee,  
favors taking amendments to the 27-year-old Anti-Ballistic Missile 
treaty to the floor so the Republican-controlled Senate can vote to 
pull the United States out of the entire treaty. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have given the president until next week to fulfill his  
legally binding certification that he will submit a succession 
arrangement to the treaty,'' the North Carolina Republican said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Consideration of such a document will be more than a political  
referendum on the treaty,'' Helms said. ``It will be a very real 
debate over whether the Senate will bring the ABM treaty out of 
legal limbo or hold it in abeyance forever.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Helms and other conservatives consider the pact dead because the  
Soviet Union, with which it was negotiated, no longer exists. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Clinton administration and other Democrats such as Sen.  
Joseph Biden, D-Del., the committee's ranking minority member, 
disagree. They say Russia as a successor to the Soviet Union must 
be consulted on any treaty modifications. 
</P>
<P>
	The ABM treaty is standing in the way of proceeding with a plan  
to establish a national missile defense system. Such a system is 
prohibited by the treaty, and the administration contends that 
Moscow would have to agree to any move by the United States to set 
one up. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia has warned that deployment of a missile defense system  
would violate the ABM treaty, trigger a new arms race and threaten 
the whole system of international disarmament treaties. China 
agrees with Russia. 
</P>
<P>
	Helms said the administration was developing blueprints for the  
system ``not on the basis of the best technology available but on 
the basis of what can be most easily negotiated with Russia in a 
revised ABM treaty.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said it was not widely known that the Clinton administration  
is seeking to reconstitute the ABM Treaty with four new partners -- 
Russia and three other former Soviet republics, Ukraine, Belarus 
and Kazakhstan. 
</P>
<P>
	``I shall do everything within my power to ensure that the ABM  
treaty is never resurrected or reconstituted, regardless of whether 
the president proposes one other party to the treaty or 20,'' Helms 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Testifying before Helms' committee, former Secretary of State  
Henry Kissinger said he supported the administration's view that if 
modifications to the treaty cannot be obtained, the United States 
should consider withdrawing from it. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the threat to the United States from missile  
proliferation was real and growing, and the ABM treaty should not 
be allowed to stand in the way of developing a missile defense 
system. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is ample time to conduct the necessary negotiations,  
since the shape of the system is still under consideration and no 
violation would occur until deployment,'' Kissinger said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said research on the new system must proceed and not be  
delayed pending negotiations. He also said deployment must take 
place as soon as a system is chosen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
