<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Results of Campaign 2000 Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Some results from a CNN/USA Today/Gallup poll on the 2000  
presidential campaign. When results don't total 100 percent, the 
remainder either didn't know or refused to answer. 

</P>
<P>
	 *Asked of Republicans or Republican leaners:    	
</P>
<P>
	--Which of these candidates would you be most likely to support  
for the Republican nomination for president in the year 2000? 
</P>
<P>
	George W. Bush, 46 percent; Elizabeth Dole, 18 percent; Dan  
Quayle, 7 percent; Patrick Buchanan, 6 percent; John McCain, 6 
percent; Steve Forbes, 5 percent; Gary Bauer, 2 percent; John 
Kasich, 2 percent; Bob Smith, 2 percent; Lamar Alexander, 1 
percent. Bush has held a lead of 20 points or more over Dole since 
the beginning of this year. 

</P>
<P>
	 *Asked of Democrats or Democratic leaners:    	
</P>
<P>
	--Which of these candidates are you most likely to support for  
the Democratic nomination for president in the year 2000? 
</P>
<P>
	Al Gore, 59 percent; Bill Bradley, 30 percent. Gore had held a  
lead of 20 points or more over Bradley since the beginning of this 
year. 

</P>
<P>
	 *Asked of all respondents:    	
</P>
<P>
	--As of today, who do you lean more toward, Al Gore, the  
Democrat, or George W. Bush, the Republican? 
</P>
<P>
	George W. Bush, 54 percent; Al Gore, 40 percent. In mid-April,  
Bush led Gore 59-38. 

</P>
<P>
	--Would you be more likely or less likely to vote for Al Gore for  
president if President Clinton were to actively support him and 
campaign for him? 
</P>
<P>
	More likely, 29 percent; less likely, 52 percent; no difference,  
18 percent. 

</P>
<P>
	The phone survey of 1,050 adults was taken Sunday and Monday and  
has an error margin of plus or minus 3 percentage points. For 
subgroups like Democrats and Republicans, the margin of error is 
plus or minus 5 percentage points. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
