<DOCNO> APW19990527.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 12:21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Germany or Mexico To Get Indy Races </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Germany or Mexico will be the next country to be  
introduced to Indy-car racing, according to CART president Andrew 
Craig. But it won't happen before 2001 and when it does, the series 
is going to have to squeeze it into an already crowded calendar. 
</P>
<P>
	``The biggest impediment,'' Craig said from CART's headquarters  
in Troy, Mich., ``is sticking it into the number of races. We have 
20 this year, up from 16 only a few years ago, and we have trouble 
finding places on schedule. 
</P>
<P>
	``The teams are committed and ready to go.''  
</P>
<P>
	Besides the United States and Canada, where 17 of this year's 20  
Indy-car races are staged, CART also runs events in Japan, Brazil, 
and Australia. 
</P>
<P>
	To please his sponsors, who provide $430 million to CART, Craig  
would like internationalize his series. Twenty-five percent of the 
sponsors have asked CART to establish a presence in Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	That would give Craig's series races on four continents and in  
the countries with the three largest economies: the United States, 
Japan and Germany. 
</P>
<P>
	His engine manufacturers -- Honda, Toyota, Ford and Mercedes-Benz  
-- are pushing for a race in Mexico. 
</P>
<P>
	The deciding factor on which country will be first hinges on a  
venue. 
</P>
<P>
	Because of the deal struck with the International Automobile  
Federation following the first race in Australia in 1991, CART is 
prohibited from racing on anything but ovals outside North America. 
</P>
<P>
	Craig says the Lausitz Ring, a 1.5-mile oval about 60 miles  
south of Berlin, is being built by developers in Germany and could 
be ready by 2001. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Europe is not accustomed to oval racing, Craig sees  
that as a positive. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no point in looking like Formula One,'' the  
English-born Craig said. ``We don't want to provide German race 
fans with something they've already got. We bring something they 
haven't seen. And its something American as well, which has an 
intrigue about it. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think most Europeans look upon oval racing with disdain,  
that's it just the business of turning left. But what we have 
found, such as in Japan, is that once they experience it, once they 
see that there is not a bad seat, that they can see every car on 
every lap, for the entire lap, attitudes change rapidly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Mexico, at least, Craig won't have to jump that hurdle.  
</P>
<P>
	Being on the North American continent, CART can stage a road  
race in Mexico and repeat its foray into that market in 1980-81. 
</P>
<P>
	And that is likely what will happen if CART returns, says Craig,  
who says there are ``a couple of tracks quite interested'' from 
Mexico. 
</P>
<P>
	A temporary road course isn't as likely, he says, since that  
involves local governments and control of the course isn't nearly 
as complete and easy as when in a confined area. 
</P>
<P>
	Further complicating matters are the recent talks with the rival  
Indy Racing League, formed in 1995 by Indianapolis Motor Speedway 
owner Tony George when he was rebuffed in his attempt to get more 
influence at CART. 
</P>
<P>
	George complained that CART was too foreign, with more than half  
of its races on road courses and a large number of non-American 
drivers. 
</P>
<P>
	If the two series merge, the Indianapolis 500 -- which had been  
the unchallenged premier race in the United States -- would return 
to the CART schedule and it would seem likely that the IRL would 
want other races from its calender absorbed. 
</P>
<P>
	That would strain the burgeoning CART schedule even more.  
</P>
<P>
	So how soon could we see Indy-cars in Germany or Mexico?  
</P>
<P>
	``Looking at it right now,'' Craig said, ``I couldn't put a date  
on it.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990527.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 23:41:27 </DATE_TIME>
