<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Serb Gov't Dismisses Indictments  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- The Yugoslav government today  
dismissed as a NATO ploy the war crimes indictments of President 
Slobodan Milosevic and four top aides. The opposition party in 
Yugoslavia -- the Democratic Party -- said the indictments for crimes 
against humanity were ill-timed and would undermine the possibility 
of a peace deal. Vladislav Jovanovic, the Yugoslav representative 
to the United Nations in New York, accused the tribunal of blindly 
following the United States and NATO and said the indictment 
undermines efforts to end the conflict. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO Flies Record Number of Sorties  
</P>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- NATO aircraft flew a record number of  
airstrikes today against targets in Yugoslavia. The 19-nation 
alliance said it flew 741 sorties on day 64 of its air operation 
against Yugoslavia, including 308 strike sorties and 74 others 
designed to suppress Serb air defenses. A NATO military spokesman 
said alliance forces had observed a major offensive by the rebel 
Kosovo Liberation Army that had pinned down Serb forces in an area 
of western Kosovo. 

</P>
<P>
	Lawmakers Hear Diverse Gun Views  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Two parents whose children were slain by  
classmates gave lawmakers diverse views today on whether the 
slayers, guns or lawmakers themselves are to blame for their 
tragedies. Darrell Scott of Littleton, Colo., told the House 
Judiciary Committee's subcommittee that he blames the April 20 
death of his daughter Rachel Joy Scott on Eric Harris and Dylan 
Klebold. But Byrl Phillips-Taylor of Richmond, Va., placed the 
blame on an AK47 for her son's 1989 death. House Republican leaders 
this week said they support the concept of the gun restrictions 
passed by the Senate, but they rejected demands to quickly 
rubber-stamp the measures. 

</P>
<P>
	Senate Tightens Weapons Lab Security  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate today voted to expand congressional  
oversight of technology exports and to tighten security at weapons 
laboratories in the aftermath of a report alleging Chinese 
espionage. The package, added to a $288.8 billion defense spending 
bill, would expand the role of intelligence agencies in reviewing 
export licenses, boost Pentagon monitoring of satellite launches in 
China and require the administration to report to Congress on any 
security breaches. 

</P>
<P>
	Pinochet's Court Bid Fails  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Former Chilean dictator Augusto Pinochet lost a  
bid today to block his extradition to Spain for a possible trial on 
charges he ordered the torture of political opponents during his 
17-year rule. High Court Judge Harry Ognall refused to give lawyers 
for the 83-year-old general permission to challenge Spain's 
extradition request. British authorities arrested Pinochet in 
October in London at the request of a Spanish judge Baltasar 
Garzon, who wants to try the former Chilean leader for human rights 
abuses committed during his 1973-90 regime. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Tumbles  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Dow Jones industrial average fell 235.23, a  
2.2 percent loss, to close at 10,466.93 today. It was the 
ninth-worst one-day point drop ever. But in percentage terms, it 
was far from a record decline. Declining issues on the NYSE led 
advancers 1,936-1,041. The Nasdaq was down 7.98 to 2,419.19. 

</P>
<P>
	Longer Trading Approved for Nasdaq  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The National Association of Securities Dealers,  
which governs Nasdaq, today approved a plan to extend trading hours 
from the current 9:30 a.m.-4 p.m. Eastern time schedule. A second 
session of the day would likely start at 5:30 p.m. and end at 9 
p.m. or 10 p.m. The changes are expected to take effect around 
September, after a review by the Securities and Exchange Commission 
and discussions with industry leaders. 

</P>
<P>
	'Star Wars' Fans No Fans of Jar-Jar  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Many fans are calling the character Jar Jar  
Binks from the new ``Star Wars'' movie an annoying goofball at best 
and a racial stereotype at worst. Since George Lucas' ``Star Wars: 
Episode I -- The Phantom Menace'' opened May 19, the Internet has 
been afire with messages calling for no less than the annihilation 
of the creature. By today, the Web site deja.com had amassed 15,000 
messages just about Jar Jar, with many saying they couldn't stand 
him. Jar Jar, a computer-animated character dropped into the frames 
next to the actors, is a bumbling sidekick who says things like 
``yousa'' and ``meesa'' for ``you'' and ``me.'' 

</P>
<P>
	McGwire Homers in Cardinals' Win  
</P>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Mark McGwire broke up Mark Gardner's no-hit bid  
with a home run with one out in the sixth inning, and drew 
intentional walks his last two at-bats in the St. Louis Cardinals' 
3-2, 12-inning victory. Eric Davis tripled and scored on a wild 
pitch for the winning run. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by GABRIEL MADWAY  
</P>
</TEXT>
