<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Women Tops at Navy Graduation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANNAPOLIS, Md. (AP) -- Women made up 15 percent of the Naval  
Academy's Class of 1999, but they walked away with more than their 
share of honors. 
</P>
<P>
	The top two graduates and five of the top 10 were women.  
</P>
<P>
	It was the best showing yet for women at the academy, where  
class standing depends on more than just good grades. Academy 
officials also consider military competency and conduct (given 
about 25 percent weight) and athletic achievements (10 percent) to 
determine the order of merit. 
</P>
<P>
	Women may have tried harder ``to show we can succeed in the  
military,'' said Josephine Nguyen, who finished second in the class 
of 868 and will enter medical school at Stanford University in the 
fall with hopes of becoming a Navy flight surgeon. 
</P>
<P>
	The top graduate was Mary Godfrey of Dousman, Wis., who was a  
member of the gymnastics team and the glee club. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Nguyen, 21, said her decision to enter the Naval Academy was  
influenced by her father, an officer in the South Vietnamese Navy 
before coming to the United States, and her 25-year-old sister, 
Minh-Tu, who also got her degree Wednesday and was commissioned as 
a Marine second lieutenant. 
</P>
<P>
	She also was motivated by a sense of duty to her adopted  
country: ``You should give something back to the country which has 
provided so much for your family.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990527.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 17:21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IRL, CART Still Won't Make Nice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	We knew they were good at making war.  
</P>
<P>
	But judging by the way things went Thursday, the bigshots at the  
Indy Racing League and Championship Auto Racing Teams still have a 
lot to learn about making nice. 
</P>
<P>
	One day after reports the rival leagues were holding  
face-to-face talks to bring the biggest names in open-wheel racing 
back to the Indianapolis 500, there was nothing to suggest a 
cease-fire was in place. Just the opposite. 
</P>
<P>
	``I get allergies in May. Those CART guys get May whine,'' IRL  
executive director Leo Mehl said. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're all sitting around their `whine' cellars right now,  
watching 50 hours of live TV from here. They're getting a lot of 
pressure from their sponsors to be at Indy and they see more people 
sitting in Turn 3 than they see at any of their tracks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Laughable as Mehl's tirade sounded at the start, it got worse.  
</P>
<P>
	``They know that if they come back, everyone gets the same  
engines and the same chassis, and they'll get their doors blown 
off,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	For nearly four years, the IRL and CART have shown each other as  
much respect as East Coast and West Coast rappers. 
</P>
<P>
	But even with all the dissing back and forth, no one but Mehl  
would dare say that savvy CART veterans Al Unser Jr. and Michael 
Andretti stay up nights worrying about the likes of Stan Wattles 
... Wim Eyckmans ... Tyce Carlson ... Jeret Schroeder. Nice guys, 
sure, and legitimate qualifiers all, but let's face it; those guys 
are more likely to be polishing the doors of Unser's race car than 
blowing them off. 
</P>
<P>
	The IRL guys are so lacking in celebrity that Steve Knapp, last  
year's rookie of the year, thought nothing about approaching the 
league's most recognizable star, Arie Luyendyk, and asking him to 
autograph a racing suit on the first day of practice. 
</P>
<P>
	``At first I thought he was kidding,'' Luyendyk said, ``but he  
was serious. It was a first for me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And then there's this revealing tidbit from Tony Stewart, the  
promising youngster who left the IRL for NASCAR. 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart was born a half-hour from Indy and learned to race in  
open-wheel cars, practically in the shadow of the speedway. This 
year he's going to attempt one of the most intriguing doubles in 
motorsports -- running the Indy 500 in the afternoon, then hopping a 
plane to race in the Coca-Cola 600 in Concord, N.C., that night. 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart is so good he might have a shot at winning both. He won  
three races during his brief IRL stay and led the Indy 500 in all 
three previous tries, finishing second in 1997. But when someone 
asked what would happen if he got squeezed for time, Stewart's 
answer said it all: 
</P>
<P>
	He'd leave Indy early -- even if he were leading with five laps  
to go. 
</P>
<P>
	And that tells you why the IRL and CART will finally put their  
differences aside and make Indy -- the Humpty Dumpty of open-wheel 
racing -- whole again. 
</P>
<P>
	When Indianapolis Motor Speedway boss and IRL founder Tony  
George chased the CART people away from his track, he said they'd 
never prosper without the prestige of the Indy 500. On their way 
out of town, CART kingpins like Roger Penske and Andrew Craig said 
the race would be diminished without the credibility the best 
drivers and teams bring to the event. 
</P>
<P>
	Both were right. It took them nearly four years and wasted  
millions to realize it. The lingering bitterness is why George, in 
acknowledging that negotiations were under way, said, ``I can't say 
I'm encouraged by anything we talked about.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A merger made sense as a business decision within the first year  
after the split. Since then, the IRL and CART have been fighting 
over a steadily declining number of sponsors and fans interested in 
open-wheel racing. 
</P>
<P>
	The corporations and crowds that used to follow either league  
increasingly are looking in the direction of NASCAR. There, without 
competition, and with all the cooperation he could ever want, Bill 
France Jr., adds pieces to his $2 billion-a-year empire almost at 
will. 
</P>
<P>
	And that's the real reason why this deal will get done.  
</P>
<P>
	France, said to be brokering the IRL-CART peace talks, is also  
boss of the International Speedway Corp., which just bought Penske 
Motorsports. Included in the package were 10 racetracks, with at 
least three more planned in the near future. He already has IRL 
racing at a few other sites. 
</P>
<P>
	With George at one elbow and Penske at the other, he can wrap  
his arms around both and knock their heads together until they come 
to their senses. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Litke is a sports columnist for The Associated Press. Write  
to him at:jlitke@ap.org. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
