<DOCNO> APW19990527.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 13:01:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Reform Jews OK Traditional Platform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	The rabbis of Judaism's liberal Reform branch are moving into  
the 21st century by looking backward for inspiration. 
</P>
<P>
	At an annual convention that concluded Wednesday in Pittsburgh,  
the Central Conference of American Rabbis ratified a new 
``Statement of Principles'' that would be barely recognizable to 
the rabbinical framers of the Reform movement. 
</P>
<P>
	It emphasizes the importance of studying Hebrew and the value of  
tradition. For some, that might mean a return to such practices 
such as wearing yarmulkes or keeping kosher. 
</P>
<P>
	At its inception in 1885, the platform for the Reform branch  
spurned Zionism and rejected Jewish ceremonial laws that the rabbis 
considered not in keeping with ``the views and habits of modern 
civilization.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Traditions that regulated diet, ritual purity and dress were  
``entirely foreign to our present mental and spiritual state,'' 
Reform's founders declared. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1999 statement is not binding, so each Reform Jew will  
decide how much of the tradition to adopt. But the text from the 
governing body of the biggest and most liberal major branch of 
American Jewry clearly reflects trends among Reform Jews, and 
American Jews in general. 
</P>
<P>
	``Reform Judaism in its early years was trying to accommodate  
modern society by Protestantizing Judaism,'' said Judith Plaskow, a 
professor of religious studies at Manhattan College who is Jewish. 
</P>
<P>
	``We who grew up in classical Reform congregations were deprived  
of a lot of Jewish knowledge and ritual that could have enriched 
our lives. There is increasing recognition of that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ellis Rivkin, professor emeritus of Jewish history at Reform's  
Hebrew Union College in Cincinnati, said tradition provides younger 
Jews a sense of security in an era when they feel threatened by 
assimilation. 
</P>
<P>
	``They fear there might be a dissolution of Judaism because of  
its openness to the world at large,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Central Conference of American Rabbis has 1.5 million  
members, but the total number of Reform Jews is difficult to 
estimate because many aren't associated with a synagogue. 
</P>
<P>
	Much of the debate at the conference concerned the policy on  
marriage to non-Jews. Some participants were concerned that the 
section could be interpreted as condoning intermarriage, when their 
intent was instead to welcome non-Jews who are willing to convert. 
</P>
<P>
	In Israel, Rabbi Avraham Ravitz of the strictly Orthodox United  
Torah Judaism party, dismissed the new Statement of Principles as 
``just words.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The statement will mean something, he said, when Reform Jews  
``return to observing mitzvot,'' the Hebrew word for deeds 
prescribed by religious law. 
</P>
<P>
	Ravitz also said Reform's shift will not affect the rancorous  
``who-is-a-Jew'' debate in Israel -- and won't change the fact that 
conversions conducted by Reform rabbis do not meet traditional 
requirements of Jewish law. 
</P>
<P>
	However, a Hasidic rabbi in Boston, Shmuel Posner, considers the  
Reform platform ``a tremendous vindication. Judaism is Judaism. You 
can't reform it, reconstruct it, conserve it.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990527.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 00:41:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Combines Work And Play </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	YULEE, Fla. (AP) -- So far during his vacation, President Clinton  
has played golf, ridden bikes with his wife -- and tried to keep 
tabs on the NATO mission in Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton received his daily security briefing on the military  
campaign Wednesday and also made phone calls to Italian Prime 
Minister Massimo D'Alema and Nobel laureate Elie Wiesel. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton and D'Alema spent 30 minutes discussing NATO airstrikes  
against the forces of Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic. The 
president asked Weisel, a Holocaust survivor and author, to travel 
to Macedonia on May 31 as a special envoy to check on refugees from 
Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	``He wants to get a sense of the conditions there and have a  
chance to talk to some of the refugees about the conditions on the 
ground,'' said White House spokesman Joe Lockhart. Wiesel will 
report back directly to Clinton after his trip. 
</P>
<P>
	Any president vacationing during a military conflict opens  
himself to questions about priorities. President Bush was 
criticized for going to his summer home in Kennebunkport, Maine, 
during the Persian Gulf buildup in 1991. But he told reporters, 
``What you don't want to do is appear to be held hostage in the 
White House.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last summer, Clinton sped away from his Martha's Vineyard  
vacation to return to Washington to preside over a U.S. strike on 
suspected terrorist strongholds in Afghanistan and Sudan. In this 
case, Lockhart said Clinton remains in close contact with his 
aides, and is not concerned that it may appear he is being too laid 
back during the ongoing NATO mission. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's important from time to time to take a chance to get  
away,'' Lockhart said. ``I don't think there's any worry on our 
part about the appearances here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton's vacation was planned long before a report on China's  
espionage was released Tuesday by a special committee led by Reps. 
Christopher Cox, R-Calif., and Norman Dicks, D-Wash. 
</P>
<P>
	But Jim Nicholson, the Republican National Committee chairman,  
said through a spokesman that it was appropriate Clinton was 
vacationing at a nature preserve: ``He's joining the ostriches with 
his head in the sand the day after the Cox committee exposed the 
worst case of espionage in U.S. history under his watch.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The White House has stressed that most of the spying detailed in  
the report occurred in the 1980s, when Republicans held the 
presidency, and Lockhart noted that Clinton spoke about the report 
Tuesday in Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton and first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton arrived Tuesday at  
the private wildlife conservation area, off an unmarked dirt road 
about 20 miles north of Jacksonville. They are staying in a 
two-story, five-bedroom house with cedar panels. 
</P>
<P>
	The president brought a bagful of books to help pass the time,  
including ``Sudden Mischief'' by Robert Parker and Carl Hiassen's 
``Lucky You.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the White House said Clinton will address the  
International Labor Organization in Geneva on June 16. The address 
will be the first by a U.S. president to the international body of 
government ministers and the leaders of unions and business 
associations around the globe. 
</P>
<P>
	Administration officials said the ILO speech will offer a deeper  
explanation of Clinton's views on trade and policy proposals to 
protect workers. The ILO, founded 1919, operates on the basis of 
consensus and often is seen as a weak enforcer of international 
labor standards. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990527.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 11:52:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Kept Up To Date on Vacation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	YULEE, Fla. (AP) -- So far during his vacation, President Clinton  
has played golf, ridden bikes with his wife -- and tried to keep 
tabs on the NATO mission in Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	The news that Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic was indicted  
by a war-crimes tribunal drew Clinton out of the house on the White 
Oak nature preserve -- but only as far as the driveway's edge. Clad 
in a blue blazer, yellow tie and khakis, Clinton said the 
indictment ``speaks to the world'' that the NATO mission in Kosovo 
is just. Then he climbed into his sport utility vehicle and rode 
back to his cottage. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton received his daily security briefing on the military  
campaign Wednesday and also made phone calls to Italian Prime 
Minister Massimo D'Alema and Nobel laureate Elie Wiesel. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton and D'Alema spent 30 minutes discussing NATO airstrikes  
against the forces of Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic. The 
president asked Weisel, a Holocaust survivor and author, to travel 
to Macedonia on May 31 as a special envoy to check on refugees from 
Kosovo. 
</P>
