<DOCNO> APW19990527.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 18:52:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmakers Warn of Chinese Backlash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The chief author of the House report detailing  
alleged Chinese espionage and the House's only Chinese-American 
lawmaker joined Thursday in urging Americans not to use the case as 
a reason to discriminate against Chinese and other Asian-Americans. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is just as anti-American to be racist as it is to commit  
espionage,'' said Rep. Christopher Cox, R-Calif., whose special 
panel this week issued a report describing several decades of 
Chinese efforts to obtain and steal U.S. nuclear weapons secrets. 
</P>
<P>
	Cox backed a resolution introduced by Rep. David Wu, D-Ore., the  
House's first Chinese-American, stating that it was wrong for 
Congress and Americans to stereotype people based on the actions of 
any individual. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to be sure that no one is unfairly vilified'' as a  
result of the charges against the Chinese government and the 
suspicions that a Chinese-American scientist at the Los Alamos 
nuclear weapons laboratory supplied China with nuclear secrets, Wu 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Wu co-sponsored the measure with Rep. Tom Campbell, R-Calif.,  
who said Chinese-Americans in his Silicon Valley district are 
keeping a low profile for fear of retribution. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. David Bonior of Michigan, the House Democratic whip, said  
his office was receiving a disturbing number of anti-Asian phone 
calls, a trend that ``must be tackled and nipped at the bud.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Patsy Mink, D-Hawaii, an American of Japanese descent, said  
other Chinese-Americans in top security jobs are ``expressing 
extreme discomfort in the way they are being treated'' because of 
the Chinese spying case. 
</P>
<P>
	Since charges arose that the Chinese tried to make illegal  
contributions to President Clinton's re-election campaign, she 
said, her office has received harassing phone calls when she speaks 
on the House floor. 
</P>
<P>
	Cox accused the Beijing government of enflaming tensions between  
the Chinese and American people with propaganda saying the 
espionage charges were based on anti-Chinese racism. ``It is a 
horrible thing for the Chinese government to whip up.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
