<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 10:11:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Oaklanders Fly Flag for Pride </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- Finally, there is a there there in  
Oakland. 
</P>
<P>
	It's up there in black and white, for anyone to see, flying from  
the top of the city's refurbished landmark, the Oakland Tribune 
tower. 
</P>
<P>
	To counter Gertrude Stein's legendary and often misinterpreted  
line about the city of her youth, a white flag with the word THERE 
in black capital letters now flies over the 21-story building. 
</P>
<P>
	John Protopappas, a developer, arranged to have it put there.  
</P>
<P>
	``Oaklanders understand what she meant,'' he said. ``It's the  
non-Oaklanders that have played up her words.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The disputed phrase came from Stein's 1937 ``Everybody's  
Autobiography'' and described her despair upon finding that her 
childhood home had been razed. Also gone were the rose bushes that 
inspired the line ``a rose is a rose is a rose.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With her usual idiosyncratic punctuation, she wrote: ``Anyway  
what was the use of my having come from Oakland. It was not natural 
to have come from there yes write about it if I like or anything if 
I like but not there there is no there there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Protopappas said he's hoping others in Oakland pick up his  
banner, so to speak. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would be nice to be driving around downtown and see a bunch  
of `There' flags,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
