the noise caused by clattering Russian fans. Two of them will also 
take a spacewalk this weekend to attach one crane and parts of 
another to the outside of the station. 
</P>
<P>
	It's the first flight to the station since shuttle astronauts  
took up the second component in December and attached it to the 
first, which was already in orbit. 
</P>
<P>
	As a result, commander Kent Rominger and his  
U.S.-Canadian-Russian crew will be the first to dock with the 
complex. Rominger, a Navy pilot, will pull up and dock the same way 
it was done during the shuttle-Mir program. 
</P>
<P>
	In November, an unmanned Russian rocket is scheduled to launch  
the next piece of the space station, a service module containing 
life-support systems. Then, NASA's space shuttle Atlantis is 
supposed to follow in December with more equipment. 
</P>
<P>
	However, everything is on hold until the Russian component --  
already more than 1 1/2 years behind -- is in orbit. And many question 
whether the Russians can finish building and testing it by 
November, given the country's economic crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	This service module, in large part, caused the six-month gap in  
shuttle launches. The fleet was grounded for more than 2 1/2 years 
following the 1986 Challenger accident. 
</P>
<P>
	To stay sharp, NASA's launch team conducted extra countdown  
practices during the hiatus and spent extra time reviewing 
procedures. 
</P>
<P>
	It paid off. Discovery's virtually flawless climb to orbit was a  
bright spot amid a number of recent failed launches of unmanned 
rockets. 
</P>
<P>
	Three satellites ended up in useless orbits and another was  
vaporized shortly after launch, all since April. In addition, two 
satellites were destroyed in launch explosions last August. None of 
the six satellites belonged to the National Aeronautics and Space 
Administration. 
</P>
<P>
	``It did not bother me, although I sensed in the surrounding  
community there was a heightened expectation, or a heightened 
awareness of the potential for failure,'' said Donald McMonagle, a 
launch manager. ``But I'm very happy to say we have, in fact, a 
good vehicle.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Discovery is due back June 6.  
</P>
