<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mavericks Give Trent Maui Vacation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- The Dallas Mavericks can't pay Gary Trent more  
than $5 million over two years. They can't guarantee him a shot at 
the NBA title. 
</P>
<P>
	They can, however, offer him fun in the sun.  
</P>
<P>
	Trent, his fiancee, infant son, parents and future mother-in-law  
are off to Maui for a week of entertainment courtesy of the 
Mavericks. Dallas hopes the goodwill gesture will convince him to 
re-sign with the team. 
</P>
<P>
	``We just want to rub his belly and let him know we love him,''  
Mavericks general manager-coach Don Nelson told The Dallas Morning 
News. 
</P>
<P>
	The 6-foot-8, 250-pound forward signed a one-year deal with  
Dallas after the lockout and had the kind of season expected when 
he was a lottery pick four years ago: 16 points and 7.8 rebounds 
per game. 
</P>
<P>
	Trent, who finished third in voting for the Most Improved Player  
award, could cash in when he becomes a free agent July 1. The 
Mavericks are trying to take advantage of the fact they have 
exclusive negotiating rights until then. 
</P>
<P>
	``My opinion hasn't changed; there's no better place for Gary  
Trent than right here,'' Nelson said. ``I'll keep trying to 
convince him of that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Teams usually can offer their own players longterm deals without  
salary-cap restraints, but Trent must be on the roster two more 
years for that option. As a result, other teams with more money 
available under the cap can offer him more lucrative deals. 
</P>
<P>
	Nelson, who has a home in Maui, called the team's unique  
approach ``recruiting with no rules.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``You name it, and we're doing it,'' Nelson said. ``But I ain't  
getting on that fishing boat. I get sick.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Point guard Steve Nash said he's glad the team is being  
proactive. 
</P>
<P>
	``Thank God somebody is doing something about keeping him,''  
Nash said. ``We need him.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990527.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 00:41:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Homeschooled Boy Wins Geography Bee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Much of what David Beihl has learned about the  
world, he's learned at home. Those lessons paid off when he became 
the first homeschooled student to win the National Geography Bee. 
</P>
<P>
	He won Wednesday by correctly answering that ``La Nina'' is the  
Spanish name for the weather condition characterized by unusually 
cold ocean temperatures in the equatorial region of the eastern 
Pacific Ocean. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've had lots of time to study. My schedule is more flexible  
than some other schools,'' said David, 13, of Saluda, S.C., He has 
been taught at home since kindergarten. 
</P>
<P>
	David's brother, Tom, 11, and sister, Debbie, 9, are also taught  
at home by their mother, Penny Beihl, 39, who has a master's degree 
in elementary and secondary education. 
</P>
<P>
	``We live way out in the country,'' said his father, Gary Beihl,  
39, who commutes an hour each way to his engineering job with Intel 
in Columbia, S.C. ``It makes us closer as a family.'' 
</P>
<P>
	David outlasted Jason Borschow, a 13-year-old eighth-grader at  
Saint John's School in Condado, just outside San Juan, Puerto Rico. 
Jason answered ``El Nino,'' to the weather question in the 
championship round of the National Geographic Society's nationwide 
geography competition. However, the word's male gender 
characterizes warm weather conditions, said moderator Alex Trebek, 
who usually serves as host of the television game show 
``Jeopardy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``You have to be calm and not blurt the answer out. You have to  
take your time and consider all the possibilities,'' said Jason, a 
three-time finalist who admitted that in the end he did not follow 
his own advice. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Jason and David were returning participants to the annual  
competition. Jason represented Puerto Rico last year and in 1997. 
David represented South Carolina last year. 
</P>
<P>
	They were among the 10 to make the finals Wednesday in the 11th  
annual competition at the society's Washington headquarters. The 
field was narrowed from 55 on Tuesday. Each contestant represented 
fourth- to eighth-graders from each state, the District of 
Columbia, Department of Defense Schools and each of the five U.S. 
territories. More than 5 million students ages 10 to 15 competed in 
their schools and states earlier this year. 
</P>
<P>
	David received a $25,000 scholarship from the society and a  
seven-day trip to Sydney, Australia, from this year's corporate 
sponsor, Bank One. 
</P>
<P>
	Jason got a $15,000 scholarship for second place. Tanveer Ali,  
13, an eighth-grader from Flint, Mich., won $10,000 for his 
third-place finish. He attends Carman-Ainsworth Junior High School 
in Flint. 
</P>
<P>
	David correctly answered all three championship round questions,  
while his opponent answered just two. In addition to the La Nina 
question, David correctly answered ``Dhaka'' when asked, ``In 1998, 
a bridge across the Jamuna River was completed about 65 miles 
northwest of what capital city?'' Dhaka is the capital of 
Bangladesh. 
</P>
<P>
	And he accurately responded, ``Honduras,'' when quizzed on which  
Central American country is the only one with direct access to the 
Pacific Ocean through the Gulf of Fonseca. 
</P>
<P>
	``He always makes us sweat bullets,'' joked Gary Beihl, who  
attributed the success of his son to homeschooling. David will 
remain in Washington for next week's Scripps Howard National 
Spelling Bee. A 13-year-old New York girl educated at home won the 
spelling bee in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	The geography bee's final contest was close as many of the  
youngsters answered several questions before being eliminated. At 
one point, Trebek joked that he would run out of questions before 
contestants. 
</P>
<P>
	The other finalists from Wednesday's rounds received $500.  

</P>
</TEXT>
