<HEADLINE> Wis. Man Charged With Hate Crimes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KENOSHA, Wis. (AP) -- A white man accused of driving onto a  
sidewalk to hit two black teen-agers on bikes has been charged with 
attempted murder and ordered to stand trial. 
</P>
<P>
	James G. Langenbach, 27, intentionally swerved his car and sped  
toward the 14-year-old boys as they rode their bicycles May 16, 
police allege. 
</P>
<P>
	A man riding a motorcycle behind Langenbach's car testified at a  
preliminary hearing Wednesday that he saw the car swerve up the 
curb and on the sidewalk about 30 feet behind the boys. 
</P>
<P>
	``In my opinion, it was floored,'' Dino Gigliotti said  
Wednesday. ``He accelerated all the way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Charges were upgraded Wednesday to two counts each of attempted  
murder while armed with a dangerous weapon, causing great bodily 
harm to a child with a dangerous weapon and leaving the scene of an 
injury accident. 
</P>
<P>
	The new charges also include a hate crime provision, which can  
add up to five years in prison and $5,000 in fines to each charge. 
</P>
<P>
	If convicted, Langenbach faces 120 years in prison on the  
attempted murder charges, 60 years on the assault charges and 16 
years on the flight charges. 
</P>
<P>
	One boy has been released from the hospital. The other was in  
satisfactory condition Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Langenbach has a history of run-ins with police and has been  
treated for psychiatric problems, records show. He had been placed 
on probation for ramming his car into a van carrying five black men 
eight years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Langenbach remained jailed in lieu of $200,000 cash bond, with  
no date set for him to plead to the charges. Public defender Dennis 
Egre, Langenbach's attorney, declined to comment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
