<DOCNO> APW19990527.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 18:21:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sprewell Unhappy Being Sixth Man </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PURCHASE, N.Y. (AP) -- Latrell Sprewell looked back Thursday on  
his first season with the Knicks, pronouncing himself happy in 
general but still unconvinced he's best suited to be the team's 
sixth man. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've accepted it, more or less,'' Sprewell said after the  
Knicks held a three-hour practice to prepare for the Indiana Pacers 
in the Eastern Conference finals. ``I'm accepting it because I know 
that's the way it's going to be and I can't change it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sprewell's displeasure at being brought off the bench has been  
an issue with the Knicks since the midpoint of the season, when he 
returned from a foot injury that cost him his early-season spot in 
the starting five. 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Jeff Van Gundy has persistently maintained that the team  
has a better chance to win with Sprewell coming off the bench, and 
that line of thinking -- Van Gundy's critics call it a stubborn 
streak -- doesn't figure to change in the conference finals. 
</P>
<P>
	But as for next season, Sprewell's agent is on record as saying  
he'll demand a trade if his client isn't a starter. And with 
Sprewell about to enter the final year of his contract, there are 
plenty of people around New York who feel the team might be better 
off trading him for a top-notch point guard. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not worried about next year, I'm thinking about this year  
and especially the game on Sunday,'' Sprewell said. ``I think I've 
handled it pretty well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sprewell has been the Knicks' leading scorer in the postseason,  
averaging 19.0 points in 32.7 minutes after averaging 16.4 points 
and 33.3 minutes in the regular season. 
</P>
<P>
	When he played for Golden State, Sprewell usually averaged  
around 40 minutes per game and -- as he'll tell you -- consistently 
ranked among the top five in that category leaguewide. 
</P>
<P>
	The argument has been made that Van Gundy is keeping three of  
his best five players under wraps because Sprewell has been more 
consistent than starter Alan Houston, Chris Childs has played 
better than starting point guard Charlie Ward, and Marcus Camby has 
outplayed starting power forward Kurt Thomas. 
</P>
<P>
	Van Gundy's insistence on adhering so strictly with his favored  
rotation is sure to be one of the questions he'll be asked by 
acting team president Dave Checketts when the two sit down at the 
end of the season to discuss whether the coach will return. It's 
yet another angle among the different power struggles that have 
taken place with the Knicks this season. 
</P>
<P>
	Thus far in the postseason, Van Gundy has only been willing to  
insert Sprewell into the game a minute or two earlier if the team 
gets off to a poor start. In their nine playoff games, the Knicks 
have been trailing or tied four times when Sprewell has checked in 
for the first time. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody knows he wants to start, but I think he's accepted  
that role as the go-to guy off the bench,'' said Camby, one of 
Sprewell's closest friends on a cliquish team whose newer additions 
don't hang out with the holdovers from last season. ``As soon as he 
gets off the bench, the Garden goes crazy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Camby is one of Sprewell's few allies on the Knicks, but the two  
did not know each other until both got to New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Like the public at large, Camby had a preconceived notion of  
what the real Sprewell was like. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought he would be this rowdy guy who goes out every night  
and talks a lot, but he's really quiet and keeps to himself,'' 
Camby said. 
</P>
<P>
	In the locker room and at practice, however, Sprewell is more  
talkative than any of his teammates. It is not uncommon for him to 
answer patiently questions for 20 minutes or more, part of his 
effort to rehabilitate his image following the choking attack on 
Golden State coach P.J. Carlesimo that he became so infamous for. 
</P>
<P>
	But for every step forward that Sprewell takes, there are those  
who feel he takes a step backward and acts selfish by expressing 
his displeasure with coming off the bench. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody wants to start in this league, and Latrell,  
rightfully so, wants to start, too,'' Childs said. ``But he's 
figured out that's he still going to get the amount of minutes that 
he would get as a starter and he's going to be in the game down the 
stretch. You always want to start, but that's something that he has 
to talk about after the season.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
