<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Help-Wanted Ads Declined in April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Help-wanted advertising in the nation's major  
newspapers declined slightly in April, but demand for jobs still 
remains strong, according to a study released Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Conference Board, a private business research group, said  
its monthly advertising index dipped to 87 last month from 88 in 
March. The index, based on 100, was 90 in April 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	``The seven-year trend of strong hiring is not about to fold  
up,'' said Conference Board economist Ken Goldstein. 
</P>
<P>
	Goldstein predicted that consumer spending and growth in wages  
will help create hundreds of thousands of new jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	The regions with the largest declines in help-wanted ads in the  
last three months were the East North Central, which includes Ohio, 
Illinois, Indiana, Wisconsin and Michigan, and New England, which 
includes Massachusetts, Connecticut and Rhode Island. 
</P>
<P>
	Increases in help-wanted ads occurred in the Middle Atlantic  
region, including New York and Pennsylvania, and East South 
Central, including Tennessee, Alabama and Kentucky. 
</P>
<P>
	The seasonally adjusted advertising index, which stood at 100 in  
the base year of 1987, is derived from measuring the volume of 
employment ads in 51 major newspapers across the country each 
month. It is used as a nongovernmental gauge of changes in local, 
regional and national job supply. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
