<HEADLINE> D-Backs Call Up Pitching Sensation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- Minor league sensation Byung-Hyun Kim's  
apprenticeship in Triple-A ended for the time being Thursday, when 
the Arizona Diamondbacks recalled him from Tucson. 
</P>
<P>
	The 20-year-old Korean right-hander, who gets four different  
breaks on his slider out of a submarine-style delivery, will join 
the Diamondbacks in New York on Friday for the first game of a 
series against the Mets. 
</P>
<P>
	``He has been pitching with a maturity far beyond his years,''  
team general manager Joe Garagiola Jr. said. 
</P>
<P>
	Right-hander Bobby Chouinard was optioned to Tucson to make  
room. 
</P>
<P>
	Injuries gave the Diamondbacks a reason to accelerate Kim's  
progress to the majors. 
</P>
<P>
	The team put Todd Stottlemyre on the disabled list last week  
when he tore his rotator cuff, and replaced him in the rotation 
with Brian Anderson. 
</P>
<P>
	The bullpen was short because of Darren Holmes' back problems.  
Holmes, who had a shot Tuesday to kill the pain caused by a bulging 
disk, is on the roster but won't be available for action until at 
least this weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Kim, who began the season with Double-A El Paso, has been a  
starter in Tucson but was expected to work out of the Diamondbacks' 
bullpen. 
</P>
<P>
	Kim attracted attention last June, when he struck out 15 U.S.  
Olympic Team batters in 6 2-3 innings. He pitched three hitless 
innings of relief against the U.S. team later last summer, and Clay 
Daniel, the Diamondbacks' international scouting director, signed 
him as a free agent this spring. 
</P>
<P>
	So far, Kim is undefeated as a pro.  
</P>
<P>
	He was 2-0 with a 2.11 ERA in 10 relief appearances at Double-A  
El Paso. Promoted to Tucson two weeks ago, he was 2-0 with a 2.60 
ERA in three starts, striking out 21 and allowing 13 hits in 17 1-3 
innings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
