<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore: GOP, NRA Fighting Gun Laws </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore called today for quick  
House action on gun control and accused Republicans of plotting to 
please the gun lobby by delaying a vote on Senate-passed 
restrictions. 
</P>
<P>
	The delay, Gore told reporters at the Capitol, ``is because some  
within the Republican caucus are so responsive to the'' National 
Rifle Association. 
</P>
<P>
	``At this very moment there are some of the other side meeting  
behind closed doors plotting to have more delays in order to 
preserve loopholes'' in firearms law, he asserted. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans have refused Democratic demands to pass the Senate's  
gun provisions this week, outlining instead a schedule for cautious 
consideration of the provisions and a vote in mid-June. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is a Second Amendment, there is a fundamental right that  
we're dealing with and therefore we should move expeditiously but 
not in a stampede,'' Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., who chairs the House 
Judiciary Committee, said Wednesday. ``We're going to do this and 
we're going to do it right.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore's comments came a week after he broke a tie vote as the  
Senate passed a Democratic measure to require background checks of 
all firearms transactions at gun shows and pawn shops. 
</P>
<P>
	The presidential candidate said the Senate bill didn't go far  
enough in gun restrictions and that the House should pass a tougher 
bill. He did not specify what additional provisions he would 
support. 
</P>
<P>
	House GOP leaders have said they support the concept of the gun  
restrictions in the Senate bill but called a hearing today to 
investigate the specifics. Speaker Dennis Hastert and other GOP 
leaders have refused Democratic demands that they approve at least 
some of the Senate gun restrictions before mid-July. 
</P>
<P>
	Appearing with Gore, House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo.,  
and about a dozen other congressional Democrats was a Virginia 
woman planning to testify later today before the House Judiciary 
crime subcommittee. 
</P>
<P>
	Byrl Phillips-Taylor of Richmond, Va., said she was turning her  
grief over her son's murder to gun control activism. Clutching a 
photograph of her son, Scott, Phillips-Taylor told reporters that 
he had been killed eight years ago by a ``classmate with a grudge'' 
and an AK-47. 
</P>
<P>
	Scott, 17, was lured by the classmate from his place of work and  
shot six times. 
</P>
<P>
	Also set to testify before the House subcommittee were NRA  
officials, the father of one of the murdered Columbine High School 
students and a Denver trauma surgeon who worked on some of the 
victims of those shootings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
