<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Alonzo Newby To Take the Fifth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- A central figure in the allegations of  
academic fraud in the University of Minnesota men's basketball 
program will not cooperate with investigators, his attorney said. 
</P>
<P>
	Alonzo Newby, who is on disability leave from his job as the  
team's academic counselor, will invoke his right to remain silent, 
his attorney, Ron Rosenbaum, said Wednesday in a letter to the 
university's outside investigators. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators want to ask Newby about allegations he made a cash  
payment to former office manager Jan Gangelhoff to tutor players at 
a time when she wasn't supposed to be associated with the program, 
and that he arranged for players' grades to be changed to keep them 
eligible. 
</P>
<P>
	University administrators said they were disappointed because  
they know of nothing Newby did that would warrant any criminal 
prosecution or liability. They said his refusal to testify may 
hamper the investigation, but suggested that his attorney may have 
left the door open for future questioning. 
</P>
<P>
	``We would genuinely like to get Mr. Newby's side of the  
story,'' said Tonya Moten Brown, chief of staff to President Mark 
Yudof. ``I think it's important for the integrity of the program 
that the truth be known. And I think we do not want negative 
inferences to be drawn by his failure to cooperate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although investigators are still negotiating with other  
witnesses, Newby is the first who has declined to participate, 
Brown said. 
</P>
<P>
	Yudof has ordered all university employees to cooperate with  
investigators. Brown said firing Newby is an option if he does not 
cooperate. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown said 120 people other than Newby may contribute useful  
information to the investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Rosenbaum said he is concerned that Newby is being set up to  
take the fall for others at the university and that the 
investigation would only serve as a means to prosecute his client. 
</P>
<P>
	``We would be in a much better position if the major newspapers  
and the university said they are done investigating and these are 
all the facts,'' Rosenbaum told the Saint Paul Pioneer Press. ``But 
I don't think that is going to happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In a related matter, Yudof met for an hour Wednesday with some  
of the students who demonstrated on campus Monday against what they 
consider special treatment for athletes accused of sexual 
misconduct. 
</P>
<P>
	Prior to the meeting, they sent Yudof an open letter with four  
demands. He accepted all of them. 
</P>
<P>
	``I basically agreed with all four points they had made in the  
letter -- that we needed a prompt investigation, and we needed to 
look into structural changes,'' Yudof said afterward. 
</P>
<P>
	The president also agreed to a public apology if it is proved  
that university officials thwarted efforts to report sexual 
offenses, and he agreed to establish a protocol for protecting 
alleged victims during the investigation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
