<DOCNO> APW19990527.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 22:41:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Another Playoff Failure for Malone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- In a career marked by numerous playoff  
failures, Karl Malone was miserable again Thursday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``This has to rank up there as one of the toughest losses in my  
career,'' Malone said after shooting 3-for-16 and scoring just 8 
points -- his lowest output in 148 career postseason games -- as the 
Jazz were eliminated from the Western Conference semifinals 92-80 
by the Portland Trail Blazers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hornacek, Stockton, (Bryon) Russell -- they all came up big.  
Everybody did, except for me,'' Malone said. ``If I could have done 
anything, we could have won. 
</P>
<P>
	``You win with pride, and you lose the same way.''  
</P>
<P>
	The veteran nucleus of the Jazz -- Malone, John Stockton and Jeff  
Hornacek -- are 35, 37 and 36 years old, respectively. All will be 
free agents this summer, and there again will be a chorus of voices 
claiming the team has gone as far as it can with them. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not the one who controls who'll be back, but I think we  
will be back,'' Malone said. ``I don't know why not.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Malone and Stockton have won with pride for the last 14 seasons,  
reaching the playoffs every season. They were in the conference 
finals four times in five seasons, and may have won a title or two 
if Michael Jordan hadn't come back from the baseball diamond. 
</P>
<P>
	They also might have a ring or two if Malone had come through in  
the clutch in key games. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1996, he missed two free throws late in Game 7 of the  
conference finals at Seattle that could have put the Jazz in the 
finals. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997, he missed two free throws at the end of in Game 1 of  
the NBA Finals at Chicago, opening the door for Jordan's 
buzzer-beating jumper that won it. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1998, he had the ball stolen from him by Jordan, leading to  
his famous title-winning jumper seconds later. 
</P>
<P>
	The Jazz were noticeably a step slower in the postseason this  
time. They were outhustled and nearly beaten in the first round by 
Sacramento, and their normally machine-like offense sputtered 
against the young, deep Blazers. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've been a little spoiled by the success of being to the  
Finals two years in a row,'' Hornacek said. ``But you can't just 
give up. I don't expect any retirements.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stockton ducked out of the locker room after the game and did  
not speak to reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some of our guys aren't 19 years old anymore,'' Jazz coach  
Jerry Sloan said. ``Are we done? We've been answering these 
questions for the last six years. I think they will be around a 
little longer. They have a right to come back.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
