<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Down 207.23 in Stock Selloff / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks resumed a downward lurch today as  
continued concerns about interest rates and inflation put the 
brakes on Wednesday's rally. 
</P>
<P>
	At 3 p.m. on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
down 207.23 at 10,494.93, more than wiping out Wednesday's gain. As 
the selloff deepened this afternoon, the Dow at one point was down 
as much as 267 points. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were mostly lower. The Standard &AMP;  
Poor's 500 index was down 18.27 at 1,286.49. The Nasdaq composite 
index, which is dominated by technology stocks, was holding on to a 
gain of 0.66, taking it to 2,427.82. 
</P>
<P>
	Even as the Nasdaq dipped repeatedly into negative territory,  
analysts attributed the stronger performance to bargain-hunting 
following a sharp selloff of Internet stocks early this week. 
</P>
<P>
	``Those stocks had been already been beaten up pretty badly, so  
today, they're resisting the decline of the rest of the market,'' 
said Robert Robbins, senior vice president and market strategist at 
Robinson-Humphrey Co. Inc. of Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow rose 171.07 points Wednesday, a gain of 1.6 percent, to  
close at 10,702.16. The rally was fed by big gains from IBM and a 
slight resurgence of Internet companies that have slid in recent 
sessions. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the selling today was attributed to investors cashing in  
on Wednesday's rally in advance of the Memorial Day weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, continued fears that inflation will prompt the  
Federal Reserve to raise interest rates drew investors away from 
stocks. Higher interest rates can crimp corporate profits as it 
becomes more expensive for companies to borrow money. 
</P>
<P>
	New government figures on the economy today kept the market off  
balance. The Commerce Department said the U.S. economy grew at a 
robust annual rate of 4.1 percent in the first quarter, yet an 
inflation gauge tied to the report rose a modest 1.1 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Bond prices tumbled, sending the yield up to 5.84 percent from  
5.80 percent late Wednesday and further pressuring stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet the government also said corporate profits showed a big  
rebound in the first three months of this year, increasing at an 
annual rate of $31.8 billion after having fallen at a rate of $5.3 
billion in the fourth quarter of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	That wasn't enough to entice buyers.  
</P>
<P>
	``There hasn't been any catalyst to bring people into the  
marketplace,'' said Barry Berman, head trader for Robert W. Baird &AMP; 
Co. in Milwaukee. The upcoming three-day holiday may also 
discourage money managers from taking big new positions, Berman 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	IBM fell 4 1/16 to 114 1/16 today, following a 2-for-1 stock  
split that took effect after the close of trading Wednesday. Some 
analysts also blamed persistent worries that computer makers will 
see their profit margins shrink as they cut prices to compete. 
</P>
<P>
	Bank and brokerage stocks, which typically suffer when interest  
rates rise, were mostly lower. J.P. Morgan was off 3 3/4 at 135 1/8, and 
Bank of America fell 2 3/4 to 63 1/4. 
</P>
<P>
	And cyclical stocks, which have risen in recent weeks, fell as  
investors locked in their gains. 3M slipped 3 7/8 to 84 15/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 13-to-6 margin on  
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 639.7 million 
shares at late afternoon, trailing Wednesday's brisk pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index was down 8.74 at 616.10, and the  
American Stock Exchange composite index was down 7.01 at 775.65. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
