<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sallie Mae Buys Student Loan Maker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Sallie Mae, the nation's largest financer of  
student loans, has made its first big strategic move since becoming 
private, agreeing to buy a New England student loan maker for $320 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	The acquisition was announced Wednesday by Sallie Mae, once a  
government-sponsored company that went private two years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Nellie Mae, with offices in Braintree, Mass., and Rumford, R.I.,  
is the seventh-largest holder of federal student loans with a 
portfolio valued at $2.6 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the agreement, Nellie Mae will become a subsidiary of  
Reston, Va.-based Sallie Mae and will retain its New England 
operations and regional sales offices across the country. 
</P>
<P>
	As a result of the deal, Sallie Mae will be making more than $1  
billion a year in loans for study at nearly 250 colleges and 
universities by next year, Albert Lord, Sallie Mae's chief 
executive officer and vice chairman, told reporters in a telephone 
conference call. 
</P>
<P>
	``It fits right into our strategy ... of expanding our presence  
on campus,'' said Paul Carey, executive vice president of Sallie 
Mae. 
</P>
<P>
	The acquisition must be approved by the Justice Department and  
Massachusetts' attorney general. Sallie Mae officials said they 
expect it to be completed by June 30. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are pleased to combine resources with Sallie Mae to  
continue to build the premier full-service education finance 
company,'' Lawrence O'Toole, president and CEO of Nellie Mae, said 
in a statement. He said the combination would enhance Nellie Mae's 
ability ``to serve our campus-based clients, students and family 
borrowers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sallie Mae, officially named the Student Loan Marketing  
Association, was a federally chartered enterprise and the nation's 
largest buyer of government-guaranteed student loans from banks 
before it became a private company. 
</P>
<P>
	It still buys many student loans from banks but also competes  
with banks by making loans directly to students and schools. Sallie 
Mae currently holds and manages $47 billion in student loans for 
more than 5 million borrowers. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of its parent company, SLM Holding Corp., were up 6 1/4  
cents at $41.18 3/4 Wednesday on the New York Stock Exchange. 


</P>
</TEXT>
