<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Indians' Wright To Meet With Budig </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- Jaret Wright's reputation took another beaning  
last weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Oops, that slipped. Make that took another beating.  
</P>
<P>
	The Cleveland Indians have been involved in two bench-clearing  
incidents this season, and both times the infield wrestling matches 
came soon after Wright hit an opposing batter in the head with a 
pitch. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month in Boston, Wright hit Red Sox outfielder Darren  
Lewis, the same player he plunked during the playoffs in October. 
Then last Saturday, Detroit first baseman Tony Clark got drilled in 
the batting helmet by one of Wright's fastballs. 
</P>
<P>
	Wright denied throwing at either hitter. Because of a past which  
includes breaking New York second baseman Luis Sojo's hand during 
spring training last year, however, Wright may be getting a 
reputation as a headhunter. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, Wright was fined by AL president Gene Budig for his  
role in Saturday's brawl. Budig also said he would meet with Wright 
and manager Mike Hargrove next Tuesday in New York to discuss the 
pitcher's ``deportment on the mound.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a concern that he might be getting that reputation,''  
Hargrove said. ``I don't agree with it, but word has gotten around 
the league that Jaret is not afraid to pitch inside -- and he does. 
You've got to pitch inside to pitch well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Indians GM John Hart said he spoke with Budig following last  
weekend's incident, and was surprised to learn that Wright was 
fined. Hart said he didn't know what Budig planned to discuss with 
the pitcher. 
</P>
<P>
	``None of us wants to see Jaret told how to pitch,'' Hart said.  
</P>
<P>
	While the Indians and Tigers were finger-pointing as they paired  
off in the infield like a hockey fight, some of the Tigers made 
references to Wright's history of dusting batters. 
</P>
<P>
	Wright, who during the fracas got wrestled down from behind by  
Detroit manager Larry Parrish, said his 0-2 fastball to Clark just 
got away from him. Wright's body language said the same as his 
shoulders slumped and he took a few steps toward the plate to see 
how Clark was. 
</P>
<P>
	``I needed an out there,'' Wright said. ``I was upset with  
myself because I hit him in the head. That's not what I was trying 
to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clark believed Wright. Others weren't so sure.  
</P>
<P>
	Hart thinks perception is blurring reality. If Wright is guilty  
of anything, Hart says it's being young, confident and blessed with 
a live, sometimes erratic arm. 
</P>
<P>
	``With Jaret, all you have to do is watch his games,'' Hart  
said. ``This guy is not blessed with the greatest of command. This 
is a guy that's still trying to find where the ball is going to 
begin with. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think a lot of this is overblown. You go back to Boston, and  
Jaret hit Lewis with a breaking ball. I mean, come on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wright refuses to give up the inside part of the plate, a tactic  
that has been used by power pitchers throughout baseball history. 
Hart, who caught in the minor leagues for the Montreal Expos, 
remembers former Dodgers pitcher Don Drysdale teaching young 
pitchers not to be afraid to move hitters off the plate -- or off 
their feet. 
</P>
<P>
	``Drysdale would tell them, two line drives and next guy goes  
down,'' Hart said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hart thinks Wright's tough-guy demeanor on the mound may add to  
the perception that he's throwing at hitters. 
</P>
<P>
	``Jaret is a tough kid, now question about it,'' he said. ``He's  
got kind of a football mentality out there. He comes after you. He 
wants to win. He wants to compete. That mentality, that presence 
out there on the mound maybe incites a little bit more than what 
the reality of the situation is. 
</P>
<P>
	``But looking at all the things that go into it. This young man  
is not a head hunter. Period.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wright's situation is similar to that of Boston's Pedro  
Martinez, said Hart. Martinez came into the majors as a 
hot-tempered, hard-thrower with Montreal, and after a few too many 
brushbacks, it wasn't long before he got labeled a headhunter. 
</P>
<P>
	But time has improved Martinez's control and his image. Now he's  
regarded as one of baseball's best pitchers. 
</P>
<P>
	``He had a reputation for throwing at people for the first two  
or three years, and then he took off,'' Hart said. ``I know Jaret 
is not out there throwing at guys' heads. It's hard to live down a 
reputation like that, but I think he eventually will.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
