<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> O'Hare May Offer Gambling Gateway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ROSEMONT, Ill. (AP) -- Got a long layover in Chicago and some  
extra change? 
</P>
<P>
	The Illinois Legislature this week approved a measure that  
allows casino gambling in Cook County, a bill Gov. George Ryan has 
said he will probably sign. 
</P>
<P>
	The casino's likely location is in Rosemont, just minutes from  
O'Hare International Airport, the world's second-busiest with 
200,000 passengers a day. Atlanta Hartsfield Airport is the 
busiest. 
</P>
<P>
	A Rosemont casino is sure to attract hordes of Chicagoans  
because it would be closer than other Illinois casinos, and 
Rosemont is accessible by the city's elevated trains. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is going to be big, real big,'' said an excited Tony  
Matassa, who owns a sandwich shop not far from the airport. 
``Everybody coming over from the airport, the employees going in 
and out, they're all going to come and eat.'' 
</P>
<P>
	No other major U.S. air hub has a casino so close, though there  
are slot machines in the terminals at airports in Las Vegas and 
Reno, Nev. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have the opportunity to attract these visitors from across  
the nation who fly into O'Hare,'' said Peter Lombardi, executive 
director of the Rosemont Convention Bureau. ``If they're delayed 
two or three hours, they can hop in a cab or the train and be here 
in a minute. Then they can get back on a plane.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Currently, the closest Illinois casino to Chicago is the Grand  
Victoria in Elgin, 15 miles west of Rosemont. It's not as easy to 
reach from the city or airport, and Grand Victoria officials fear a 
Rosemont casino will siphon off a big chunk of their business. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a simple matter of convenience,'' general manager Pete  
Dominguez said. ``People will only go as far as they have to go.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Whether a casino near the airport will pull most of its money  
from travelers' wallets is open to debate. 
</P>
<P>
	Maryland Heights, Mo., is a suburb of 25,000 people about a  
10-minute drive from the St. Louis airport. Like Rosemont, it has a 
thriving hospitality industry, with 1 million visitors a year 
staying in its hotels. 
</P>
<P>
	Even so, ``the casinos estimate perhaps 20 percent of their  
patrons come from outside of the immediate region,'' city 
administrator Mark Levin said. ``Most of the money comes from in 
and around the St. Louis metro area.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But gambling critics disregard the notion that casinos attract  
tourists and help boost the local economy. 
</P>
<P>
	``Gambling really hasn't brought in tourism,'' said Steve Taylor  
of the anti-gambling organization Casino Watch. ``All you're 
getting is local convenience gambling.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ten casinos have been licensed to operate in Illinois. Only one  
licenseholder would be eligible to take advantage of the 
Legislature's action -- the owners of a failed riverboat casino in 
East Dubuque. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
