<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 04:32:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Strawberry Baseball Future Shaky </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TAMPA, Fla. (AP) -- Avoiding jail didn't free Darryl Strawberry  
to resume his baseball career. 
</P>
<P>
	The New York Yankees outfielder pleaded no contest to drug and  
solicitation charges Wednesday, but it's unclear if or when he will 
be reinstated to play. 
</P>
<P>
	``The next step is between major league baseball and Darryl,''  
said Yankees general manager Brian Cashman. ``After that issue is 
resolved, we will make a decision.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Strawberry was sentenced to 18 months of probation and ordered  
to undergo testing for drugs twice a week. He is prohibited from 
going within 100 feet of bars, required to complete more drug 
treatment and perform 100 hours of community service. 
</P>
<P>
	In the meantime, he remains on leave from the Yankees and faces  
possible suspension as a multiple offender of baseball's drug 
aftercare program. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now that Darryl Strawberry's legal proceeding has been  
resolved, I will promptly review all of the facts and circumstances 
surrounding this matter in order to determine what action is 
appropriate under baseball's drug policy,'' commissioner Bud Selig 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The commissioner added that he would consult with medical  
advisers from baseball, as well as the players' union. 
</P>
<P>
	Yankees manager Joe Torre said he couldn't discuss Strawberry's  
status until baseball decides what to do. 
</P>
<P>
	``My concern is about Darryl as a person,'' Torre said at Yankee  
Stadium. ``In my four years here, he has been nothing but a model 
citizen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to ordering Strawberry to stay out of bars, Florida  
Circuit Judge Jack Espinosa Jr. asked local law enforcement 
officials to provide the athlete with a map of Tampa ``hot spots'' 
to avoid. 
</P>
<P>
	Strawberry, accompanied by his wife, Charisse, and lawyer Joseph  
Ficarrotta, apologized outside Hillsborough County courthouse. He 
spoke from a handwritten statement before riding off in a white 
van. 
</P>
<P>
	At the time of his arrest April 14, the eight-time All-Star was  
in Tampa working out in hopes of making a comeback from colon 
cancer surgery in October. 
</P>
<P>
	``My recovery has not been easy,'' he said. ``I am, however,  
committed to it and now that I have finished chemotherapy and feel 
healthy, I'm looking forward to the future.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Strawberry, 37, was charged with possession of 0.3 grams of  
cocaine and offering an undercover female police officer $50 for 
sex. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither Strawberry nor his lawyer answered questions outside  
court. Ficarrotta said Strawberry pleaded no contest ``to get this 
matter behind us and to go forward with his life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors insisted the outfielder did not get special  
treatment. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is his first criminal drug offense,'' said assistant  
state attorney Pam Bondi. ``That's why he was placed on probation 
with intensive drug treatment and community service.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Following the arrest, Strawberry was placed on administrative  
leave that barred him from training or playing for the Yankees or 
any of their farm teams. 
</P>
<P>
	The Yankees have struggled at times this season, and Torre  
conceded there have been occasions that having Strawberry on the 
team might have helped. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you are losing games and leaving men on base, you tend to  
look for more bats,'' he said. ``There have been a few games where 
we could really use a left-handed bat off the bench. 
</P>
<P>
	``Straw is an imposing figure. He intimidates the opposition. It  
is a nice weapon to have.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
