<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Suspect Fingered in Atheist Death </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- A former office manager for Madalyn Murray  
O'Hair killed the missing atheist, her son and her granddaughter 
out of hatred and greed, according to an affidavit from an agent of 
the Internal Revenue Service. 
</P>
<P>
	The affidavit, unsealed Wednesday, for the first time presents  
the government's theory behind the mysterious disappearance of Mrs. 
O'Hair, Jon Garth Murray, and Robin Murray O'Hair in September 
1995. The three vanished from San Antonio along with $500,000 in 
gold coins. 
</P>
<P>
	David R. Waters, who faced a court hearing today in Austin on a  
weapons charge, orchestrated a plot to steal $600,000 from Mrs. 
O'Hair's United Secularists of America, the affidavit states. He 
has not been charged in the case. 
</P>
<P>
	The document, citing a confidential informant, also states  
Waters had a deep hatred for the woman whose 1963 U.S. Supreme 
Court decision, along with a ruling the previous year, struck down 
organized prayer in public schools. 
</P>
<P>
	``Waters ... expressed fantasies of killing Madalyn,'' the  
affidavit states. ``He spoke about seeing Madalyn suffer and 
snipping off her toes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Waters' lawyer, Patrick Ganne, told the San Antonio Express-News  
on Wednesday that he hadn't seen the document. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. O'Hair became famous in the 1960s with her battle to remove  
prayer from schools. She later tried to remove the phrase ``In God 
We Trust'' from U.S. currency and stop potential jurors from saying 
``so help me God.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When the O'Hairs vanished, authorities wondered whether they  
were victims of foul play or had merely run off with their 
organization's money. Others suggested that Mrs. O'Hair, who was 77 
and ailing, had gone off to die quietly so Christians wouldn't pray 
over her. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities, however, have recently suggested the O'Hairs'  
remains were buried in barrels, but two recent searches of a ranch 
near San Antonio failed to find either barrels or bodies. 
</P>
<P>
	The affidavit from IRS special agent Edmund Martin names Waters,  
along with Gary Karr, now imprisoned in Detroit; Danny Fry, who was 
killed shortly after the O'Hairs vanished; and Gerald Lee Osborne 
of Fort Worth. 
</P>
<P>
	The affidavit was used in March to obtain a search warrant of  
Waters' Austin apartment. The search yielded, among other items, 
personal correspondence of Jon Murray, the document said. 
</P>
<P>
	The agent also stated that Waters was responsible for the death  
of Fry, whose headless, handless body was dumped in Dallas County 
two days after the O'Hairs vanished. 
</P>
<P>
	According to an informant, Karr has talked about Waters  
committing four murders in Texas following a card game. 
</P>
<P>
	``After the card game, Waters drove four people involved in the  
card game back home. Waters killed them, took the jewelry (rings 
and Rolexes) off the bodies, and buried them in a field in Texas 
near a subdivision,'' read the affidavit. 
</P>
<P>
	Waters used a Ford van rented by Karr to transport the bodies,  
and Karr told the informant that the persons killed included the 
O'Hairs, the affidavit said. 
</P>
<P>
	Waters worked for Mrs. O'Hair in Austin in 1993 and 1994 and  
``was open about his dislike of the O'Hairs and made comments about 
harming Madalyn,'' the document said, citing an informant. 
</P>
<P>
	The informant said that after Waters pleaded guilty in May 1995  
to stealing money from the O'Hairs, Mrs. O'Hair wrote a long 
article in the American Atheist newsletter detailing his criminal 
history. 
</P>
<P>
	``At this point in time, Waters had serious change of attitude  
regarding the O'Hairs,'' the affidavit said. 
</P>
<P>
	Waters met Karr when the two were cellmates in Illinois. Waters,  
who had served time for beating a teen-ager to death, was back in 
prison for assaulting his mother while Karr was in for kidnapping 
and armed robbery. 
</P>
<P>
	Water was released in 1987. He quit as the office manager of  
American Atheists in 1993 and admitted stealing $54,000 from the 
group's accounts. Waters was given probation and ordered to repay 
the money. 
</P>
<P>
	Karr was freed in 1995, four months before the O'Hairs  
disappeared. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
