<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Ruling Party Office Burned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- An office of the ruling Golkar Party  
was set on fire today in the worst attack on the party since 
campaigning for Indonesia's June 7 parliamentary elections began 
eight days ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The blaze broke out in the two-story building in North Aceh,  
just hours before tens of thousands of rallying opposition-party 
supporters choked the streets of Jakarta, the capital. 
</P>
<P>
	Police said six people set the building on fire with gasoline  
after warning a guard to run away. No one was injured in the fire, 
they said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are searching for the culprits and continue to investigate  
it,'' police Lt. Col. Iskandar Hasan said. 
</P>
<P>
	The northwestern province of Aceh, 1,100 miles northwest of  
Jakarta, is embattled by a violent separatist movement. National 
election officials said Wednesday that balloting in Aceh could be 
postponed. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, former President Suharto delivered a letter to the  
attorney general's office today giving government investigators 
permission to search for and seize any money of his they found 
stashed away in foreign bank accounts. He also repeated his 
contention that he has no money overseas. 
</P>
<P>
	Suharto, 77, has been the target of allegations over his wealth  
since he quit following protests and riots a year ago. The 
allegations have become a major issue in the campaign for a new 
Parliament that will help select a head of state later this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Two government officials will leave Sunday for Europe to check  
into allegations in a recent Time magazine article that Suharto and 
his family amassed $15 billion during his 32 years in office and 
recently transferred $9 billion from Switzerland to an account in 
Austria. 
</P>
<P>
	Golkar was Suharto's party and dominated politics under his  
tight-fisted rule, regularly winning elections amid claims of 
vote-rigging. It now is lagging in opinion polls, largely because 
of its links with Suharto. 
</P>
<P>
	Opposition parties have accused President B.J. Habibie,  
Suharto's hand-picked successor and Golkar's presidential 
candidate, of wanting to protect the former leader and going soft 
on him in the investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Several Golkar vehicles have been vandalized, and Golkar flags  
have been burned in Jakarta, where the party has been keeping a low 
profile. 
</P>
<P>
	In the capital, huge crowds of flag-waving supporters of the  
National Mandate Party and the Justice Party paraded down the 
city's main boulevard on the tops of buses and the backs of trucks 
and motorcycles. It was the third time in eight days that the 
streets were filled with opposition supporters. 
</P>
<P>
	In contrast, rallies by Golkar in Jakarta a few days ago fizzled  
with low turnouts. 
</P>
<P>
	There were no signs of the election campaign in Aceh's oil- and  
gas-rich town of Lhokseumawe. Less that 50 percent of eligible 
voters have registered in the province, where separatist rebels are 
campaigning for a boycott of the election. 
</P>
<P>
	Home Affairs Minister Syarwan Hamid said Wednesday that  
balloting in Aceh could be postponed because of a lack of voters 
and outbreaks of violence. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, six people were killed in two separate attacks in  
the troubled province on the island of Sumatra. Separatists are 
suspected. 
</P>
<P>
	A small group of rebels has been fighting for a separate Islamic  
state in Aceh since the 1970s. The Indonesian military has cracked 
down hard on separatists, and rights groups have accused the army 
of killing and torturing hundreds of people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
