<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bonds Drop on Inflation Jitters / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bonds fell for a second session Thursday despite  
another exodus of money from stocks, as the appeal of safer 
fixed-income investments was outweighed by inflation worries. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond fell 5/8 point,  
or $6.25 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves in the 
opposite direction, rose to 5.84 percent from Thursday's 5.80 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices of short-term Treasurys fell 5/32 to 7/32 point, while  
intermediate maturities fell between 11/32 point and 17/32 point, 
reported Bridge Telerate. 
</P>
<P>
	The market failed to benefit from a steep selloff in stocks,  
which often sends investors searching for a haven such as 
Treasurys. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial average of 30 blue-chip stocks fell  
235.23 points, or by 2.2 percent, to 10,466.93 amid mounting fears 
of rising inflation and interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	Those concerns, sparked by worries the economy is growing too  
fast, also pressured bonds, which are less attractive when prices 
are rising quickly. 
</P>
<P>
	Notably, the Commerce Department reported Thursday that the  
biggest consumer spending spree in 11 years kept the economy 
growing at a robust rate of 4.1 percent in the year's first 
quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	In other fixed-income trading on Thursday, yields on three-month  
Treasury bills slipped to 4.63 percent, while the discount fell 
0.01 percentage point from Wednesday to 4.51 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Six-month yields rose to 4.81 percent as the discount rose 0.02  
percentage point to 4.63 percent, and one-year yields rose to 4.96 
percent as the discount rose 0.05 percentage point to 4.71 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, rose to 4.87 1/2 percent, up from 4.81 percent late Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds fell 1/4 point to 121 5/8. The average yield to 
maturity rose to 5.39 percent from late Wednesday's 5.37 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
