<DOCNO> APW19990527.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 17:01:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks End Lower; Dow Down 235.23 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks tumbled Thursday as renewed worries of  
inflation and higher interest rates sent the market back into its 
retreat from record heights. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial average fell 235.23, a 2.2 percent  
loss, to close at 10,466.93. It was the ninth-worst one-day point 
drop ever, and the steepest since Sept. 30, 1998, when the 
blue-chip average fell 237.20. But in percentage terms, it was far 
from a record decline. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader market indicators also fell, although their losses were  
comparatively modest. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 fell 23.35 to 
1,281.41, and the Nasdaq composite index fell 8.03 to 2,419.15. 
</P>
<P>
	Just this week, the Dow has tumbled 362.35 points, or by 3.3  
percent. The steep selloff Thursday made the previous day's 
171.07-point gain seem like a distant memory. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yesterday's market looked really good, but without a  
follow-through, it's hard for stocks to pick up steam,'' said Barry 
Berman, head trader for Robert W. Baird &AMP; Co. in Milwaukee. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the selling came from investors cashing in on  
Wednesday's rally in advance of the Memorial Day weekend. But the 
strongest factor, analysts said, was the continuing fear that a 
rekindling of inflation will prompt the Federal Reserve to raise 
interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	New government figures on the economy kept the market off  
balance Thursday. The Commerce Department said the U.S. economy 
grew at a robust annual rate of 4.1 percent in the first quarter, 
exacerbating fears that the Fed will raise rates to prevent the 
economy from overheating. 
</P>
<P>
	That depressed bond prices, sending the yield of 30-year  
Treasurys rising to 5.84 percent from 5.80 percent Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Commerce Department report also revealed news that could  
have heartened the market. An inflation gauge tied to the gross 
domestic product rose a modest 1.1 percent, and corporate profits 
showed a big rebound in the first three months of this year. 
Profits rose at an annual rate of $31.8 billion after having fallen 
at a rate of $5.3 billion in the fourth quarter of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	But David Orr, chief economist at First Union Capital Markets,  
pointed out that the fourth quarter included $13.5 billion in 
lawsuit settlements by tobacco companies. Without those crushing 
payments, the increase in profits would have been much more modest. 
</P>
<P>
	Corporate profits have loomed in the background of the  
interest-rate watch. Higher rates typically cut into profits as it 
becomes more expensive for companies to borrow money. 
</P>
<P>
	IBM, which soared more than 15 points Wednesday before a 2-for-1  
stock split that took effect at the close of trading, fell 2 1/8 on 
Thursday to 116. Some analysts also blamed persistent worries that 
computer makers will see their profit margins shrink as they cut 
prices to compete. 
</P>
<P>
	Bank and brokerage stocks, which typically suffer when interest  
rates rise, were mostly lower. J.P. Morgan, a component of the Dow, 
lost 3 3/4 to 135 1/8 and Wells Fargo fell 2 1/8 to 39 1/4. 
</P>
<P>
	And cyclical stocks -- those with fortunes tied to swings in the  
economy -- fell as investors locked in gains from a recent upward 
surge. 3M, down 2 13/16 to 86, and Caterpillar, down 2 7/16 to 55 3/8, 
were among the worst-performing Dow cyclicals. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts attributed the Nasdaq's stronger performance to  
bargain-hunting following a sharp selloff of Internet stocks early 
this week. 
</P>
<P>
	``Those stocks had been already been beaten up pretty badly, so  
today, they're resisting the decline of the rest of the market,'' 
said Robert Robbins, senior vice president and market strategist at 
Robinson-Humphrey Co. Inc. of Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	Nonetheless, investors sent many Internet companies lower again,  
choosing instead to buy high-tech veterans like Intel, which rose 1 
7/16 to 53 1/8. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues outnumbered advancers by an 11-to-6 margin on  
the New York Stock Exchange. Consolidated volume totaled 978.9 
million shares, compared with 1.06 billion in the previous session. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index fell 10.82 to 614.02, and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index dropped 8.27 to 774.39. The Russell 
2000 index of smaller companies fell 2.49 to 432.92. 
</P>
<P>
	Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 0.33 percent.  
Germany's DAX index closed 2.3 percent lower, Britain's FT-SE 100 
fell 0.6 percent, and France's CAC-40 ended 1.1 percent lower. 
</P>
<P>
	Friday morning, trading in General Motors stock will reflect the  
spinoff of its Delphi Automotive Systems unit. GM, which closed 
Thursday at 82 7/8, will open at 68 1/2. 




</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
