<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Former NYC Mayor: I'm for Bradley </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Former New York City Mayor Ed Koch, who  
supported Al Gore the last time he ran for president, said Thursday 
he does not believe the vice president can win the White House. 
</P>
<P>
	And, Koch said, ``If I had to vote tomorrow, I'd vote for  
(former New Jersey Sen. Bill) Bradley,'' Gore's only declared 
Democratic rival. 
</P>
<P>
	While the Koch remarks alone might not be troubling for Gore  
loyalists, there has been increasing concern in recent weeks among 
some of the vice president's current supporters that his campaign 
is lagging. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked about Koch's comments, Gore campaign spokesman Roger  
Salazar said that ``as people get to know more about Al Gore, we 
think they'll respond to that and we feel very confident that he's 
going to win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1988, Koch was one of Gore's major supporters as the  
presidential campaign headed into the New York primary. But after 
then-Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis swept that contest, Gore 
bowed out of the race. 
</P>
<P>
	Calling Gore ``a nice guy,'' Koch said ``the reason I don't  
think he can get elected is that he can't separate himself from 
President Clinton's record, the good and the bad.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
