<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> US OKs Moving Poor To Managed Care </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- The federal government has given the state  
permission to move 1.5 million Medicaid recipients in New York City 
into managed care health plans. 
</P>
<P>
	The switch from traditional fee-for-service based plans was  
advocated by both Gov. George Pataki and New York Mayor Rudolph 
Giuliani as a way to improve care for the poor and reduce costs. 
</P>
<P>
	It also means Medicaid recipients could face fewer choices in  
physicians and other care providers. 
</P>
<P>
	About 650,000 of the state's 3.5 million Medicaid recipients are  
already enrolled in managed care programs; in 1997, the federal 
government granted approval to add eight upstate New York counties. 
</P>
<P>
	Pataki had long sought federal approval to force New York City  
recipients into managed care. They will be added over two years. 
</P>
<P>
	Pataki has complained that New York has the highest Medicaid  
cost in the country at about $24 billion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
