<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Train Victim Feared Deportation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) -- A woman who led four of her children on  
a fatal walk along railroad tracks may have feared she was about to 
be deported, a police officer who knew the family said. 
</P>
<P>
	The fatal collision on the tracks was the first of two in the  
state this week. An unidentified man was struck and killed by a 
northbound Metro North train just after 9 p.m. Wednesday. A Metro 
North spokesman said the victim was apparently walking on the 
tracks. 
</P>
<P>
	Julia Toledo and three of her sons, aged 3, 6 and 12, were  
killed at 2:20 a.m. Tuesday when they were hit from behind by an 
Amtrak train in Fairfield. A 10-year-old son remained in critical 
condition early today. 
</P>
<P>
	``Her sister had threatened to have her deported,'' Police  
Officer Jose Reyes, who knew the family from his work in the local 
DARE program, said in today's editions of The Hartford Courant. 
``She was having problems with the sister to the point she had to 
move.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Friends, he said, believe Toledo feared that her sister was  
trying to have her committed to a psychiatric facility and take 
guardianship of the youngsters. 
</P>
<P>
	``She didn't want her sister to know where she was staying,''  
Reyes said. 
</P>
<P>
	Attempts to reach the sister, Maria Toledo, by phone and at her  
home were unsuccessful Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Other pressures on Julia Toledo had been mounting recently. Her  
marriage was failing and her husband had returned to Ecuador. She 
quit her job after having trouble finding day care for her 
children, and she had left her apartment and moved into a shelter. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, officials have ruled the deaths of Toledo, 46, and her  
sons an accident, not suicide. 
</P>
<P>
	``She was obviously fleeing, but we don't know why. We wished we  
had known she was in trouble, because we could have helped her,'' 
said Sister Brenda Lynch of Caroline House, an educational center 
for immigrant women where Toledo took English lessons and other 
classes. 
</P>
<P>
	Lynch said following train tracks is a common practice in Latin  
America. Also, Toledo may have believed it was safer to follow the 
tracks than walk through an impoverished neighborhood in the middle 
of the night. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a direct way, the tracks. ... What she did would make  
sense to her,'' Lynch said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
