<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 06:06:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Discovery Departs For Space Station </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- Space shuttle Discovery blasted off  
for the new international space station today, ending a six-month 
launch drought for NASA. 
</P>
<P>
	The 4.5 million-pound ship, carrying seven astronauts and a full  
load of space station supplies, soared into a hazy sky at 6:49 a.m. 
as a brilliant yellow sun emerged above the horizon. 
</P>
<P>
	``You guys have a great mission,'' the launch director told the  
crew just before liftoff. 
</P>
<P>
	The space station was soaring 235 miles over the Atlantic, due  
east of the Carolinas, when Discovery took off in pursuit. They're 
due to link up early Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Because a space shuttle hadn't flown since December -- making  
this the longest gap between shuttle launches since the Challenger 
disaster -- NASA was especially vigilant during flight preparations. 
</P>
<P>
	The only major problem in the past month was hail, which  
pummeled Discovery's fuel tank and forced a one-week delay. 
</P>
<P>
	Its external fuel tank speckled with patches, Discovery holds  
more than 4,300 pounds of spare parts, tools, laptop computers and 
clothes for the station's first permanent residents, due to move in 
early next year. 
</P>
<P>
	During the 10-day mission, Discovery's seven astronauts will not  
only haul supplies into the space station, they will also fix 
broken U.S. and Russian equipment and install mufflers to reduce 
the noise caused by clattering Russian fans. Two of them will also 
take a spacewalk to attach one crane and parts of another to the 
outside of the station. 
</P>
<P>
	It's the first flight to the station since shuttle astronauts  
took up the second component in December and attached it to the 
first, which was already in orbit. 
</P>
<P>
	As a result, commander Kent Rominger and his  
U.S.-Canadian-Russian crew will be the first to actually dock with 
the complex. Rominger, a Navy pilot, will pull up and dock the same 
way it was done during the shuttle-Mir program. 
</P>
<P>
	In November, an unmanned Russian rocket is scheduled to launch  
the next piece of the space station, a service module containing 
life-support systems. Then, NASA's space shuttle Atlantis is 
supposed to follow in December with more equipment. 
</P>
<P>
	However, everything is on hold until the Russian component --  
already more than 1 1/2 years behind -- is in orbit. And many question 
whether the Russians can finish building and testing it by 
November, given the country's economic crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	The repeated delays in the Russian service module caused the  
six-month gap in shuttle launches, as did ongoing problems with a 
NASA X-ray telescope that's supposed to be hoisted aboard the 
shuttle Columbia. 
</P>
<P>
	To stay sharp, NASA's launch team conducted extra countdown  
practices during the hiatus and spent extra time reviewing 
procedures. 
</P>
<P>
	It paid off. Discovery's safe climb to orbit was a bright spot  
amid a number of recent failed launches of unmanned rockets. Three 
satellites ended up in useless orbits and another was vaporized 
shortly after launch, all since April. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, two satellites were destroyed in launch explosions  
last August. None of the six satellites belonged to NASA. 
</P>
<P>
	Discovery is due back June 6.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990527.0255 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 02:51:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Close Down / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The Tokyo stock market's main index slipped today  
in light trading as many institutional investors held back to 
assess recent corporate earnings announcements. The dollar edged 
higher against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 122.43 yen in the late afternoon, up 0.33 yen  
from late Wednesday in Tokyo and also above its late New York level 
of 122.17 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 53.33 points,  
or 0.33 percent, closing at 16,177.19. On Wednesday, the average 
gained 16.29 points, or 0.10 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Many Japanese companies have released earnings results for the  
last fiscal year, which ended March 31, with most of them posting 
declined profits amid the nation's worst recession since World War 
II. 
</P>
<P>
	Trading today was somewhat choppy in the absence of fresh  
market-moving news, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market lacks energy to test higher levels,'' said Kazunori  
Jinnai, deputy general manager of the equity department at Daiwa 
Securities SB Capital Markets. 
</P>
<P>
	Volume on the exchange's first section was estimated at 396  
million shares, down from Wednesday's turnover of 452 million 
shares. Despite the Nikkei's fall, advancing issues outnumbered 
decliners 621 to 530, with 156 unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was down 1.15 points, or 0.09 percent, to 1,302.17 
points. The TOPIX closed down 5.36 points, or 0.41 percent, 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Disappointment that an overnight Wall Street rally did not spark  
a stronger move in Tokyo also pushed the Nikkei index down about 
200 points at one point in the afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	In New York, the Dow Jones industrial average rose 171.07  
points, or 1.6 percent, to 10,702.16 at Wednesday's close. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar drifted higher against the yen  
on buying by Japanese institutional investors and overseas funds 
early in the session. 
</P>
<P>
	But traders said the dollar's upward momentum later petered out  
because players were uncertain about its near-term direction. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar ranged between 122.27 yen and 122.74 yen in today's  
trading. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was quoted at 127.58 yen, down  
from 129.36 yen late Wednesday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 213 10-year Japanese government  
bond rose to 1.4950 percent from 1.4150 percent late Wednesday, 
driving its price down to 99.17 yen from 99.86 yen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
