<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Discovery Departs For Space Station  
</P>
<P>
	CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- Space shuttle Discovery blasted off  
for the new international space station today, ending a six-month 
launch drought for NASA. The 4.5 million-pound ship, carrying seven 
astronauts and a full load of space station supplies, soared into a 
hazy sky at 6:49 a.m. as a brilliant yellow sun emerged above the 
horizon. During the 10-day mission, Discovery's seven astronauts 
will not only haul supplies into the space station, they will also 
fix broken U.S. and Russian equipment and install mufflers to 
reduce the noise caused by clattering Russian fans. 

</P>
<P>
	Pakistan Says It Shot Down Indian Jets  
</P>
<P>
	ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) -- In a major escalation in the battle  
over Kashmir, Pakistan said today it shot down two Indian fighter 
jets that crossed into its territory along the border. Kashmir, a 
Himalayan territory divided between India and Pakistan, is also the 
flashpoint between two earlier wars between these uneasy neighbors. 
The attacks came as Indian helicopter gunships launched fresh 
rocket attacks in Kashmir today, the second day of a campaign to 
dislodge Pakistan-backed guerrillas from the disputed frontier. 

</P>
<P>
	Yugoslavia Pounded by NATO Strikes  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO warplanes pounded more targets  
in the Yugoslavian capital and elsewhere early today. The private 
Studio B television said 53 missiles hit Belgrade and the 
surrounding area overnight in one of the fiercest NATO attacks on 
the capital since the bombing started March 24. Meanwhile, reports 
surfaced that Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic has been 
indicted on war crimes charges. U.S. officials in Washington, 
speaking on condition of anonymity, said an indictment against 
Slobodan Milosevic had been issued by a U.N. court Tuesday, 
accusing him of atrocities in the Balkans. 

</P>
<P>
	Ex-Secretary Fingered in IBM Scam  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Authorities say 25 people pocketed more than  
$1.3 million from insider trading, a scheme that began with a 
former IBM secretary familiar with company expansion plans. The 
Securities and Exchange Commission said the illegal trades -- many 
by novices to the securities markets who did not even have accounts 
-- were touched off when Lorraine K. Cassano told her husband that 
International Business Machines Corp. was about to acquire Lotus 
Development Corp. Lotus stock jumped nearly 90 percent when the 
1995 deal was announced. 

</P>
<P>
	Ruling Party's Office Set on Fire  
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- A Golkar Party office was set on fire  
today -- the worst attack on the ruling party since the campaign for 
Indonesia's June 7 parliamentary elections began eight days ago. 
Witnesses and police said no one was injured in the incident in the 
troubled northwestern province of Aceh, site of a violent 
separatist movement. National election officials said Wednesday 
that balloting in Aceh there could be postponed. 

</P>
<P>
	Pinochet Lawyers Back in Court  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The lawyers for Gen. Augusto Pinochet will argue  
today that Britain's top law enforcement official erred when he 
allowed the Spanish extradition request for the former Chilean 
dictator to go forward. They are seeking permission to appeal that 
decision in the High Court. If the judge allows it, a panel of 
judges will be assigned to hear the challenge. Pinochet was 
arrested Oct. 16 in London on a Spanish warrant charging that he 
ordered the torture of opponents during his 17-year regime from 
1973-1990. 

</P>
<P>
	``Home Improvement'' Draws Big Ratings  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The last ``Home Improvement'' drew an estimated  
35 million viewers, making it the fourth most-viewed series finale 
of the 1990s. The show, which starred Tim Allen, went off the air 
Tuesday after an eight-year run. Only ``Seinfeld,'' ``Cheers'' and 
``The Cosby Show'' drew more viewers during their series finales. 
The show had a 21.2 rating and a 34 share, meaning a third of the 
television sets in use at the time were tuned in to ``Home 
Improvement.'' By comparison, the season's top-rated series, 
``ER,'' averaged 25 million viewers this year. 

</P>
<P>
	Japanese Stocks Finish Lower  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stock prices finished lower today as  
investors turned cautious amid corporate earnings announcements. 
The Nikkei Stock Average lost 53.33 points, closing at 16,177.19. 
Yesterday, the average gained 16.29 points. 

</P>
<P>
	Manchester United Is Champion  
</P>
<P>
	BARCELONA, Spain (AP) -- Manchester United today won the top  
title in European soccer. United scored two goals in injury time to 
edge Bayern Munich 2-1 and gain the Champions Cup. Teddy Sheringham 
and Ole Gunnar Solksjaer scored to give Manchester its first 
Champions Cup since 1968. United became the first English team to 
win the triple crown of league championship, Football Association 
Cup and the Champions Cup. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by LISI de BOURBON  

</P>
