<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Longer Trading Approved for Nasdaq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Come autumn, investors could be buying and  
selling shares of Microsoft Corp. and 99 other companies on the 
Nasdaq Stock Market while watching Ally McBeal. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Association of Securities Dealers, which governs  
Nasdaq, on Thursday approved a plan to extend trading hours from 
the current 9:30 a.m.-4 p.m. Eastern time schedule. A second 
session of the day would likely start at 5:30 p.m. and end at 9 
p.m. or 10 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
	The changes are expected to take effect around September, after  
a review by the Securities and Exchange Commission and discussions 
with industry leaders. 
</P>
<P>
	``This business of extended hours is a serious market-quality  
question, and it needs to be addressed with a great deal of 
seriousness,'' said Frank Zarb, chairman and chief executive of the 
National Association of Securities Dealers. 
</P>
<P>
	The SEC has been urging restraint, proposing a delay until next  
year so that the securities industry would not be extending trading 
hours at the same time it is confronting the Year 2000 computer bug 
and preparing to shift from reporting stock prices in fractions to 
the use of decimals. 
</P>
<P>
	But Zarb said Nasdaq is still sticking with its plans for  
starting night trading around September. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is clear the marketplace needs this kind of innovation, and  
we are going to provide the leadership to get us from here to 
there,'' Zarb said. 
</P>
<P>
	The groundbreaking decision, which could throw many Wall Street  
companies into chaos, is being made to accommodate the growing 
number of investors who trade at home over the Internet. But the 
securities industry, especially smaller firms, will have to find 
ways for brokers and backroom recordkeepers to accommodate the 
nighttime business. 
</P>
<P>
	In a poll for the CNBC financial cable news channel, 53 percent  
of active investors 21 years of age or older liked the idea of 
trading well into the evening, while 31 percent opposed the move. 
The poll of more than 500 people and had a margin of error of plus 
or minus 4.4 percentage points. 
</P>
<P>
	Initially, trading would be limited to Nasdaq's 100 largest,  
nonfinancial companies, led by Microsoft and including such other 
well-known stocks as Intel Corp., Northwest Airlines Corp. and MCI 
WorldCom Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks would still have a final, closing price reported at the 4  
p.m. end of the daytime session. Any after-hour trades would count 
toward the following day's stock price. 
</P>
<P>
	Securities subject to stock splits, or stock dividends would be  
suspended from trading in the evening session. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are calling on the industry to do the right thing, to  
coordinate and be responsible and move in unison so the investor 
can be properly protected in the new world of extended hours,'' 
Zarb said. 
</P>
<P>
	In a statement after the vote, SEC Chairman Arthur Levitt said  
the SEC supports ``investor choice in trading hours. Before 
widespread trading begins outside of regular hours, however, a 
number of investor protection and market integrity issues need to 
be addressed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Those issues include broad distribution of stock price data and  
the capacity of computer systems to handle the trading load. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this week, the chairman of the New York Stock Exchange  
said the Big Board also is considering a plan to extend its trading 
hours. 
</P>
<P>
	All of the traditional markets are facing increased competition  
from overseas exchanges, which often trade shares of U.S.-based 
companies, and from alternative computer-based exchanges in the 
United States and abroad. 
</P>
<P>
	Separately, Zarb acknowledged that he has been approached by New  
York city and state officials about moving into part of the new 
facility that is being built for the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have looked at it and we have asked them for more  
information,'' he said, but added, ``Based upon what we know now, 
it's not our favorite option by a longshot.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
