<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dad in Kidnap Case May Plead Guilty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- A man accused of kidnapping his two young  
daughters 20 years ago and moving them to Florida will plead guilty 
in a plea bargain that will spare him jail time, the Boston Herald 
reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	Stephen Fagan will enter a guilty plea to kidnapping on Friday,  
the newspaper reported, citing sources it did not identify. 
</P>
<P>
	Fagan, 57, is accused of taking his two daughters from ex-wife  
Barbara Kurth in Massachusetts in 1979, moving them to Florida, 
telling them their mother was dead, and raising them under assumed 
names. 
</P>
<P>
	Fagan claims he rescued the girls from an unfit and alcoholic  
mother, a charge Kurth denies. 
</P>
<P>
	His daughters, Rachael and Lisa Martin, who are now in their  
20s, have steadfastly supported him since his arrest last year in 
Palm Beach, Fla. 
</P>
<P>
	Fagan is expected to receive probation and pay a fine, the  
newspaper said. He was charged with two counts of kidnapping, each 
of which carries a maximum penalty of 10 years in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	Kurth's brother said in a phone interview with The Associated  
Press early today that he was aware discussions for a plea 
agreement were under way, but did not know details. 
</P>
<P>
	``We hadn't been told which way it would go,'' Peter Kurth said  
from his home in Burlington, Vt. ``I think she (Barbara) will be 
glad this aspect of it will be resolved.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fagan's attorney, Richard Egbert, did not immediately return  
messages left at his home and office. 
</P>
</TEXT>
