<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmakers Fight Wine-Sales Limit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Through phone calls and meetings, lawmakers  
from wine-growing regions have been trying to persuade their 
colleagues to defeat a measure to limit mail-order and Internet 
sales of alcohol. 
</P>
<P>
	The provision has been touted as a way to curb alcohol sales to  
minors, and its popularity is such that the Senate voted 80-17 to 
add it to a juvenile crime bill passed last week. Similar 
legislation is expected in the House shortly. 
</P>
<P>
	The provision has split the alcohol industry. While the issue  
affects all alcohol products, winemakers eager to find new markets 
outside the distributorships have taken the lead in fighting the 
legislation. On the other side are the big wholesalers, which seek 
to maintain their control of sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Some states already have laws prohibiting intrastate shipments  
of alcohol, such as through the mail, but courts have ruled that 
the states cannot enforce the laws. The Senate-passed provision 
would allow states to go to federal court and seek an injunction 
blocking such sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Opponents of the bill cast the dispute as an industry fight that  
the federal government should stay away from. Supporters say the 
federal government should act to prevent minors from buying alcohol 
through the Internet and prevent companies from evading state taxes 
and state laws by shipping their products directly to consumers. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is a public policy issue regarding alcohol access, underage  
sales and taxation,'' said David Dickerson, vice president of the 
Wine and Spirits Wholesalers of America. 
</P>
<P>
	Leading the charge on Capitol Hill against the measure is a  
group of 75 House members that calls itself the Congressional Wine 
Caucus. The bipartisan group includes lawmakers from wine-growing 
regions nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. George Radanovich, a third-term Republican who owns a  
central California winery that ships more than 4,000 cases a year, 
is one of them. He has been calling House Republican leaders to 
make the pitch against the legislation. 
</P>
<P>
	He argues that the federal government should stay out of the  
matter and let the industry decide whether beer, wine and liquor 
can be sold directly to customers through the mail and Internet. 
Currently, the products are sold through distributorships. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're working the leadership to convince them this is big  
business vs. small business and nothing more,'' Radanovich said. 
``The motivation behind this is big national distributors trying to 
kick small wineries out of the market.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Amo Houghton, R-N.Y., another member of the caucus, said  
that expanding sales over the Internet will allow wineries to find 
new markets. He said some New York wineries can't get their 
products distributed now. ``The old distribution system in wine is 
collapsing,'' Houghton said. ``It will collapse because of the 
Internet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the lawmakers are so concerned about the potency of the  
issue of underage drinking that they are pushing their own bill. It 
would require that all packages containing alcohol be labeled and 
that someone age 21 or older be required to show identification and 
sign for the shipment if delivered by mail. The Senate juvenile 
crime bill contains such a provision. 
</P>
<P>
	``If there are concerns, we are able and willing to meet those  
concerns,'' said Simon Siegl, president of the American Vintners 
Association, part of a coalition, calling itself Free the Grapes, 
which is supporting the lawmakers' efforts. Members of the vintners 
association gave $228,591 to federal candidates in 1997-98 and 
spent $40,000 on lobbying last year. Another coalition member, the 
Wine Institute, made $66,535 in contributions in the last election 
and spent $60,000 to lobby in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	On the other side are wine, beer and liquor distributors who  
have formed Americans for Responsible Alcohol Access. The Wine and 
Spirits Wholesalers of America spent $430,000 lobbying last year 
and made $275,809 in campaign contributions. The National Beer 
Wholesalers Association, which contributed $1.2 million to federal 
candidates during the last election cycle and spent $450,000 on 
lobbying in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Their coalition also includes the American Academy of Pediatrics  
and the National Safe Kids Campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	The House may have two opportunities to address the issue -- the  
provision is in the Senate-passed crime bill and Rep. Robert 
Ehrlich Jr., R-Md., plans to introduce separate legislation to 
limit mail sales. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
