<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Forbes Names Chairman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republican presidential candidate Steve Forbes  
has chosen Ken Blackwell to be national chairman of his 
presidential campaign, making the Ohio secretary of state one of 
the highest-ranking blacks in the 2000 race. 
</P>
<P>
	Blackwell will be a top spokesman and strategist for politics  
and policy, Forbes said in a joint interview with Blackwell on 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's an individual of true principle. He understands the  
principles of my campaign,'' Forbes said. ``Whether the issue is 
taxation or school opportunity, we've been on the same page.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Blackwell said he believes Forbes is the only candidate who can  
inspire hope, create opportunity and include minorities in his 
political coalition. ``Steve has always been an advocate for the 
politics of inclusion,'' Blackwell said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Ohio secretary of state's office is responsible for  
certifying elections. Blackwell's spokesman Carlo LoParo said there 
was no conflict with Blackwell remaining as secretary of state 
while joining a presidential campaign. ``The integrity of the 
office should not be in question,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	LoParo said Blackwell also planned to remain as co-chairman of  
the Census Monitoring Board. Rep. Carolyn Maloney, R-N.Y., had 
called for his resignation because he signed on with Forbes. 
</P>
<P>
	Blackwell, 51, was elected secretary of state in November after  
serving as Ohio's treasurer. He considered running for governor, 
but was persuaded by party leaders to keep the primary clear for 
Bob Taft, who went on to win the governor's race. 
</P>
<P>
	He was regional chairman of Jack Kemp's 1988 Republican  
presidential campaign and also was county chairman for the 
presidential campaigns of Ronald Reagan and George Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	He gives Forbes an inroad in Ohio -- one of the battleground  
states of the presidential campaign. He also is one of the highest 
ranking minorities in any presidential campaign, Democratic or 
Republican. 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes, who campaigned for Blackwell in 1998, said the new  
chairman was one of the few GOP leaders who fought against a 
proposed sales tax increase in Ohio. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Texas Gov. George W. Bush formally opens  
an Iowa campaign office next week, with Wisconsin Gov. Tommy 
Thompson presiding over the ceremonies. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush has not yet started campaigning for the Republican  
presidential nomination. But backers have been carefully building a 
campaign organization in the state where precinct caucuses launch 
the nominating season. 
</P>
<P>
	The campaign has leased office space, hired a state campaign  
manager and communications director and begun to build a field 
operation. The office opens June 4. 
</P>
<P>
	Thompson's high-profile role in opening the campaign offices is  
yet another indication of the backing that Bush is getting from the 
GOP establishment. 
</P>
<P>
	While he has not formally endorsed a candidate, Thompson, who  
once considered making the race himself, has conceded Bush is 
likely to win the Republican nomination unless misfortune strikes 
his campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Elizabeth Dole would be satisfied with the  
$200,000 annual salary paid to presidents. 
</P>
<P>
	In a letter to House Speaker Dennis Hastert, the Republican  
presidential contender said the proposal to double the salary for 
future presidents was ``ill-advised.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She said $200,000 was ``fair and appropriate,'' given the  
``cost-free housing'' in the White House, free travel, the use of 
Camp David and ``perks'' like a bowling alley, movie theaters and 
putting greens as added compensation for the president. 
</P>
<P>
	``The value of these benefits adds up to millions of dollar  
annually,'' Dole said in the letter. ``When all these benefits are 
taken into consideration, I believe the taxpaying public would join 
me in opposing a presidential pay raise.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Congress is debating whether to raise the president's salary for  
the first time in almost 30 years. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Tony Coelho, Al Gore's newly installed  
campaign general chairman, named the vice president's longtime 
adviser and aide Marla Romash as deputy chairman Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Romash has served as Gore's communications director during his  
first term as vice president and also when he was a U.S. senator. 
</P>
<P>
	Romash has a long history of media and campaign experience. She  
began working for fellow Connecticut native Christopher Dodd's 
first senatorial campaign and served as his press secretary in the 
early 1980s. She also worked for several years as a newspaper 
reporter and television news producer. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE -- Political writer Ron Fournier and reporters Mike  
Glover and Doug Kiker contributed to this report. 
</P>
