<HEADLINE> Women World Cup Soccer Selling Well </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Women's World Cup organizers have passed 400,000  
in ticket sales, well past their initial projections for the 
tournament that starts in less than a month. 
</P>
<P>
	However, unlike the men's World Cup, the FIFA Women's World  
Championship, as it officially is called, is relying almost 
exclusively on fans from the United States, women's World Cup 
president and CEO Marla Messing said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 62,000 tickets have been sold for the  
tournament-opening doubleheader in East Rutherford, N.J., which 
matches the United States vs. Denmark and Brazil vs. Mexico. 
</P>
<P>
	Messing said the tournament is averaging more than 23,000  
tickets per doubleheader, including 16,000 for those not involving 
the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike the men's World Cup, this year's event, which runs June  
19-July 10 in seven U.S. venues, all games except the semifinals 
are doubleheaders. 
</P>
<P>
	Messing said her staff initially projected ticket sales of  
386,000, but has since revised that to 475,000, and Messing 
personally feels that 500,000 is more than reachable. 
</P>
<P>
	In mid April, organizers had said they had sold 325,000 tickets.  
</P>
<P>
	``Our gut tells us that 95 percent (of ticket sales) are from  
the U.S.,'' said Messing. ``People are buying tickets because they 
want to be part of the World Cup experience.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
