<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Senate OKs US Exercizes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MANILA, Philippines (AP) -- After weeks of emotional debate, the  
Philippine Senate approved an accord Thursday that will allow 
American troops to resume large-scale military exercises in the 
former U.S. colony. 
</P>
<P>
	The Visiting Forces Agreement garnered the support of 18 of the  
23 senators. 
</P>
<P>
	Thousands of activists, nuns and priests protested outside the  
Senate. Riot police and soldiers, some with tear gas canisters, 
formed a wall around the Senate building with their shields. 
</P>
<P>
	The accord, signed by Philippine and U.S. officials last year,  
will permit the United States to resume major ship visits and 
large-scale joint exercises which were suspended in 1996. Defense 
Secretary Orlando Mercado said he expects the first exercises to be 
held in about six months. 
</P>
<P>
	Military ties with the United States, which ruled the  
Philippines for nearly half a century, have remained a sensitive 
issue since the Senate forced the closure of the last U.S. base in 
1992. 
</P>
<P>
	A majority of Filipinos support the agreement, according to  
recent surveys, but the Catholic Church and left-wing groups have 
strongly opposed it. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics say the agreement would limit the Philippine  
government's right to prosecute American soldiers who commit crimes 
and would drag it into conflicts with enemies of the United States. 
The presence of U.S. troops would also encourage prostitution, they 
say. 
</P>
<P>
	Many of those backing the agreement argued the need to bolster  
the country's security because of disputes with China over 
territories in the South China Sea. 
</P>
<P>
	At the U.S. Embassy, about 200 young leftist activists hurled  
stones as they tried to storm the building, but riot police forced 
them back with truncheons and shields. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
