<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Campbell Soup Successor Named </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) -- Campbell Soup Co. on Thursday named a former  
paper company executive as its chairman, replacing David W. 
Johnson, the leader credited with turning around the food company. 
</P>
<P>
	Philip E. Lippincott, the longest serving member on the  
company's board of directors, was elected chairman, effective, Aug. 
1. He succeeds Johnson, who is retiring July 31. 
</P>
<P>
	Camden-based Campbell said Dale Morrison will remain as its  
president and chief executive officer, positions held by Johnson 
until 1997 when Johnson announced his retirement. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson, 66, a native Australian, came to Campbell as its CEO in  
1990 from Gerber Products Co. He was the first outsider to head 
Campbell in the 130-year history of the company. He became chairman 
in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	His first task was to quell dissension among members of the  
controlling Dorrance family, heirs to the inventor of condensed 
soup who were considering selling the company. 
</P>
<P>
	In his first year, Johnson led a major restructuring, closing  
plants and selling off businesses. Campbell shed 11,000 workers, 
including 800 at its Camden soup factory, which was eventually 
demolished. 
</P>
<P>
	During his tenure, Johnson led Campbell to a dramatic  
turnaround, focusing on improving sales and boosting stock prices 
and total investor return. Johnson owns company stock worth about 
$75 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson was scheduled to retire in July 1998 when his five-year  
contract expired, but the board of directors asked him to remain 
until the end of the 1999 fiscal year. 
</P>
<P>
	Lippincott, 63, became chief executive officer of Scott Paper  
Co. in 1982 and its chairman a year later. He held both positions 
until 1994. Lippincott has been on Campbell's board of directors 
since 1984. 
</P>
<P>
	Charles R. Perrin, chairman and chief executive officer of Avon  
Products, Inc., was elected to fill Johnson's seat on the 16-member 
Campbell board. 
</P>
<P>
	Campbell sells soup under its familiar red-and-white label and  
other varieties, Godiva chocolate, as well as vegetable juices, 
sauces and baked goods. It is the world's largest soup maker and 
the sixth-largest food company in the United States with 1998 
fiscal year sales of $6.7 billion. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
