<HEADLINE> Most Asian Markets Close Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Most Asian stock markets rose Wednesday,  
shrugging off losses in the two largest regional markets and taking 
cue from overnight gains on Wall Street. 
</P>
<P>
	But in Tokyo, the benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average  
slipped Thursday to shed 53.33 points, or 0.33 percent, closing at 
16,177.19. On Wednesday, the average gained 16.29 points, or 0.10 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Many institutional investors held back to assess recent  
corporate earnings announcements, analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the U.S. dollar drifted higher against the  
Japanese yen on buying by Japanese institutional investors and 
overseas funds early in the session. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 122.43 yen in the late afternoon, up 0.33 yen  
from late Wednesday in Tokyo and also above its late New York level 
of 122.17 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	The yen's recent strength sent Seoul's key index higher. The  
Kospi index closed up 1 percent, or 6.61 points, to 726.66. 
</P>
<P>
	A relatively strong yen is believed to be positive for the price  
competitiveness of South Korean companies, which directly compete 
with Japanese companies in roughly half of their exports. 
</P>
<P>
	In Hong Kong, stocks ended lower on concerns over worsening  
U.S.-China ties offset gains by market heavyweight HSBC Holdings. 
</P>
<P>
	The blue-chip Hang Seng Index fell 0.8 percent, or 100.63  
points, to 12,308.53. It had gained 0.5 percent Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	A U.S. congressional report released Tuesday said China has  
stolen U.S. nuclear and missile secrets over the past two decades, 
aggravating battered U.S.-China relations. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Ng, dealing director at Sassoon Securities Ltd., said  
souring U.S.-China relations have clouded the prospect of China's 
quick entry to the World Trade Organization, which hurt 
China-related shares. 
</P>
<P>
	But Singapore shares and some smaller Asian markets rose on  
gains on Wall Street where the Dow Jones industrial average rose 
171.07 points, or 1.60 percent, on Wednesday to end at 10,702.16. 
</P>
<P>
	Singapore's Straits Times Index closed 22.04 points, or 1.2  
percent, higher at 1915.77. Share prices were also supported by 
bargain-hunting after recent losses. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere:  
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK: Thai shares rebounded despite some selling by investors  
cashing in on recent gains, dealers said. The SET index closed up 
6.07 points, or 1.3 percent, at 464.28. 
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA: Shares fell as investors cashed in on recent gains. The  
JSX Composite Index closed down 0.4 percent, or 2.671 points, at 
603.116 points. 
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR: Shares rose as local institutional investors  
scooped up blue chips. The benchmark Composite Index, closed up 
6.52 points, or 0.9 percent, at 760.34 points. 
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Shares ended higher, buoyed by Wall Street's gains and  
investors positioning on certain stocks ahead of Friday's release 
of first quarter economic data. The PSE Index rose 12.53 points, or 
0.5 percent, to 2,402.88. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: Australian shares ended broadly weaker after nervous  
investors ignored a sharp rise on Wall Street and instead took 
their lead from a drop in the futures market and a rise in bond 
yields. The All Ordinaries index finished at 2,904.7, down 13.8 
points, or 0.5 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	TAIPEI: Taiwan shares ended moderately higher amid expectations  
of an improving economy and on gains on Wall Street. The Weighted 
Price Index closed up 42.38 points, or 0.6 percent, to 7,469.01. 
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: Shares finished higher, boosted by hefty gains by  
Air New Zealand Ltd. The benchmark NZSE-40 Capital Index closed 
26.12 points, or 1.2 percent, higher at 2,126.72. 
</P>
</TEXT>
