<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gov. Vetoes Execution Moratorium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) -- Citing concerns about its  
constitutionality, Gov. Mike Johanns vetoed legislation that would 
have made Nebraska the first state to place a moratorium on 
executions. 
</P>
<P>
	``The death penalty is the law of Nebraska,'' the first-term  
governor said Wednesday. ``We have an obligation to enforce that 
law.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The bill called for a two-year moratorium on executions while a  
study was done to see if the death penalty is being applied fairly. 
Death sentences could have been issued during the moratorium, but 
no executions would have taken place. 
</P>
<P>
	Johanns, a Republican who supports capital punishment, said he  
received more than 250 letters, e-mails and calls on the matter, 
including a call from Pope John Paul II's representative in 
Washington D.C., urging him to sign the bill. 
</P>
<P>
	Johanns said he did not let politics or religion play a role in  
his decision. The GOP platform supports the death penalty while the 
Catholic Church opposes capital punishment. Johanns is a devout 
Catholic. 
</P>
<P>
	It appears unlikely that lawmakers have enough votes to override  
the veto. The measure passed Nebraska's one-house Legislature last 
week on a 27-21 vote. Thirty votes are needed for an override. 
</P>
<P>
	The moratorium was proposed by Omaha Sen. Kermit Brashear, a  
death penalty supporter and former Republican candidate for 
governor. He presented the measure as an amendment to state Sen. 
Ernie Chambers' bill to abolish the death penalty. 
</P>
<P>
	Chambers, an independent, fumed over Johanns' decision.  
</P>
<P>
	``I see the governor as a perfidious individual. He decided to  
toy with the wrong man,'' Chambers said. ``He'll have a chance to 
see what my intentions are in the coming sessions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this week, state Attorney General Don Stenberg said a  
moratorium on executions approved by lawmakers would violate the 
state constitution and ``usurp powers granted ... to the executive 
branch.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Three men have been put to death since Nebraska resumed  
executions in 1994 after a 35-year hiatus. 
</P>
<P>
	Other states have considered moratoriums but have not adopted  
legislation, according to the Death Penalty Information Center, a 
Washington-based group critical of how capital punishment is 
applied. 
</P>
<P>
	Florida officials stopped executions for a year after a fire  
started during a 1997 electrocution. The Illinois House recently 
passed a resolution urging the governor to impose a six-month 
moratorium. 
</P>
<P>
	The American Bar Association and the National Conference of  
Catholic Bishops also have called for such moratoriums. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990527.0270 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 05:51:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IRA Conversion Cutoff Is Oct. 15 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Taxpayers who discovered they are not eligible  
to convert a traditional IRA to a Roth IRA but missed the April 15 
deadline for switching back got a six-month extension Wednesday 
from the Internal Revenue Service. 
</P>
<P>
	Based on research into its own regulations regarding automatic  
extensions, the IRS determined these taxpayers should have until 
Oct. 15 to switch the Roth individual retirement arrangement back 
to a traditional IRA, preserving their full tax advantages for 1998 
returns. 
</P>
<P>
	The problem came up when some taxpayers had converted to the  
Roth IRA in calendar 1998, then discovered their adjusted gross 
incomes topped the $100,000 limit to make the change or that they 
were ineligible because they were married but filed separate tax 
returns. 
</P>
<P>
	Under Wednesday's decision, these taxpayers can undo the switch  
as long as they filed their 1998 tax returns on time and then file 
an amended return by the normal three-year deadline of April 15, 
2002, to reflect the change. 
</P>
<P>
	Roth IRAs have proven wildly popular with people saving for  
retirement because, unlike regular IRAs, contributions are made on 
an after-tax basis but withdrawals are tax-free. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
