<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gingrich Backs Old-Style Debates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Former House Speaker Newt Gingrich is  
injecting himself into the 2000 presidential campaign, suggesting 
that the Lincoln-Douglas debates of the mid-19th century are a 
better model for sorting out candidates than the 
made-for-television soundbites of today. 
</P>
<P>
	In a letter to be sent to senior GOP leaders, Gingrich suggests  
a series of encounters in which each contender is allowed to 
present a 15-minute speech on a prearranged topic, and then answers 
questions for five minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	``This approach would establish an adult rhythm of responsible  
people describing important ideas in a serious way,'' Gingrich 
wrote to Republican Chairman Jim Nicholson, all 50 state GOP chairs 
and all Republican members of Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	Abraham Lincoln and Stephen Douglas held a series of three-hour  
debates in their campaign for an Illinois Senate election in 1858. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously the modern age would not afford that kind of  
opportunity to nine or 10 different candidates,'' Gingrich wrote. 
``On the other hand, there is nothing which requires us to reduce 
the presidency to an average soundbite of nine seconds.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gingrich, who had been exploring a run for the White House,  
served four years as speaker. He left Congress at the end of last 
term after Republicans unexpectedly lost seats in the elections. 
</P>
<P>
	--------	 
</P>
<P>
	The House Republican leadership is moving to counter an effort  
to force campaign finance legislation to the floor this summer, and 
hoping to reassure GOP supporters of the bill that leaders will 
follow through on a promised debate in September. 
</P>
<P>
	On the same day that six Republicans broke ranks and signed a  
petition to force the measure to the floor as quickly as possible, 
one committee announced plans to conduct public hearings on the 
issue in June and July. 
</P>
<P>
	And House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., reaffirmed his  
intention to bring the measure to the floor in September. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the speaker feels very comfortable with the  
schedule,'' said his spokesman, John Feehery. ``It's disappointing 
that they decided to sign this discharge petition.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some prominent GOP supporters of campaign finance legislation  
withheld their signatures during the day. 
</P>
<P>
	``For now, I'm uncommitted,'' said Rep. Zach Wamp of Tennessee,  
who has battled his party's leadership on the issue in the past. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Marge Roukema of New Jersey said, ``Conditions were very  
different when Gingrich was here. There was no alternative and he 
was absolutely adamant'' about his opposition to bringing the issue 
to the floor. 
</P>
<P>
	--------	 
</P>
<P>
	It takes 218 names on a petition to force legislation to the  
floor. Thus far there are 201, including 196 Democrats and the five 
Republicans who signed Wednesday. They are Reps. Chris Shays of 
Connecticut; Mike Castle of Delaware; Michael Forbes of New York; 
Greg Ganske of Iowa; Connie Morella of Maryland and Nancy Johnson 
of Connecticut. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need to act on campaign finance reform now, not tomorrow,''  
Shays said. 
</P>
<P>
	Thus far, 16 Democrats have withheld their names. Party  
officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said they expect a 
few to sign the petition, thereby increasing pressure on the 
Republicans who have called for an early vote but don't want to 
buck their own party's leadership. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
