<DOCNO> APW19990527.0272 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 03:01:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Secretary Fingered in IBM Scam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Twenty-five people pocketed more than $1.3  
million from insider trading, a scheme that began not with a Wall 
Street wizard but an IBM secretary familiar with company expansion 
plans, authorities say. 
</P>
<P>
	The Securities and Exchange Commission said the illegal trades --  
many by novices to the securities markets who did not even have 
accounts -- were touched off when Lorraine K. Cassano told her 
husband that International Business Machines Corp. was about to 
acquire Lotus Development Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	When the 1995 deal was announced, Lotus stock jumped nearly 90  
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Among those charged was a pizzeria owner, a bank vice president,  
a private school teacher, a grocery store owner, a lawyer, the 
president of a direct-mail marketing company, a doctor, an engineer 
and several stockbrokers. Of those charged, 13 live in New York, 
and six in New Jersey. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've seen a shift away from the Wall Street kingpins to Main  
Street America,'' SEC enforcement director Richard Walker said as 
the government watchdog of the securities industry announced one of 
its biggest cases. 
</P>
<P>
	In papers filed in federal court in New York, the SEC said Mrs.  
Cassano told her husband, Robert M. Cassano, a paging 
communications company salesman, who then told two friends who 
agreed to purchase stock for him. 
</P>
<P>
	Those two friends told others and soon the information had  
spread to family members, friends and stock brokers, the SEC said 
in the civil action. 
</P>
<P>
	The illegal trading happened during a 6 1/2-hour period on June 2,  
1995, the SEC said. Three days later, IBM announced its takeover 
offer for Lotus and the value of Lotus stock leaped from $32.50 per 
share to more than $61. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Cassano, a secretary in the Volumes and Revenue Department  
of the Software Group at IBM in Somers, N.Y., was suspended then 
fired. 
</P>
<P>
	The SEC said Mrs. Cassano first learned of the pending Lotus  
deal when she was asked to copy documents in late April or early 
May 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	The SEC said Robert Cassano pleaded guilty to insider trading in  
1998. At least six others have pleaded guilty in the case so far. 
</P>
<P>
	The SEC is asking the court to order the defendants to return  
their ill-gotten gains and pay a fine equal to three times the 
amount. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cassanos could not immediately be reached for comment.  

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990527.0273 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 12:52:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IBM Exec Claims Microsoft Pressure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) -- During one of the lowest points of the  
soured relationship between two of the computer industry's giants, 
Microsoft offered an alliance with IBM if it agreed to sacrifice 
its rival operating-system software, an IBM manager told lawyers 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	He said that in a meeting during a trade show in Las Vegas with  
top Microsoft executives -- including Bill Gates -- IBM rejected the 
overture and said it planned to sell both Windows and its own OS/2 
operating system, which ultimately proved a commercial failure. 
</P>
<P>
	Garry Norris, the IBM manager who will be one of the  
government's final witnesses in its antitrust trial with Microsoft, 
contended in sworn testimony Thursday that Microsoft exerted 
pressure on IBM to cut its sales of OS/2, the software product that 
competed directly with Windows until the popularity of OS/2 waned 
in late 1994 and 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	He also testified that major computer makers, such as Compaq  
Computer Corp., agreed not to sell OS/2 on their machines because 
of threats from Microsoft. 
</P>
<P>
	Norris said a Compaq executive told him Microsoft had promised  
in 1993 ``to make it difficult for Compaq'' if it sold IBM's 
product, and he revealed that IBM complained about the alleged 
threats to the Justice Department as early as 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Norris, who works for IBM at nearby Research Triangle Park, will  
be the government's second witness during the rebuttal phase of the 
trial, which resumes Tuesday in Washington after a 13-week recess. 
A Microsoft lawyer, Rick Pepperman, questioned Norris in North 
Carolina about his expected testimony. 
</P>
<P>
	Norris said that after IBM rejected Microsoft's alleged offer in  
1994, Microsoft took an unusually tough stance negotiating the 
wholesale price that IBM paid to put Windows on computers it sold 
to consumers. 
</P>
<P>
	Norris said that weeks before the August 1995 rollout of an  
important new version of Windows, Microsoft threatened to end 
negotiations, which were at a standstill. The companies finally 
reached an agreed price, ``15 minutes before the launch of Windows 
95,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	IBM had paid only $9 for earlier versions of Windows, what it  
believed to be the lowest price paid by any company. But Microsoft 
wanted about $46 for Windows 95 -- much more than IBM believed some 
other computer makers were paying. 
</P>
<P>
	``Microsoft told us repeatedly, `Because you compete with us,  
you're going to get unfavorable terms and conditions,''' Norris 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Norris said IBM's costs rose from $40 million to $220 million.  
</P>
<P>
	Although the exact price that Microsoft charges for Windows is  
one of the industry's most closely guarded secrets, previous 
testimony indicated that favored companies, such as Compaq Computer 
Corp., generally pay less than IBM. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was told they (Compaq) received that deduction because they  
didn't compete with Microsoft,'' Norris said. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft contends that Compaq received lower prices because it  
qualified for some volume discounts and because Compaq helped 
develop some important technology that was incorporated into 
Windows 95. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of its antitrust case, the government alleges that  
Microsoft bullies the nation's computer manufacturers. Lawyers say 
it uses prices to punish its enemies and reward its friends, and to 
stem potential competition among operating system software, 
Microsoft's most lucrative franchise. 
</P>
<P>
	Court papers indicate Norris will testify at the trial about the  
threats Microsoft allegedly made over IBM's support of OS/2 and 
Internet browser software from Netscape Communications Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Norris' deposition was the second of three scheduled this week.  
The government will depose a Microsoft witness, software executive 
Gordon Eubanks, on Friday in California. 
</P>
<P>
	Reporters are allowed to attend the depositions under a 1913 law  
covering antitrust depositions, which are normally conducted in 
private. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990527.0274 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 06:50:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  India, Pakistan Tensions Escalate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DRAS, India (AP) -- Two Indian fighter jets went down in Pakistan  
today as India launched a second day of rocket attacks in Kashmir 
to dislodge Pakistan-backed guerrillas from the disputed frontier. 
</P>
<P>
	Pakistan said it shot down the jets, but Indian officials said  
one crashed due to mechanical failure and the other was shot down 
when it tried to rescue the first pilot. 
</P>
<P>
	The downing of the planes and the use of Indian air power  
indicated a major escalation in the battle over Kashmir, a 
Himalayan territory divided between India and Pakistan. 
</P>
<P>
	Bitter rivals, India and Pakistan have fought two of their three  
wars over the Himalayan state and continue to skirmish daily along 
the ``line of control'' that divides Kashmir. 
</P>
<P>
	The increased tensions between the world's two newest nuclear  
powers alarmed world leaders and brought calls for concern from the 
United Nations, the United States and Britain. 
</P>
<P>
	India said it had aimed rockets today and Wednesday at Pakistani  
soldiers and guerrillas entrenched in rugged, snowcapped mountains 
in the Indian-held part of Kashmir. Pakistan, however, denied that 
its troops were involved and said India's aircraft had bombed 
Pakistani territory. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pakistan army said today it shot down an Indian MiG-27 and a  
MiG-21 fighter jet. One pilot survived and was arrested and another 
died, it said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The planes were well inside Pakistan territory,'' said Army  
spokesman Brig. Rashid Quereshi. ``We already had given India a 
warning.'' 
</P>
<P>
	India acknowledged that two planes were down. One jet had  
mechanical failure and the pilot had to eject in hostile terrain, 
said Air Vice Marshal A.K. Mullick, a defense spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
	A second jet was shot down when it went to rescue the downed  
pilot, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Pakistan's Information Minister called for immediate U.N.  
intervention and said the downing of the aircraft was 
``vindication'' of Indian territorial aggression. He urged India to 
open negotiations with Pakistan and called on U.N. chief Kofi Annan 
to immediately send a special envoy to the region. 
</P>
<P>
	A 465-mile ``line of control'' -- established after the last war  
in 1971 -- divides Kashmir between the two countries. Muslim 
guerrillas have been fighting with Indian security forces in 
Kashmir since 1989, a conflict that has killed more than 15,000 
people. 
</P>
<P>
	Kashmir is the only Muslim-dominated region in largely Hindu  
India. Pakistan, an Islamic republic, says Kashmiris should have 
the right to self-determination. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Indian soldiers fire frequently to thwart Muslim  
guerrillas from trying to sneak into India, this time satellite 
photos reportedly showed that 600 guerrillas had pushed nearly four 
miles into India, in areas uninhabited by the army, officials said. 
Intelligence agencies said the rebels possess antiaircraft 
missiles, radar, snowmobiles and sophisticated communications 
equipment. 
</P>
<P>
	Pakistani Foreign Minister Sartaj Aziz said Pakistan knew  
nothing about the infiltrators. ``No one knows where they come from 
and who they are,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Pakistan continued to fire mortar shells into Indian-held areas  
of Kashmir today, even after Indian air force jets attacked the 
intruders Wednesday, said Indian Maj. Gen. J.J. Singh. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Indian air strikes have been very effective,'' Singh told  
a news conference in New Delhi. ``In most cases, the intruders have 
been isolated.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This afternoon, a few Pakistani shells fell on a deserted  
mountainside overlooking Kargil, a town in a fertile valley a few 
miles from the disputed frontier. An Indian artillery battery, 
hunkered behind a ridge high up in the hills, immediately fired 
back nine 105mm shells at the Pakistani village of Olghing Thong. 
</P>
<P>
	Air Commodore Subash Bhojwani, air officer for operations, would  
not say how long the airstrikes would continue. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not possible to lay down the time frame. This is war,''  
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Singh said the attacks Wednesday and today resulted in ``heavy  
casualties'' among the intruders -- mainly Afghans and Pakistani 
soldiers -- with many of them killed and wounded. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pakistani army claimed today that Indian troops suffered  
heavy casualties and were repulsed when they attacked Pakistani 
military outposts on the border. 
</P>
<P>
	Annan, as well as the United States and Britain, called on all  
parties to stop the fighting, fearing that Kashmir could become a 
nuclear flashpoint. 
</P>
<P>
	A regional Indian military official said the dispute was an  
internal Indian matter. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is not a warlike situation at all. It's a local  
problem,'' said V.S Budhwan, an army corps commander at Kargil, a 
town a few miles from the border. 
</P>
<P>
	Indian officials said Wednesday that at least 160 Afghan  
guerrillas and Pakistani soldiers have been killed since the two 
countries exchanged mortar and artillery fire over the last two 
weeks. Thousands of residents have fled the region. 
</P>
<P>
	Indian aircraft began attacking rebel positions in the  
17,000-foot peaks at dawn Wednesday. Later, MiG jets and MI-25 
helicopters roared over Dras, a village a mile from the border 
between the two countries. 
</P>
<P>
	In Dras, 100 miles northeast of state capital, Srinagar, Indian  
army officers said 70 infiltrators had entrenched themselves on the 
slopes of the mountains at one spot Wednesday, looking down at 
Indian army convoys 2,700 feet below. 
</P>
<P>
	Army officers in the area said the infiltrators must have taken  
months to occupy the posts. Indian opposition parties criticized 
the army failure to spot them earlier. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990527.0275 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 06:50:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
