<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Funding for Discount Internet OK'd </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Schools and libraries will share $2.25 billion  
for Internet hookups and other communications services under a 
federal decision Thursday to approve the maximum funding allowed. 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Communications Commission approved the amount, an  
increase of nearly $1 billion from current levels, despite concerns 
that it would cause higher telephone charges. The money is 
collected from phone companies, which usually pass on the fees to 
customers. 
</P>
<P>
	Three commissioners supported the maximum level, and two  
opposed. Commissioner Michael Powell said he would have supported a 
lower amount, but not $2.25 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	The funding will help wire 528,000 poorer or rural classrooms to  
the Internet, benefiting some 40 million kids. 
</P>
<P>
	``Success in the next millennium will be more and more dependent  
on access to information,'' said Bob Chase, president of the 
National Education Association. ``Now, all Americans, regardless of 
age, income level or geographic location, will have the opportunity 
to learn anything in the world.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Education Secretary Richard Riley called the commission's action  
``a very significant step toward preparing America's students for 
the future.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The commission, under its rules, is allowed to set aside up to  
$2.25 billion a year for the education-rate program, or E-rate. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics fear the full funding will lead to higher phone bills.  
</P>
<P>
	``Every billion dollars of direct fees is $10 per household, per  
year in America,'' said Commissioner Harold Furchtgott-Roth, the 
other dissenter on the funding level. 
</P>
<P>
	His calculations translate to $22.50 per household each year.  
But the chief of the commission's Common Carrier Bureau, Larry 
Strickling, offered a cost of about $4 a year per phone line. He 
said the program gets some of its costs from wireless subscribers, 
who were not included in the staff calculations. 
</P>
<P>
	Proponents say the increase will be offset by some $1 billion  
worth of savings expected later this year in certain long-distance 
telephone fees. Those reductions, however, have come into question 
since a federal appeals court ruled last week that there was 
inadequate explanation for the way the fees were calculated. 
</P>
<P>
	Responding to criticisms about cost, FCC Chairman Bill Kennard  
said, ``We can't afford to leave poor kids in America in the dark 
ages.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The commission last year scaled back the program's budget after  
consumer groups and some lawmakers called for cuts or halts in 
funding. Instead, the commission authorized $1.93 billion for the 
program's first 18 months, a rate of about $1.3 billion a year. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 32,000 applications already have been filed for the  
program's second full fiscal year, which begins July 1. Demand is 
estimated to total $2.44 billion -- more than the $2.25 billion 
available. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission said the program should be able to fund all  
requests for Internet access and telecommunications services such 
as telephones and satellites. Money would be left to fill only some 
of the requests for internal wiring. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990527.0277 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 12:41:35 </DATE_TIME>
