<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Feds Open Hearings On NYPD Tactics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A federal commission waded into the tense and  
politically charged debate over police tactics, hearing hours of 
testimony from critics, defenders and purported victims of the New 
York Police Department. 
</P>
<P>
	Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and Police Commissioner Howard Safir  
defended the department Wednesday against a parade of witnesses who 
said the city's falling crime rate has come at the price of 
citizens' civil rights. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rev. Al Sharpton, who led protests against the February  
police killing of West African immigrant Amadou Diallo, said 
Giuliani and Safir have helped set a tone of disdain for minorities 
that encourages abuse and harassment. 
</P>
<P>
	``Something told (former Officer) Justin Volpe that he could get  
away'' with sodomizing Haitian immigrant Abner Louima, Sharpton 
said, referring to the officer who pleaded guilty this week in one 
of the city's most notorious brutality cases. ``That's frightening, 
and we should have (federal) civil rights monitors in the 
precincts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Three other officers are still on trial for allegedly beating  
Louima and a fourth, a police sergeant, is charged with covering up 
the 1997 incident. 
</P>
<P>
	The eight-member U.S. Civil Rights Commission has the power to  
issue recommendations or appoint an independent federal monitor to 
take over the NYPD if it finds a pervasive pattern of violations. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Giuliani's and Safir's testimonies were punctuated with  
hisses and murmurs of ``liar, liar'' from some spectators. 
</P>
<P>
	``Let's not confuse crime-fighting with brutality,'' Sharpton  
said. ``If you're a criminal with blue jeans on or a blue uniform, 
we want you in jail.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, police were trying to determine whether an officer  
fired at a black teen-ager in the Bronx early Wednesday or whether 
his gun went off accidentally. 
</P>
<P>
	Dante Johnson, 16, was critically injured after he ran from  
officers who believed he and another teen might have been armed, 
police said. The boy was struggling with Officer Mark Conway when 
he was shot. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson's family said he was unarmed and returning home after  
playing basketball. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
