<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Panel OKs More Airport Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House Transportation Committee has  
approved a large increase in airport spending, with its Republican 
leader saying that improving airport safety and facilities is worth 
taking a bite out of the GOP's tax cut plans. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel, on a voice vote Thursday, endorsed a plan to increase  
the Federal Aviation Administration budget from $9.7 billion this 
year to $15.4 billion in 2004. The total increase from current 
spending plans over the five-year period would be $14 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Committee Chairman Bud Shuster, R-Pa., a powerful advocate of  
airport and highway programs, said the increase could be paid for 
by reducing the GOP's planned 10-year $778 billion general tax cut 
by $14 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	But the bill, which should reach the House floor in mid-June,  
faces opposition from fiscal conservatives, the administration and 
the Appropriations Committee which is responsible for drawing up 
annual federal budgets. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill would enact one of Shuster's prime goals, separating  
from the general budget the Aviation Trust Fund, which holds 
revenues from airport user taxes, and using those taxes exclusively 
for airport improvement. 
</P>
<P>
	Currently those revenues go into the general budget, and since  
more money comes in than is spent on airport projects, the balance, 
now $10 billion and expected to rise to $91 billion by 2009, lifts 
the overall budget surplus that Republicans hope to turn into a tax 
cut. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is wrong to use aviation taxes to finance a general tax  
cut,'' Shuster and the committee's ranking Democrat, Rep. James 
Oberstar of Minnesota, wrote in a letter to other House members. 
</P>
<P>
	Shuster and Oberstar, who last year were successful in moving a  
similar highway trust fund off-budget, said all the increased 
spending would come from unused aviation trust fund money and that 
it was ``absolutely false'' that other federal programs would have 
to be cut. 
</P>
<P>
	But isolating the trust fund from the general budget is strongly  
resisted by appropriators, who guard their control over the annual 
budget process. 
</P>
<P>
	Transportation Department Secretary Rodney Slater, in a letter  
to Shuster, also said that putting up a ``firewall'' around 
aviation taxes ``would provide the FAA with a guaranteed funding 
stream without providing incentives to use those funds 
efficiently.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Slater said that while he supported many of the objectives of  
the bill, ``I would be unable to recommend that the president 
sign'' it in its current form. 
</P>
<P>
	Thursday's proposal modified an FAA bill the committee approved  
in March that would have doubled aviation spending over five years. 
That proved too much for the GOP leadership, which is already 
struggling to abide by budget spending caps while living up to its 
promise for an across-the-board tax cut. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill would increase the FAA's facilities budget by 50  
percent, take steps to increase service and competition at small 
airports and provide more money for new runways and air traffic 
controllers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
