<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                         *Kelso Gillenwater    	
</P>
<P>
	TACOMA, Wash. (AP) -- Kelso Gillenwater, retired publisher of The  
News Tribune of Tacoma and former publisher of the Tri-City Herald, 
died Wednesday at age 52. 
</P>
<P>
	Gillenwater, who had suffered a mild heart attack in 1997,  
retired as publisher of The News Tribune that same year. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to The News Tribune, Gillenwater was also  
responsible for three weekly newspapers in the region: The 
Peninsula Gateway, The Pierce County Herald and the Northwest 
Guardian, the U.S. Army newspaper serving Fort Lewis. 
</P>
<P>
	Prior to coming to Tacoma in 1991, he was publisher of the  
Tri-City Herald in Kennewick for 10 years. Both papers are owned by 
McClatchy Newspapers. 
</P>
<P>
	Gillenwater began his 32-year career in newspapers in the South,  
working as a reporter for dailies in Bristol, Va., Greensboro, 
N.C., and Memphis, Tenn. 
</P>
<P>
	After six years of reporting, Gillenwater and partners purchased  
one daily and several weekly newspapers in north and central 
Florida. In 1976, he joined Landmark Communications in Norfolk, 
Va., and became president of the company's small-newspaper 
division. 

</P>
<P>
                            *Ray Kimball    	
</P>
<P>
	DE QUEEN, Ark. (AP) -- Ray Kimball, who started his 79-year  
newspaper career as a boy at his father's paper and worked until 
two months ago as publisher of the weekly De Queen Bee and De Queen 
Daily Citizen, died Wednesday at age 91. 
</P>
<P>
	In the early 1940s, Kimball developed a Teletypesetter network  
that eventually linked nine Arkansas dailies. Later, the system was 
used by other newspaper groups and The Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	His newspaper also was among the first in Arkansas to make its  
news available on the World Wide Web. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1992, he received the National Newspaper Association's  
highest award -- the Amos Award -- given for outstanding 
contributions to the newspaper business and his community, and his 
support of the nation's community newspapers. 
</P>
<P>
	The newspapers he owned or published included the Horatio Times  
weekly, the weekly Sevier County Citizen, and the Magnolia Banner. 
He also served a three-year stint as an aviation officer in the 
Navy. 
</P>
<P>
	Survivors include a daughter and three granddaughters.  

</P>
<P>
                         *George M. Perazich    	
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- George N. Perazich, an industrial economist  
and engineer who published research on the viability of nuclear 
power, urban renewal and developing ocean resources, died Wednesday 
of a brain tumor. He was 94. 
</P>
<P>
	Perazich, in a career that spanned 50 years, conducted studies  
under the auspices of the Works Progress Administration, the 
National Bureau of Economic Research, the National Planning 
Association and the National Science Foundation. 
</P>
<P>
	He was director of industrial rehabilitation for the U.N. Relief  
and Works Agency from 1944 to 1947. 
</P>
<P>
	A native of Yugoslavia, Perazich studied economics and  
engineering at the University of California at Berkeley. During his 
career he also taught there and at the University of Chicago. 

</P>
<P>
                        *William Schield Jr.    	
</P>
<P>
	MILWAUKEE (AP) -- William Schield Jr., a senior vice president at  
Robert W. Baird &AMP; Co., a stock brokerage firm, died Tuesday in a 
car accident. He was 72. 
</P>
<P>
	Schield and his wife, Charlotte, were killed when their car went  
off the road near the northern coast of Spain while on vacation. 
</P>
<P>
	Schield was known at Baird, which he joined in 1958, for his  
personal research into companies and for his insistence that 
clients keep stocks they had purchased. 

</P>
<P>
                            *Waldo Semon    	
</P>
<P>
	HUDSON, Ohio (AP) -- Waldo Semon, who won a patent for bubble  
gum, developed vinyl and helped create synthetic rubber during 
World War II, died Wednesday. He was 100. 
</P>
<P>
	Semon worked for the B.F. Goodrich Co., where one of his first  
assignments was to make a rubber adhesive from polyvinyl chloride. 
Instead, he found a way to make PVC into a flexible, elastic 
material that became widely used in the plastic industry. 
</P>
<P>
	Semon earned 116 U.S. patents by the time he retired in 1963,  
including one for bubble gum. In 1995, Semon was inducted into the 
National Inventors Hall of Fame in Akron. 

</P>
<P>
                           *James Watrous    	
</P>
<P>
	MADISON, Wis. (AP) -- Artist James Watrous, whose murals of  
scenes featuring legendary logger Paul Bunyan adorn the University 
of Wisconsin-Madison Memorial Union, died Tuesday at age 90. 
</P>
<P>
	Watrous, who was associated with UW-Madison for nearly seven  
decades, was paid $18.75 a week for his labor when he started 
painting the Memorial Union murals as a graduate student in 1933. 
He completed them in 1936. 
</P>
<P>
	He also painted murals for federal buildings in Park Falls and  
Grand Rapids, Minn., among other buildings. 
</P>
<P>
	Watrous is credited with leading the campaign for creation of a  
campus art museum, which was dedicated in 1970 and named after the 
late UW President Conrad Elvehjem. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990527.0288 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 12:52:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Board of Trade Sets Eurex Vote </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- The Chicago Board of Trade set June 24 as the  
date its membership will vote on a broad alliance with a 
fast-growing all-electronic exchange and announced other measures 
Thursday in an attempt to fend off competition that has challenged 
its dominance. 
</P>
<P>
	Those measures include slashing fees for large customers who  
want to trade electronically and lobbying federal regulators to 
relax restrictions the CBOT contends hampers growth of U.S. 
exchanges. 
</P>
<P>
	The moves highlight a startling about-face for the world's  
largest futures exchange, which is in danger of losing that title 
this year to the Frankfurt-based Eurex electronic exchange. In 
January it chose a go-slow approach by sticking with the 
auction-style trading, known as open outcry, that many call an 
anachronism. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, exchange Chairman David P. Brennan called Eurex  
``the best business alternative'' and urged members to accept the 
alliance, which insiders say is virtually identical to the one they 
rejected nearly six months ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chicago exchange has not revealed details of the pairing,  
but news reports have indicated it involves giving up its 
electronic trading platform, known as Project A, in favor of 
Eurex's electronic platform and cross-trading each other's 
contracts over the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	The Project A platform was a key sticking point in the previous  
failed alliance bid. Smaller traders, called locals, also have been 
reluctant to cede authority to outsiders and abandon a 150-year 
tradition, which could possibly lead to job losses. That 
intransigence has killed merger hopes with rival Chicago Mercantile 
Exchange several times. 
</P>
<P>
	But large trading firms appear to be gaining the upper hand in a  
power struggle at the Board of Trade. 
</P>
<P>
	Board members recently backed exchange President Thomas Donovan,  
an advocate of speedier change, after Brennan sought to have him 
removed. And the Board of Trade Clearing Corp. voted Wednesday to 
change the way its directors are elected, giving larger firms more 
power in decision-making. 
</P>
<P>
	Such large trading firms have migrated to computer-based  
trading, saying it is easier and cheaper because it saves keeping 
expensive staff at individual exchanges. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our members and customers told us what they want, and the  
board acted quickly and decisively to keep their business,'' 
Donovan said Thursday of the board's actions. 
</P>
<P>
	Many in the industry say U.S. exchanges must adopt electronic  
trading amid stiff competition from overseas exchanges and 
over-the-counter trading. 
</P>
<P>
	Exchanges in London and Paris clung to open outcry, only to find  
much of their business stolen away by Eurex. They now have been 
forced to cut jobs and seek alliances with Eurex to survive. 
</P>
<P>
	Former exchange Chairman Patrick Arbor, who narrowly lost a  
re-election bid in December, had argued the Board of Trade must be 
prepared to end the open outcry system if it wanted to save many of 
the Chicago area's 150,000 futures industry jobs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990527.0289 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 09:11:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Religion Today  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- To be truly Catholic, what should colleges do?  
Keep crucifixes on classroom walls? Require religion courses? Spurn 
gay student organizations? Hire only theology professors who back 
the church's ban on women priests? 
</P>
<P>
	Beyond such specific disputes, there's a far broader debate in  
progress concerning the nation's 235 Catholic colleges and 
universities, which enroll 670,000 students. Many leaders in higher 
education have been engaged in a protracted struggle with Pope John 
Paul II's Vatican over how Catholic loyalty is defined and who 
defines it. 
</P>
<P>
	The conflict originated in 1967 when a conference of U.S. campus  
administrators declared that ``the Catholic university must have a 
true autonomy and academic freedom in the face of authority of 
whatever kind, lay or clerical.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the decades since, many U.S. Catholic campuses have  
secularized, becoming less distinguishable from other schools. For 
instance, a recent survey of a dozen church-related schools showed 
that only 57 percent of teachers were Catholic. And Rome has been 
upset by continual criticisms of church teachings from professors 
on U.S. Catholic campuses. 
</P>
<P>
	To strengthen the Catholic commitment of campuses worldwide, the  
pope issued a 1990 decree, ``Ex Corde Ecclesiae.'' It recognized 
universities' institutional autonomy and academic freedom, but only 
``within the confines of the truth and the common good.'' Rome 
directed the bishops in each nation to write policy statements 
applying the pope's rules. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1996, the U.S. bishops endorsed a policy that was pretty much  
what colleges wanted. But the Vatican's education congregation 
bounced the document, directing the Americans to do a rewrite with 
more teeth. The U.S. bishops are now considering a second version 
fashioned to Rome's specifications. 
</P>
<P>
	The rewrite specifies, among other things, that a majority of  
board members and teachers should be Catholic if possible, that 
college presidents must take a prescribed oath of church fidelity 
and that anyone appointed to teach Catholic theology needs a 
``mandate,'' or endorsement, from the hierarchy. 
</P>
<P>
	The text also says theology teachers are responsible for  
presenting ``authentic'' doctrine and that church authorities would 
have the power to withdraw their endorsement in case of trouble. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. hierarchy's committee on these issues meets June 28-9  
to consider proposed changes and plans to have a third version 
ready for action when all the American bishops meet in November. 
</P>
<P>
	The committee chairman, Bishop John Leibrecht of Springfield,  
Mo., explains: ``We're looking for a way, agreed upon by bishops 
and universities and the Vatican, that will better ensure the 
Catholic nature of our institutions of higher education, even as 
they continue to participate in the broader context of American 
higher education.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A tall order.  
</P>
<P>
	The most important proposal on Leibrecht's desk comes from the  
Association of Catholic Colleges and Universities, with the added 
endorsement of the Jesuit college organization and three major 
groups of Catholic scholars. It would delete the specific demands 
in the Vatican-inspired draft in favor of a vaguer commitment to 
``Catholic ideals, principles and attitudes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Monika Hellwig, executive director of the ACCU, contends that  
unless the bishops shift to a less legalistic policy, colleges will 
be saddled with problems over contracts, accreditation, and public 
aid. ``Some of the small colleges would absolutely not survive,'' 
she says. 
</P>
<P>
	After an April visit to Rome, Hellwig is convinced that the top  
officials of the Vatican education congregation are not pushing for 
a tougher policy. She thinks pressure is coming from lower-ranking 
Vatican staffers, especially in the agency that enforces canon law. 
But if the American bishops back the ACCU's plea for a softer 
policy, says Hellwig, the matter could be appealed to the pope. 
</P>
<P>
	Hellwig is confident that a majority of bishops will favor  
something like the policy that her colleges want. ``However, what 
we really need to make a strong case in Rome is the same kind of 
majority we got the first time around.'' The bishops' 1996 approval 
was nearly unanimous. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have our work cut out for us,'' she acknowledges. One  
factor is that only 57 of the 221 Catholic dioceses contain 
church-related colleges where educators can influence bishops. 
Hellwig says that ``bishops who don't have colleges are not 
informed, but they vote.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Another factor of unknown impact is the Cardinal Newman Society,  
which was formed six years ago to lobby for strict application of 
the pope's 1990 decree. For instance, the society is protesting 
that 21 Catholic colleges invited commencement speakers this year 
who hold pro-choice views on abortion. The society is backed by 28 
prominent Catholics, including the presidents of five conservative 
Catholic colleges. 
</P>
<P>
	Patrick Reilly, the society's executive director, contends that  
the ACCU has spent nine years preventing implementation of the 
pope's policy and calls the latest ACCU proposal ``irrelevant and 
unhelpful.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Respect for church authority and teaching is the first step  
toward maintaining Catholic identity,'' Reilly complains. ``At some 
Catholic universities, the disrespect is palpable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	George Marsden, a Protestant historian teaching at the  
University of Notre Dame, thinks today's Catholic schools are 
similar to Yale or Princeton in the 1920s when they were still 
talking about their Protestant identity but on the path toward 
secularization. 
</P>
<P>
	``The richness of America is enhanced if we have Catholic  
institutions,'' Marsden believes, so he would like to see strongly 
religious campuses. ``If you dismantle the supporting institutions 
of subcultures, you create a national culture unable to find its 
moral bearings.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The Vatican is right to be concerned, but it can't be done the  
way they want to do it without causing tremendous reaction.'' If 
Catholic schools are to remain identifiably Catholic, he believes, 
it will not be the doing of bishops from outside but their own 
administrators and faculty members. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
