<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dunlap's Double-Eagle Shot of Day  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	POTOMAC, Md. (AP) -- Scott Dunlap made only the third double  
eagle in Kemper Open history Thursday when his 3-iron second shot 
found the pin from 218 yards at the sixth hole. 
</P>
<P>
	``I ripped a low cut and I was hoping to get it there,'' Dunlap  
said. ``I thought it rolled past the hole. I was giving the club 
back to my caddie and I heard the crowd go ballistic.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The shot moved Dunlap from level par to 3-under, which was also  
his score at the end of the round. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a dicey shot,'' he said. ``You miss and you get six.  
But I'm the kind of guy that goes down swinging.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The previous double eagles at the Kemper also came at the  
520-yard sixth, which has a dogleg to the right and a creek in 
front of the green. Mark Brooks made the hole in 2 in the third 
round in 1991, and Woody Austin did the same in the first round 
last year. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *DADDY ELS:* Ernie Els bypassed the Kemper Open to play in  
Europe this week, but golf isn't the first thing on his mind right 
now anyway. 
</P>
<P>
	The two-time U.S. Open champion became a father for the first  
time this week. 
</P>
<P>
	``I spent the whole day on the phone after the birth,'' Els said  
Thursday. ``It was like winning a major.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Els' wife, Liezl, gave birth to the 8-pound girl on Wednesday.  
They were married in South Africa on New Year's Eve, but also have 
homes in Orlando, Fla., and in London. 
</P>
<P>
	Els is still planning to play in the Volvo PGA Championship,  
which starts Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Golf right now is not at the top of the agenda,'' Els said.  
``I'm just going to play and see what happens. But I'm not worried 
either way. Everything is healthy, and that's the most important 
thing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Els said his daughter probably will be named Samantha.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *GREEN LIGHT FOR BROWNE:* Olin Browne's victory in last week's  
Colonial has earned him a spot in the U.S. Open. 
</P>
<P>
	Browne was granted a special exemption Thursday by the United  
States Golf Association to play in the June 17-20 major at 
Pinehurst, N.C. 
</P>
<P>
	Browne was given the exemption because he has won twice on the  
PGA Tour since last year's U.S. Open. His other victory came at the 
1998 Hartford Open. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *BORN UNAMERICAN:* Brian Watts can't understand why he's not  
eligible for the Ryder Cup. Although born in Canada, he's lived in 
the United States since he was 6 months old and became a citizen 
when he was 16. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would do anything for my country,'' said Watts, the surprise  
story of 1998 when he finished second at the British Open. ``I find 
it is a very strange ruling, especially when you look at the 
Olympics. You have got Olympians that only get their citizenship to 
play on the U.S. team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The PGA of America contends that only American-born players can  
be considered for the Ryder Cup. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *DIVOTS:* Daniel Snyder, whose $800 million offer to buy the  
Washington Redskins was approved this week by the NFL, made an 
appearance at the balcony overlooking the 18th hole. Snyder signed 
autographs before disappearing into the pavilion. ... Carlos 
Franco, winner earlier this month in New Orleans, was disqualified 
when he missed his tee time for unknown reasons. He had not 
contacted PGA Tour officials as of late Thursday. ... John Daly 
carded a triple-bogey 8 on the sixth hole. He shot a 78. 
</P>
</TEXT>
