<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Study Reveals Staph Vaccine Hopeful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A new vaccine against staph infections, an  
increasingly dangerous threat to hospital patients, has been tested 
successfully in animals, researchers report. 
</P>
<P>
	In studies at Brigham and Women's Hospital in Boston, the  
vaccine was able to protect mice and rabbits from lethal doses of 
strains of staphylococcus aureus bacteria, researchers report today 
in the journal Science. 
</P>
<P>
	Researchers worldwide are scrambling to find new vaccines  
against staph because the common bacterial infection is becoming 
more resistant to drugs such as penicillin. Some strains of staph 
now even are partially resistant to vancomycin, a drug that has 
been the last line of defense against the microbe. 
</P>
<P>
	Staph infections strike a half million American hospital  
patients a year, particularly those having heart valve surgery, 
knee and hip replacement, and kidney failure patients who are on 
dialysis. Outside the hospital, the microbe can cause infections 
ranging from skin abscesses to pneumonia, meningitis, and 
infections of the bone and heart. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Gerald B. Pier, co-author of the Science study, said the  
vaccine he and his colleagues developed is based on a molecule that 
staph makes only when the microbe starts an infection inside the 
body. This molecule, called PNSG, normally is not seen in 
laboratory cultures of staph, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``This molecule appears to be critical for infection and disease  
progression,'' Pier said. ``All staph aureus strains that we have 
looked at in the lab, and that's well over 50, have it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pier and his co-workers isolated the PNSG molecule from staph  
infection specimens. They then injected purified PNSG into 
laboratory mice and rabbits. 
</P>
<P>
	In all cases, Pier said, the animals developed antibodies that  
reacted powerfully against staph bacteria. He said mice with such 
antibodies were injected with double-lethal doses of staph bacteria 
that was partially resistant to vancomycin. All of the test mice 
survived, he said, but 80 percent or more of the mice not protected 
by PNSG shots died of staph infection. 
</P>
<P>
	Pier said human trials of the PSNG vaccine should start within  
18 months. 
</P>
<P>
	When a staph vaccine is developed, Pier said it probably will be  
used most commonly to protect patients having surgery and people at 
high risk of burns or wounds, such as firemen, policemen and 
soldiers. 
</P>
<P>
	Pier said it also may be possible to inject healthy people with  
a vaccine and then extract antibodies against staph. These 
antibodies could be injected into accident victims and others 
hospitalized unexpectedly. Such antibodies probably would protect 
against staph infections for up to two weeks, Pier said. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Anthony S. Fauci, director of the National Institute of  
Allergy and Infections, said the vaccine research was ``a hopeful 
step against a very worrisome pathogen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fauci, in a statement, said that emerging strains of staph that  
are partially resistant to vancomycin are ``most troubling'' and 
that ``new treatments and ... and effective vaccine are urgently 
needed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nabi, a drug company in Boca Raton, Fla., is conducting clinical  
trials of a staph vaccine among 1,800 patients who are on dialysis. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nabi vaccine is based on molecules that are different from  
the ones in the vaccine under study by Pier and his group. Results 
of Nabi's vaccine study will be announced late next year, company 
official Tanina Frouge said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
