<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Charter Buying Another Cable TV Co. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Paul Allen's Charter Communications Inc. is  
making its second cable television acquisition in two days, 
announcing today it is buying Fanch Communications Inc. Terms were 
not disclosed. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal for Denver-based Fanch comes a day after Charter  
disclosed it had agreed to acquire Falcon Cable TV of Los Angeles 
for $3.6 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	It is part of a buying spree that is making Charter one of the  
nation's biggest cable system owners, ranking behind only AT&AMP;T 
Corp., Time Warner Inc. and Comcast Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Fanch has about 547,000 subscribers, boosting Charter's base of  
subscribers to about 5.5 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Allen, who co-founded Microsoft Corp. with Bill Gates, purchased  
Charter in July 1998 and has spent about $16 billion on cable 
purchases over the past past two years. 
</P>
<P>
	Charter is buying the Fanch properties from a group that  
includes two funds managed by the Blackstone Group of New York, 
Narragansett Capital Partners and some affiliates of Fanch. 
</P>
<P>
	Fanch has 308,000 customers in West Virginia and Pennsylvania,  
bringing Charter's presence in those states to about 400,000 when 
other deals are completed. 
</P>
<P>
	Fanch also has 140,000 customers in Michigan, Indiana, Kentucky,  
Louisiana and Wisconsin. 
</P>
<P>
	The Falcon deal brings Charter 1 million subscribers in 27  
states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
