<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> McCain Accepts Award for Reagan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Ronald Reagan may have earned the title  
Conservative of the Century, but it was presidential contender John 
McCain who picked up the award. 
</P>
<P>
	Former first lady Nancy Reagan designated McCain to accept the  
honor bestowed on her husband Wednesday night by the American 
Conservative Union. The Arizona senator used the event to salute 
what he called the ``genius'' of the former leader of his party -- 
an unrelenting faith in freedom and patriotism. 
</P>
<P>
	``He knew that America's efforts to help humanity secure the  
blessings of liberty are what truly distinguish us from all other 
nations on earth,'' McCain told a crowd of hundreds in a ballroom 
at the Washington Hilton, where Reagan was shot in 1981. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain said Reagan's legacy of fighting against communism and  
other threats to the free world are still important lessons today. 
</P>
<P>
	``That doesn't mean that we have to risk lives and resources  
needlessly, lurching ineffectually from one crisis to another,'' 
McCain said. ``But it does mean that we should defend our interests 
and values when they are threatened.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said the nation should adhere to Reagan's guiding principles  
of being ``sure of ourselves, firm in our purpose and proud of our 
heritage.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Republican senator has spoken out several times on U.S.  
action in Kosovo, notably to criticize President Clinton for ruling 
out the use of ground troops. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain, a former prisoner of war, said then-Governor Reagan also  
served as a personal inspiration for him during his captivity. When 
McCain returned home from Vietnam, he discovered that many 
prominent figures in the country spoke pessimistically about 
America's future. But unlike them, Reagan believed in the nation's 
claim to greatness, McCain said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Of that, Ronald Reagan was supremely confident, and he became  
president to prove it,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990527.0303 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 18:36:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IRL Chief Douses CART Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- The Indy Racing League is no closer to  
ending its feud with rival CART, despite talks aimed at bringing 
the two sides together, IRL's president said today. 
</P>
<P>
	In his most extensive comments on the 4-year-old split in  
American open-wheel racing, Tony George accused CART of fueling 
reports of a reconciliation to boost its stock price, soothe 
sponsors and divert attention from the Indianapolis 500. 
</P>
<P>
	While admitting once again that it would be difficult for both  
series to survive, George said he got no indication of common 
ground at a meeting last week with Andrew Craig, chief executive 
officer of Championship Auto Racing Teams. 
</P>
<P>
	``As long as we have different philosophies, we're never going  
to strike any kind of accord,'' George said. ``I can't say I'm 
encouraged by anything we talked about.'' 
</P>
<P>
	George, also president of the Indianapolis Motor Speedway, began  
the IRL in late 1995 as a low-cost, ovals-only alternative to CART. 
The older organization responded by boycotting the Indy 500, taking 
away some of the luster from the world's most famous race. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not going to compromise ourselves just to get them back  
here,'' said George, preparing for his fourth 500 without CART. 
``It's as simple as that. The IRL is doing very well with its 
growth at this stage. Obviously, we've shown we don't need them to 
have a successful event.'' 
</P>
<P>
	CART, which holds the Motorola 300 at Madison, Ill., on  
Saturday, is making plans to expand its 20-race schedule to other 
overseas markets, mentioning Germany and Mexico as possible sites. 
But Craig stressed his teams also want to go back to Indy. 
</P>
<P>
	``All we are attempting to do is to act in good faith for what  
we believe is in the best interest of the sport and the fans,'' 
Craig said after being told of George's comments. ``We have made no 
secret of the fact that all our teams would like to race in 
Indianapolis.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The two sides face major hurdles, such as totally different  
chassis and engine specifications. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have no idea where all the speculation is coming from,''  
Craig said. ``We strongly believe that it's best not to comment on 
any of these specific issues at this time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	George said he met with Craig in March and they got together  
again last week in Indianapolis. George also has met with NASCAR 
chief Bill France Jr., portrayed as the potential broker of a deal 
between the two open-wheel series. 
</P>
<P>
	France's International Speedway Corp., which owns and operates  
NASCAR, recently bought Penske Motorsports. That gave ISC 10 
racetracks, with at least three more planned in the near future. 
</P>
<P>
	George said his talks with Craig focused on their general  
support for open-wheel racing, but didn't focus on specifics for 
bringing the two sides together. 
</P>
<P>
	``Certainly, he wasn't trying to cast himself as someone who has  
all the answers,'' George said. ``It was more to express an 
interest in what we're doing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Though nearly all of the most-established drivers remained with  
CART after the split, George clearly feels he has the upper hand 
because the IRL has the Indy 500. He said talk of a merger is 
merely an attempt to bolster CART, which is a publicly traded 
company on the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	``They need to continue to give some glimmer of hope that  
something is in the offing to help keep their stock price where 
they want it to be,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	George's right-hand man, IRL executive director Leo Mehl, also  
gave little hint of a compromise earlier Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I call it the May whine,'' Mehl said. ``Those CART guys are  
very concerned with what's going on here. If they come back here 
with the same engines we use, the same chassis, they'll get their 
doors blown off.'' 
</P>
<P>
	George and Mehl said there would be no attempt to reach a deal  
that would allow the CART teams to return to the Indy 500 unless 
they run the other 10 IRL races, too. 
</P>
<P>
	George conceded that neither open-wheel series is likely to  
reach the popularity of NASCAR's stock-car series unless they 
merge. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sooner or later, it will have to come to just one series for  
it to flourish,'' George said. ``I don't know and I don't have a 
crystal ball to predict what that outcome might be.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
