<HEADLINE> Olympic Officials Prepare Response </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Atlanta Olympic officials will provide a detailed  
response to a congressional inquiry into the city's bid for the 
1996 Summer Games early next week, a spokesman said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Georgia Amateur Athletics Foundation will provide a far more  
thorough response than the one prepared for an IOC investigation of 
the bid cities from 1996 through 2004, spokesman Lee Echols said. 
</P>
<P>
	The inquiry will be ``a good opportunity to start clearing the  
air on some of these issues,'' Echols told The Atlanta 
Journal-Constitution. 
</P>
<P>
	Specifically, the House Commerce Committee has questions about  
excessive gifts, favors and visits offered to International Olympic 
Committee members. 
</P>
<P>
	The committee, which looked into the scandal that tainted Salt  
Lake City's bid for the 2002 Winter Olympics, is now trying to 
determine whether Atlanta bidders bribed IOC delegates in return 
for votes. 
</P>
<P>
	Atlanta Olympic organizers have admitted to exceeding spending  
limits on gifts for IOC members, but told IOC investigators in 
March that they did nothing wrong. 
</P>
<P>
	Congressional investigators will be examining Olympic records  
contained in 1,400 boxes at the Atlanta History Center. 
</P>
<P>
	The Georgia Amateur Athletics Foundation, which is embroiled in  
a legal fight with members of the media to keep some bid records 
sealed, recently opened the nine boxes of documents. 
</P>
<P>
	The records are also at the center of a legal dispute over  
whether the public should be allowed to view documents detailing 
Atlanta's bid for the games. 
</P>
<P>
	The released records included scores of thank-you notes,  
fund-raising letters, newspaper articles and marketing plans, 
including one that warned Atlanta leaders that ``lobbying the 
90-member IOC voting bloc is tricky business, not unlike walking 
through a minefield at midnight.'' 
</P>
<P>
	However, they showed no evidence of the problems that tarnished  
Salt Lake City's Olympic bid. 
</P>
</TEXT>
