<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lawyer-Writer Is Dead at Age 69 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LEXINGTON, Ky. (AP) -- Kent Hollingsworth, who shaped The  
Blood-Horse weekly magazine into one of the thoroughbred racing's 
most respected trade journals, is dead at the age of 69. 
</P>
<P>
	Hollingsworth, who served as editor, then publisher of The  
Blood-Horse from 1963-86, died Wednesday night at the University of 
Kentucky Medical Center. The cause of death was not known. 
</P>
<P>
	A native of St. Louis, Hollingsworth also was a lawyer and  
teacher. When he became editor of The Blood-Horse, the magazine had 
a circulation of 6,800 and a staff of 30. When he departed as 
publisher 23 years later, the circulation had reached 21,700 and 
the staff numbered 101. 
</P>
<P>
	Under his leadership, the magazine expanded its reputation as an  
authoritative source of information, commentary, statistics and 
analysis on thoroughbred racing and breeding. He wrote the highly 
respected ``What's Going On Here?'' column. 
</P>
<P>
	In recent years, Hollingsworth returned to the practice of law  
and served as a Distinguished Lecturer in equine law in the Equine 
Industry Program at the University of Louisville. 
</P>
<P>
	He began his journalism career as a news photographer and sports  
writer for the Lexington Leader in 1954. He also has authored five 
books. 
</P>
<P>
	He was president of the National Turf Writers from 1968-70;  
president of the Thoroughbred Club of America from 1974-75; vice 
president of the National Museum of Racing at Saratoga Springs, 
N.Y., and chairman of the Racing Hall of Fame Committee from 
1982-86. 
</P>
<P>
	Hollingsworth donated his body to the University of Kentucky  
Medical Center for teaching purposes. 
</P>
<P>
	He is survived by his widow, Mary; six children: Val of  
Versailles; Randolph and Letitia Gray of Lexington; Amery Nies of 
Erie, Pa.; Wright of Missoula, Mont., and Charles Constant of 
Baltimore; a sister, Dorcas Wiedemann of Scott County; and a 
brother, Vertrees, of Pinehurst, N.C. 
</P>
<P>
	A memorial service will be held at a later date at the Kentucky  
Horse Park in Lexington. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
