<DOCNO> APW19990527.0311 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 17:41:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hectic Hurricane Season Predicted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Federal officials predicted a busier-than-usual  
Atlantic hurricane season today and urged people in hurricane-prone 
areas to think about how they will handle the storms. 
</P>
<P>
	This is the first time the National Oceanic and Atmospheric  
Administration has issued a preseason forecast. It calls for three 
or more intense hurricanes -- two is normal -- and will be updated in 
August, at the height of the June-to-November season. 
</P>
<P>
	The outlook was issued at the National Hurricane Center, during  
a news conference attended by officials from the National Weather 
Service, the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration and 
the Federal Emergency Management Agency. 
</P>
<P>
	Forecasters expect more hurricanes this year in part because of  
La Nina. The opposite of El Nino, La Nina brings cooler-than-normal 
temperatures to the part of the Pacific Ocean off South America 
that sees warmer water temperatures during El Nino. 
</P>
<P>
	Forecasters anticipate two conditions that could facilitate  
hurricane development: low wind shear in parts of the Atlantic 
Ocean and the Caribbean Sea and a wind pattern off of west Africa 
that may feed developing storms. 
</P>
<P>
	Advances in technology are helping forecasters warn people more  
accurately and further in advance, but the public has to do its 
part, too, according to the weather service's director, Jack Kelly. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the final analysis, even a perfect warning is an academic  
exercise if people don't get it or haven't thought about what they 
would do,'' he warned. 
</P>
<P>
	During the recently completed annual session of the Florida  
Legislature, a statewide building code was proposed for Florida 
that would eliminate some strict code requirements already in place 
in South Florida to lessen hurricane damage. 
</P>
<P>
	FEMA Director James Lee Witt said he does not think it is his  
place to comment on state and local building codes. But, he was 
quick to add: ``I think we should build better, develop safer 
communities.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The officials also took the occasion to urge all residents in  
areas that could be affected by hurricanes to heed any and all 
evacuation orders. 
</P>
<P>
	Hurricane center director Jerry Jarrell, however, also cautioned  
against unnecessary flight. 
</P>
<P>
	``You tend to have too many people evacuate,'' he said. ``Trust  
me, there's not enough roads to get us all to Atlanta.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990527.0312 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 14:41:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Katz Works To Rebuild ABC Sports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Howard Katz is rebuilding ABC Sports. It's nothing compared to  
what Sean McManus had to deal with when he took over at CBS three 
years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Although ABC is struggling to re-establish its sports identity  
after being thought of as an extension of fellow Disney-owned ESPN, 
Katz has far more to work with than McManus did. 
</P>
<P>
	For one thing, ABC has ``Monday Night Football,'' the top-rated  
show on the network. It also has the Triple Crown, the top college 
football bowl games and a solid golf package. 
</P>
<P>
	``I definitely see some similarities there between the two  
situations,'' said Jim Spence, who worked for ABC for 25 years and 
runs a consulting agency. ``The image at CBS was pretty low, 
probably even lower than what ABC's is right now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Katz's first order of business since being hired as president of  
the sports division in March -- after ordering the walls at ABC to 
be painted -- was to secure a five-year deal with the Indianapolis 
500 last week. 
</P>
<P>
	With Indy's plummeting ratings, it may not seem like a big deal.  
But the network could not afford to lose a race with such 
tradition. 
</P>
<P>
	``Indy is symbolically important for the network,'' Spence said.  
``Plus, my feeling is that there is going to be a settlement 
between the IRL and CART ... and I think Indy will become Indy 
again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The two racing circuits have begun talks about a possible merger  
after four years of feuding. 
</P>
<P>
	Next up for Katz is the Triple Crown. ABC's deal expires after  
the Belmont Stakes on June 5 and the bidding figures to be far more 
competitive than for Indy. Fox, NBC and CBS should all be in the 
mix. 
</P>
<P>
	But even though CBS may be interested in landing the horse  
racing package, it is not such a necessity these days. 
</P>
<P>
	When McManus took over at CBS in December 1996, the network was  
in disarray. His priority was to reacquire the NFL, which he did a 
year later. Then he made certain to extend CBS' PGA coverage, U.S. 
Open tennis and Big Ten and SEC basketball packages. He also 
broadened the network's NASCAR coverage and locked up high-quality 
talents Jim Nantz and Phil Simms. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, less than three years later, CBS' sports division is among  
the elite. 
</P>
<P>
	Katz's challenge is to do the same.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'd love to be able to restore ABC Sports to the level it once  
had,'' Katz said. ``One of my goals is to give a lift in morale 
around here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One of the ways to keep employees' spirits high and restore the  
ABC tradition is to try to keep from being perceived as ``ESPN3.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Another would be to take advantage of the current dispute  
between Major League Baseball and ESPN, and pick up the baseball 
package if it becomes available. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *WHAT'S UP, DOC?:* Turner analyst Doc Rivers is a candidate for  
several NBA head coaching vacancies, despite limited experience 
that includes a stint as a CBA ``coach's aide'' during the NBA 
lockout. 
</P>
<P>
	Madison Square Garden president Dave Checketts also inquired  
about him -- not for a job as coach but as the New York Knicks' 
general manager to replace the fired Ernie Grunfeld. 
</P>
<P>
	Rivers, who played for the Knicks when coach Jeff Van Gundy was  
an assistant, would be interested in the GM job -- but he'd rather 
coach. Rivers interviewed for the Washington job and has been 
mentioned for the Orlando position. 
</P>
<P>
	He also said Van Gundy shouldn't be fired.  
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know what more he can do,'' Rivers said. ``I don't  
think he needs to do anything more.'' 
</P>
<P>
