<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Panel May Boost Airport Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The chairman of the House Transportation  
Committee moved Thursday to put a dent in his own Republican 
party's tax cut plans with a proposal to increase airport spending 
by $14 billion through 2004. 
</P>
<P>
	The committee, by voice vote, approved Bud Shuster's revised  
plan to gradually increase Federal Aviation Administration spending 
from $9.7 billion this year to $15.4 billion in 2004. The annual 
increases would total $14 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Shuster, R-Pa., a fierce advocate of infrastructure spending,  
said all the extra spending would come from the Aviation Trust 
Fund, which holds revenues from airport user taxes. He would 
separate the fund from the general budget so that user taxes could 
not be used for non-aviation programs. 
</P>
<P>
	That move could seriously affect future budget considerations --  
the trust fund currently has a balance of $10 billion, and that is 
expected to rise to $91 billion over the next decade. But Shuster 
said it could be done without harming other federal programs if 
Republicans trimmed their plans for a $778 billion tax cut over the 
next 10 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Shuster said it was ``grossly unfair'' to use airport taxes to  
fund a general tax cut rather than for improvements in airport 
safety and facilities. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year Shuster succeeded in isolating a similar highway trust  
fund from the general budget. Shuster's efforts have met strong 
opposition from the House and Senate appropriations committees, 
which see the budget changes as a loss of control over how federal 
dollars are spent. 
</P>
<P>
	``It looks like it's heating up and that's fine,'' Shuster said  
of his differences with the appropriators. 
</P>
<P>
	Thursday's proposal modified an FAA bill the committee approved  
in March that would have doubled aviation spending over five years. 
That proved too much to handle for the GOP leadership, which is 
trying to restrain spending while pushing a big general tax cut. 
</P>
<P>
	The new version, which is expected to reach the House floor in  
mid-June, was backed by the ranking Democrat on the committee, Rep. 
James Oberstar of Minnesota. ``This is the best possible 
solution,'' he said. ``It will work.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Transportation Department Secretary Rodney Slater, in a  
letter to Shuster Wednesday, said that while the administration 
supports the program goals of the bill, it opposes separating trust 
fund revenues from the general budget. 
</P>
<P>
	Building a firewall around airport taxes, he said, would  
``provide the FAA with a guaranteed funding stream without 
providing incentives to use those funds efficiently.'' Slater said 
he would be ``unable to recommend'' that the president sign the 
bill in its current form. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill would increase the FAA's facilities budget by 50  
percent, take steps to increase service and competition at small 
airports and provide more money for new runways and air traffic 
controllers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
