<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Votes To Block Base Closings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Ignoring Pentagon pleas, the Senate voted  
60-40 on Wednesday to block a round of cost-saving military base 
closings proposed for 2001. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration argued the closures were needed to  
free up funds to help modernize a military stretched even thinner 
by the conflict in the Balkans. 
</P>
<P>
	But Republicans said they mistrusted the process, renewing  
allegations that President Clinton meddled in 1995 to save jobs at 
bases in vote-rich California and Texas. And Democratic support for 
another round was mixed, with Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., 
among the opponents. 
</P>
<P>
	Late Wednesday, the Senate turned down, 77 to 21, a move by Sen.  
Bob Smith, R-N.H., to cut off funding for U.S. participation in the 
NATO military campaign against Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith told senators that Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic  
``has accomplished what he wanted to accomplish,'' driving ethnic 
Albanians out of Kosovo. ``I don't know what we're achieving in 
continuing to bomb.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Senate leaders of both parties said such a stark action  
would undercut NATO and U.S. troops in the region. Previous efforts 
in the Senate to either scale back or step up the military campaign 
have also been defeated. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the third year in a row that the administration's plan  
for additional base closings was rejected by Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	At the White House, spokesman Barry Toiv called the Senate  
action ``a vote in favor of wasting defense resources that are 
needed to maintain our defense readiness.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In what also is becoming a perennial vote, the Senate rejected  
51-49 a move to lift a ban that prohibits abortions at military 
hospitals -- even if the woman pays for it herself. 
</P>
<P>
	The sponsors of ending the prohibition, Sens. Patty Murray,  
D-Wash., and Olympia Snowe, R-Maine, argued that the restriction 
put a heavy burden on military women stationed overseas. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are asking a lot of these young women. We should at least  
allow them to pay for this procedure, in a military hospital, where 
it is safe,'' Murray said. Opponents argued that it still would 
amount to a partial federal subsidy. An identical attempt was 
rejected 49-44 in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	The votes came as the Senate inched toward passage of a $288.8  
billion defense spending bill for the fiscal year that begins Oct. 
1. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill provides $8.3 billion more than Clinton asked for a  
variety of Pentagon programs for next year, including a 4.8 percent 
across-the-board military pay raise next Jan. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	The base closings vote rejected a move by Sens. John McCain,  
R-Ariz., and Carl Levin, D-Mich., to revive the proposal. 
</P>
<P>
	``We should be ashamed, or a little ashamed. Find me one  
military expert who says we don't have to close bases,'' said 
McCain. 
</P>
<P>
	But Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., called the  
proposal ``one more stick in the eye that will adversely affect our 
military men and women.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The timing could not be worse'' for additional base closings,  
Lott said. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense Secretary William Cohen contends that closing antiquated  
bases -- many of them Cold War relics -- could save the Pentagon 
nearly $4 billion a year that would be better spent on aircraft 
carriers, jet fighters and other crucial hardware. 
</P>
<P>
	But Congress has always been reluctant to close bases, and is  
still smarting from previous rounds, in 1991, 1993 and 1995, that 
closed 70 bases and depots. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have not seen the kind of savings that were promised,''  
said Sen. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif. She said that in the 1995 round, 
``California got hit so hard, I couldn't even begin to tell you. We 
still have bases sitting there that haven't been cleaned up and 
cannot be reused.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The administration's proposal for two new rounds of base  
closings -- one in 2001 and another in 2005 -- was rejected this 
month by the Armed Services panel. McCain and Levin had sought to 
win approval for just one round. 
</P>
<P>
	Armed Services Committee Chairman John Warner, R-Va., contended  
it was impossible to create a truly nonpartisan process for base 
closings, particularly while Clinton remains in office. The 
existing process calls for Congress to authorize a round of 
closings, then for the independent Base Realignment and Closure 
Commission to select the bases. 
</P>
<P>
	But Republicans contend Clinton poisoned the process to save  
jobs at McClellan Air Force Base in Sacramento, Calif., and Kelly 
Air Force Base in San Antonio, both targets of a 1995 round. ``The 
sticky fingerprints of politics got in there,'' Warner said. The 
administration denies doing anything illegal as it tried to find 
private-sector jobs for base workers. 
</P>
<P>
	Toiv, the White House spokesman, said Wednesday that the Defense  
Department calculates that the steps taken at McClellan and Kelly 
``has already saved taxpayers $200 million and will save $2.6 
billion over the next 15 years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	The bill is S. 1059.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
