<HEADLINE> Warfield Introduction Worth $629,529 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DAYTON, Ohio (AP) -- A jury has decided that an introduction to  
pro football Hall of Famer Paul Warfield is worth at least 
$629,529. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal court jury on Wednesday awarded that amount to  
businessman Richard Rentz, who said his introduction of Warfield to 
two Miami, Fla., businessmen led to a lucrative license to design, 
manufacture and distribute NFL athletic sportswear. 
</P>
<P>
	Warfield, who played for the Cleveland Browns and Miami Dolphins  
in the 1960s and 1970s, was dismissed as a defendant in Rentz's 
civil lawsuit before the trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Rentz, of nearby Washington Township, said that in exchange for  
introducing Armando Mendez and Ignacio Mendez to Warfield, Rentz 
received an oral contract that called for him to receive 1 percent 
of the gross sales of their company, Dynasty Apparel Industries 
Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Those sales have exceeded $62.9 million since Rentz made the  
introduction at a baseball game in Cincinnati in the fall of 1990, 
according to testimony. 
</P>
<P>
	The jury also found that Rentz is to continue to receive 1  
percent of Dynasty's gross sales as long as the company and 
Warfield remain in their joint venture. 
</P>
<P>
	Dynasty's attorney, Jeffrey Cox, told the jury Rentz had no  
contract or understanding with Dynasty or the Mendez brothers to 
receive 1 percent of Dynasty's gross sales. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's a very expensive introduction,'' Cox said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
