<DOCNO> APW19990527.0320 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 04:32:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Racing Needs More Than Luck </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	A brilliant piece of marketing, Tim Smith was told -- having a  
horse bid for the Triple Crown twice in the first 14 months of the 
National Thoroughbred Racing Association's existence. 
</P>
<P>
	The NTRA commissioner laughed.  
</P>
<P>
	``That's dumb luck,'' he said. ``Sometimes it's more important  
to be lucky.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Luck always has been a major player in horse racing on the track  
and at the mutuel windows. Unfortunately, it seems it has had a lot 
to do with the operation of the sport, where cooperation often has 
been an also-ran. 
</P>
<P>
	That's the purpose of the NTRA -- get some cooperation among the  
various tracks and racing interest groups to boost the sport 
through marketing 
</P>
<P>
	``What our mission is, is to improve the economic conditions in  
the industry,'' said Smith of the organization that opened for 
business April 1 with the financial backing of five founding 
members -- the Jockey Club. Breeders Cup Ltd., Keeneland 
Association, Oak Tree Racing Association and National Thoroughbred 
Association. 
</P>
<P>
	``There have been no major complaints,'' Smith said. ``Part of  
what the industry learned in the first year is you can accomplish 
more working together.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Not everybody, however, has been happy about everything the NTRA  
has done or is trying to do. That of course is natural in a 
business as competitive as horse racing. Bettors aren't the only 
ones looking for an edge. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides, it seems that the people who operate race tracks have  
long been more attuned to the swashbuckling ways of boxing than to 
the corporate structure of professional team sports. 
</P>
<P>
	In this age of casino gambling, state lotteries and ferocious  
competition for the leisure-time dollar, people in racing have 
little choice but to cooperate. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're off to a good start,'' Smith said. `A lot more remains  
to be done.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Three of things the NTRA has accomplished are launch a new,  
national brand for thoroughbred racing, start national and co-op 
advertising campaigns and significantly increase racing's profile 
on national television. 
</P>
<P>
	There are always huge crowds at the Kentucky Derby and  
Preakness, and there will be one at Belmont Park on June 5 when 
Charismatic will try to win the Belmont Stakes and Triple Crown. 
Adding spice to the proceedings will the presence of sensational 
filly Silverbulletday. 
</P>
<P>
	Attendance, however, on a daily basis nationally can no longer  
rival what it used to be when betting on horses was sports betting. 
But you no longer have to go to the track to bet. In fact, in an 
increasing number of places you don't even have to leave home to 
bet. This is an area in which the NTRA is concentrating. 
</P>
<P>
	The NTRA realizes that it's important to get new people  
interested enough in racing to visit a track. If he or she gets 
interested enough to bet on a fairly regular basis, it doesn't 
matter if the wager is made on or off track. 
</P>
<P>
	So advertising and racing on television are important.  
</P>
<P>
	``We doubled the number of hours on broadcast television, and  
there's been a healthy increase on cable TV as well,'' Smith said. 
``The more racing on television, the more general fan interest is 
created.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Initiated this year was the ``NTRA Champions on Fox Series,''  
which hasn't pleased everyone in racing. But, Smith said, the 
series format is not chiseled in stone, that changes can be made. 
</P>
<P>
	But it's nonstop televising of racing and racing information  
that is the NTRA's goal. 
</P>
<P>
	``At the cost of $300 million over the next three or four years,  
we're committed to establishing and launching a basic cable network 
over 24 years to 30 million homes,'' Smith said. ``The likelihood 
is that only a fraction of those homes would open up a (wagering) 
account. But only a small percentage would be a big number.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The NTRA definitely can be winner, if those involved in racing  
ride it to the wire. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990527.0321 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 17:21:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmakers Hear Diverse Gun Views </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Two parents whose children were slain by  
classmates gave lawmakers diverse views Thursday on whether the 
slayers, guns or lawmakers themselves are to blame for their 
tragedies. 
</P>
<P>
	Darrell Scott of Littleton, Colo., told the House Judiciary  
Committee's subcommittee that he blames the April 20 death of his 
daughter, Rachel Joy Scott, 17, on Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are people behind those instruments of death,'' Scott  
told the panel. ``I do believe Eric and Dylan bear primary 
responsibility for my daughter's death, not the guns themselves.'' 
.
</P>
<P>
	But Byrl Phillips-Taylor of Richmond, Va., placed the blamed an  
AK47 for her son's 1989 death at the hands of a ``classmate with a 
grudge.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The easy availability of guns got my baby killed,''  
Phillips-Taylor told the panel, urging lawmakers to pass the 
mandatory background checks for gun show transactions and other new 
firearms restrictions voted by the Senate last week. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Senate has demonstrated that it cares about keeping guns  
away from children,'' she said. ``And that may be the turning point 
that every mother like me has been waiting for.'' 
</P>
<P>
	House Republican leaders this week said they support the concept  
of the gun restrictions passed by the Senate, but they rejected 
demands from Democrats to quickly rubber-stamp the measures. 
</P>
<P>
	Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde, who has co-authored gun  
control bills in the past, said careful consideration of the 
legislation next month would ensure that new controls would not 
infringe on the Second Amendment right to bear arms. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans at Thursday's hearing criticized the Clinton  
administration as failing to prosecute violators of existing 
firearms laws while pushing for more gun restrictions. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Bob Barr, R-Ga., suggested that if the Ten Commandments had  
been posted at high schools where the shooting occurred, ``we would 
not have had the tragedies that bring us here today.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Replied Deputy Attorney General Eric Holder Jr.: ``If the young  
people and adult criminals who committed these crimes had a tougher 
time getting their hands on guns, these horrible crimes might have 
been prevented.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Vice President Al Gore, who broke a 50-50 Senate tie last week  
in favor of the new gun show restrictions, returned to the Capitol 
Thursday to accuse House Republicans of trying to please the 
National Rifle Association. 
</P>
<P>
	``At this very moment, there are some of the other side meeting  
behind closed doors plotting to have more delays in order to 
preserve loopholes'' in firearms law, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	NRA Executive Vice President Wayne LaPierre told the House  
subcommittee Thursday that the Senate bill was a ``red tape 
nightmare.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Basically it would extend the reaches of the federal  
government into the homes of this country,'' LaPierre said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the NRA supports mandatory gun show background checks  
and other concepts in the Senate bill, but not as written. For 
example, he said, the Senate would ``your uncle's skeet-shooting 
range'' as a gun show subject to government regulations. 
</P>
<P>
	Scott, testifying at the request of committee Republicans,  
supported LaPierre's complaint that some gun control advocates were 
seeking to put the blame for the shootings at the NRA's doorstep. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't believe that they are responsible for my daughter's  
death,'' said Scott, who said he was not a member of the group and 
does not own a gun. 
</P>
<P>
	Scott also scolded lawmakers about their eagerness to pass more  
laws despite the cultural causes behind school shootings. 
``Political posturing and restrictive legislation are not the 
answers,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
