<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 14:21:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Charity Replaces Chief Amid Rumors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Feed The Children has replaced the  
director of its Nashville distribution center amid an investigation 
into whether he and other employees stole donations to the 
worldwide charity. 
</P>
<P>
	Steve Highfill and about six other administrative employees of  
the relief agency were videotaped by WTVF-TV taking boxes of 
donated goods from the charity's warehouse. Highfill told the 
station he saw nothing wrong with allowing administrative staff to 
take donated items. 
</P>
<P>
	Agents from the Tennessee Bureau of Investigation raided the  
employees' homes Monday. They carried out boxes and bags of 
brand-name clothing -- some with tags still on -- shoes, videos, 
blankets, food and other goods they suspect were donated for poor 
people. One box had ``Merry Christmas to me'' written on the top. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, Larry Jones, president and founder of the relief  
agency, said Highfill was being replaced by Jones' longtime friend 
and colleague Don Richardson while Tennessee authorities and his 
own staff investigate. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones would not say whether Highfill or any other Nashville  
employees had been suspended or fired. 
</P>
<P>
	There was no answer at Highfill's home on Thursday.  
</P>
<P>
	Nashville is home to one of the Oklahoma City-based charity's  
two U.S. distribution centers. Jones said it was unclear how much 
may have been taken from the warehouse. 
</P>
<P>
	The charity receives about $150 million in cash every year and  
$150 million worth of donated goods, but Jones could not say how 
much of that goes through Nashville. 
</P>
<P>
	WTVF reported Thursday that warehouse workers apparently were  
ignored in December and January when they called Feed The 
Children's headquarters to report that Highfill and others were 
taking donations. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope our investigation brings that out because that's new to  
me,'' Jones said. 
</P>
<P>
	The workers told WTVF that they saw recently employees take  
boxes meant for Kosovar refugees and Oklahoma City tornado victims. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones said he would look into the possibility some of the  
donations were taken legitimately -- that workers were bringing 
clothing home to clean it or taking goods to needy people who could 
not get to the warehouse. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
