<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Youngest Pacer Not on Playoff Roster </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- The Indiana Pacers welcomed teen-ager Al  
Harrington with affection, taught him, adopted him as one of the 
family. 
</P>
<P>
	When the regular season ended, though, the first-round draft  
pick out of high school was not even included on their playoff 
roster. 
</P>
<P>
	He knew why.  
</P>
<P>
	``It was an up and down season for me,'' the 6-foot-9 forward  
said Wednesday after practice. ``When I first came in I expected to 
play a lot, but we've got a veteran ball club and their goal is to 
win a championship. 
</P>
<P>
	``So I realized I wasn't going to play as much as I planned on,  
but I learned a lot this year, sitting and watching these guys 
play,'' he said. ``They're true champions, even though they don't 
have the ring yet. They know what it takes to win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Pacers open the best-of-7 Eastern Conference championships  
against the New York Knicks on Sunday. It's the fourth time in six 
years Indiana has reached the conference finals. 
</P>
<P>
	Harrington played in 21 games during the regular season,  
averaging 2.1 points and 1.9 rebounds. He was a fan favorite from 
his very first appearance in a preseason scrimmage, when he took 
the public address microphone and sang the ``Barney'' theme song as 
part of a rookie initiation. 
</P>
<P>
	He played fewer than eight minutes a game, showing veteran moves  
at times but rookie mistakes at others. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a difficult year for him,'' coach Larry Bird said. ``It  
was a shortened season (because of the lockout) and he came in and 
didn't know what to expect. 
</P>
<P>
	``We played every other night and really didn't get a lot of  
practice time, so Al's got a long way to go, there's no question 
about that,'' Bird said. ``But if he works hard in the summer and 
comes back with a fresh mind and really remembers what we try to 
teach him, hopefully he can get off to a better start and then 
maybe get in there and play a little more.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Before the first-round series with Milwaukee, the Pacers  
activated veteran Fred Hoiberg from the injured list in place of 
Harrington. Mark Pope and Mate Skelin, on the injured list most of 
the season, also are continuing to practice during the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was difficult in the beginning, but I'm over that now,''  
Harrington said. ``It was a business decision, and I have to deal 
with it and do whatever I can to make sure it never happens 
again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Harrington, 19, was the 25th pick in the draft, out of St.  
Patrick's High School in Elizabeth, N.J. He came to Indianapolis 
last summer and lived with veteran forward Antonio Davis. 
</P>
<P>
	``I learned a lot from Antonio, a lot of life things,''  
Harrington said. ``I learned a lot from guys like Sam Perkins. I 
hang out with him a lot. All these guys have been very beneficial 
to me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So while his veteran teammates prepare for the Knicks,  
Harrington still is practicing, working on his game, getting a jump 
start on next year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm going to work regardless. It's only my first season,'' he  
said. ``If I stay healthy, I could play 20 years. This is only one 
year.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
