<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gucci Wins Court Battle With LVMH </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) -- A Dutch court ruled Thursday in  
favor of Italian fashion house Gucci and against the French company 
LVMH Moet Hennessy Louis Vuitton which is waging a hostile takeover 
battle for Gucci. 
</P>
<P>
	The Amsterdam District Court rejected a demand by LVMH that  
Gucci's strategic alliance with French retailer 
Pinault-Printemps-Redoute be annulled. 
</P>
<P>
	It also rejected LVMH's call for an investigation into Gucci's  
management. 
</P>
<P>
	Gucci Chairman Domenico de Sole said he was ``very pleased''  
with the decision. ``We will now move forward to implement our 
alliance with PPR,'' De Sole said. 
</P>
<P>
	The court did rule in LVMH's favor, however, by ordering Gucci  
abandon its employee stock option plan set up earlier this year. 
</P>
<P>
	LVMH made an offer for Gucci in March but asked the court in a  
lawsuit filed in April to overturn measures taken by Gucci to avoid 
the bid, including issuing new shares to PPR. 
</P>
<P>
	The court, in a written statement earlier this month, banned the  
Italian group from investing $2.9 billion in proceeds from the sale 
of the 40 percent stake to PPR. 
</P>
<P>
	PPR's purchase of the 40 percent stake effectively diluted the  
34 percent stake LVMH already had in Gucci to around 20 percent and 
reduced its voting rights. 
</P>
<P>
	Gucci has said the sale was needed to fend off LVMH's ``creeping  
takeover.'' It will hold its annual shareholders' meeting after the 
court's ruling. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
