<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 4 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	War Crimes Panel Indicts Milosevic  
</P>
<P>
	THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) -- In a historic announcement, an  
international tribunal today indicted Slobodan Milosevic and four 
powerful aides, calling the Yugoslav president personally 
responsible for planning and carrying out a gruesome campaign of 
war crimes in Kosovo. It was the first time an international court 
has charged a sitting head of state with such crimes and 
atrocities. In Belgrade, a government minister was immediately 
defiant, saying Yugoslav authorities would not recognize the 
jurisdiction of the U.N. war crimes tribunal. 

</P>
<P>
	Albright: No Immunity for Milosevic  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said  
today there is no possibility of an immunity deal for Yugoslav 
President Slobodan Milosevic to achieve peace in Kosovo. Albright 
said that the indicted Milosevic must be taken to the Hague for 
trial on war-crimes charges. ``He has to be turned over,'' she 
said. Albright said the indictment would have no impact on NATO's 
air campaign, humanitarian efforts or diplomatic moves to solve the 
Kosovo crisis. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Drops 253.90  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks resumed a downward lurch today as  
continued concerns about interest rates and inflation put the 
brakes on yesterday's rally. Just before the closing at 4 p.m. EDT, 
the Dow industrials were down 253.90 points at 10,448.26. Declining 
issues on the New York Stock Exchange led advancers 1,953-974. The 
Nasdaq was up 0.70 at 2,427.87. 

</P>
<P>
	India, Pakistan Tensions Escalate  
</P>
<P>
	DRAS, India (AP) -- Pakistan said it downed two Indian fighter  
jets in the disputed Himalayan region of Kashmir today, increasing 
tensions between the nuclear powers. India confirmed the loss of 
two aircraft but said only one was shot down. Earlier, Indian 
helicopter gunships fired rockets at Kashmir's mountains for a 
second day -- the first time the two rivals have used air power in 
Kashmir since India's 1971 war with Pakistan. India says it is 
trying to push out hundreds of Pakistan-backed guerrillas who have 
infiltrated Indian-held Kashmir near the unofficial border. 

</P>
<P>
	Reno Criticizes Aides on China Wiretap  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Attorney General Janet Reno today criticized  
aides for not asking her whether to wiretap a nuclear weapons 
scientist suspected of spying for China. The Senate, meanwhile, 
voted to expand congressional oversight over technology exports. 
The Senate approved a bipartisan package of measures designed to 
tighten controls on technology exports, require the administration 
to keep Congress better informed of Chinese satellite launches and 
to beef up security at U.S. weapons labs. But efforts to act on a 
more extensive series of measures in the House was put off until 
next month. 

</P>
<P>
	Netanyahu Departs Parliament  
</P>
<P>
	TEL AVIV, Israel (AP) -- Outgoing Prime Minister Benjamin  
Netanyahu, trounced in elections earlier this month, quit politics 
today but left the door open for a possible return in the future. 
``I will resign from the Knesset but in no way will I resign from 
the struggle for the future of Israel,'' he told Likud members 
today. Aides have said Netanyahu will write a book and hit the U.S. 
lecture circuit. 

</P>
<P>
	Survivor of Train Accident Dies  
</P>
<P>
	BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) -- The 10-year-old Ecuadorean boy who was  
struck and gravely injured by a train that killed his mother and 
three brothers died today. Jose Francisco Urgiles Toledo died at 
Bridgeport Hospital two days after the accident. The boy, his 
brothers and their mother were struck by an Amtrak train as they 
walked across a trestle in the middle of the night. He lost most of 
his left leg and suffered severe brain injuries and multiple broken 
bones. 

</P>
<P>
	Highway Fatalities Fell in 1998  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Highway fatalities fell again in 1998, with  
alcohol-related traffic deaths hitting a record low last year, 
according to preliminary figures released by the government today. 
Overall, 41,480 people were killed on the nation's highways in 
1998, down from 42,103 in 1997. Alcohol was involved in 15,936 
traffic fatalities, or 38.4 percent of total highway deaths, as 
opposed to 16,189 fatalities, or 38.6 percent, the year before. It 
is the lowest level since the government began keeping records in 
1975. 

</P>
<P>
	Sampras Bounced From French Open  
</P>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- Pete Sampras lost in the second round in the French  
Open today to 100th-ranked Andrei Medvedev, 7-5, 1-6, 6-4, 6-3. 
Earlier, Jennifer Capriati advanced to the third round over fellow 
American Lilia Osterloh. Also advancing were Lindsay Davenport, who 
survived a three-set scare from 16-year-old Justine Henin of 
Belgium, and Monica Seles, who won in straight sets. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by GABRIEL MADWAY  
</P>
</TEXT>
