<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lakers May Want Rambis As Coach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The Los Angeles Lakers are leaning strongly  
toward hiring Kurt Rambis as permanent coach, according to a 
published report. 
</P>
<P>
	The Los Angeles Times reported Thursday that several  
unidentified sources close to the situation said key Laker 
executives favor the selection of Rambis, who took over on an 
interim basis from Del Harris in February. 
</P>
<P>
	No contract negotiations have begun and team executive vice  
president Jerry West and general manager Mitch Kupchak have yet to 
formally present Rambis as their choice to owner Jerry Buss, the 
sources said. 
</P>
<P>
	Lakers spokesman John Black said the team had no comment on the  
Times report. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are not ready to discuss that publicly yet,'' Black said.  
</P>
<P>
	Rambis led the Lakers past Houston in the first round of the NBA  
playoffs before losing four straight to San Antonio. 
</P>
<P>
	``The feeling is this team has to grow together, and you don't  
do that by firing the coach after such a traumatic season,'' one 
Times source said. 
</P>
<P>
	West and Kupchak surveyed key Laker players about Rambis and  
several -- led by a rousing endorsement by Kobe Bryant -- said they 
would fully support his return, the Times sources said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990527.0335 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 05:51:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Conservatives Angry Over Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Now it's Speaker Dennis Hastert's turn to deal  
with House conservatives unhappy with the way this year's budget 
fight is shaping up. 
</P>
<P>
	For years, it was House Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., who bore  
the brunt of conservative anger over end-of-year concessions to 
President Clinton on spending. Unhappiness over last fall's deal 
with Clinton that added $21 billion in spending was one factor in 
Gingrich's toppling from the speakership last year. 
</P>
<P>
	With Gingrich gone, his less confrontational successor, Hastert,  
is dealing anew with unhappy conservatives who say leaders are on 
course to again let Clinton win billions in additional domestic 
spending. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are set up for the same kind of train wreck we had last  
year with the present'' leadership strategy, said Rep. Mark 
Sanford, R-S.C., one of the conservatives. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday and Wednesday, conservatives all but halted House  
work on the first spending bill of the year, a $61 billion measure 
financing farm and food programs. The group has forced votes on a 
pile of amendments, such as cutting $300,000 for peanut research 
and $5 million for wood research. 
</P>
<P>
	The group was losing almost every vote, but their point was  
clear: Current GOP strategy is flawed and ensures Clinton will win 
billions in extra spending this fall. And since that money is 
likely to come from Social Security surpluses, that means 
Republicans will have broken their pledge not to touch that 
program's money. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is not about the agriculture bill,'' said one of them,  
Rep. Tom Coburn, R-Okla. ``It's about keeping our word to not spend 
Social Security money, and having a plan to not spend it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The conservatives' slowdown tactics forced Hastert, R-Ill., to  
abandon plans for the House to complete the first two of the 13 
annual spending bills for fiscal 2000 this week. Instead, the bills 
won't be considered until lawmakers return from their weeklong 
Memorial Day break next month. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite conservative demands, most lawmakers believe that  
billions of extra dollars will go to schools, the environment and 
other social programs for the fiscal year starting Oct. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	At least some of that money is likely to come from breaking  
spending limits imposed by the GOP-written budget Congress approved 
last month. The source of that money: Social Security surpluses. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, White House budget chief Jacob Lew signaled the  
Clinton administration was content -- for now -- to let Republicans 
continue to struggle. 
</P>
<P>
	In a speech at the Brookings Institution, Lew criticized  
Republicans for planning spending bills so low that they are 
``gambling with our future.'' But he also said finding extra money 
by breaking the spending caps would be an ``abandonment of fiscal 
discipline.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That statement, in effect, makes it harder for the spending  
question to be resolved soon because the GOP is unlikely to suggest 
breaking the budget limits before the administration does. 
</P>
<P>
	Lew suggested a way out that has little chance of passage:  
Overhaul Social Security and Medicare, then pay for added domestic 
spending by increasing cigarette taxes and fees for food safety 
inspections, as well as following other money-raising suggestions 
Clinton made in his budget in February. 
</P>
<P>
	The conservatives' success in derailing that schedule  
spotlighted how hard it is for Hastert to control the House with 
the GOP's narrow margin, in which defections by just five 
Republicans can sink a bill. 
</P>
<P>
	Rather than threatening the mavericks, participants in a  
closed-door GOP meeting Wednesday said Hastert called on 
Republicans to work together and said a budget strategy would be 
ready soon. 
</P>
<P>
	Under current GOP plans, $536 billion has been distributed among  
the 13 spending bills in a way that all but ensures that about five 
of the bigger, more controversial bills will not pass the House, 
let alone become law. These cover education, veterans, national 
parks and other domestic programs. 
</P>
<P>
	Conservatives want the $536 billion rearranged so all 13 bills  
can pass the House, giving the House a better bargaining position 
with Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	The conservatives' tactics have also frayed tempers.  
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Sonny Callahan, R-Ala., said in an interview that  
conservatives were using ``demagoguery'' in introducing a parade of 
amendments. 
</P>
<P>
	``They all believe the entire world is watching C-SPAN,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	On the House floor, Coburn answered complaints from farm-state  
lawmakers about the conservatives' ``nitpick'' amendments by 
calling them ``a little bit arrogant'' for objecting to debating 
the bill's content. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
