<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mortgage Rates Rise Slightly / National Mortgage Survey  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The average interest rate on 30-year  
fixed-rate mortgages remains at the highest level in more than two 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	The average stayed at 7.23 percent for a second straight week,  
the highest level since November of 1997, according to a weekly 
survey by Freddie Mac, the mortgage company. 
</P>
<P>
	So far this year, rates have fluctuated between 6.74 percent at  
the end of January and the current 7.23 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Fifteen-year mortgages, a popular option for refinancing,  
averaged 6.84 percent this week, up only slightly from 6.83 percent 
a week earlier, Freddie Mac reported Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	On one-year adjustable-rate mortgages, lenders were asking an  
average initial rate of 5.73 percent, down from 5.76 percent the 
previous week. 
</P>
<P>
	The rates do not include add-on fees known as points, which  
averaged at or just over 1 percent of the loan amount for all three 
types of mortgages. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
