<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 05:51:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gun Groups Say Laws Aren't Enforced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- As Congress struggles with new gun control  
proposals, the question of whether the federal government does 
enough to enforce the laws already in place has become a key 
dispute. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Rifle Association and some Republicans say that if  
America really wants to crack down on gun crimes, the answer lies 
in enforcing the more than 20,000 existing local and federal gun 
regulations. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you're going to pass a federal law, it sends a wrong  
message not to prosecute it,'' said James Baker, the NRA's chief 
lobbyist. ``And if you're not prosecuting, why do you need more 
laws?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Since President Clinton took office, federal prosecutions of  
gun-related crimes have dropped more than 40 percent, the NRA said. 
The nation has a zero-tolerance policy against young people 
bringing guns to school, for example, yet the federal government 
over the past two years prosecuted just eight children for that, 
Baker notes. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Clinton administration says gun groups are using the  
wrong statistics, looking only at the drop in prosecutions since 
1992, when violent crime overall -- and thus prosecutions -- began to 
drop after historic highs. 
</P>
<P>
	Gun groups also ignore the recent federal cooperation with local  
police to prevent illegal sales and go after people who commit 
crimes with guns and the dealers who illegally supply them. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is disingenuous for them to criticize when they are looking  
at the wrong numbers,'' Justice Department spokesman Brian Steel 
said, adding that federal, state and local prosecutions together 
have climbed. 
</P>
<P>
	Moreover, federal laws are often aimed at preventing gun  
violence -- by keeping felons from buying guns, for example -- more 
than at producing prosecutions. The Brady Law's instant background 
checks have prevented 250,000 felons from buying guns, Steel says. 
And some crimes, such as those by teen-agers and children, are 
simply better handled by local authorities, Attorney General Janet 
Reno said last week. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet even gun-control advocates agree more could be done. The  
Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms should more aggressively 
put out of business any licensed gun dealer who breaks federal 
rules, says Douglas Weil, research director for the Center to 
Prevent Handgun Violence. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials do plan to review ``just what needs to be done with  
state and local authorities to ensure the appropriate prosecution 
of these cases,'' Reno said last week. Republicans are expected to 
grill her deputy on the issue at a hearing Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	A program in Richmond, Va., praised by the NRA in newspaper ads  
and before Congress, has dominated much of the enforcement debate. 
After local and federal officials began Project Exile, which 
mandates a five-year jail term for any felon caught with a firearm, 
gun murders dropped by 41 percent in one year. 
</P>
<P>
	Rochester, N.Y., also has signed on to the program, but the NRA  
complains the Clinton administration isn't providing money to 
duplicate the effort nationwide. Nevertheless, Clinton praised the 
program in a March radio address as Richmond's police chief looked 
on. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want to give cities the flexibility to do whatever works in  
their community,'' Steel said. ``Richmond had a particular problem 
with convicted felons getting guns. Boston had a problem with 
gangs. They used different strategies, and they both had success.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Indeed, the Boston program, begun in 1995, traces where young  
criminals got their guns and has become a precursor of the ATF 
effort to trace guns used in juvenile crime -- a program Clinton is 
expanding. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate passed a bill last week that includes a measure to  
revoke gun ownership rights for anyone convicted of a firearms 
crime as a juvenile, new background checks at gun shows and a 
requirement that safety devices be sold with all new handguns. The 
House is expected to take up similar proposals in mid-June. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet even as lawmakers consider new restrictions, they insist the  
focus should be on enforcement, perhaps by giving more money to 
police and to federal prosecutors or to gun-safety education 
programs. 
</P>
<P>
	``To really maximize our impact ... we've got to prosecute the  
laws we've got,'' said Sen. Jeff Sessions, R-Ala. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
