<P>
	GDP Growing at 4.1 Percent Rate  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The biggest consumer spending spree in 11  
years kept the economy growing at a robust rate in the year's first 
quarter. The economy grew at an annual rate of 4.1 percent, even 
though the country's trade deficit was a bigger drag on growth than 
previously thought, the Commerce Department said. The government's 
new figure for gross domestic product represented a slight downward 
revision from a 4.5 percent figure released a month ago, but it 
still showed a remarkably strong economy. The GDP report also 
showed that corporate profits, which had been in the doldrums, had 
a sizable rebound for the first quarter. 

</P>
<P>
	Help-Wanted Ads Declined in April  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Help-wanted advertising in the nation's major  
newspapers declined slightly in April, but demand for jobs still 
remains strong, according to a new study. The Conference Board, a 
private business research group, said its monthly advertising index 
dipped to 87 last month from 88 in March. The index, based on 100, 
was 90 in April 1998. The regions with the largest declines in 
help-wanted ads in the last three months were the East North 
Central, which includes Ohio, Illinois, Indiana, Wisconsin and 
Michigan, and New England, which includes Massachusetts, 
Connecticut and Rhode Island. 

</P>
<P>
	Board of Trade Sets Eurex Vote  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- The Chicago Board of Trade set June 24 as the  
date its membership will vote on a broad alliance with the 
Frankfurt-based Eurex electronic exchange. The Chicago exchange has 
not revealed details of the pairing, but reports have indicated it 
involves giving up its electronic trading platform in favor of 
Eurex's and cross-trading each other's contracts over the Internet. 
CBOT also announced other measures today in an attempt to fend off 
competition that has challenged its dominance, including slashing 
fees for large customers who want to trade electronically and 
lobbying federal regulators to relax restrictions. 

</P>
<P>
	Europe Gold Prices Go Tumbling  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Investors afraid that Switzerland and the  
International Monetary Fund might sell some of their gold reserves 
are unloading their own holdings of the metal, sending prices to 
20-year lows. Gold sank to $268.20 a troy ounce in early trading in 
London today, down 90 cents from yesterday's closing price and the 
latest in a series of 20-year lows, before recovering somewhat to 
finish the day at $268.80. On the New York Mercantile Exchange, 
where prices of futures contracts reached a 20-year low yesterday, 
gold for June delivery rose $1 today to close at $270.50 an ounce. 
The last time gold traded at these levels it was on the rise, 
headed for a peak of $875 an ounce in January 1980. 

</P>
<P>
	Small Businesses Push Tax Cut Plan  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Small-business advocates and their Capitol  
Hill allies lined up today behind Republican legislation that would 
cut taxes $30 billion over five years and include larger deductions 
for health insurance and business meals. The most costly item, at 
$15 billion over five years, would lower from 39.4 percent to 34 
percent the top individual income tax rate for partnerships, 
including closely held ones known as S corporations, and certain 
other small businesses. Rep. Jim Talent, R-Mo., chairman of the 
House Small Business Committee, said supporters will seek to 
include the package in the larger 10-year, $778 billion tax cut 
Republicans intend to put together this summer. 

</P>
<P>
	IBM Exec Claims Microsoft Pressure  
</P>
<P>
	RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) -- An IBM manager told lawyers today that  
Microsoft had offered an alliance with IBM in the early 1990s if it 
agreed to sacrifice its rival operating-system software, OS/2. 
Garry Norris, who will be one of the government's final witnesses 
in its antitrust case, said that IBM rejected the overture and said 
it planned to sell both Windows and OS/2. Norris also testified 
that major computer makers, such as Compaq, agreed not to sell OS/2 
on their machines because of threats from Microsoft. IBM's system 
ultimately proved a commercial failure. IBM stock closed down 2 1/8 at 
116 and Microsoft fell 1/8 to 78 3/8. 

</P>
<P>
	Fed Proposes Special Loans to Banks  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Federal Reserve is proposing a plan for  
special lending to banks, thrifts and credit unions that might need 
emergency money because of the Year 2000 date change. The central 
bank is seeking public comment on the proposal, which would offer 
these special loans to financial institutions from Nov. 1 through 
next April 7. The plan would allow banks, thrifts and credit unions 
``to confidently commit to supplying loans to other financial 
institutions and businesses through the rollover to the new 
century,'' the Fed said. Last year, the Fed ordered an additional 
$50 billion of new currency to put into circulation in the event 
people make a run on banks and automated teller machines late in 
the year. 

</P>
<P>
	Coca-Cola Creates Diversity Council  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Coca-Cola, facing a racial discrimination  
lawsuit, has established a council to work on diversifying its 
staff. M. Douglas Ivester, chairman and chief executive officer, 
sent an e-mail to employees yesterday saying the Diversity Advisory 
Council will help ``assure that we are able to achieve our 
different, better and special standard and to maximize the benefits 
of diversity in our work force.'' Heading the new council will be 
Carl Ware, a company senior vice president who heads Coke's Africa 
Group, and Jack Stahl, senior vice president and head of the North 
America Group. Ware is Coke's senior black executive. 

</P>
