libraries pay for Internet hookups won approval today for the 
maximum $2.25 billion allowed. The Federal Communications 
Commission approved the funding level, which represents an increase 
of nearly $1 billion from current levels. The money is collected 
from phone companies, which often pass on the fees to customers. 
The commission's chairman, Bill Kennard, said the funding would 
help wire 528,000 poorer or rural classrooms to the Internet, 
benefiting some 40 million kids. Critics fear the full funding will 
lead to higher phone bills. 

