<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fed Proposes Special Loans to Banks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Federal Reserve is proposing a plan for  
special lending to banks, thrifts and credit unions that might need 
emergency money because of consumers' fears about the Year 2000 
date change. 
</P>
<P>
	The central bank is seeking public comment on the proposal,  
which would offer these special loans to financial institutions 
from Nov. 1 through next April 7. 
</P>
<P>
	The plan would allow banks, thrifts and credit unions ``to  
confidently commit to supplying loans to other financial 
institutions and businesses through the rollover to the new 
century,'' the Fed said recently in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the second major step taken by the central bank designed  
to avert possible Year 2000 disruptions in the nation's banking 
system. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year the Fed ordered an additional $50 billion of new  
currency to put into circulation in the event people make a run on 
banks and automated teller machines late in the year. By year's 
end, $200 billion in currency will be stored in government vaults, 
up from the $150 billion normally held in reserve. That's in 
addition to the $460 billion in notes circulating in the United 
States and abroad. 
</P>
<P>
	For the special Year 2000 loans, the interest rate charged by  
the Fed would be slightly higher than the prevailing ``federal 
funds rate,'' currently around 4.75 percent, which banks charge 
each other for overnight loans. 
</P>
<P>
	``We think it's helpful,'' said Jim McLaughlin, director of  
regulatory affairs at the American Bankers Association. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the special loans would provide an extra cushion of cash  
to the system as a backup if needed, although the trade group 
anticipates that very few banks will have to use it. 
</P>
<P>
	The central bank acknowledged that ``uncertainty surrounds  
potential developments over the period'' because of the millennial 
date change. But it stressed that it does not expect widespread or 
prolonged computer disruptions from the technology problem, caused 
by the possibility that some computers originally programmed to 
recognize only the last two digits of a year could interpret 2000 
as 1900. 
</P>
<P>
	Government regulators have lauded the nation's banking industry  
for its work preparing for the date change. 
</P>
<P>
	Bankers have promised consumers that ATM machines, credit cards,  
checks and banking services will function normally through the date 
change. 
</P>
<P>
	However, banks, thrifts and credit unions, all of which are  
closely regulated, are linked with numerous companies that provide 
services to banks and operate with less government supervision. 
</P>
<P>
	Last Friday, the Fed and four other bank regulatory agencies,  
worried about the Year 2000 readiness of a big ATM service company 
in the West, ordered it to get in shape by June 30 or face possible 
contract cancellations by its 750 bank customers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
