<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Tightens Up on Tech Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate easily approved measures today to  
expand oversight of technology exports and to tighten security at 
weapons laboratories in the aftermath of a House report alleging 
Chinese espionage. 
</P>
<P>
	But efforts toward broader measures fell victim to partisan  
wrangling in both congressional chambers and were postponed until 
after a 10-day congressional recess for Memorial Day. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Democrats used delaying tactics to stall a GOP-sponsored  
measure that would reorganize the Energy Department after the 
proposal drew a veto threat from the Clinton administration. The 
proposal would create a new assistant secretary for defense 
programs who would report directly to the president and Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., put off action on that  
measure Thursday until a later date as the Senate worked toward 
completion of a $288.8 billion Defense Department spending bill. 
</P>
<P>
	Once the controversial amendment was jettisoned, the Senate  
passed the defense bill 92 to 3. It would spend $8.3 billion more 
than President Clinton requested in the fiscal year that begins Oct 
1, including authorizing a 4.8 percent across-the-board military 
pay raise next Jan. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier, by voice vote, the Senate adopted a set of proposals by  
Lott that was also endorsed by Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, 
D-S.D. 
</P>
<P>
	The package would expand the role of intelligence agencies in  
reviewing export licenses, boost Pentagon monitoring of satellite 
launches in China and require the administration to report to 
Congress on any security breaches. 
</P>
<P>
	It would also put the FBI solely in charge of all background  
investigations of workers at Energy Department weapons 
laboratories. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, efforts by the House to take up its own package,  
including many recommendations from the espionage report, drew 
political fire from both sides, prompting House Speaker Dennis 
Hastert to abruptly postpone action until next month. 
</P>
<P>
	The senior Democrat on the House espionage panel, Rep. Norman  
Dicks of Washington, accused Republican leaders of blocking 
consideration of some of the panel's recommendations that are 
supported by the administration. 
</P>
<P>
	One was a measure to register support for steps already taken or  
being planned by Energy Secretary Bill Richardson to increase 
security at nuclear weapons labs. The Energy Department's nuclear 
weapons lab in Los Alamos, N.M., was a target of alleged Chinese 
espionage. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's an insult,'' Dicks said. ``I am very disappointed that  
the Republican leadership has chosen to take a partisan approach to 
implementing our report. We spent nine months working on this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans denied they were trying to stifle debate.  
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Christopher Cox, R-Calif., chairman of the espionage  
investigation, told reporters Dicks should have been allowed to 
present his amendment and suggested there had been a 
misunderstanding. 
</P>
<P>
	The ``silver lining,'' Cox said, is that the House now will have  
more time to work out a more comprehensive package. 
</P>
<P>
	Democratic opposition to going ahead with the House debate was  
compounded by the objections of Republican conservatives, who 
criticized a leadership decision to strip from the overall defense 
bill a provision by the House Armed Services Committee to block 
funds for the military operation in Yugoslavia after Oct. 1 
</P>
<P>
	Republican leaders said they had done so to ease administration  
concerns that such language would undermine U.S. troops in the 
Balkans -- and blamed Democratic leaders for causing the impasse. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a breakdown on the president's side of the agreement,''  
said Hastert. 
</P>
<P>
	The impasse on the Senate side was over an amendment by Sens.  
Pete Domenici, R-N.M., and Frank Murkowski, R-Alaska, to create a 
new assistant secretary for defense programs in the Energy 
Department. 
</P>
<P>
	He or she would have wide-ranging authority and could bypass the  
energy secretary in dealing directly with the president and 
Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	Richardson, the energy secretary, opposed the proposal as too  
extensive and, in a letter to Senate leaders, complained ``this 
proposal would effectively cancel my six-month effort to strengthen 
security.'' He said he would threaten a veto if it were adopted. 
</P>
<P>
	Murkowski said, ``This is an effort to establish  
accountability.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The three who voted ``no'' on final Senate passage of the  
defense bill were Russ Feingold, D-Wis.; Herbert Kohl, D-Wis., and 
Paul Wellstone, D-Minn. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	The bills are H.R. 1401 and S 1059.  
</P>
</TEXT>
