<HEADLINE> Maxwell Auditors Settle Lawsuit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Coopers &AMP; Lybrand today agreed to pay more than  
$108 million over its role in the affairs of the late media baron 
Robert Maxwell. 
</P>
<P>
	Coopers &AMP; Lybrand, which merged with Price Waterhouse in 1998 to  
form PricewaterhouseCoopers, was the auditor for Maxwell 
Communication Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Maxwell disappeared in mysterious circumstances at sea off his  
yacht in 1991. Earlier that year, his empire had collapsed. 
</P>
<P>
	The company administrators sued Coopers &AMP; Lybrand for $160  
million for failing to spot any problems at the Maxwell 
corporation. 
</P>
<P>
	The accounting firm will pay the settlement in three stages with  
$8 million payable immediately, $56 million due in July and a final 
$44.2 million payable in July 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	The money raised in the settlement will be used to pay  
outstanding creditors of Maxwell Communication, including banks and 
other businesses that are owed a total of nearly $3 billion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
