<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 15:51:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IRL Reducing Speeds for Texas Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- The Indy Racing League, reeling from a crash  
that killed three fans, hopes slower speeds will make the stands 
safer. 
</P>
<P>
	The IRL announced Thursday it has imposed new engine rules for  
the June 12 race at Texas Motor Speedway, a high-banked oval where 
speeds of more than 228 mph were run a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Executive director Leo Mehl said engines must operate at no more  
than 10,000 rpms after Sunday's Indy 500. The new specifications, 
which reduce the cars' horsepower, will be used for the remaining 
seven IRL events, beginning with the Longhorn 500. 
</P>
<P>
	``This will definitely slow the cars down,'' Mehl said. ``There  
are obvious reasons for doing that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was the second major IRL change this week. On Monday,  
officials unveiled a new system that uses cables in cars in an 
attempt to prevent wheels and suspension parts from reaching the 
stands during wrecks. 
</P>
<P>
	Three fans died and eight were injured when debris flew into the  
stands during a crash at the May 1 Visionaire 500 at Lowe's Motor 
Speedway in Concord, N.C. 
</P>
<P>
	The IRL already reduced rpms from 10,500 to 10,300 at the  
beginning of this season. Mehl said the latest change should cut 
the top speeds at Texas to about 220 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	A year ago, the best speed for the June race at Texas was more  
than 228 mph. It dropped to about 224 mph for a second IRL event in 
September at the 1.5-mile track in Fort Worth. 
</P>
<P>
	The Texas and Lowe's tracks are almost identical high-banked  
ovals. Indianapolis Motor Speedway is much flatter, so the risk of 
debris flying into the stands is not as great. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lowe's and Texas tracks are both owned by Bruton Smith's  
Speedway Motorsports Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need to show Bruton and everyone else that we are  
responding to the tragedy at Charlotte,'' Mehl said. ``This is one 
of the ways we can do that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At least one driver doesn't like the change. Greg Ray, who will  
start from the middle of the front row at the Indy 500, said it 
would be difficult for teams to make such a significant adjustment 
with only two weeks between races. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's too quick, just too quick to make changes like that,''  
Ray said. ``They should have announced it earlier, like six or 
eight weeks ago.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mehl disputed Ray's view of the situation, noting that each car  
is equipped with a ``rev limiter'' to control rpms. The changes 
were supported by several drivers -- including defending champion 
Eddie Cheever. 
</P>
<P>
	``Anything we can do to improve safety is not a mistake,'' Mehl  
said. ``The drivers like to go fast. Some drivers want to race 
side-by-side going 240 mph.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cheever compared the IRL change with restrictor plates, a  
carburetor device imposed by NASCAR to reduce speeds for its stock 
cars on superspeedways at Daytona Beach, Fla., and Talladega, Ala. 
</P>
<P>
	``Believe me, 5 mph slower is not going to make it a worse race  
than we have now,'' Cheever said. ``The changes they've made are 
very intelligent. Is it the final solution? No. It's a continuing 
process.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sam Schmidt, the seventh-fastest qualifier at Indy, said the  
teams always find ways to adapt to new rules. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's remarkable that they lowered it to 10,300 and we're going  
3 mph faster than we were here last year, as far as the pole 
speed,'' he said. ``I don't think it's going to make it any worse 
of a race. It may slow it down, but it may make it just more 
exciting for the fans.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
