<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Poll: Clinton Help May Hurt Gore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore might want to keep his  
distance from President Clinton on the campaign trail, a new poll 
suggests. 
</P>
<P>
	A CNN/USA Today/Gallup poll released Thursday indicates the  
public, by a 52-to-29 percent margin, says Clinton's active help in 
Gore's campaign would make them less likely to vote for Gore for 
president. 
</P>
<P>
	The poll indicates Americans respect the vice president as a  
person, but have not yet warmed to him as a candidate. 
</P>
<P>
	Four out of five see him as a good husband and father, and a  
majority say he has the experience to be president, is honest and 
trustworthy and cares about the needs of people like them. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore has a 2-to-1 lead in the poll among Democrats and those  
leaning Democratic against his sole challenger for the party's 
nomination, former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley. 
</P>
<P>
	But four out of 10 of all respondents say there is no chance  
they would vote for Gore. 
</P>
<P>
	Almost two-thirds of all respondents say Gore doesn't inspire  
them and 54 percent say he lacks vision on how to solve the big 
problems facing the country. Fifty-seven percent say his stands on 
issues are too close to Clinton's. 
</P>
<P>
	Mark Penn, a pollster and Gore adviser, noted Gore has taken a  
commanding lead among Democrats and has closed the gap in a 
head-to-head matchup against the GOP front-runner, Texas Gov. 
George W. Bush, from 21 points behind a month ago, to 14 points 
behind now. 
</P>
<P>
	``(Gore) is seen as honest, trustworthy and caring about people  
... Those are exactly the qualities that people say are the most 
important to them and what they're looking for in the next 
president,'' Penn said. 
</P>
<P>
	``They give high job approval to President Clinton, but they  
want to see what the vice president would do if he were elected 
president.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush leads Elizabeth Dole, former Red Cross president, by almost  
a 3-1 margin among those inclined to vote Republican, with other 
GOP candidates in single digits. 
</P>
<P>
	The phone survey of 1,050 adults was taken Sunday and Monday and  
has an error margin of plus or minus 3 percentage points. The 
margin of error for subgroups like Democrats and Republicans is 
plus or minus 5 percentage points. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
