<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Avis Settles Wheelchair Complaint </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Avis, the nation's second largest rental car  
company, agreed Thursday to provide wheelchair-accessible shuttle 
buses at all its airport locations, the Justice Department 
announced. 
</P>
<P>
	The out-of-court agreement with the department resolves a 1996  
complaint by a wheelchair-using traveler who argued that Avis Rent 
A Car, Inc., violated the Americans with Disabilities Act by not 
providing an accessible bus between Detroit Metro Airport and Avis' 
off-site rental facility. 
</P>
<P>
	Avis agreed to ensure that each of its 36 airport shuttle  
systems has at least one wheelchair-accessible vehicle by Dec. 31, 
2000. 
</P>
<P>
	During negotiations, Avis agreed to expand the settlement beyond  
Detroit Metro to all its airport shuttles, the department said. 
</P>
<P>
	When the department's investigation began in 1997, only six of  
Avis' 286 shuttle vehicles were equipped with lifts for 
wheelchairs, the department said. Currently, 126 accessible 
vehicles are in use at Avis's airport locations nationwide. The 
agreement will bring that number to at least 153 accessible 
vehicles. 
</P>
<P>
	``As the summer travel season begins this Memorial Day weekend,  
airline travelers who use wheelchairs will be able to go from the 
airport terminal to their rental cars as easily as other 
customers,'' said acting Assistant Attorney General Bill Lann Lee, 
head of the civil rights division. ``This is a model agreement and 
Avis should be commended for its cooperation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The ADA requires that companies operating shuttles over a fixed  
route ensure that newly acquired vehicles large enough for more 
than 16 people are accessible to the disabled, including those with 
wheelchairs. And Avis agreed to replace or refurbish every large 
shuttle vehicle it has acquired since Aug. 25, 1990. 
</P>
<P>
	Avis has already added wheelchair lifts to two vehicles at the  
Detroit Airport that the department determined should have them. 
The company also has removed architectural barriers in Detroit. And 
Avis agreed to continue to provide curbside service for the 
disabled at all airport locations although it is not required 
everywhere, said John Wodatch, chief of the department's disability 
rights section. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
