<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FDA Drug Warning Rule Taking Effect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Consider the scenario: Your doctor prescribes  
Propulsid to ease severe nighttime heartburn, but forgets to ask if 
you're taking other medicines. And you forget to mention that 
another doctor recently prescribed the antibiotic erythromycin. 
</P>
<P>
	But if you take Propulsid and erythromycin together, you could  
die. 
</P>
<P>
	You're lucky. You read the special ``Patient Medication Guide''  
that Propulsid's maker provides with each box. 
</P>
<P>
	In bold print it says, ``What is the most important information  
I should know about Propulsid?'' The answer: Don't take it with any 
of nine other drugs, including erythromycin, or you risk a fatal 
irregular heartbeat. 
</P>
<P>
	The day before Janssen Pharmaceuticals voluntarily issued these  
special medication guides, a Washington man bought Propulsid at a 
local pharmacy. The only warning he received was a drugstore 
printout that said, ``This medication can rarely cause irregular 
heartbeat and fainting,'' and later urged users to ``tell your 
doctor'' if they are taking certain other medicines. 
</P>
<P>
	Quite a difference, noted Propulsid purchaser Larry Sasich of  
the consumer advocacy group Public Citizen. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, a new Food and Drug Administration regulation goes  
into effect, letting the government mandate explicit 
consumer-warning brochures, called Medguides, for up to 10 drugs a 
year deemed exceptionally risky. The idea is to tell patients what 
steps can lower their chances of a dangerous side effect. 
</P>
<P>
	Only two or three drugs, like Propulsid, voluntarily come with  
Medguides today. Instead, consumers usually receive prescription 
information from computer printouts or leaflets distributed by 
drugstores, with no accuracy oversight. The special Medguides, in 
contrast, will be printed by drug manufacturers and attached to 
their products, and contain FDA-specified warnings in laymen's 
terms. 
</P>
<P>
	A drug that comes with a Medguide ``gives a signal to consumers  
that this is a product they should really be careful about,'' said 
Nancy Ostrove, FDA's chief of drug information. 
</P>
<P>
	It's part of growing efforts by medical groups to educate  
doctors and patients to use medicine more safely. 
</P>
<P>
	An estimated 2 million Americans are hospitalized annually from  
drug side effects, and 100,000 die. Some side effects are 
unavoidable or a surprise, but experts say the vast majority of 
prescription-caused deaths are preventable. Education isn't the 
only protection -- they point to efforts such as computers that 
catch risky drug interactions if consumers fill all their 
prescriptions at one pharmacy. 
</P>
<P>
	But the FDA's new Medguides are controversial.  
</P>
<P>
	Two years ago, Congress killed a previous FDA attempt to make  
every prescription drug bear a Medguide. Opponents said the FDA was 
interfering in pharmacy practice and that putting high-profile 
warnings even on less risky drugs might scare patients away from 
valuable medicine. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, Congress gave drugstores until 2001 to distribute their  
own prescription information voluntarily to 75 percent of 
Americans. 
</P>
<P>
	A senator introduced a last-minute attempt to block Tuesday's  
new Medguide regulation, saying it violates Congress' intent to 
give voluntary programs a chance. Some pharmacist groups are upset, 
too. Congress, however, has made no move to fight the issue again. 
</P>
<P>
	FDA supporters say the new Medguides are legal because the  
government has the authority to single out risky drugs for special 
warnings. Indeed, the FDA already requires for about 70 drugs 
special ``patient labeling'' such as the fine-print insert that 
comes with birth control pills, but the government seldom forces 
the actual distribution of those labels, as it will with Medguide. 
</P>
<P>
	The Medguide controversy aside, drugstores are distributing more  
information to consumers. A recent FDA survey found about 70 
percent of patients are getting some information beyond what dose 
to take and how often, up from less than half of patients in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	The accuracy of those leaflets is not yet known. FDA's first  
formal look at prescription information quality is scheduled for 
this summer. But Public Citizen recently examined 59 leaflets that 
come with prescription painkillers and said just 25 percent 
appropriately warned patients to quit taking the pills if they 
developed symptoms of stomach ulcers, a dangerous side effect of 
painkillers. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE -- Lauran Neergaard covers health and medical  
issues for The Associated Press in Washington. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
