<HEADLINE> Arts Chief Wants $50M for Programs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The head of the National Endowment for the  
Arts asked senators Thursday for an additional $50 million to 
spread his agency's work to underserved areas of the country. 
</P>
<P>
	Some members of Congress have complained that NEA grants  
concentrate too heavily on big cities such as New York and Los 
Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	For the current year, the NEA has $98 million in federal funds.  
President Clinton has requested $150 million for the fiscal year 
beginning Oct. 1. Of that, $50 million would go for a new 
three-year program called ``Challenge America.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The first year, 2000, will target funding to communities that  
lack a significant arts presence,'' NEA Chairman Bill Ivey told the 
Senate committee that authorizes NEA funding. 
</P>
<P>
	Ivey outlined a series of goals for the NEA, starting with arts  
education and including after-school programs. On Wednesday, a 
Justice Department expert on delinquency told an informal group of 
Congress members that pilot after-school arts programs have reduced 
the number of young people getting into serious trouble. 
</P>
<P>
	``Numerous recent studies conclude that children actively  
engaged in music, theater, dance and the visual arts demonstrate 
improved learning ability ... in other subject areas, including 
math and science,'' Ivey said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ivey's testimony was submitted to the Senate Health, Education,  
Labor and Pensions Committee. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
