<DOCNO> APW19990527.0361 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 19:19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Hails Milosevic Indictment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	YULEE, Fla. (AP) -- President Clinton today praised an  
international tribunal's war-crimes indictment of Yugoslav 
President Slobodan Milosevic, saying the action ``speaks to the 
world in saying that the cause we are fighting for in Kosovo is 
just.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Briefly leaving his vacation cottage at White Oaks Plantation,  
Clinton said the indictment will help deter future war crimes and 
``make clear to the Serbian people precisely who is responsible for 
this conflict and who is prolonging it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The president did not answer questions on whether he can now  
negotiate peace with Milosevic, or whether NATO should pursue an 
arrest. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton spoke shortly after he issued a written statement that  
cheered the indictment and said NATO's objectives remain unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	He said NATO's airstrikes are exacting a heavy price on  
Milosevic's leadership. ``We see the impact they are having in the 
protests against his policies, the desertions in his army, the 
difficulties his troops in Kosovo are having in maintaining their 
grip on the area,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	In his earlier statement, Clinton urged other nations to support  
the tribunal's decision and ``cooperate with its efforts to seek 
justice.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The U.N. War Crimes Tribunal in The Hague, Netherlands, today  
indicted Milosevic and four top aides on charges of planning and 
carrying out war crimes against ethnic Albanians in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	The tribunal issued arrest warrants for the four, marking the  
first time an international court has charged a head of state with 
such atrocities. Milosevic could face a life sentence if captured 
and convicted. 
</P>
<P>
	Thousands of ethnic Albanians are believed to have been slain by  
Serb forces in Kosovo. But the tribunal specifically charged the 
five Serbian leaders with the forced deportation of 740,000 Kosovar 
Albanians and the murder of 340. 
</P>
<P>
	``The objectives of NATO's military effort remain unchanged,''  
Clinton said. ``The Kosovar refugees must be able to go home with 
security and self-government; Serb forces must leave Kosovo; and an 
international security force with NATO at its core must deploy. We 
intend to persist with our efforts until our objectives are 
achieved.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The United States and its NATO allies have stopped short of  
insisting on Milosevic's ouster. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
